<HEADLINE>Amec promises improved results</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<FLAG>business digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979073</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONSTRUCTION and engineering group Amec yesterday reiterated its pleas to
shareholders to reject the hostile bid from Kvaerner, the Norwegian owner of
the Govan shipbuilding yard on the Clyde.
Amec said the offer for its Ordinary and Preference stock, valuing the company
at #361m, was ``inadequate''. This assertion is based on its record #2300m
order book and what it says are strong growth prospects.
Amec said the bid did not take into account the firm's forecast 39% increase in
operating profit for 1995 and forecast 12% rise in turnover for 1996. It added
that Kvaerner recognised the potential of Amec's businesses and covets its
position in the UK oil and gas sector, its international strengths, and its
project management and design skills.
Blowers purchase
CLYDE Blowers, the specialist engineering group, has bought Richard Simon &amp;
Sons, a Nottingham-based manufacturer of weighing, packing and systems control
equipment, for #2.5m.
Clyde Blowers announced the acquisition as executive chairman Jim McColl
revealed ``a very encouraging start to the year'' at the company's annual
meeting in Glasgow. ``I am confident of further strong growth in this year,''
he said, noting that Clyde Blowers had trebled its pre-tax profit to #1.5m in
the 12 months to September 30. Clyde Blowers shares closed up 7p at 205p.
Joint bid remains
ICELAND and N Brown hope Littlewoods will reconsider its proposed joint bid for
the group which is Britain's largest family owned-business. At an EGM on
Thursday, a 79% majority voted against pursuing any external approaches for the
group. However, Iceland and N Brown said they would welcome any reconsideration
of their proposals by the Littlewoods board. The two companies made a joint
approach to Littlewoods in mid-November.
Courts' profit fall
TOUGH trading conditions in the UK hit Courts furnishing stores at the interim
stage. Pre-tax profits were down 10% to #4m, but the dividend is raised by 5%
to 2.1p from 2.0p. UK sales dropped 2.4% in the first half, although trading,
in what is the most important half for the group, shows a slight recovery.
Overseas sales grew by 20% with strong trading in Malaysia and Singapore.
Courts say there is scope to expand in the UK and overseas, particularly in
south-east Asia.
Crying into beer
LONDON-based brewer Fuller Smith &amp; Turner criticised Chancellor Kenneth Clarke
for not reducing beer duty in the Budget despite the tide of imports coming in
from France. The amount of imports is said to have reached 1.1 million pints
per day.
The comments were made by chairman Anthony Fuller as the group reported record
interim profits of #5.1m compared with #4.2m previously. The interim dividend
goes up from 2.65p to 2.92p. The hot summer and the opening of six new pubs
contributed to the strong performance.
</TEXT>
