<HEADLINE>A sentimental flash of obsessive self-love</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979074</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FUNNY old week for public service broadcasting, such as remains. Channel 4
began it by interpreting its generous remit as a feeble excuse to tag a weekend
of soap opera re-runs onto the 35th anniversary of Coronation Street just as
BBC2 was following the Labour Party in its search for a prophet through The
Wilderness Years (Sunday). It was hard to say which of the plots was less
plausible.
Channel 4's thinking, if thinking it is, seems to be that the capacious
portmanteau ``popular culture'' means any old tart can be scraped from the
bottom of the barrel and treated with reverence. Re-running an episode of the
misbegotten Eldorado might just have distracted attention from the deeply
risible Hollyoaks. Ray Gosling's The Coronation Street Years may have said more
about how the nation has altered than Hugo Young's ponderous The Last Europeans
(all Sunday). But what this theme weekend really exposed was the infinite
depths of TV's self-love.
Thus, 1986 may have been a bad year for Labour (which year in the eighties was
not?) but could it match the profound significance of Sheila Grant's rape in
Brookside? The events of the early sixties may have left Britain further out of
the European mainstream and given Young a trail to follow, but what was that to
a re-run of a 1963 Coronation Street? TV makes its own icons, and bids us
worship.
There is, now, more soap frothing from the box than ever, and it is, in
consequence, worse than ever. But that fact, in its turn, has allowed
television's pop tarts simply to argue that there was once a golden age of
gritty serial drama with tough scripts and fine acting, a national passion play
that united us all by its sheer humanity. Old soaps thus become worthy of
preservation and study, cultural events to be cherished like any other.
The trouble is, and despite all the praise of commentators who have made
slumming it into a career, Soap Weekend proved only that most of what the
nation has lapped up over the years has been cheap melodrama and unredeemed
banality. The form itself - endless narratives, stereotypical characters, the
fiction of ``realism'' - militates against any hope of art.
The national obsession with the genre suggests, meanwhile, that a shabby nation
has become sentimental about its own decay.
None of this is to underestimate sentiment. As The Wilderness Years began to
make clear, it was sentiment as much as stupidity that forced Labour from
office. Reverence for British institutions combined with sentimentality over
its socialist past, one neatly cancelling out the other, did as much harm to
the party as the Tories ever did. But what was striking - apart from the
impossible youth of the politicians captured on film - was the lack of
sentiment most of them felt for one another. Most people in the People's Party,
on this evidence, hated most of the other people.
To which it might be added: in keeping with what is taken to be the present
sentiment of the nation, The Wilderness Years, on its first outing, was the
best propaganda Tony Blair could hope for in his efforts to transform Labour.
If everyone then was so wrong, how could he fail to be right? Then again, there
was a time when few people doubted that the revered Robert Baden-Powell was
right about everything. Sentiment was for him and the nation's boys loved him -
almost as much, on the evidence of The Secret Lives series (Channel 4,
Thursday), as he adored them.
This splendid series has had a merry time performing the necessary public
service of chopping the legs from national monuments. It ignores the juvenile
proposition that you cannot apply modern opinions to the past (handy for
Hitler, among others, if it were true) and simply lays out the evidence. It
makes the useful case - one that cannot be made too often - that heroes need
careful watching.
Thus, this essay on the author of Camp Fire Yarns (deeply camp, in fact)
explored all the clean, hearty, manly virtues that allowed B-P to turn Scouting
into the biggest movement the world has seen outside politics and religion.
Virtues like a love for pig-sticking (``Oh mummy! You should have seen how I
stuck it in him!''), an addiction to public executions, shameless militarism, a
belief in racial superiority, and the devoted study of photographs of naked
boys. The usual thing.
That B-P was a repressed homosexual with a sadistic streak (he advised Scout
masters to take masturbators ``in hand'') seemed fairly clear.
His usefulness within the Edwardian class system, his unease among women
(mummy's fault), and his arrested emotional development were also pretty
obvious. But perhaps for that reason Secret Lives was oddly gentle, as though
accepting that this bizarre character was a product of bizarre circumstances,
more to be pitied than despised. Given the huge influence of his movement,
however, you wonder what that says about the Britain that honoured him so.
You wonder, too, thinking of Britain and public service broadcasting, whose
brainwave it was to offer the Inside Story Special: Inside 25 Cromwell Street
(BBC1, Monday), in which the children of Fred and Rosemary West offered their
version of what went on and why. There comes a point at which explanation
becomes exploitation and this piece, ripe with tales of abuse and terror, came
perilously close to it.
One argument says the public has the right to know; another that it has the far
more important right to understand. Now we know, do we understand? If not - and
who claims otherwise? - why are we invited to watch? The revolting thought is
that this programme, for some, was just another part of the evening's
entertainment.
Finally, since documentaries have dominated the week, the column's commendation
for Lido (BBC2, Wednesday), a work so good it's hard to say why. Ostensibly a
gentle portrait of Brockwell Park lido in South-east London, it turned out to
be a sunny and sweet study of human variety, from the one-parent families
frolicking to the Cabinet secretary keeping in shape.
Nothing exciting happened, short of a jolly lesbian wedding, and nothing of
great importance was said. These were people, merely, caught for a moment in
the passing show. The sort of people you never see in soap operas, in fact, and
not a national hero among them.
</TEXT>
