<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forte expects profits to surge</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979075</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORTE forecasts a surge in profits and details the way it ``will create value''
for shareholders in its formal defence document against the hostile #3300m bid
from Granada.
The group projects a 46% rise in pre-tax profit to #185m before exceptionals
for the year to January 1996. The surplus on disposals of Gardner Merchant,
Harvester, Puritan Maid, Lillywhites and Griersons will add a further #76m.
Excluding these extras, earnings per share will be 40% ahead at 14.1p.
``This hostile bid is inadequate and has no commercial logic. Coming at an eary
stage of the cyclical upswing, it is an attempt to acquire on the cheap the
value the new management team is creating,'' chairman Sir Rocco Forte declares.
Forte makes no reference to dividends at this stage, clearly because it wants
to retain ammunition for further circulars to shareholders. A large increase is
a foregone conclusion, and Forte notes that operating cashflow is recovering
strongly and will comfortably cover dividend payments after investing #175m in
capital programmes.
The defence document does not include the traditional attack on the bidder,
though this will surely come later.
Trading so far in the second half of the trading year is said to have
strengthened further. London hotel revenue per available room is up 14% in the
past four months, with a better mix. Provincial hotels are up 7% and
international 1%. If Paris, where conditions have been especially difficult, is
excluded then there is a 9% rise.
Little Chef and Welcome Break had a difficult summer, but sales are now moving
ahead of 1994.
The #240m raised through disposals will cut gearing to 50% by the year-end and
further divestments are planned. Hotels will generate net cashflow of #100m
this year, more than some observers had considered likely.
The projected profits are not unexpected as they are only a little above
consensus market expectations and are in line with the estimate from Forte's
own broker, UBS, after it had downgraded its forecast from #190m in October.
Forte points out that the business has been fundamentally reorganised into
distinct, brand-focused businesses supported by a corporate team of 50.
Reporting lines have been shortened, with clear responsibility and
accountability for performance, cashflow and returns.
``Revitalisation of the management team has enabled us to make substantial
progress in implementing our strategy through radical organisation and cultural
change,'' states Sir Rocco. ``We have created clearly defined business units,
shortened lines of communication, and brought the management closer to the
customer.
The group says that closure of divisional offices and de-layering management
has produced cost savings of #25m per year. Strong financial controls and
efficient purchasing have been introduced. Forte points out that disposals
totalling #950m over three years have yielded a surplus of #500m, with a
further #200m of disposals announced or underway.
``Realising the value of significant hotel assets while retaining management
contracts is fast becoming an attractive option as the hotel market
strengthens,'' it states.
Granada has criticised the plan to demerge the restaurant activities because,
for one thing, purchasing economies would be lost. Forte rejects this, saying
the two businesses are becoming increasingly distinct, with synergies between
them less important. So in terms of transaction value, hotels are high spend,
roadside restaurants low; hotels have advance bookings, restaurants are
immediate purchase.
Sir Rocco adds that demerger will deliver greater operational focus, more
efficient allocation of resources and shareholder choice. He hopes to implement
the demerger by the middle of 1996. However, there are no clues over how much
shareholders would be better off through the demerger.
Forte details how its brands have leading positions in their markets and
explains how it hopes to improve their performances. Overall, the defence
document contains nothing new to worry the Granada camp, which will now be
preparing its riposte.
</TEXT>
