<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>When it can pay to hedge your investment bets</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ken clay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>personal finance</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979076</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE UK share market scored gains of around 20% this year which is not at all
bad going. A cheer for the bulls who said the FTSE-100 index could hit 3750 but
a stale bun with no icing on it for the bear who worried that it could drop to
2800.
Some investors like to keep their money in their home market. Some get dizzy
when the market hits new peaks as it has been doing recently. Where it goes
from here depends, as always, partly on what happens on Wall Street and in
other overseas economies and partly on interest rates, as much as on domestic
economic considerations.
Short term it seems worth bearing in mind that the run up to Christmas and the
early days of the new year are more often than not times when shares do well.
Longer term, next year is bound to see even more concentration of interest on
what is likely to be the result of the next General Election.
For what it is worth, predictions for the FTSE-100 index for next year have
ranged from not much change to 3900 or even 4200. The prospect of 4200, it has
to be admitted, gives me a slight attack of vertigo bearing in mind the
political risks. It is possible to argue though that there is scope for
dividends to rise whether you accept the Chancellor's growth target or the more
modest figure market experts have been forecasting.
For those who prefer to hedge their bets and feel they would like some of their
money overseas in a period of election uncertainty, brokers have been getting a
lot more confident about Japan. Tokyo has already staged an encouraging
recovery but has a long way to go if it is ever to hit its previous (dizzy)
heights.
Investors have responded by putting new money into investment trusts
specialising in Japan and being net buyers of Japan unit trusts despite the
earlier couple of false starts to recovery.
NatWest Securities is ``strongly bullish'' on Japanese shares on a 12-month
view. It says: ``The policy paralysis that characterised official behaviour in
the first part of 1995 has been replaced by renewed efforts to stimulate
demand. Although consumer demand remains fragile and low wage rises and rising
unemployment are undermining confidence, the Government's policy initiatives
mean that economic activity should show a marked improvement in 1996.''
Its prediction for the end of next year is that the Nikkei Dow index could hit
23,000. The timing of the big bounce is, however, uncertain. Domestic Japanese
investment institutions may stay on the sidelines for a while until there is a
discernible pick-up in corporate profitability.
Further rises in the share market are ``critically dependent on the economy's
showing some signs of improvement in the face of the authorities' renewed
efforts to stimulate demand''.
NatWest also cautions that a falling yen is ``a precondition of a rising equity
market''.
One of the major things which has worried investors about Japan has been the
banking crisis. Merrill Lynch, which also likes Japan, comments: ``In the past,
around the world, banking crises have proved to be major buying opportunities.
This is because an easier monetary stance is adopted to prevent a systemic
crash of the banking system.''
Japanese interest rates have already been brought down to 0.5% and ``the Bank
of Japan has to maintain interest rates at a very low level for at least the
next year to give Japanese banks time to rebuild profits''.
The case for Japanese shares is that earnings will accelerate - the brokers
predict that earnings per share should at least double over the coming two
years - but as interest rates are held down shares will remain on high
price-earnings multiples.
If this proves correct it should be good news for the domestic Japanese
investor. But the overseas investor has to think about the prospect of a fall
in the value of the yen. NatWest emphasises that a cheaper yen is ``central to
Japan's recovery prospects''. So the authorities are likely to continue to
encourage the currency to drop against the dollar.
Howard Flight of currency and bond specialist Guinness Flight, who earlier
forecast that the yen would drop to 120 to the dollar, expects continued yen
weakness from current levels.
He says the Bank of Japan ``has developed a sense of real crisis about
deflationary pressures in the Japanese economy and in particular the bad debt
problems of the banking system''. So he predicts that the policy of low
interest rates is unlikely to change until there is evidence of a sustained
recovery in the Japanese economy.
If all this is correct it follows that an overseas investor has to lose on the
currency if he or she is to gain on the stock market. The solution: leave it to
the experts and buy a specialist investment trust which is hedging its position
in Japanese shares against the yen.
Hedging does indeed seem worthwhile because Merrill Lynch is predicting a yen
dollar rate of 120 and NatWest a yen sterling rate of 178. That would eat up a
fair chunk of an unhedged gain even if the Nikkei index does hit 23,000.
Hedging policy among the specialist trusts ranges from a few with none to up to
40% or so.
Among the trusts most liked by NatWest is Edinburgh Japan, which at the time of
writing has hedging of 40%, and the NatWest analysts have set a ``target''
share price gain for next year (based on their net asset value forecasting
model) of almost 30%. Second is Invesco Japan Discovery with 25% hedging and a
target price rise of 27%.
Merrill Lynch recommends Baillie Gifford Japan and Baillie Gifford Shin Nippon,
both of which are also projected to rise 20% or more by NatWest. It also likes
the look of a number of warrants including Invesco Tokyo and Fleming Japan.
</TEXT>
