<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Devro to raise #31m for purchase</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979077</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DEVRO, the Scottish maker of sausage skins, is raising #31m through a placing
and open offer of shares to help pay for its purchase of the US firm Teepak
International.
The new shares will be placed at 230p each, and Devro shareholders will be
entitled to buy one share for every 10 Ordinary held. Devro shares rose 12p to
251p.
The share issue has been underwritten by Charterhouse Bank, and an
extraordinary general meeting will be held on January 3 to approve it.
Devro agreed to buy Teepak for #87m in March, but the US Federal Trade
Commission only gave approval this week.
The enlarged Devro will have a big share of the US market in sausage skins. The
FTC has, therefore, forced the company to sell its existing collagen casings
business in the US.
Devro is paying for Teepak with up to #30m in cash and a mixture of Ordinary
and Preference shares. It will also take on #100.6m of Teepak's debt.
Devro has arranged a #120m facility with First National Bank of Chicago to
cover this debt and provide working capital. Completion of the deal is expected
on January 5.
Devro said trading had improved since it announced interim pre-tax profits of
#14.7m for the six months to June and it is confident of a satisfactory result
for the year.
</TEXT>
