<DOCNO>GH951209-000005</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000005</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Laporte's shares nosedive</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979079</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PROFIT warning from chemicals group Laporte sent the shares nosediving
yesterday by 172p to 611p.
New chief executive Jim Leng, who made his name at Low &amp; Bonar, has wasted no
time in shaking up the business, announcing the closure of several of its 100
factories around the world. These are smaller sites which Mr Leng said were
taking up too much management time or which were not making sufficient returns
on capital.
The total number of job losses among its 7100 staff has not been disclosed.
Following the completion of an operational review, Bedfordshire-based Laporte
has concluded that a restructuring programme and asset write-down is required
which will require a provision in the current year of #85m.
The site closures, rationalisation and cost reductions will cost #50m. The cash
element of the charge is #30m and is to be recovered by selling underperforming
assets and properties. The net debt of the group at 31 December, 1995 is
expected to be around #190m.
The restructuring provision coupled with declining demand for chemicals by the
construction and bulk polymer industries and poor trading in Australia and
South America, is expected to reduce profits by 10% compared with the #123.5m
made last year.
Profitability will also be adversely affected by the withdrawal from joint
ventures and a #5m higher interest bill associated with the substantial capital
expenditure programme and acquisitions made during the year. However the group
said it expected to maintain the final dividend at 14.5p net.
Mr Leng said the planned restructuring was directed at reducing the number of
operating sites and the cost base. He added that he believed the core group was
``in good shape''. He noted that several of the businesses were continuing to
trade strongly despite challenging market conditions.
In future, the focus is going to be on core and growing businesses in areas
such as pharmaceutical intermediary products and chemicals for the electronics
industry.
Mr Leng said that the benefits of the restructuring programme will start to
feed through in 1996 and be fully effective in 1997. He is no stranger to
reorganisation having overseen a major overhaul at the Dundee-based packaging
and materials firm Low &amp; Bonar where he was chief executive until his move nine
weeks ago.
</TEXT>
