<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Companies are rushing to put their services on the Internet Net financial gains</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>anthea masey</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979080</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is already going down in history as the Internet Christmas. In the UK around
900,000 people are surfing the Net and, with home computers and modems the
hottest selling items for the second year running, the number hooking up to the
information super-highway could double over the next year.
However, for many people, the experience has been less than riveting. Take
financial services. Most commentators say the home computer is poised to
revolutionise the consumer's relationship with the financial services industry,
as the telephone did 10 years ago, but that we aren't there yet.
Danny Bowers of MoneyWorld, the first UK personal finance publisher on the
Internet, says around 120 financial companies and organisations have some sort
of presence.
``There was a big burst of interest about six months ago. Companies found it
easy to put out information on the Internet and it gave their executives a big
thrill calling up their literature at home on their PCs. But consumers are
looking for something more than the information they can pick up in the High
Street for free. They want to be able to do business over the Net.
``This is the next stage of development and there are now between 30 and 40
companies who can communicate with their customers over the Internet to a
greater or lesser degree,'' he explains.
Sharelink, the telephone stockbroking service, is one of the first to exploit
the medium. It provides Europe's first Internet share dealing service using
prices automatically updated by Electronic Share Information (ESI), which costs
from #5 a month.
Sharelink is hedging its bets with the Internet by also offering a dealing
service through Infotrade, a financial information service owned by Mitsubishi,
which offers constantly updated share prices using CD-ROM technology.
Which system will win out is anyone's guess at the moment. Infotrade hopes to
sign up 100,000 private investors over the next four years. Chris Lambert,
Sharelink's special projects manager, says it will all come down to price in
the end. ``Telephone bills versus the cost of CD-ROMs, although in the end the
Internet does have the advantage that the information only has to be provided
once, it doesn't have to be sent out on CD-ROM.''
So far, Barclays is the only bank to have exploited the Net's ability to enter
into a dialogue with its customers. In March it began offering quotations for
travel insurance and in May it introduced a mail order service, BarclaySquare.
This is the equivalent of an electronic High Street. You can order goods from
14 stores including wine from Sainsburys, books from Blackwells and tickets
from Eurostar, and pay by credit card.
Credit card numbers are scrambled so they can only be read by the recipient.
However, many people worry that these secret codes may be broken.
This is a concern The Insurance Club has recognised. It is jointly owned by
Independent Insurance and insurance broker Bervale Mead. The club offers
buildings and contents insurance via the Net. Chairman Judith Malim says
payment is either by credit card or by post. ``We think we are the first
company producing quotations and setting up policies over the Internet, but we
do recognise that many consumers won't want to put their credit card details
out over the Net.''
But is the service popular? She says that between 50 and 100 people call up her
pages every day. ``Around 30% of these then go on to get quotations. We have
been surprised by the amount of E-Mail we get as a result. For example, people
E-Mail us to say that the quotation was attractive and they will be in touch
again when their policy is up for renewal. No-one ever phones or writes to an
insurance company to tell them that.''
She admits it is early days with the Internet. ``It is only just beginning. As
a company we have a range of products for the increasing number of people who
work from home, and as these people are often using the new technologies, we
are hoping to put these products out on it soon.''
Anyone who has ever surfed the Net knows how difficult it is to find your way
around without the right addresses. MoneyWorld (http:// www.moneyworld.co.uk)
carries a directory of most of the UK financial services companies offering
information or products in this way. Barclays can be reached at http://
www.barclays.co.uk; ESI is at http://www.esi.co.uk; Infotrade is at http://
www.infotrade.co.uk, and The Insurance Club is at http://
www.insuranceclub.co.uk
</TEXT>
