<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BT and Oftel go to war over access charges</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS, and CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979081</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANOTHER row has broken out between BT and its regulator Oftel over the
calculation of the charges rival telecom operators have to pay BT to access its
network for delivering calls.
BT has objected to Oftel's excluding certain significant costs from the
calculation. As a result, the determination of the charges will be delayed,
with completion expected next month. The delay reflects a further deterioration
in relations between BT and its regulator.
Oftel accuses BT of trying offload some costs which have nothing to do with
other operators' access to its network onto its competitors. Director General
of Telecommunications, Don Cruickshank declared: ``Oftel remains of the view
that other operators ought not to have to contribute through interconnection
charges to BT's large redundancy costs, vacant accommodation, chairman's office
and publicity costs (which include the costs of campaigns to win back customers
from other operators.''
However, he concedes that there is a heavier burden of proof on Oftel to show
why these costs should be excluded and where they should properly fall than had
been thought. So BT has been asked to provide more information on the origin,
breakdown, and allocation of these costs.
The matters in dispute account for around 15% of interconnection charges.
q BT yesterday confirmed plans to establish a European works council for
employees.
The move is expected to embarrass Ministers, who will see it as further
evidence of UK industry embracing European integration and undermining the
Government's opt-out of the EU social chapter.
However, a BT spokesman denied this was the company's intention. He said:
``This is our way of trying to ensure dialogue between ourselves and staff
representatives.
``We are now very much a European company, with interests across the Continent,
and we wanted to give those employees a means of formal communication with the
company. It has nothing to do with Government policy.''
All 135,000 BT staff will be consulted on the format of what will become known
as the European consultative council. The scheme, expected to be formalised by
next summer, is understood to be the largest such project in Britain.
In the UK, it will run in tandem with the company's traditional union
negotiations.
Other UK companies to have set up similar councils include United Biscuits and
ICI.
</TEXT>
