<DOCNO>GH951209-000008</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000008</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pension decision proves costly</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>family finance</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Cartoon</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979082</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
q.I will take early retirement in the autumn next year with a company pension.
I should be obliged if you could advise me on the various options. These are a
pension of #18,000 a year; one of #15,000 with a #40,000 tax-free lump sum; or
an increase of #1000 in the pension in either case with a reduction of #3000
when I reach 65 and receive the state pension.
I will be 54 when I retire. I have a #30,000 Standard Life low-cost endowment
mortgage at a concessionary rate of 5% which matures in early 2001. I have
savings and investments totalling #28,000. I am married with two children. One
will graduate in the near future and the other has a further three years of
study. I have no other outstanding commitments apart from replacing my company
car.
n.It is worth taking the cash option because if you buy an annuity or invest it
in PEPs you will pay less tax and it also gives more flexibility. At your age
your life expectancy is 21 years. On this basis you would be giving up #30,000
of income in the final 10 years of your life in exchange for an extra #11,000
in your first 11 years of retirement, if you take the #1000 extra option.
You could argue that you will be able to make more use of the extra income when
you are younger, though #1000 does not go far. On the other hand you might be
grateful for the extra income the state pension will bring when the time comes.
You may actually need more income when you are elderly, to pay for nursing home
care for example.
If you have every expectation, on your personal and family health record, of
living to a ripe old age, #1000 a year extra now does not look like much of a
bargain.
q.I am very interested in negotiating a re-mortgage with an alternative lender,
but am concerned about leaving the Halifax Building Society as I would lose my
entitlement to the basic distribution at converson. Obviously final figures are
not available but can you give your estimate of what the basic distribution is
likely to be, so I can properly consider the pros and cons of moving lender?
n.It is estimated that the basic distribution will consist of Halifax shares
with a value of roughly #600. Further information will be given probably
towards the end of 1996 as flotation is not expected before 1997. The exact
timing depends on market conditions.
q.I would like to invest #6000 in a PEP and one friend has recommended the Save
&amp; Prosper general managed PEP while another has suggested Alliance Trust. Could
you give your views on these or any others worth considering?
n.The first thing to remember is that a PEP investment is for the longer term,
meaning at least five years. Save &amp; Prosper has made great strides in recent
years to improve its investment performance and has a good chance of being in
the top performance quartile in future. The advantage of the Alliance Trust PEP
is its very low charges and spread of investment trusts available.
Another you might consider is Schroder, with investment in its UK Enterprise
unit trust which has a strong track record and uses a well-proven selection
method. Perpetual is another manager you might think about. It is impossible to
predict which will perform the best. All you can look for is a consistent
standard of performance across the range of funds of an investment manager,
coupled with low charges.
q.You recently mentioned the possibility of an employee making additional
voluntary contributions to either the employer's pension scheme or to a scheme
of your own choice. Can you say what the limit is for these payments and, if
they have not been made in earlier years, is it possible to catch up by
increasing payments this year?
n.A person in pensionable employment is allowed tax relief on contributions of
up to 15% of earnings, subject to a maximum earnings limit of #78,600. The
total of normal annual contributions plus additional voluntary contributions
(AVCs) must not exceeed the 15% limit.
For example, if your employer's scheme is contributory and you normally pay 5%
of salary, you may make AVCs of up to 10% of earnings to either your employer's
scheme or to a free-standing AVC plan. For this purpose, earnings usually
includes salary, bonus, commission and the value of taxable benefits in kind.
Unlike retirement annuity contracts and personal pension plans for the
self-employed and individuals not in pensionable employment, it is not possible
to obtain tax relief for unused limits for earlier years. Nor is it possible to
relate payments back to an earlier year. If, therefore, you are considering
AVCs action is required before April 5 for relief to be obtained in the current
tax year.
q.My wife and I separated last January but as it has only recently become clear
there will be no reconciliation I have not yet informed my tax office. What
will be the position regarding the married man's allowance which I still
receive, and what tax relief will I be entitled to for maintenance payments?
n.As your separation is now permanent you should advise the Inland Revenue as
soon as possible. The date of separation falls part way through the tax year
1994-95 but you will be entitled to the full married couple's allowance for
that year. The allowance ceases to be available for the tax year 1995-96
onwards. To qualify for tax relief maintenance must be paid under a court order
or a legally binding agreement between you both drawn up by your lawyer.
You will be able to claim tax relief on payments up to the amount of the
married couple's allowance (#1720). The relief is usually given in your PAYE
coding in place of the allowance. Your wife will not be liable to tax on the
payments she receives from you, but you are not entitled to tax relief on the
excess if the maintenance exceed the limit.
When you inform the tax office you will be required to complete a form giving
full details of the separation and to supply a copy of the maintenance order or
agreement.
q.Following the recent press coverage over Shell Brent Spar and British Gas
boardrooom salaries, the role of pension funds in applying pressure to these
companies was raised.
I wrote to the pension fund managers for our company asking them to provide me
with details of equities held and explain the rationale for investments, that
is maximising returns versus so-called ethical considerations. I was told that
only figures for the top-10 UK and foreign holdings were available, from the
annual report. A very detailed breakdown of equities held by geography and
business sector was also available.
Can you advise what rights I have to obtain a more detailed breakdown of
equities held? Can you also provide details of any organisations that can help
employees/members of pension funds extract more information?
n.The only obligation the fund has is to provide details of investments held in
the annual report to members in the way yours does. But there is no reason why
the fund manager should not also supply a list of the shares held at the date
of the report.
It might be better to approach the trustees, through the member-appointed
trustee if there is one, rather than go directly to the manager. It is likely
they will have a more detailed breakdown. Getting information out of trustees
should be easier when new rules come into effect in April 1997. These will give
members the right to appoint at least one-third of them.
There is no reason why you should not receive a detailed breakdown more often
than once a year, after all the fund manager only has to press a button on his
computer to get a print out of the portfolio. In practice the manager is likely
to resist this because it would be like having someone peering over his
shoulder.
There are two organisations active in this area, the Pensions Industry Research
Committee (0171 250 3311) and the Ethical Investment Research Service (0171 735
1351).
q.On my retirement in July 1994 I was advised to invest #6000 in M&amp;G Dividend
fund. I realise the first year incurs charges but still think the return is
disappointing. After six months it was valued at #5980 and after a year #6224.
Should I continue with this PEP? I was also advised to invest #7000 in a
Prudential with-profits bond. I am puzzled by the life assurance factor. Also
your opinion on its performance would be appreciated. I have no need of income
from these investments.
n.A year or so is far too short a time in which to assess the performance of an
investment based on shares. Both the products you refer to are well regarded
and you should stick with them. If after four or five years they are
disappointing you could think again, but you must give them a fair chance.
The life assurance element of the Prudential bond you can ignore - it is just a
technicality. It is a low-risk investment designed to provide a steady
performance over the long term with low volatility. You don't have to receive
the income on either product. If it is not necessary, it can be reinvested.
q.I have held Abbey National and TSB shares since flotation at cost prices of
100p and 115p respectively. Despite your oft quoted advice about not putting
too many eggs in one basket, I kept the holdings in anticipation of an Abbey
National takeover of TSB. Instead it was Lloyds. I recently read that an
analyst said Lloyds shares were over-bought? What does this mean? Should I sell?
n.When an analyst takes the view that a share has been over-bought he is saying
the price has been driven too high by the weight of buying. There is some
evidence this has occurred with Lloyds, and, therefore, TSB. Indeed, the whole
banking sector looks pricey.
There is nothing wrong with taking a profit. You have done well out of the two
shares. As you do not tell us what other investments you have or how large your
holdings in Abbey National and TSB are, it is difficult to give specific
advice. You could sell the TSB and reinvest the proceeds elsewhere, while
holding on to Abbey National in the hope of it being involved in corporate
activity and perhaps benefiting from a pick-up in the housing market.
Caledonian Newspapers Limited and the editor of The Herald accept no legal
responsibility for the answers given in these columns. Readers are invited to
submit concise questions for answer in the paper. No correspondence can be
entered into.
</TEXT>
