<HEADLINE>FOOD Direct debit on cards for Safeway</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979083</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ARGYLL'S Safeway food chain hopes to increase the appeal of its ABC customer
loyalty cards by adding a direct-debit feature.
A top Argyll executive said the group plans to make the transformation next
year. Shoppers would be able to pay for their groceries with the ABC card,
which already entitles them to discounts and special offers.
Safeway's loyalty card scheme was expanded from 130 to all 365 of its stores on
October 23, just a few weeks after rival Tesco announced a 16% rise in interim
profits. The success of Tesco's own loyalty card was mainly credited for the
increase.
Argyll chairman Sir Alistair Grant said Safeway's ABC loyalty scheme had been a
great success in its first six weeks of operation. About 3.5 million shoppers
already have the card. It is used by up to 70% of customers at some Safeway
stores.
``It's been very helpful,'' Mr Grant said. ``We think it has put up sales two
or three points already.'' He said the recently-announced Christmas price watch
guarantee and the popular ``Harry'' television advertisements also had Safeway
heading for strong Christmas sales.
The ``Harry'' adverts, featuring a worldly-wise young child shopping with his
parents, have the highest recognition rating of any food store television
campaign.
The ABC card will also be used in conjunction with Safeway's self-scanning
shopping, where customers use a hand-held unit to scan their own groceries and
cut down on checkout time. The card will be used to unlock the scanning units
from a dispenser.
Self-scanning is already being used in the company's Airdrie and Perth stores.
The system will be installed in another 30 UK stores by the end of this year.
</TEXT>
