<HEADLINE>Timely Tessas and guaranteed returns</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Christopher Sims</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979084</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABBEY National has launched three new Tessa accounts - 3rd Edition, which pays
interest varying from 5.85% to 6.6% depending on the amount saved; Fixed Rate,
which pays 7% guaranteed with a bonus so investors can benefit from rises in
base rates, and Guaranteed Growth which promises 141% growth and a similar
bonus. The last two are available only to those with a maturing Tessa.
STANDARD Life has launched a range of guaranteed bonds, with or without
participation in the FTSE-100 index, over three, four or five years. With 100%
exposure to the index there's a minimum return of 105% of investment over three
years, 110% over five. With no index exposure returns are 115% and 127%.
LEGAL &amp; General has published a free guide to the 1995 Pensions Act. For a copy
telephone 0800 318327.
FIDELITY Brokerage has launched a margin trading service for private investors
so they can borrow against the security of an existing portfolio for further
investment or other purposes. Up to half the value of the ``marginable''
portfolio, which has to be made up of 500 eligible securities, can be borrowed
via a facility from the Bank of Scotland, which will provide a cheque book. The
rate is 11.5% to 10% depending on loan size.
SKIPTON Building Society has a new account paying 6.5% gross for amounts over
#30,000. Instant access is available for a penalty of 30 days worth of interest
on the sum withdrawn.
</TEXT>
