<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Furnishing growth</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>scottish business extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979085</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BY August next year a 110,000 sq ft factory on the Queenslie Industrial Estate,
on the edge of Glasgow's Easterhouse, will be put to productive use again, for
the first time since the early eighties.
Once the Olivetti company made typewriters here. But, long before manual
keyboards gave way to personal computers, laser printers and word processing
packages, the place closed, one more victim of the waves of corporate
restructuring which swept Scotland at that time.
In phases next year, the new occupant, a 50-year-old local family-owned
business, will turn this echoing space into a factory manufacturing furniture.
Sakol Furniture currently makes its ranges of mainly lounge furniture, in a
listed maze of mill buildings in Fielden Street, in another part of Glasgow's
East End.
Display, cocktail and corner units start as raw sheet materials and wood
veneers, being broken down into sections, matched, machined, assembled,
finished and polished on three floors in an operation which - due to the
building's daunting layout - renders the use of modern production flow
techniques impossible.
The move to Queenslie will be a liberation. It should radically reduce the time
spent by the 120 staff moving products from floor to floor by one cramped lift.
It will maximise the efficiencies to be gained from Sakol's investment in
modern woodworking equipment. But Queenslie is also twice the size of Fielden
Street. And furniture sales are heavily dependent on the buoyancy of a housing
market which, in recent years in the UK, has been pretty much in the doldrums.
So is the family behind Sakol Furniture being over ambitious? Are they biting
off more than they can chew? Gordon Sakol, who with brother Derek constitutes
the second generation in charge at Fielden Street, says they have spent much of
the 50th anniversary year debating that very point.
They have decided - with Sakol already a well-established and respected name in
the UK marketplace and beginning to make inroads into Ireland as well, and with
a healthy financial base from which to expand - that this is the moment to move
forward.
``Some people advised us that this is not the time to move,'' says Gordon
Sakol, the company's finance director. ``But things have gone in cycles from
when time began. We've come out of every cycle to date. And inevitably the
housing market and demand for furniture will bounce off the floor once more.
``As a company we are solid enough and sufficiently well-known to grow and
diversify and secure our place in the market when it turns up. We are confident
we can double sales in the next five years and, as a result, increase our
workforce by 25%.''
I admire that kind of commitment, from family owners who, given the reserves
built up over the past 50 years and their present profitable place in a highly
competitive marketplace, could freewheel for years without taking on any
additional risk.
But, like a lot of other family businesses, the Sakols seem to really care
about the people around them, many of whom have worked for the business for 30
years or more. ``We feel very strongly about them,'' says Gordon. ``We've got a
social conscience.''
Jim Carr, who is general manager in charge of production and has been with the
business since he was 16, is looking forward to the move. Frank Denny, the
production manager, who showed me round Fielden Street has had two spells at
Sakol Furniture and, this time, plans to continue until he's 70.
That kind of two-way commitment matters. Although most furniture making has
long since moved from solid wood to veneered composite boards, the craft skills
needed to retain a reputation for quality are still in demand. And, as Gordon
Sakol confirms, some skills are in short supply.
The roots of the present-day Sakol Furniture stretch back to before the Second
World War when Derek and Gordon's grandfather refurbished and resold
second-hand furniture from a barrow. Then, when their uncle Jack returned from
the army, came the move into manufacture.
In those days family-owned furniture businesses flourished in towns and cities
all over the country. Jack's brothers, Malcolm and Bernard, joined the business
too. Malcolm, who is now company chairman, undertook the main selling role, at
a time when the number of local manufacturers was matched by a plethora of
independent retail outlets.
When Malcolm was out on the road, Gordon recalls, he might have three or four
calls to make in a place the size of Kilmarnock. ``Now you can hardly find a
single independent furniture retailer in a town the size of Leeds.''
The shift in the balance of furniture retailing to the multiples and
increasingly demanding customers - they want more and more detail such as
curves and bits carved out, says Gordon, and they can drop a fad, like that for
limed oak finishes, within two seasons of it being introduced - present big
challenges to a manufacturer the size of Sakol.
The present team - Derek, who left a career as an architect 10 years ago to
become managing director, but still deploys some of his old skills designing
new ranges, and Gordon, who is a chartered accountant - have just appointed a
new sales director, Ken McConnell, from a large retailer, and are, despite all
these challenges, looking to the future with confidence.
Just before he died two months ago, Derek and Gordon talked to their own
father, Bernard, about their expansion plans. They took him to see the new
premises. He approved. Sakol Furniture has set its face against stagnating.
Growth, it believes, is the only way forward.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000012</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000012</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cone people of Papa Westray</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM HEWITSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra westering home</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979086</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Jim Hewitson in his latest missive from Orkney, reflects on longevity, the
importance of correct headgear and the strange object supplied by the council
AH, AUTUMN, season of mists and Nora Batty hats, of mellow fruitfulness and
lifeboat guild bring-and-buy sales. At least that man Keats got it half right.
We may not have the traditional piles of leaves to scuff around here in the
treeless kingdom of Papa Westray but in her russet train autumn does bring
heaps of activity hereabouts.
It wouldn't be fitting, however, to launch into my regular dispatch from the
outer edge without making mention of a man who saw more Papay autumns than
most. Johnny from North Rendall who died in October had a lifetime which
stretched from one end of the century to the other, and was one of the small
band of islanders who were children during the First World War.
We'll miss his rattly old van which gave him freedom when arthritis, the curse
of these damp north isles, set in. He was the slowest driver in Christendom -
and proud of it - and invariably you would find him sitting down by the pier,
waiting for the creel boats to return from Weelie's Taing, pipe smoke
spiralling from the driver's window, the finger raised in salute of the passing
backpacker.
Johnny was a big man in every way and it's strange, isn't it, how we all have
very different memories of folk who've finally jumped aboard the Stygian ferry.
On the eve of the funeral, fencehanging north of Daybreak as Bill o' the Links
weeded his tatties, I recalled Johnny talking of the great adventure of his
life, a voyage to join the Hudson's Bay Company, cut short by the Second World
War. In fact, Johnny had seldom been off his isle. Bill, on the other hand,
remembered his almost obsessive fear of mice.
Four score years and more was Johnny's allocation and he made use of every
precious moment.
The lifeboat guild bring-and-buy is a traditional landmark at the threshold of
winter and an opportunity I seldom miss to supplement my stock of ever-more
outlandish, even eccentric, headgear. Over the years I've collected all sorts
of tammies, balaclavas, caps, bunnets and helmets, everything from my
bait-stained Thunder Anchor baseball cap, which qualified me as a sort of
Nordic Hemingway, to a woolly Tibetan affair kindly brought back from the top
of the world by Jocelyn of Micklegarth.
My collection is, of course, a working one and selection of appropriate
headgear for weather conditions is always an important moment in the day.
Anyway the clothes stall at the sale round at the school had the usual
treasures from the island attics, some of the recycled articles I'm sure making
their second or third appearance at the annual sale. I'm fairly certain that
Dick Francis thriller was the self-same novel which I introduced to the
merry-go-round in the early eighties.
There amidst the offerings was a green silk Nora Batty turban which I
immediately coveted. Morag, knowing my headgear fetish well enough, threatened
to walk out when I made to try it on for size. Worse, while we argued the toss,
Jim the postie stepped in to snap up a brown checked bunnet with an expanding
headband which had been my second choice. Since then Jim has taking to slipping
it on his head whenever I'm down at Backaskaill buying stamps. But mock not,
Jim. There's always next year.
I did come away with a nice windcheater, a plastic stegosaurus, and a neat
leather belt, so all was not lost. More importantly the sale, including the
obligatory tea and Papay home-bakes, raised the staggering total of #350 for
the work of the RNLI from the 40 or so folk who attended.
Elsewhere, the CIA can relax. Put away the X-Files and forget about the Papay
parallelogram. The rash of wee green plastic cones in Papa Westray's back
gardens is not the vanguard of some alien invasion fleet. The cones are nothing
more sinister than our latest earth-friendly bins, enabling the citizens of the
far-flung isles to recycle all our food waste in our own backyards. In an
ambitious move the Orkney Islands Council has offered a bin to every household,
and by all accounts there's been a good take-up.
However here at School Place, at least, we're struggling to fill the cone, what
with a dog (recently arrived Spot), cats, goat and donkey, as well as the
horses, constantly on the lookout for food scraps, there's not a lot left over
to consign to the decomposition basket. More than 100 local authorities in
Britain have already tested and are introducing the bin, according to the
publicity blurb.
However, one important element in the scheme may be lacking in this vicinity.
Apparently you need plenty of sunshine to allow the process to build up a head
of steam.
If, however, the cones fail in their original purpose we can always adapt them
as space-age lobster creels, landing markers up at the airstrip, conical rabbit
hutches, gargantuan flower pots or maybe, just maybe, with a bit of clever
hacksaw work all-weather mobile shelters, made-to-measure body armour to keep
out the Atlantic blousters.
The cone people of Papa Westray - that would be something special for the US
spy satellites to cast their beady lenses upon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
