<HEADLINE>The woman who knows her station</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GAVIN BELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979087</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n Wheels in motion: Elaine Maudsley waits patiently on the station at
Carnforth, recalling the time 50 years ago when she appeared in Brief
Encounter, left. The film is the centre-piece of a proposed tourist attraction,
to be housed at the station. Here Celia Johnson as Laura, tells Myrtle Bagot
(Joyce Carey) and Albert Godby (Stanley Holloway) how it all began: ``just
through me getting a little piece of grit in my eye.''
Elaine Maudsley saw the blossoming of Celia Johnson and Trevor Howard's
hopeless love in Carnforth tearoom. Now, Gavin Bell reveals, she may see the
atmosphere of Brief Encounter again
For passengers on the West Coast main line between Scotland and the south,
Carnforth Station in Lancaster is a brief encounter. From the windows of an
Intercity express hurtling through it, there is a blur of boarded-up buildings,
a high wire fence enclosing the platforms, and a big old clock. It is unlikely
that passengers notice the clock displays a choice of times on its two faces,
and neither is correct.
The errant clock is at least in keeping with the atmosphere of the station, a
forlorn place abandoned by railway staff more than 20 years ago and left to
mourn alone the passing of the age of steam which once breathed clamorous life
through it. Now efforts are being made to revive its fortunes by re-creating a
romantic episode in its history - when it was transformed into Milford
Junction, where Celia Johnson and Trevor Howard gazed at one another with
hopeless love in David Lean's black and white classic Brief Encounter.
On the 50th anniversary of the making of the film, there are proposals to
create a themed restaurant and a small exhibition centre in the buildings which
appeared in some of the most poignant scenes. It is envisaged that the
restaurant in the old booking hall would have posters and other memorabilia of
the film, while a visitors' centre in the former refreshment room would have
audio and visual displays featuring Noel Coward's screenplay and the haunting
theme music from Rachmaninov's Second Piano Concerto.
The initiative has come from Railtrack, which acquired the station last year
from the British Rail property board. A long-term lease on generous terms has
been offered to prospective developers, and a short-list of interested parties
is being drawn up with a view to reaching a decision in a few months. The lease
extends only to the buildings, as two of the platforms are still used for local
train services.
Steve Tyler, a Railtrack spokes-man, sees the old refreshment room being
restored to the way it was in the 1940s, with LMS teacups, a big tea urn and
rock cakes, and monitors playing various scenes from the film.
``We're open to offers, of course, but we're hoping potential entrepreneurs
will share our vision for Carnforth. We get lots of tourists turning up to
wander around, and some of them even know the lines and re-enact their
favourite scenes on the platform. But there's nothing for them to see really,
it's a bit disappointing for them. So we're hoping this will be the answer.''
Many of the enthusiasts are Japanese - apparently there is a cinema in Tokyo
that shows the film throughout the year because Japanese have a high regard for
chaste love.
Mr Tyler points out that there is already a Brief Encounter restaurant at a
station near Norwich, which does good business, and he suggests the real thing
offers an even better investment opportunity. ``Apart from the romantic
aspect,'' he says, ``it is good for us to have a thriving business at the
station that creates a good image and attracts further investment in the
railways.''
A good omen is the recent recovery of a plaque commemorating the making of the
film, which was stolen from the station two years ago. It seems the thief had a
twinge of conscience, because it turned up in a plastic bag on the steps of a
nearby police station. It is now at Lancaster museum, pending the refurbishment
of the station.
Carnforth has an added attraction in an engine shed near the station, where a
private collector has assembled a museum of steam engines and rolling stock. It
attracts a large number of railway buffs, particularly for summer excursions on
the old trains, who would probably enjoy a cuppa in a 1940s Brief Encounter
tearoom while watching Lean's dramatic scenes of steam engines roaring past the
platforms.
But it will take some impressive special effects to re-create the magic of
Carnforth in the era of Brief Encounter. In those days, all the LMS trains
heading north would stop to take on coal and water for the long climb up Shap
Fell. The refreshment room on the island platform was continually busy with
passengers waiting for their locomotives to refuel, or for connections to Leeds
and Manchester. The railway was the biggest employer in the town, and the
station was its heart, throbbing to the sound of steam and whistles.
Now the water tower and the gas lamps have gone, the station master's office
has been demolished, and electrification has covered the tracks with a cobweb
of power lines. Only local services to and from places like Morecambe and
Barrow stop here now, and you have to buy your ticket on the train because
there has been no railway staff at Carnforth since the early 1970s.
But the fine old buildings are intact, defying dereliction with handsome
facades of local sandstone and ornate windows that give them the genteel
appearance of a country manor house rather than a railway station.
Local sentiment has been offended by the run-down of the station. ``It's a
disgrace now,'' says taxi driver John Bainbridge. ``Falling to bits, it is.
It's a shame really, because Carnforth was a beautiful old station, always well
looked after.''
The scheme to renovate it has the unqualified approval of Mrs Elaine Maudsley,
a former waitress in the refreshment room who appeared briefly in the film as
an extra. ``I'm thrilled for Carnforth this is happening,'' she says.
Mrs Maudsley is enjoying a brief return to the media spotlight as a local
celebrity, half a century after her acting debut: ``It's lovely being reminded
of those days. There was such a sense of comradeship after the war, and of
course when the film people arrived it was very exciting.'' She remembers being
paid the huge sum of 37s 6d a night for walking up and down the platform, at a
time when her weekly wage was 10s 6d.
She also remembers Stanley Holloway, as the station ticket collector, ruining
several shots by grabbing playfully at her leg as he climbed on to the platform
from the tracks. ``Everybody was laughing, but eventually Mr Lean told me to
move further up the platform.''
Mrs Maudsley has another reason for remembering the refreshment room with
fondness. A few months after the film crew left, a young man working in an
ammunition dump across the road came in for a morning coffee. ``I was engaged
to somebody else at the time, but he had the most wonderful voice and I fell
for him just like that, and he fell for me. We were married six months later.''
The marriage lasted 46 years, until her husband's death three years ago. Mrs
Maudsley regrets that he did not live to see the restoration of the station:
``He would have loved all this, he really would.''
So whatever happens at Carnforth, passengers flashing through the little
station may reflect that at least one brief encounter there lasted a lifetime.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000014</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000014</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Widows find that crime does pay</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Harry Conroy</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>business diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979088</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Widows Investment Management, the fund management subsidiary of
Scottish Widows, obviously believes that crime does pay. It has taken a small
stake in the Corrections Corporation, the largest prison management company in
the US.
Investment manager Alan Denholm sounded more like Tory ministers Michael Howard
or Michael Forsyth when he explained the reason behind the investment, saying:
``It is undoubtedly a growing business.''
Perhaps in the not too distant future we will witness takeover battles within
the Edinburgh financial community, with the customers, formerly known as
inmates, being offered sweetners to favour a particular company.
Scottish Widows Investment Management could in these circumstances steal a
march on its rivals by offering prisoners in Barlinnie or Saughton the
opportunity to exchange a cell in Glasgow or Edinburgh for one in Miami.
Copter across
the Mersey
IT would be factually incorrect to say Clyde Helicopters is spreading its
wings, but you will understand what I mean when I explain that it is now
offering Liver Bird tours across the Mersey which allow passengers to see some
of the sights of Liverpool from 1500ft up.
Liverpool is famous for both its Anglican and Roman Catholic cathedrals, and
during a recent press preview trip the pilot, having passed the Anglican
establishment, pointed downwards saying: ``And that's the Catholic Cathedral''.
A local journalist shouted from the back of the Jet Ranger helicopter: ``No it
isn't, that's Paddy's Wigwam.''
Anyone who knows the cathedral would agree it is an apt description, although
perhaps not a politically correct statement, and I'm sure it is an accurate
reflection of Liverpudlian humour.
Capital launch
pad for service
THE fund management community was out in force this week for a party in
Edinburgh hosted by Reuters, the financial information and news agency group.
John Parcell, managing director of Reuters UK and Ireland, was among those
attending. I am not biased but he has a lot going for him. He was once a
journalist. In fact, he was a frontline Reuters correspondent in Cambodia for
four years, which may be why he decided to cross over to management.
The strength of Scotland's financial sector explains why the information group
has chosen Edinburgh for its UK launch next week of a service which delivers
brokers' research on screen, saving a few forests in the process.
Making Poland
miles better
MICHAEL Kelly still carries Glasgow's banner whenever he is given the
opportunity. He has just returned from a trip to Lublin in Poland where he was
attending a seminar supported by the British Know How Fund to advise the Polish
city on how best to market itself.
The Glasgow's Miles Better campaign was taken as a model and Kelly, who was
Lord Provost when it was launched, was asked to outline the benefits it brought
to the city.
While in Lublin, he met Professor James Craig, who was helping organise the
seminar. Craig, a former member of the Islanders folk group, has been living in
Poland for 10 years.
Art show does
the business
SEVERAL weeks ago we told Business Diary readers of a Patrons &amp; Painters
Exhibition in The Smith Gallery being held to raise funds for the Prince's
Scottish Youth Business Trust as well as promoting up and coming artists.
We are pleased to report that it was a resounding success with #10,000 worth of
art being sold. We are told that among those who bought paintings were former
Euro MP, and strong supporter of the arts, Janey Buchan, and Scottish TV's Kaye
Adams.
The organiser, photographer John Rae, was delighted to be able to present a
cheque for #4500 to the PSYBT as a result. The cash will fund two new
businesses in Central Region.
Telling tales from
dizzy heights
LORD Weir was seen recently at the top of tall, rather ancient library steps in
the lower Signet Library in Edinburgh, but he was not searching for an antique
tome.
He was, in fact, giving a speech at a dinner to mark the retirement of Bob
Knox, senior maritime partner at Henderson Boyd Jackson.
It appears that in their student days the pair were climbing buddies, and the
industrialist was using the steps to demonstrate how they had scaled some dizzy
heights in their time.
Speaking easy
out in Beirut
ANN Murdoch of Speakeasy Scotland thought someone was pulling her leg when she
answered the phone in her home at Lower Largo and heard a voice saying: ``This
is Beirut calling.''
However, it turned out the caller wanted her to provide a speaker for a St
Andrew's night do in the Lebanese capital organised by the local Caledonian
Society.
This is the reason Bob Crampsey's dulcet tones were not heard over the airwaves
last Saturday coming from a Scottish football ground - he was entertaining
several hundred guests in Beirut's city hall.
Horsing around
the new houses
EDINBURGH is soon to receive its eleventh equestrian statue thanks to a deal
between Edinburgh District Council and Cala Homes Scotland.
The bronze statue will stand outside the company's Silvermills development in
Stockbridge as part of the Percent for Art scheme under which the developer
provides a public work of art.
Sculptor Eoghan Bridge, who specialises in horse subjects, has agreed to
include an eagle in his work at the special request of Cala Homes chairman Alan
Downie. ``I call our management team the Eagles,'' Downie explains, ``so you
could say this is a way of recognising their successes over the last few
years.''
Bridge has now created a quarter-size model of Horse, Rider, Eagle which will
stand 13ft high when finished next spring. Perhaps locals will dub it The Eagle
Has Landed when it appears on their landscape.
</TEXT>
