<HEADLINE>Off to another</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anne Johnstone</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979089</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Anne Johnstone finds a wealth of imagination in store for younger readers
in the latest stirring tales
CHRISTMAS came early this year to the Palmer family, thanks to The Herald.
Faced with the pleasantly festive task of choosing a selection of best books
for under-eights, we recruited the critical faculties of this family of small
bookworms who live at Carbeth near Glasgow: Jack, seven; Harriet, five;
Charlie, four; baby Lucy, and their mum, Debbie. They fell on the task with
enormous enthusiasm and, on your behalf, waded through more than 40 books in
three days. Here's our choice for each child.
Baby Lucy. Lucy's attention span is a bit limited just now, seeing as she's
barely two months old! But within a year she'll be a toddler spurning rattles
and mobiles and (if her siblings are anything to go by) already a budding print
addict. Debbie would be delighted if friends and relatives opt to give their
latest addition books instead of toys but when you've had four children you're
entitled to admit that lots of baby books are extremely tedious for mum. This
time Debbie is going on strike. ``Now they have to enchant me too. I'm tired of
boring baby books.''
Here is her selection for Lucy: What's Hiding Here (Dorling Kindersley Snap
Shot book, #2.99). ``We all loved this with its clear bright photographs,''
says Debbie. What's munching behind the leaf? What's stored in the toolbox?
Lift the flaps to find out. This is just the sort of thing to appeal to a
baby's natural curiosity. Playtime Rhymes by Sally Gardner (Orion, #10.99).
``I'm going straight out to get this. It's much more than a nursery rhyme book,
many of which are full of ditties you never hear these days. This one has
lovely illustrations and it includes all the rhymes our children encounter at
school and playgroup (for example Five Little Ducks and Three Little Monkeys).''
The Walker Baby Bear, 25 Stories for the Very Young (Walker Books, #9.99).
``Great value and lots of my favourite authors and illustrators are included,''
says Debbie, but she wasn't sure about the way whole books were crammed on to
one or two spreads. ``Toddlers love the excitement of turning the page to find
out what happens next.''
Stroke Henry by Rod Campbell (Campbell Books #4.50), a tough board book which
invites young readers to touch and feel different textures - a clean towel, a
shiny ball, and Henry the dog's tickly tummy.
Charlie (4): Charlie is a blond charmer with lots of energy and very definite
ideas about what he likes.
Maisy's House by Lucy Cousins (Walker Books, #12.99). Not so much a book, more
an amazing free-standing model of the mad mouse's house. ``This is my best
one,'' grins Charlie. A small book guides you through Maisy's day from the
first brush of the gnashers to the final goodnight. You create the action with
press-out models.
There It Is! by Richard Fowler (Campbell Books, #5.99). An I-Spy game in book
form. ``Boys seem to love these books. Because the pictures are so busy and
complex, it takes them ages to find things which is great for keeping them
quiet.'' says Debbie.
The Snow Lambs by Debi Gliori (Andre Deutsch, #9.99). This beautiful and
original book is based in Scotland, like its author. Sam, a farmer's son, loses
Bess his beloved sheepdog. The warm, golden farmhouse interior contrasts with
the grey icy night outside as Sam frets about Bess, but all ends happily.
The Cross Rabbit by Nick Butterworth (Collins, #4.99). Another gentle tale of
Percy the park keeper and his friends. Charlie says watch out for the sledging
mice.
Two Bears and Joe by Penelope Lively (Viking, #9.99). Another daydream book
with animal connections in the Lion in the Meadow mode. This one is brought to
life by Jan Ormerod's charming illustrations. ``I like those bears,'' says
Charlie.
Harriet (5) is very competent and independent for her age. Her often serious
expression hides an impish sense of fun. She reads well but still likes to be
read to.
The Sleeping Beauty by Phillida Gili (Transworld, #9.99). ``I loved this one
best and I took it to bed with me. It's a pop-up where wonderful things happen.
Look, the spinning wheel actually turns round,'' says Harriet.
An Edwardian Doll's House (HarperCollins, #12.99) is another piece of amazing
paper engineering. Climb the stairs, open the cupboards, even lift the loo
seat! But is it really a book?
The Jolly Pocket Postman (Heinemann, #10.99) by Janet and Allan Ahlberg. Anyone
else would have flogged this concept to death by now but in the hands of the
Ahlbergs (Janet sadly died this year), the Jolly Postman seems to ride on
forever. This time he flies, too, and even shrinks.
A Band of Joining-In Stories (Doubleday, #9.99). Pat Thomson is an anthologist
with an unerring eye for stories with child appeal. This latest volume with 11
stories offers unbeatable value.
Little Green Fingers by Mary Ann Van Hage (Macdonald Young Books, #8.99). An
attractive book with bright illustrations and easy-to-follow instructions for
the embryonic gardener. Harriet liked the idea of hyacinths in a basket
decorated with little pink and mauve stars. An attractive Christmas present she
could make on her own.
Jack (7) is a fluent and voracious reader of both fiction and non-fiction. He
loves poetry. His choice: Dinosaur (Viking, #8.99) in the World Unfolds series.
In this clever concept, there's a choice between reading it as a book or
unfolding it as a chart. It's wise not to underestimate the amount and level of
scientific information which a bright and well-motivated seven or
eight-year-old can absorb. This book doesn't.
Knights by John Howe (Tango Books, #12.99). A dragon rears itself from the page
and you get to find out what a medieval knight wore under his armour in this
clever and exciting pop-up.
Little Wolf's Book of Badness by Ian Whybrow (Collins, #9.99). ``In the morning
I didn't get dressed until I'd finished it,'' says Jack. The story is a zany
inversion in which Little Wolf is expelled from the lair to be made bad at
Uncle Bigbad's Cunning College. Rib-tickling pictures by the ubiquitous Tony
Ross.
Monster Poems, collected by John Foster (OUP, #3.99). Delightfully scary poems
on such universal themes as the teacher who mutates into a monster and the
monster behind the loo. Wickedly funny illustrations by Korky Paul.
Lassie Comes Home by Eric Knight (Hamish Hamilton, #10.99) may be a bit
sickeningly sentimental for mum but six and seven-year-olds like their slush
undiluted. Rosemary Wells' retelling of this classic tale of a collie's
hazardous lone journey across Scotland at the turn of the century, filled the
bill for Jack, especially Susan Jeffers's illustrations.
</TEXT>
