<DOCNO>GH951209-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Multitudes of Santas</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anne Johnstone</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979090</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHRISTMAS books don't make great Christmas presents because children want to
read them in the run up to December 25 rather than on the day itself.
Nevertheless, there's a gigantic market in them. Here are the ones the Palmer
children liked best.
The Story of Christmas (Dorling Kindersley, #7.99), ages four to seven. Anita
Ganeri's simple yet moving text and big bright photos of a rather up-market
school nativity make this book irresistible.
Maisie's Merry Christmas by Aileen Paterson (The Amaising Publishing House,
#3.50), ages four to eight, in which Maisie lands the starring role in
Cinderella in the Morningsaide panto. ``I enjoyed the jokes but felt most of
them went right over the children's heads,'' says Debbie Palmer. Only her
seven-year-old listened to the end. ``I liked the budgie best,'' he says.
The Christmas Miracle of Jonathan Toomey by Susan Wojciechowski (Walker Books,
#9.99), ages four to nine, is a strongly moralistic Christian tale with
fabulous illustrations by P J Lynch. ``It was the best sort of story because it
made me cry in the middle but it was happy at the end,'' says Jack.
Letters from Father Christmas by J R R Tolkien (Collins, #12.99), ages five
plus, uses Ahlberg-style pull-out letters in these facsimile extracts of
Tolkien's original letters written to his youngest son Christopher. Follow the
adventures of the naughty North Polar Bear and Ilbereth, the elf. ``We all
really loved this. It's the sort of book you would come back to again and
again,'' says Debbie.
A Message for Santa by Hiawyn Oram and Tony Ross (Andersen Press, #8.99), ages
three to eight. FC has an exchange of correspondence with Emily who likes
everything about Christmas except Santa coming down the chimney. ``A lot of
children share this fear, including one of ours, and I think this book tackles
the subject brilliantly,'' says Debbie. Santa proves most understanding. Well,
he would, wouldn't he? Hope he's good to you, too.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hollywood's family values</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON KERR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979091</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KEEP it in the family has long been one of Hollywood's mottos. In the silent
era, various sets of sisters arrived in Los Angeles to make their names in the
movies.
The Talmadge girls did well for themselves, at least in terms of who they
married: Norma's husband was studio chief Joseph Schenck, while her sister
Natalie married Schenck's biggest star - Buster Keaton. Constance Talmadge was
a featured player with D.W Griffith's company. It also employed Lillian and
Dorothy Gish, who had come to Hollywood for Lillian's role in Griffith's The
Birth of a Nation in 1914. Four years later they starred together in Hearts of
the World.
During the 1920s, the Barrymores - one of America's greatest and oldest acting
dynasties - first came to prominence. John, Ethel and Lionel came from theatre
and made their names - independently - in Hollywood. In 1932 they made their
one and only film together - Rasputin and the Empress.
While the Barrymores were hamming it up as the Russian royals, the mischievous
Marx Brothers were creating havoc in a string of comedies at Paramount Studios.
The four Marxes - Groucho, Harpo, Chico and Zeppo - all appeared in The
Cocoanuts (1930), Animal Crackers (1930), Monkey Business (1931), Horse
Feathers (1932) and Duck Soup (1933). Even more brothers, and a few sisters,
appeared in Mr Smith Goes to Washington in 1939. Bumbling governor Guy Kibbee's
young brood was played by the Watson children - Coy, Vivian, Gloria, Louise,
Harry, Billy, Delmar, Garry and Bobs.
Of all the Watson weans, Bobs was the only successful child actor (he also
appeared in Boys Town with Mickey Rooney and Spencer Tracy, and On Borrowed
Time, with the aforementioned Lionel Barrymore). In many cases in Hollywood
history, one sibling is a star, and the other(s) can merely revel in or rebel
against reflected glory, his/her own talent obscured by comparisons.
Eric Roberts (who topped the cast list of the well-received 1984 movie, The
Pope of Greenwich Village) may well have had starring roles long before anyone
had heard of Pretty Woman, but now he is only thought of as the brother of
Julia. They appeared together on film before Julia had hit the big time - in a
dire movie called Blood Red, in 1988.
Beau Bridges is in a similar predicament: his acting career may stretch back to
the 1940s, but baby brother Jeff is the one with the looks and the fan club
that goes with them. They acted together as children (their father is actor
Lloyd), but their most famous co-appearance was in The Fabulous Baker Boys with
Michelle Pfeiffer, in 1989.
One solution for siblings who don't wish to overshadow, or be overshadowed by,
one another is to avoid acting together and to change one of their surnames:
Shirley MacLaine and Warren Beatty have both had hugely successful careers
which were entirely independent of each other. Similarly, Joan Fontaine and
Olivia De Havilland never starred in the same movie: they kept their scenes for
the gossip columns which fed off their rivalry and bitchery. They, however,
were both true stars and Oscar winners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Christmas gift for homebuyers could lead to greater things</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Gillian Barton</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979092</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHRISTMAS has come early for homebuyers. Mortgage rates are down again - and
there's hope of further reductions if the Chancellor takes the hint. The UK's
largest lender, the Halifax, shaved 0.25% from its 7.99% at the end of last
week, meaning a new standard rate of 7.74%. That translates into a fall of
almost #9.50 a month in repayments on a #50,000 interest-only mortgage and just
over #7 for an ordinary repayment loan.
Many other societies and banks have followed suit - although the Royal Bank and
Bank of Scotland have yet to make a move - typically shaving the cost of a
standard mortgages by between 0.2% and 0.4%.
Any cut in repayments is welcomed by borrowers, of course, but the most
important effect of this latest round may be that it adds a bit more confidence
to the housing market. After a long, bleak period, culminating in this summer's
low point, there are tentative signs of a brighter future. New loans promised
to buyers in October, but not yet taken up, topped #4800m, the highest monthly
figure since last November.
Another sign that the worst may be over came in the latest statistics on house
prices. Figures from the Halifax show that although they rose by only 0.3%
during November, that was the fourth consecutive monthly increase.
``This small monthly rise is encouraging,'' the society says. ``It confirms our
view that house prices are no longer generally falling and remain more or less
stable. Any rises will depend on improvements in consumer confidence which
should occur as incomes are boosted by tax cuts in 1996.''
Mortgage lenders were disappointed Chancellor Kenneth Clarke failed to announce
any specific help for the housing market in the Budget. Many had been hoping
for the abolition of stamp duty which adds at least #600 to the cost of buying
a home valued at #60,000 or more. And some had been looking for alterations to
the mortgage tax relief system to provide a special boost for first-time buyers.
But in the absence of any specific aid, mortgage lenders have decided to strike
out alone. This is the second time in recent months they have cut rates without
the spur of a reduction in bank base rates. The last move downwards was in
September when Abbey National led the way with a 0.35% cut even though bank
rates had not budged.
That action by lenders didn't prompt a reduction in interest rates generally
but it looks like being more successful this time. Pressure is mounting on the
Government and the Bank of England to announce a cut sooner rather than later
to provide the boost to the economy lacking in the Budget.
As mortgage lenders have twice pre-empted the Government, they may not respond
with further reductions if the next fall in bank base rates is very small. Even
so, many lenders are looking for further cuts in home loan costs in the near
future and economists believe interest rates will remain low for the next two
years.
One result of all this is to make fixed-rate mortgages less attractive. Apart
from headline grabbing rates such as Bristol &amp; West's 0.95% one-year fix for
first-time buyers, longer term rates are pretty much in line with the new lower
variable rates. It looks more sensible, therefore, to opt for a loan that
offers an attractive discount on a variable rate so you will still benefit if
borrowing costs do go even lower.
Meanwhile, hopes that interest rates will revive the housing market could be
wide of the mark if Britain's house valuers are to be believed. A poll by
NatWest found they reckon that cutting rates is a less effective way of
restoring the health of the market than increasing mortgage relief or boosting
jobs - and they believe the changes to income support for mortgages taken out
since October 1 are having a worse effect than envisaged six months ago.
Optimism about the future course of house prices remains pretty high in
Scotland, however. Here 13% of valuers expect they will rise over the next
three months compared with just 2% in the rest of the UK. But there are growing
signs of a mismatch between supply and demand. Although the number of
properties coming on to the market is going up there are fewer buyers.
``Despite this, valuers here are much more optimistic than their southern
colleagues,'' says NatWest. A third of them, more than anywhere else and twice
the proportion for the UK as a whole, believe confidence has returned to the
property market overall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Myths, magic and mystery</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jennifer Cunningham</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979093</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF a certain modern princess had listened more carefully in the nursery, she
would have known that the wedding was the end of the fairytale and not the
beginning, and garnered a few useful hints about dealing with adversity.
So let's stop being sniffy about witches, wizards, fabulous beasts, tyrannical
kings and all-conquering heroes. They say, after all, there are only seven
stories and the rest are variations, reworkings and new settings.
Even would-be sophisticates can be charmed with an old-fashioned fairytale at
Christmas. A new selection of Hans Christian Andersen; edited, translated and
illustrated by Erik Blegvad, (Heinemann #12.99), offers a dozen of the prolific
Dane's 156 tales including well-loved favourites such as The Steadfast Tin
Soldier and The Emperor's New Clothes with some likely to be new.
Equally seasonally Scandinavian for young readers are Alf Proysen's Mrs
Pepperpot and Astrid Lindgren's Pippi Longstocking. Pippi Longstocking's
After-Christmas Party (Viking #8.99) is a merry account for newly-independent
readers of just what a good time children can organise for themselves without
meddlesome grown-ups. The ever-dafter adventures of Mrs Pepperpot who shrinks
to the size of her kitchen namesake for a series of strange adventures, and
wages continual battle for supremacy against her dour husband, are as
delightful as ever in the latest paperback collection. It deserves the modern
classics label bestowed by Puffin (#3.50).
Nearer home, Moira Miller's Hamish stories manage to be simultaneously couthy
and supernatural. It is an unlikely, but entertaining combination produced by a
modern Celtic version of ingenuity or courage outsmarting the Wee Folk as
Hamish, Mirren and Mither take on Grizelda Grimithistle and her ilk to avert a
series of domestic disasters from their croft at Camusbuie. Hamish and the Wee
Witch and Hamish and the Fairy Gifts, both with appealing line drawings by
Mairi Hedderwick (Canongate Kelpies #3.50) should be known to every bairn in
Scotland.
Garrison Keillor takes us bang into the commercial reality of television
advertising in Cat, You Better Come Home, a bittersweet fable for a modern age.
It is a gentle pastiche - a concoction of Aesop, Edward Lear and T S Eliot - on
the perils of greed in which a cat called Puff goes off in the huff to lead the
life of Riley, only to return the battered prodigal. This is a picture book for
the not-so-young, the paintings by Steve Johnson and Lou Fancher provide a
visual feast which will appeal to adults as much as children (Faber #9.99).
Paul Warren has created his own mythical world in Caleb Beldragon's Chronicle
of the Three Counties (Heinemann #9.99). It is a runic complexity with its own
history, geography, calendar and legal systems leading to the secret of the
Malbigon. Illustrated with maps and family trees to aid serious puzzle-solvers,
it took the graphic artist turned rock musician 10 years to complete and should
guarantee silence for several hours.
Old tales from many lands are gathered in The Golden Hoard (Orion #14.99), the
first of four volumes of myths and legends from around the world retold by
Geraldine McCaughrean, who has the gift of simplifying without losing the
imagery or characteristic voice of a story. The 22 collected here range from
Robin Hood to Greek, Roman, and Native American myths. They are matched with
similarly simple and colourful paintings by Bee Willey.
The age-old challenge of the tyrant father locking his beautiful daughters away
from the corruption of the outside world is reworked by Garry Kilworth in The
Bronte Girls (Mammoth #3.99). He explores the power struggles which go on
behind the facade of family life in a clever juxtaposition of life in the
Bronte family at Haworth Parsonage as lived out by their latter-day namesakes,
and life in a single-parent family. A fascinating and challenging tale for the
over-11s.
A perfectly-executed fairytale in modern dress is The Big Bazoohley by Peter
Carey (Faber #9.99). This is a tale of a child who saves the day by a
combination of endurance and a particular form of honesty. Full of beautiful
cameos of modern life and lightly salted with hilarity, I hope for more writing
for children from the creator of Oscar and Lucinda.
In a sequel which will delight her many fans, adults as well as children,
Theresa Breslin has brought Kezzie home to Clydeside. A variation on the theme
of exile, A Homecoming for Kezzie (Methuen #10.99) relates the wartime
adventures of the plucky heroine with a tenderness combined with historical
accuracy which will have hankies out throughout the land.
The enduring and delightful Indian (as in cowboys and) Little Bull, from Lynne
Reid Banks, has come out of the cupboard and on to the big screen. The Indian
in the Cupboard (Collins #3.99) has been republished to coincide with the film
version of the engrossing adventures which follow from young Omri's sudden
responsibility for a very demanding Indian Brave.
Probably the girls' equivalent in the tried and tested toys league is the
doll's house. In The Doll's House (Oxford University Press #5.99) Rachel
Anderson plaits three strands of past, present and social class around Number
Seven, the very special present for Miss Amy Winter's seventh birthday.
Cynics should be directed to Fatso in the Red Suit, (Faber #8.99) an all-too
realistic, but nevertheless entertaining collection of poems from Matthew
Sweeney.
Children, on the whole, still prefer to escape into the realm of fantasy - and
there's a bundle of politically-corrected Enid Blytons ranging from adventures
to school stories (Mammoth #2.99) for their stockings.
n Turn to pages 8 to 11 for the Herald writers'
Books of the Year
</TEXT>
