<HEADLINE>Newly able to offer gamut of software technology</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>trailblazers</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979095</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is only 20 months since the launch of Gamut Technologies. Yet as a leading
provider of client/server software technology in the UK, and sole Scottish
agent for Sybase (UK), this Glasgow-based company is already blazing a trail on
several fronts.
Gamut is the only firm in Scotland, says its business development director,
George Knox, which has taken world-class information technology and marketed it
specifically to local companies. (Sybase was founded in the US in 1984 and has
built a strong reputation for innovation, leadership and reliability in
client/server software services.)
It is also Europe's first recognised Sybase Education provider; it is the only
company to have undertaken thorough research into the Scottish information
technology market and, therefore, to have the understanding and capacity to
provide a range of consultancy and training services which focus exclusively on
the needs of local clients.
All this, and a turnover of #1.2m in the first year (which is expected to rise
to #2.4m in the second), has been achieved without resort to loans, overdrafts
or grants.
Knox and customer services director Nick Archer gained years of computer
experience with a large US-based international software company. As Scots, they
saw that their homeland was being poorly served by suppliers of information
technology.
Invariably it was an English software company, or an international one with an
English base, which sold systems here. The inevitable consequences were less
understanding of particular Scottish problems, poor training and skills
transfer, and a second-rate technical support service.
Knox and Archer decided to change this. They put together a business plan and,
as a result of participating in a Glasgow Enterprise Business Venture
Programme, were joined by Jim Hall, who became legal and financial director.
Gamut Technologies was formed in March 1994, its only capital the directors'
savings.
From the beginning they knew what they were doing. By getting exclusive UK
agency for Sybase - the first company to deliver technology powerful enough for
on-line, mission-critical applications, and now a $1000m concern which
distributes over a wide area network - Gamut had the capacity to deliver real
performance improvements for its customers. The directors were also aware of
the importance of providing good customer support.
Gamut focused on the top 200 Scottish companies; the bigger the organisation,
the greater the need for change to enable them to remain competitive, and the
greater the need for comprehensive training and support to accompany the new
technology. With Sybase, which Knox claims is a uniquely flexible system, it
was able to provide the optimum capability to its customers.
It has employed staff of the highest calibre. Their commitment to the very best
professional training and customer support ensures that, with the installation
of new IT systems, the scope for improvements in management systems and
business processes is maximised.
With a client list that already includes such big names as the Bank of
Scotland, the Royal Bank, Standard Life, General Accident, AT Mays and Harper
Collins, Gamut is ready to be a major player in the Scottish business community.
The award and entry
The scheme is a joint initiative of The Herald and Ernst &amp; Young, business and
financial advisers, to recognise organisations which demonstrate innovation and
ingenuity in their operations and procedures. Forms can be obtained by sending
in the coupon below.
Entries should be based on one or a combination of:
innovation/ingenuity
business performance
product/service quality
management calibre
marketing flair
contribution to the local/Scottish economy
Rewards
The monthly winner will be presented with an award certificate and will be
featured in an article. The overall TrailBlazer of the Year will send a company
specialist on an agreed specialist management training course at the renowned
Harvard Business School.
</TEXT>
