<TEXT>
Antique doll
fetches #1900
A RARE antique doll sold for nearly double its expected price at an auction
organised by Phillips in Edinburgh yesterday.
The small Jumeau doll, valued at between #800 and #1200, went for #1905 at a
sale of dolls, teddy bears, and collector's items. The doll, dressed in its
original muslin French-style dress, was made in Paris in 1880.
Citadel award
A SCHEME to redevelop the derelict Citadel site in Ayr received the Patrick
Geddes planning award yesterday. The project includes a swimming pool, shops,
and housing. The award, from the Saltire Society and the Patrick Geddes Trust,
was presented to architects Pankaj Patel and Andrew Taylor, and the project's
joint promoters, Kyle and Carrick District Council and Enterprise Ayrshire.
House siege
ARMED police surrounded a house in Merlinford Drive, Renfrew, for two hours
yesterday after reports that an occupant was threatening to fire a shotgun.
Police said a man had been taken into custody.
No to clinic
AN APPLICATION to open a body therapy clinic at 42 Caledonian Crescent, in the
Dalry area of Edinburgh, was refused by the district licensing committee
yesterday.
Baseball theft
A YOUTH yesterday admitted stealing 22 baseball bats from a sports store at
Charleston Academy, Inverness. Sentence was deferred until December 28 on Jody
Donald, 18, of Assynt Road, Inverness.
Death bid charge
GLASGOW man Billy Thompson, 29, of Provanmill Road, Glasgow, was remanded in
custody at Glasgow Sheriff Court yesterday on a charge of attempted murder. He
is accused of shooting Mr Scott Phin, 27, in the groin outside his home in
Barmulloch, Glasgow, on Thursday night.
Pottery raid
A #15,000 collection of Wemyss Ware pottery has been stolen from a country
house on the Kirkton of Mailor road, near Perth. The owners have offered a
four-figure reward for information leading to its recovery.
Euro warning
TAYSIDE Regional Council's trading standards department yesterday warned
businesses to think twice before signing contracts with companies which offer
to help them get grants from the European Union. It said that, in most cases,
small businesses would be paying for these services, regardless of whether or
not they actually received any grants.
</TEXT>
