<HEADLINE>Forsyth wields tartan tax taunt in Scottish counter-attack<#LIN+ E> Blair bids to wreck Tory `lie machine'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979097</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR leader Tony Blair last night claimed the Conservatives had retreated
from the business of Government into a dirty campaign of lies and propaganda
which showed they were now ``training for Opposition.''
He told a party fund-raising dinner in Glasgow that Ministers no longer ran
departments but managed propaganda at the public's expense. ``It is our task to
rebut their lies, counter their propaganda and put with conviction the new
Labour agenda with a clarity and force that overwhelm the lie machine.''
It was the culmination of a day which had seen Mr Blair enter the lion's den in
Edinburgh to address the city's Chamber of Commerce and Enterprise on his plans
for a Scottish parliament with the power to raise or lower income tax by 3p.
In a counter move there was the release of no fewer than six Scottish
Conservative speeches castigating New Labour and his plans for a ``New Union''
outlined in an exclusive interview yesterday in The Herald.
The Labour hierarchy was suggesting yesterday that in the interview the
suggestion that the party would not use the power to raise income tax in the
first Scottish parliament was ``misconstrued,'' but Mr Blair's own remarks made
it clear that this was the thrust of his preferred approach to seeing off Mr
Forsyth's onslaught on what he has dubbed the ``tartan tax.''
There were immediate expressions of unease from Labour's Liberal Democrat
partners in the Scottish Constitutional Convention, while the SNP claimed that
having come to Scotland to clear the air, Mr Blair had succeeded only in
muddying the water.
Accusing Mr Blair of dictating policy to his own party in Scotland, SNP leader
Alex Salmond said he was proposing ``a pushover, not a parliament, which would
be even more firmly under Westminster's thumb than a local council.''
But the main attack came from the Conservatives. The president of the Board of
Trade, Mr Ian Lang, told constituency workers in Galloway that a Labour
Government would trigger a ``dramatic exodus'' of private investment from
Britain.
Dumfries MP Sir Hector Monro, party vice-chairwoman Annabel Goldie, and
Scottish Office Ministers Raymond Robertson and Lord James Douglas-Hamilton all
queued up to attack Mr Blair.
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth led the charge, highlighting yesterday's
Herald interview in which the Labour leader indicated that his party would not
seek to utilise the tax power in the first term. ``Not since Napoleon's retreat
from Moscow have we seen such a shambles,'' said Mr Forsyth.
``Mr Blair realises that the tartan tax would be immensely damaging to Scotland
- that is why he is wriggling. The ruthlessness with which he has left his
colleagues in the constitutional convention swinging in the wind is wonderful
to behold.''
But Mr Blair said last night that Mr Forsyth was at the wheel of the Tory lie
machine
in Scotland, not so much a Scottish Secretary as a party propagandist. ``Nobody
voted for 20 new Tory taxes in 1992 but they got them just the same,'' he said.
``They lied about their own tax plans then. They are lying about our tax plans
now.''
He said ``the Tory lie machine has moved up a gear as an election nears, but we
have seen nothing yet. They will smear, as they always do, and lie and cheat
and spend vast sums on untruthful propaganda.''
He cited recent examples, including one where party chairman Dr Brian
Mawhinney's own press officer conducted briefings on a sensistive immigration
case, the smears about the school opt-out ballot in his own constituency, and
the ``disgraceful whispering campaign'' to undermine the Speaker of the Commons.
He described this process as: ``A few anonymous quotations in the tabloids. The
broadsheets pick it up. A briefing appears that MPs, including Dr Mawhinney's
parliamentary aid, are monitoring the Speaker for signs of bias. This is an
absolute disgreace, but all in keeping with what is happening.''
However, Mr Forsyth kept up the pressure on the taxation issue. ``An alcoholic
asking for the keys of an off licence on the basis of a promise that he would
not take a drink would have more credibility with the Scottish people than Mr
Blair and his pathetic assertion that he would create a power to raise a tartan
tax but that it might not be used and that we must await a manifesto to find
out.''
Benedict Brogan writes: Meanwhile, Deputy Prime Minister Michael Heseltine
accused Mr Blair of showing a lack of leadership over the tartan tax. The
Labour leader's devolution plans had ``come unstuck,'' he said.
``My hearts go out to the Scots after Mr Blair's latest fudging on whether or
not his Scottish parliament would raise a tartan tax. Within a few hours he
appeared to change his tune - and then changed it back again - because he
realises that the tartan tax is electoral suicide,'' he said.
``Whenever he is called on to show leadership, as those in Government must do
every day, he falters, caught between the devil and the deep blue sea. His
strategy is simple: if he is asked a difficult question, just smile and utter
soothing words. It's when he's forced to make hard decisions that his options
run out.''
</TEXT>
