<HEADLINE>Suspended sentence for ship's captain as court says council officials were inebriated Blame shared in Belarus deaths</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979098</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE captain of a cruise ship involved in the deaths of two Aberdeen City
Council officials has been given a three-year suspended jail sentence for
breaching regulations.
However the court in Gomel, Aberdeen's twin city in the former Soviet Union,
heard that the two Aberdeen officials ``were in a state of inebriation''.
Their own infringement of safety regulations, in addition to the infringement
of the Belarus Department of Transport's regulations by Captain Oleg Gavrilyuk,
is said to have cost the officials their lives.
Deputy chief executive Ann Hughes, 44, and principal environmental health
officer Iain McDonald, 36, were part of a delegation of 41 who flew to Gomel in
June.
They were in a team looking at ways of helping Gomel, which is the area worst
affected by the Chernobyl disaster. They died on June 7 at the end of a rest
day spent cruising on the River Sozh.
Last night a spokeswoman for Aberdeen solicitors Paul and Williamsons said on
behalf of Mr McDonald's widow that they believed the suggestion they were
inebriated to be totally untrue and that they had witnesses to say they were
not in that state.
Yesterday's report, in a Gomel morning newspaper, said that the delegation were
taken by representatives of the city executive committee on the excursion to
the district of Proletarski Luk.
The sun had already started to go down but people decided to cool off in the
river ``and two of them - a man and a woman - jumped into the water''.
The report reiterated what was described by other council officials on their
return: that the remainder of the party stayed on shore as the hosts prepared
dinner on the beach.
It was when the barbecue was ready and the two could not be found that a search
for them started.
``They called out to them over and over again and searched, but to no avail.
The sad news only became clear after several days,'' the newspaper Reklamnoe
Prilozhenie reported.
The article said that a lengthy inquiry had established that after Captain
Gavrilyuk berthed the Burevestnik she started to drift away from the shore. He
attempted to start the engine unsuccessfully and spent 10 or 15 minutes in the
engine room to repair it.
``It must be pointed out that Oleg was on his own on the trip without any crew,
which is an infringement of the regulations laid down by the Ministry of
Transport,'' the article said.
``In this way all responsibility for the safety of passengers while the vessel
is in motion or stationary was laid on the shoulders of the captain.
``Without checking whether the sides of the boat were clear he started the
engine and the propellers started dragging the Scots - who were in an
inebriated state and had swum very close to the boat - into the mechanism of
the boat.
``Their own infringement of swimming safety rules and the infringement of the
traffic regulations by the captain cost the Scottish people their lives.
``Taking into account all these circumstances and taking into consideration the
good work record of Captain Oleg Gavrilyuk, the court gave him a three-year
suspended sentence.''
Last night the spokeswoman for Mrs McDonald's solicitors said that she had
spoken to Mrs McDonald and she was obviously very upset at the suggestions. Her
understanding was that her husband and Ann Hughes were not swimming together
and that her husband had drowned while trying to save his colleague.
She said it was completely wrong to suggest that they had been in a drunken
state and it was ``offensive and insulting to the memory of her husband''.
The spokeswoman declined to reveal whether Mrs McDonald had raised any civil
actions in relation to her husband's death. No-one for Aberdeen District
Council was available for comment.
</TEXT>
