<HEADLINE>BSE scare cattle are locked up</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979099</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COWS at the centre of a BSE scare were locked up at a secret location in
Lanarkshire last night.
The six cows were seized by Strathclyde Trading Standards officers as the
animals were being taken to an abattoir for slaughter.
The officers are becoming increasing involved in hunts for BSE-infected
animals. It is alleged the beasts were declared free of BSE at an auction in
Lanark on Monday.
However, Trading Standards officers were alerted when different cows to those
cleared were presented at the abattoir, it is claimed.
Suspicions were raised when ear tags on the beasts were allegedly found to be
different when they arrived for slaughter.
Last night, Mr Stuart Graham, Strathclyde Trading Standards principal officer,
refused to go into details about the Lanarkshire case.
However, he did reveal that any such investigation would take at least four
days because of the amount of back-tracking required to check the history of
where the animals were kept and their owners.
``Our role is to make sure there is no false description,'' he said.
The inquiry comes after it emerged that six Scottish farmers are under
investigation in a separate case. It is alleged they completed forms claiming
cows had been reared in an environment free from any case of BSE for six years.
</TEXT>
