<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gesture transformed into ritualScottish Chamber Orchestra, City Hall, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979100</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Gesture transformed into ritual
DESPITE the wee identification tag at the top of this review, last night's
concert by the Scottish Chamber Orchestra was more than music, as it included
dance. But then, inexpert though I may be in the technicalities of the latter
form, I suspect that it was more than dance too.
And before my words start going round in circles, I'd better explain that last
night the SCO launched the first of the Glasgow Commissions, a two-year series
of collaborative projects, promoted by the orchestra and Glasgow District
Council's department of performing arts, that will bring four composers
together with artists of different disciplines. No-one can predict what will
result: two distinct works, a joint effort, something less - or more - than
both of them together . . . anything goes.
Inverness-born Alasdair Nicolson and choreographer/ dancer Laurie Booth
launched the series last night with The Last Meeting, drawn (loosely) from
Greek legend and the final meeting of Orpheus and Eurydice. The orchestra, with
strings divided antiphonally, and wind and percussion ranged across the back of
the stage, defined the space.
And that was the first parameter. Laurie Booth, dancing alone (with two canes
as minimal props) operated within a very limited space. To a highly expressive
score (more of which anon) a concentrated dance unfolded. Perhaps because of
the limitations of area, Booth's entire body seemed focused into precise and
significant movement - literally from neck to knee, from finger to toe.
It wasn't narrative, it wasn't descriptive. It was gesture transformed into
ritual. Stylistically, it was extraordinary in that - to an untrained eye - it
seemed to encompass a range of expressive movement drawn from a huge historical
sweep. It contained the exactness of mime, the elasticity of contemporary
gymnastics, the explosiveness of acrobatics, the slowness and deliberateness of
Japanese Noh theatre, absolute stillness, the exquisite poise and balance of
martial arts, and - almost continuously - the intricate wrist, hand, and finger
ballet of the East.
To complement this captivating, fluid movement, Nicolson has produced one of
his finest scores, stunningly atmospheric, with plaintive horn calls simulating
(if you want narrative style) the lovers, evocative, heaving sighs on the
orchestra, distinctly oriental timbres, and a wild and warlike dance that -
without breaking the ritual mode - suggested an almost sacrificial, pagan-like
quality to the music.
Not conventionally dramatic (and therefore a match for Booth's choreography)
Nicolson's music for The Last Meeting seemed - on first encounter - more
intensely concentrated, more clearly focused, and almost more purposeful than
much of his music that I've heard to date. However much the two artists might
have intended an audience to focus on the narrative factor, each element -
dance and music - was in itself so assured in its execution, that they could be
taken together without further reference. Perhaps it is the case that new
contexts bring more out of folk; if so, then that is what this project is all
about.
Ivor Bolton conducted a brilliant performance by the SCO, the first of several
last night, including a gorgeous account of Bach's most ravishing cantata,
Weichet Nur, with pellucid singing from soprano Nancy Argenta and cool, sensual
oboe playing from Robin Williams, which was followed by a stunning,
quasi-period style performance - lean and clean - of Telemann's highly
imaginative Water Music, with the SCO strings and wind in their most boisterous
and virtuosic form. Fascinating concert; same show tonight at the Queen's Hall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
