<HEADLINE>It's all change to the new #2 in your pocket</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979101</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE #1 coin is to get a big brother, the #2 coin. The innovation, however, will
not jeopardise the family of 40 million #1 notes, currently issued by the Royal
Bank of Scotland.
The final design has not been decided but the #2 which will be issued in 1997
will be a two-tone Continental-style coin, with a silver centre and a yellow
outer ring. Not to be outdone, the Royal is planning its own innovation in the
same year with a commemorative #1 note to mark the 150th anniversary of the
birth in Edinburgh of Alexander Graham Bell.
The Royal Mint will issue the #2 coin as well as a slimmed down 50p piece
towards the end of 1997, Chancellor Kenneth Clarke said yesterday in a Commons
written reply.
The decision to introduce the coins follows a lengthy consultation exercise on
the future of the country's small change involving the public and 1000
different organisations, including banks, the retailing and vending industries,
the blind, and the elderly.
The #2 coin will be bigger and heavier than the #1 coin but lighter than two #1
coins. The idea of a #2 note was rejected because it would cost too much and
not last long enough.
However, the Royal Bank of Scotland, the only bank on mainland Britain with #1
notes still in circulation, said the announcement would not lead it to change
its policy.
A spokesman said: ``There is still a significant desire for the #1 note in
Scotland. We have about 40 million #1 notes in circulation and are happy to
continue with them. What does worry us is the quality of the notes which get in
a very bad condition when they rub up against change. A #2 note is not
impossible but we have no plans for one.''
The spokesman was unable to draw a comparison between the cost of notes and
coins because while they produced notes, coins were produced by the Royal Mint
and they had no figures for their costs.
The Alexander Graham Bell commemorative #1 note will be issued in March 1997.
The Royal has already produced Britain's only other commemorative banknotes:
for the 1992 Edinburgh Summit and the centenary of Robert Louis Stevenson's
death.
The new 50p piece will be a smaller and lighter version of the existing - and
unpopular - seven-sided coin introduced in 1969. The modifications will bring
the 50p coin into line with the 5p and 10p pieces, both of which have been made
smaller and lighter in recent years.
Until now, #2 coins have been minted only to mark special occasions such as the
1986 Edinburgh Commonwealth Games, the 300th birthday of the Bank of England in
1994, and the 50th anniversary of the end of the Second World War.
The new coin will be the first new denomination to go into general circulation
since 1983. It will bear the Queen's head on the front, while the design for
the reverse will be selected by the Royal Mint Advisory Committee, which is
headed by the Duke of Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A cinema fairy story</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979102</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
William Russell describes the life and times of Edward Burns, the answer to all
those people who wonder whatever happened to the British film industry
A 15-city tour in 16 days giving 12 interviews a day - who said an actor's life
was easy? - is what Edward Burns had to survive when he was sent out to
publicise his first film, The Brothers McMullen. But then he had more of an
interest in its success than most actors since he was also the writer and
director.
Made at weekends over an eight-month period for an outlay of $25,000, he sent
it to the 1993 Sundance Festival as a ``calling card,'' hoping if it was well
received to get money to make a second film. In the event he walked off with
the Grand Jury Prize and at 25 the career of his dreams had turned into reality.
Now 27, the gangling New Yorker, in London to promote the film all over again,
said it was difficult returning to it because since then he had made his second
film, She's The One - on a slightly larger budget of $3m. ``The fact that the
Brothers was taken up for distribution for 20th Century Fox and has done
everything that it has is the icing on the cake,'' he said. ``Two weeks after
Sundance I had the money to make my second film.''
The fairy story does not end there, because having finished She's The One last
month, he is now about to start work on his third feature. His story is the
answer to all those people who wonder whatever happened to the British film
industry. You don't need lottery money. You need luck, dedication, and nerves
of steel.
Born in Queens, raised on Long Island, he discovered screen writing while a
student at Oneonta College, Albany, and realised this was what he wanted to do.
He had, until then, thought he might be the next great American novelist. His
father, a retired New York policeman, had given him a book about screen writing
to read and, having realised this was it, he transferred to a college with a
film department, started to write screenplays, and earned his living by working
in television.
The Brothers is about three Irish Catholic New Yorkers, whose abusive father
has died. At his funeral their mother announces she is off to live in Ireland
with the man she really loved, a decision which forces the trio to face up to
the problems in their own lives. The oldest son is happily married, but tempted
into an affair, the middle one, played by Burns, is a womaniser who cannot
commit himself to a relationship, and the youngest, devoutly Catholic, is
deeply inhibited.
Burns said he had made it because he was not seeing films which bore any
relation to the people he knew. The only one he had seen about Irish Americans,
State of Grace, was about West Side gangs and had nothing to do with his
lifestyle. He and his friends spent their time trying to hold down a job to pay
the rent, attempting to make relationships work and coping with being Catholics.
``I chose comedy because I did not want to get up on a soap box and preach,''
he said. ``If you can make your point, and make people laugh, it is a far more
effective way of getting your message across than beating them over the head,''
he said.
``We got the film in the can for $25,000 because the entire cast worked for
deferred pay and we also deferred $100,000 of costs to the film lab. At the end
of the day it probably cost $420,000, but the nice thing is, that after we sold
it to Fox, all those people got paid. And the actors have gone on to other
acting jobs. They have quit waiting on tables and working in dry cleaners. The
film has been good for everyone.''
Faced with constant rejection by Hollywood, he was told by his father that he
would just have to make it on his own, and he would find the money. He came up
with $15,000 and then another $10,000 and Burns started work. Since his father
was a retired cop it was not just a question of his writing a cheque out, and
the money had come in instalments.
``It is a catch-22 situation with scripts you send to Hollywood,'' he added.
``You cannot get anyone to read them unless you have an agent, and you must
have sold one to get an agent. They did not want to take a gamble one me.''
His second film, also set in New York's Irish community, is about a father who
insists his sons go fishing with him each weekend, and on giving them unwanted
and useless advice about how to run their lives while ignoring the fact his own
is a mess. He hopes it, too, will be funny - and say something about being
Catholic.
As for the future, he is what he wanted to be - a film maker. But not in
Hollywood. He intends to remain in New York. ``I have plenty to write about,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
