<DOCNO>GH951209-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shoe firm collapse puts 200 out of work</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979103</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO hundred shoe factory workers have lost their jobs.
The employees of the Kilmarnock Shoe Company in Ayrshire still do not know if
they will receive their back pay in time for Christmas.
The receivers were called into the plant yesterday after the firm collapsed
with debts of #1.5m.
Mr Richard Rendle, of receivers Baker Tilly, said: ``We will be trying to sell
the business as a going concern in the near future.''
The Kilmarnock MP, Mr Willie McKelvey, said that if a buyer could be found
within the next 10 to 12 days some of the jobs could be saved.
Mr John Blaney, the Strathclyde regional councillor for Kilmarnock, said:
``This is another disaster for the town. They were a large and long-standing
employer.''
</TEXT>
