<DOCNO>GH951209-000030</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000030</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NEWS DIGEST</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979104</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Missing man
CONCERN is growing for an 85-year-old man who went missing from his home in
Menzieshill Road, Dundee, on Thursday. Police appealed for anyone who may have
seen Mr Hugh McNabb to contact them. Mr McNabb is 5ft 4in and was wearing a
brown anorak, brown trousers, and brown shoes.
Sports hall boost
A #2.1m project to create a major new sports centre at Oban's swimming pool has
moved closer with confirmation of a #150,000-plus package from the area's local
enterprise company, Argyll and the Islands Enterprise.
Power repairs
HYDROELECTRIC will spend #6.5m next year repairing and replacing overhead
lines. Another #8.2m will be spent on upgrading supply in a number of
communities in the Grampian area.
Pottery raid
A #15,000 collection of Wemyss Ware pottery has been stolen from a country
house on the Kirkton of Mailor road, near Perth. The owners have offered a
four-figure reward for information leading to its recovery.
Hopes rise for
Creagan bridge
HOPES have been raised again that a bridge will be built over Loch Creran,
cutting miles off the journey between Oban and Fort William.
Lorn Councillor Campbell Cameron, who has had a letter from Scottish Roads
Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton, said: ``Lord James has now confirmed in
writing that the Creagan bridge scheme will be reassessed after this year's
public expenditure survey and prior to next year's annual statement on trunk
roads construction.''
Open lectures
DUNDEE University opens its doors to the public for a series of five Christmas
lectures next Tuesday. The subjects are architecture, medicine, conservation,
the nation state, and careers.
</TEXT>
