<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Marcella Evaristi</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979105</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ERIC Cullen was in his last year of college when he took part in a pilot
(``Season's Greet'') for what was to become the massively successful Rab C
Nesbitt series, in which he played wee Burnie ``the child from hell''. Instant
fame, street recognition; a life was turned around in the signing of a
contract. Cullen talked of the soaring self-esteem and satisfaction which came
with the transformation from the unknown ``wee man'' of four feet four, to
famous character actor. It was interesting that he described the career break
as a ``child's dream come true'' and though I think he was partly talking of
the character's anarchism, his description betrayed a kind of ambivalence as to
his own adult status.
Since he was 13 years old (and looking about eight) Cullen was systematically
sexually abused by a relative, who also set him up for abuse by other men -
until his late twenties. Two years ago, this uncle from a non-fictional hell,
left pornographic material at Cullen's flat. Cullen willingly showed the police
the material, the information was leaked to the press, and the nightmare began;
sections of the press bayed ``monster'', the contract dissolved and Cullen was
in Barlinnie.
Supportive friends saw him through the appeal process which eventually led to
the sentence being quashed, but there was the breakdown, the hospitalisation,
and the attempted suicide to surmount.
Despite the intense and harrowing trauma made into seedy tabloid fodder, Cullen
states that ultimately the experience has led to his release from the misery
perpetrated by blackmailing tormentors, against two of whom he is now seeking
prosecutions. But while the story itself was important, and worth attending to,
I did have a sense of a lost opportunity here.
Cullen's language was generalised, his parallels unrevealing. The press, he
said, acted ``as if he had started the First World War'' - there was,
ultimately, little that was really telling, or specific in his account.
Television work was enjoyable because, like beauty contestants, he ``enjoyed
meeting people''. It could be argued that after your life has been ripped to
pieces by sex-and-perversion headlines, the retreat into the commonplace
expression is an understandable response. But John Fergusson, who was doing the
interviewing on Radio Scotland's Sudden Change, could perhaps have facilitated
a more personalised candour. I don't know who to blame for the snatches of
guitar chords punctuating the programme but they were naff beyond belief.
When Charles Kennedy interviews he is confident and bright enough to ask the
light-hearted question; he happily articulates his presuppositions about his
interviewee, which elicits an energetic response activated into replacing the
questioner's guess with the subject's self-revelation. It's a strategy which
works well. In Kennedy in Conversation (also from Radio Scotland) this week he
was talking to Sir Clive Sinclair, entrepreneurial inventor and chairman of
Mensa.
With the true extent of car pollution being hushed up and the number of asthma
cases rising dramatically, Sinclair sensibly argued for a Park and Ride policy
which would improve our cities, without putting car-dependent rural communities
at risk.
Having invented the pocket calculator which was bad news for slide-rule
sellers, Sinclair carries a slide-rule with him all the time (``it doesn't need
a battery'') and far from being a gadget-freak, his phone is immobile, and at
his weekly poker game he delights in the fact that his friends with personal
organisers take five times as long as those with diaries to organise the next
session. He is the amused recipient of letters from ``nut-cases'' who have this
idea for a car with a propellor on its roof which would need no other fuelling
- being rather non-techno I can't recall why it wouldn't work - but his
argument convinced me.
Kennedy suggested that they might get some takers at certain Lib-Dem fringe
meetings . . .
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Consumer confidence could settle debate over `mad cow disease'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979106</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCIENTISTS, meat producers, and politicians have all had their say in the BSE
debate. Now, in the past week, consumers have begun to make their views known.
Two days ago, it was announced that UK beef sales for November had dropped 5%
on the same month last year.
Yesterday, Scotland's largest meat producers and auction company predicted beef
prices would drop again next week in what was described as ``almost a crisis
situation''.
Two factors sparked the controversy. Last month, a World in Action documentary
claimed 600 BSE infected cows were being eaten each week in the UK. Shortly
afterwards, neuropathologist Sir Bernard Tomlinson added to fears about ``mad
cow disease'' by claiming humans could be at risk.
Glasgow shoppers yesterday said the media coverage in general had shaped their
views on BSE and its alleged human equivalent Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD).
In Partick, catering assistant Donna Bruce, 29, was worried enough to plan a
meeting with her young son's teachers.
``I'd rather it wasn't served in schools just in case there's a risk,'' she
said. ``But I don't buy much processed red meat anyway so it doesn't affect
what I buy at the shops.''
Mother-of-two Tina Thorburn, 28, said: ``My husband hasn't eaten beef for
weeks. He used to eat it all the time but now wants us to stop eating it as
well. He thinks the Government is covering up the whole thing. We should be
told what is happening,'' she said.
Student Garry Brown, 20, of Kelvingrove, said his trolley was packed with
sausages, hamburgers, and pies. ``I follow the news but it won't affect what
food I buy. So few people have actually been affected that it all seems to be a
bit of worry over nothing.''
Mr Neil Rafferty, of Hyndland, echoed that opinion. ``I won't stop eating red
meat products unless they start putting human beings in them.''
Ms Elizabeth Kilpatrick, of Thornwood, said: ``I'm not particularly worried.
There are so many different opinions about it. One expert says one thing and
another says the opposite. I'll just carry on doing my normal shopping.''
South Side supermaket shoppers were generally more suspicious. Pensioner Sarah
Clyne, of Eastwood, said: ``I think it is having an affect because the prices
are going down. Personally, I don't think I can risk eating it because there's
been so much about it in the newspapers and television.''
Her friend, Mary Rae, said: ``I like red meat so I never give it a thought.''
Mother-of-three Marina McCarter, 30, of Newlands, said: ``I didn't buy any
sausages today and that was because I saw a TV documentary which made me think
about it.''
Husband and wife John and Annabel Wright said it would be more of a concern if
they had younger children.
Mr Alistair Donaldson, Scottish general manager of the Meat and Livestock
Commission, said he was not surprised at the mixed public reaction and sales
downturn.
``That was a reflection of the concerns the public obviously have, which
emphasises the need for proper reassurances that beef is safe.''
Mr Eddie Gillanders, marketing executive for Inverurie-based ANM Group,
Scotland's largest red meat supplier and auction company, said the price of an
#830 carcass was expected to fall by up to #50 (16p a kilo) next week, three
times the price drop for the previous week and five times a ``normal'' fall.
He said: ``It is very unusual to have such a large drop which almost amounts to
a crisis situation. It is worrying but the reaction you have obtained is mildly
encouraging because people still seem to have the confidence to continue buying
meat.''
Mr John Scott, president of the Scottish Association of Meat Wholesalers, said
the issue of BSE would be on the agenda at a monthly meeting of the
organisation in Perth today. However, he added: ``The problem isn't convincing
each other, it's getting the message across to the public.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Woman was `like a rag doll'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979107</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SECRETARY was like a ``rag doll'' minutes after meeting the man accused of
drugging and murdering her.
A waitress told yesterday how Mr Richard Karling, 43, bought two cups of coffee
and a fresh orange shortly before Miss Dorothy Niven, 33, arrived at the
Pancake Place in Union Street, Glasgow.
The waitress, Miss Patricia Lambert, 31, told the High Court in Glasgow, that
Miss Niven looked fit and well when she joined Mr Karling at his table.
Minutes later, she became unwell and sat with her elbows on the table holding
her head in her hands.
Miss Lambert told Mr William Totten, prosecuting: ``She was like a rag doll.
You could have done anything with her.''
Mr Karling, of Bellview Crescent, Ayr, denies that on June 27 last he
administered Temazepam to Miss Niven in the Pancake Place.
He further denies taking her in a taxi to her home at Silvan Place, Busby,
Renfrewshire, forcing her face into a pillow, and murdering her.
Mr Karling has lodged special defences of incrimination alleging a former
fiance, Mr William Lynch, murdered Miss Niven, and also of alibi.
Questioned by Mr Totten, Miss Lambert said there was no sign that Miss Niven
was sweating or that her eyes were bloodshot when she arrived.
Earlier, the court heard how para-medics were called to her home the following
afternoon.
Mr Karling, who had let them into the house, asked them: ``Is she away? Is she
dead?''
The trial, before Lord Johnston, continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
