<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BT Scottish Ensemble, RSAMD, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Conrad Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979109</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PLACE works by Bach and Shostakovich together in the same concert, and the
chances are they will interlock. Do it twice over, and the programme structure
should be all the firmer. In such company, Vaughan Williams last night could
have seemed an uninvited guest.
But there was a connection in the person of the award-winning young oboist,
Daniel Bates, who brought to the English composer's airy Concerto for Oboe and
Strings the same sort of serenity he bestowed on Bach's Double Concerto in D
minor with Clio Gould as his violinist partner. As a result, the provincial
intruder proved not so out of place after all, and his dancing rhythms,
alongside Bach's, brought their own rustic integrity to the evening.
Rusticity, however, was not what Shostakovich's Two Pieces for String Octet, Op
11, were about, any more than was his Eighth String Quartet in its richer-toned
arrangement for string orchestra. Here, with a brilliance of attack that did
nothing to conceal the music's underlying bleakness, the BT Scottish Ensemble
made as strong a case for the inflated version of the quartet as one is likely
to encounter.
Indeed, hearing it in the same concert as the pieces for octet made it sound
all the more convincing. As for the tensions of the latter spiky little
fragments, in which ideas were tossed nervily from one pair of players to
another, they seemed filled with portents of Shostakovich's darker, later
style. A robust, firm-limbed account of Bach's A minor Violin Concerto, with
Clio Gould as soloist, opened the programme.
</TEXT>
