<DOCNO>GH951209-000036</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000036</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Marianne Faithfull, Queen's Hall, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Rob Adams</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979110</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
``This Weimar is a loose town,'' explained Marianne Faithfull as her selection
of Kurt Weill songs veered off into unlikely sounding tales of Harry Nilsson's
funeral and a final scraping of the Irish tradition. The songs she chose, she
said, all had a knife-edge quality.
Life in the raw has long been her stock in trade. Although she's been in the
gutter herself, with her persona of rock's grand-but-frayed duchess she can't
really get away with singing the blues. But she's got a right - and the
personal experience - to sing Don't Smoke in Bed and the required leer to seek
Alabama Song's whiskey bars and little boys.
What her voice lacks in trueness, it more than makes up for in its abrasive
believability. It certainly carried the gig. When her actions threatened to get
over hammy (and this was inevitable in a woman for whom lighting a cigarette
can take on the proportions of a three-act drama) her cracking huskiness
conveyed credible hurt.
With just Paul Trueblood's unfussy piano accompaniment as a backdrop she worked
the stage, adding a little la la-ing dance to a gaunt Boulevard of Broken
Dreams, sitting down for a confidential verse, kneeling for extra pleading
emphasis on Au Fond de la Seine (in convincing French) - and, with a look two
parts relief to one of defiance, getting up again.
Between songs she grew from initial reticence into a kind of still-youthful but
slightly loopy school teacher about to spill beans (if there are any left to
spill) at any moment. She needn't have been shy - grown men were loudly
confessing their love for her. And if her unaccompanied She Moved Thro' The
Fair creaked a bit, this well-used song has seldom sounded more eerie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
