<DOCNO>GH951209-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Struggle with gang Head is stabbed to death at school</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979111</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A HEADTEACHER died in hospital last night after being stabbed outside his
school.
Mr Philip Lawrence was attacked when he went to help a 13-year-old pupil who
was being assaulted by a gang outside St George's Roman Catholic School, in
Lanark Road, Maida Vale, London.
Paramedics performed emergency surgery on Mr Lawrence after he had staggered
into the school.
A Scotland Yard spokeswoman said: ``It appears that as one of the schoolboys
left the school premises he was approached by a small group of male youths. The
teacher, who was in the vicinity, intervened.
``The man sustained a stab wound but managed to stagger back into the school
and raise the alarm. The suspects are believed to have made off on foot into
roads nearby.''
The boy was also taken to hospital with head injuries.
Surgeons had battled throughout the evening to save the life of Mr Lawrence,
48, a father of four, at St Mary's Hospital, Paddington.
One pupil said: ``There was a gang outside the school and they were fighting
with a boy.
``Then the headteacher suddenly ran out and tried to come between them. One of
the gang lashed out with something looking like a baseball bat and then they
grabbed the teacher and stabbed him somewhere around the stomach.
``The teacher looked very pale and the last I saw of him was when he staggered
towards the door of the school.
``I saw the youths run down the hill. I think one was black with sunglasses and
another was Chinese wearing a white top.''
Police were unable to confirm whether the murder weapon used to stab Mr
Lawrence was a machete.
The main school hall was used as an interview room by two dozen or so police
officers investigating the attack.
Mr Albert St Ange, 32, who runs North Paddington Boys Club, opposite the
school's main entrance, said trouble had been brewing between local gangs of
youths in recent weeks.
Some teenagers who use his club had told him of the tension in the area.
He said: ``From what I can gather, there has been conflict between a couple of
groups of kids.''
He said Mr Lawrence had been a asset to the school and ``a real stickler for
discipline.''
A spokesman for Westminster City Council paid tribute to Mr Lawrence, who had
been a head teacher at the school for three years.
He said: ``The city council wish to express its regret that Mr Lawrence should
lose his life in this way and offers its sincere condolences to his family.''
A spokesman for the board of governors said: ``We are shocked and appalled at
the sudden and tragic loss of such an outstanding friend and colleague.
``At the moment our thoughts are with his family and we will be offering them
all the support we possibly can.''
One local resident said he was not surprised there had been trouble. ``When I
come out in the morning to go to work there are kids hanging around smoking
cigarettes and sometimes drugs. There is always a lot of fighting between
different groups.''
</TEXT>
