<DOCNO>GH951209-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The War in Heaven, The Tramway, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alexander Linklater</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979112</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE problem of adapting any poem for the stage is finding a visual equivalent
for an essentially verbal experience. Here, where the subject of Sam Shepherd
and Joseph Chaikin's radio play is an angel lost between earth and heaven, that
problem is doubled because it's already the theme of the poem. Heaven or earth,
abstract or material: the angel can't quite become either. Nor can 7:84's
production.
A luminous, neatly designed set and gently meandering music create the
appropriate impression of limbo. The angel, divided between three performers,
is rendered in three tones of incantation: sorrow of loss, joy of discovery,
and anger in bewilderment. Michael Cannon, Sheila Docherty and Pauline Sweeney
put great intensity into this, but they can't make the poem something it isn't.
It remains words and not drama.
An exception to this may be Michael Cannon. His real-life blindness exactly
partakes of the angel's dilemma. His movements - you are aware - are made
simultaneously on a lit stage and in his own non-visual world. He becomes the
nearest this production gets to a dramatic representation of the poem's ideas.
I didn't understand why he wasn't given the line which reads, ``There was a
time when the light from my eyes was so powerful it would blind the sun. Now
look. No light, nothing.''
The poem was written after Joseph Chaikin suffered a stroke which left him
virtually unable to speak. It draws on the half-world element in such an
experience. 7:84 render this well enough as a recital but don't give persuasive
evidence that the abstract needs to be materialised.
</TEXT>
