<HEADLINE>Kafelnikov moves closer to jackpot</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979113</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TENNIS
YEVGENY Kafelnikov moved closer to his biggest cheque yet in the sport when he
reached the semi-finl stage of the Grand Slam Cup in Munich after a success
against Jacco Eltingh of Holland.
After having dropped the first set, the Russian battled back to win 3-6, 6-3,
6-2 in the $6m tournament, the most lucrative event in the game.
In today's semi, Kafelnikov will meet Goran Ivanisevic, who reached the last
four without having to pick up his racket after Pete Sampras withdraw from
their quarter-final because of a knee injury.
Three-times Wimbledon champion Boris Becker faces American Todd Martin in the
other semi-final.
There are no rankings points at stake in the German tournament, but the huge
prize money still tempts many of the top players to brave the freezing Bavarian
weather and extend the tournament season into December.
The winner will take home $1.625m.
Eltingh used his strong serve-and-volley game to the full to take the first
set, but he needed to show composure in the decisive stages. Kafelnikov played
some superb returns and passing shots to save several set points before Eltingh
took the set after 33 minutes.
The Russian lifted his form to win the second set and then took the initiative
in the decisive third set with a first break of serve in the fifth game before
serving out for the match.
Becker, who won the inaugural event in 1990, is pleased with his form. ``I
guess it's because of my serve. I don't remember serving like I've been doing
the last three-four weeks.''
</TEXT>
