<DOCNO>GH951209-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Defier of planners is jailed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979114</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FARMER who buried his illegally built home under a mound of earth in a bid to
fool planners was jailed yesterday for three months.
He was also told to demolish the house.
Trevor Sedgbeer insisted that, by removing the roof and top storey, he had
complied with an order to reduce it to the original ground level.
However, Mr Justice Sachs said the 47-year-old farmer had been shown
considerable indulgence by the courts and South Hams District Council, Devon.
``The time has now come, whilst it gives me no pleasure, for me to commit him
to prison for three months,'' said the judge. The sentence was for contempt of
court.
Mr Sedgbeer remained defiant as he was led away by the High Court tipstaff to
face Christmas in prison. He will appeal.
``I don't regret what I did,'' he said. ``It just shows what I have said all
along - the courts are always on the side of the council. They seem to get away
with whatever they like.''
He had spent more than #2000 fighting to overturn the council's refusal of
planning permission.
He said: ``They will probably demolish it while I'm in prison but I'll just put
another one up.''
The farmer's continued refusal to pull down the house near Totnes led to a
series of hearings at which he was given more time to demolish, culminating on
April 21 this year in a three-month jail order.
On May 9, council enforcement officer Michael Huxtable visited the site and
found a mound of earth. He took photographs and was convinced the house had
been demolished.
However, in October, when he revisited the site, he discovered the mound of
earth was covering the whole of the ground floor of the house.
Mr Sedgbeer had simply knocked off the top storey, left it as a bungalow, put
soil on top and grassed it over.
Mr Sedgbeer said he and his wife had owned the land for 22 years and lived on
it for many years, with permission, in a mobile home. The house was originally
a cow barn, he said, and he pointed out that three other ``whacking great
barns'' in the locality had been given consent for conversion.
``Our home has the support of the village and neighbouring farmers and property
owners,'' he said.
He told the judge the mound of earth coincided with the original ground level
before construction and as far as he was concerned he had complied with the
enforcement notice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Miller's unexpected solution to dugout stress A little humour will ease the managerial strain</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>this sporting life</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979115</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN a season when the physical drain on football managers has been manifested in
alarming style, with the dugout collapses of both Paul Sturrock, of St
Johnstone, and Allan McGraw of Morton, it seemed an appropriate moment to
discuss the demands of the job with a man who did take it on for three years at
one of the country's biggest clubs. Willie Miller tackled the impossible dream
immediately following a career as a player which spanned 18 years, much of it
at the highest level.
He went straight from the Aberdeen dressing room where he had been the
unquestioned team leader to the manager's office. No trophies were collected in
his stint as manager but he would point to four cup semi-finals reached, two
cup finals, and two runners-up spots in the premier division as evidence that
he didn't do too badly.
Looking back, he concedes that he was unlikely to survive his last season when
the team was fighting relegation. ``If there were people trying to get me moved
on when we were getting to second place twice in three years I don't suppose I
had much chance when we were struggling near the bottom.''
Miller, who was shrewd enough to make business investments and pension
arrangements as a player which removed at least one burden of the job -
worrying about his own finances - has thought long and hard about most aspects
of the management game, and has some interesting thoughts on the pressures
under which they are put.
``Nowhere else in the world are managers expected to do what they do in this
country. You are responsible for everything, from bringing through young
players, organising a scouting system throughout the country, negotiating
contracts, negotiating transfers, finding new men somewhere to stay, and making
sure their families are happy.
``The work load on managers in Britain is immense, all-encompassing. It is
virtually a general manager and coach rolled into one.''
His introduction to the gaffer's role came suddenly when Alex Smith was sacked
in much the same way that he himself was to be sent on his way three years
hence. The major difference was that Miller had been a huge success as a
Pittodrie player, a little legend of his own in the town, and upon whom immense
expectations were laid.
He acknowledges with hindsight that those expectations were far beyond realism.
``I had some good times, even as a manager, at Aberdeen. Some people forget
what was achieved in those three years. Unfortunately, we did have a huge
problem with the finances at that time which has since been eased slightly by
the share issue and sale of Stephen Wright.
``I would love to have landed one trophy to give me breathing space to put the
long term plans to work.''
He was delighted to see his former team win the Coca-Cola Cup and still has
very soft spot for his old club. ``I think when you have been a big-name player
with the club the expectations are all the higher when you become the manager.
Maybe it is just the old Scottish tradition that if you have been up there they
like to see you fall on your bum.''
Miller is not entirely convinced by the argument that says the route straight
from dressing room to manager's office is a bad one. ``Obviously, any
experience is good and people who have other jobs and learn from others get
good experience, but I honestly don't think I would have tackled the Aberdeen
job any differently. You learn as you go along anyway.''
Miller never had the image of being one of the game's stand-up comics which
makes his next observation perhaps all the more intriguing. ``One thing I did
learn and one thing I do believe is necessary to take the strain off managers
is a sense of humour. I know people didn't think I had one but my friends and
people I work with know differently.
``I learned early on that keeping a sense of humour about the place is
absolutely essential. When I look back at the expectations of the club and my
own expectations which were just as high it was totally unrealistic.
Remembering the financial difficulties, the restrictions on me in terms of
being unable to bring the kind of players I wanted to the club, and the money
that Rangers and Celtic were spending it was not a bad feat to finish second in
the league. But I don't think the fans or anyone else gave that much credit.
``I needed that sense of humour, especially in the second year when the rumour
mongers had me out of the job and someone coming into it. When people demand
those kind of results it certainly adds to the pressure.''
Miller insists that in those circumstances it is a prerequisite to have a
laugh. His conviction is that all managers, even if they are not blessed with a
laid-back nature, have to develop a lighter outlook in order to withstand the
vicissitudes that inevitably will attack them.
``I am not saying you have to treat the game frivolously or anything like that
but you can't just let the worries overcome you. You have to enjoy it even when
you are going through a bad spell.''
The former Scotland World Cup man points out that for at least two hours every
day during the week the football manager is a very happy man. ``That is when he
is doing the coaching out on the park with the lads. He is at his happiest and
most content then. He has to learn to contend with the other 22 hours.
``You have to learn to enjoy those as well and that is when the sense of humour
is required.''
The real test of his ability to handle the pressures would have come at sleep
time when many a manager finds that his mind refuses to go into the overnight
garage. As a player, Miller had the reputation that he could nod off standing
in the middle of Union Street at rush hour. That didn't change when he took on
the major problems of the manager's seat.
``There are so many things go through your mind all your waking hours that it
must be murder to have it during the night as well. I know you wonder about
whether you should play him or not, should you change the system, should I play
Eoin Jess or not even when he is having a bad spell?''
Is it a lonely job? ``Yes, there is no doubt about that. You make the
decisions. You talk to your staff, who in my case were fully integrated into
the decision-making process, but at the end of the day you are a lonely figure
because it is you who will take the stick and you who is let down when they
take your job away. Unfortunately, while a manager has to make long-term plans
they don't matter the way they do in business outside football.
``You have to live from day to day, game to game.''
His own financial acumen meant that the loss of his job did not bring
deprivation but, being a Bridgeton boy, he saw enough of unemployment as a lad
to appreciate the weight of the extended burden of relying on football for your
living.
``That must make things an awful lot worse and I am glad that I did make
provision for the day I stopped playing.''
Not surprisingly, because that is the way managers are, Miller has not vowed to
steer clear of the hot seat forever more. ``If the right offer came along I
would relish and go at it with a will. We love the game and it is great to be
involved.''
Since he left Pittodrie he has been enjoying his exposure as a media pundit
which some see as the epitome of poacher turned gamekeeper. ``I know that I can
be much more forthright in saying things now but when you are a manager you
have to protect your club and players when you talk publicly.
``Now I can give an honest opinion and if it hurts someone, too bad.''
That is a sentence of which he can be sure he will be reminded, if or when the
day dawns he returns to the team-leader role.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
