<DOCNO>GH951209-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Doctors describe Scottish flu outbreak as `average'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979117</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE incidence of flu in Scotland is more than double the rate in England and
Wales but was dismissed by Scottish experts yesterday as only an average
outbreak of the disease.
Counterparts south of the Border have described the situation there as a
fully-fledged epidemic.
One Scottish analyst said the incidence of flu in Scotland was no more than was
expected at this time of year and claimed the use of the term epidemic was
unhelpful and alarmist.
Figures released yesterday show there were 375 cases of flu per 100,000 people
in Scotland in the week ending December 2 compared with 178 per 100,000 in
England and Wales in the week ending December 3.
The Scottish figures increased by about 30% on the previous week's rate of 295
cases per 100,000, while those in England and Wales increased by 40% from 138
per 100,000.
One of the doctors monitoring levels of the infection in England and Wales, Dr
Douglas Fleming, director of the Royal College of General Practitioners'
Birmingham research unit, said yesterday: ``There are sufficient cases across
the country (England and Wales) that we would regard this as just reaching a
moderate epidemic level.''
However, experts at Scotland's national surveillance unit for infection
described this year's outbreak north of the border as ``fairly average''.
Commenting on the Scottish figures, Dr Peter Christie, consultant
epidemiologist at the Scottish Centre for Infection and Environmental Health at
Ruchill Hospital in Glasgow, said: ``There is nothing to distinguish this year
from previous years. Last year (1994-95) was quiet, the year before (1993-94)
was busier. This year (1995-96) looks like being somewhere in between the two.''
Asked if experts regarded the outbreak in Scotland as an epidemic, he said:
``It's not a helpful term. Basically we see a lot of flu at this time every
year and, in terms of the past few years, at the moment this looks like being a
fairly average year. To say it is an epidemic doesn't help in interpretation or
action taken. The term epidemic has alarming overtones.''
Dr Christie said the latest Scottish figures followed another 30% increase in
the previous week and a 110% rise the week before that, indicating that the
rate of increase was levelling off.
He added: ``My interpretation of the results north and south of the border is
that the incidence of flu looks similar but we (Scotland) have got going
earlier.''
Meanwhile, Dr Fleming said the increase in England and Wales had been seen in
all parts of the country (England and Wales) and in all age groups.
He added: ``A rate of 178 per 100,000 population is higher than is seen in many
winters, though it is still less than the peak rate of 1993 which was 235 per
100,000.'' He said there were no indications that the current epidemic would
exceed the 1993 level.
Flu accounts for 3000 to 4000 deaths in a typical year but the figure can be
much higher in epidemics. During the epidemic of 1989, there were 29,000
flu-related deaths.
Government scientists had forecast accurately the strain of flu now at large -
``A Johannesburg'' - and there were sufficient stocks of the correct vaccine.
There were an estimated six million people in the high-risk category who ought
to be immunised.
These included the elderly, people suffering from asthma and bronchitis, and
those with weak immune systems. People with heart trouble, kidney failure or
diabetes and patients receiving cancer treatment or being given steroids were
also vulnerable. Others were advised to stay at home and allow the illness to
run its course.
A Department of Health spokeswoman said: ``We would urge anyone in a vulnerable
group to have jabs but flu is not life threatening for ordinary, healthy
people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>French threat puts peace pact in doubt</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979118</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Bosnia peace agreement was under threat last night after France issued an
ultimatum to the Bosnian Serbs - return our two pilots or face the consequences.
France's hard-line statement threw the peace implementation conference in
London into some confusion.
Foreign Minister Herve de Charette warned that the situation was critical and
France would take action if the pilots, who were shot down in August, were not
returned.
``This is a critical situation,'' he told the conference. ``It puts in danger
the peace process for which we have worked for solong. France considers that
the fate of the two French pilots of the Atlantic Alliance concerns us all. We
are determined to mobilise all our efforts. We are determined to carry through
all the consequences of a refusal to reply.''
Mr de Charette's warning followed a letter from French President Jacques Chirac
to Serbia's President Slobodan Milosevic, in which he set out France's demands
in unequivocal terms.
Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind, chairing the conference at Lancaster House,
said there was great sympathy for the French concerns. ``We strongly endorse
the desire of the French Government to have this information provided
immediately,'' he said.
There was speculation that the crisis could force the French to delay the
signing of the peace agreement, which is scheduled to take place in Paris next
Thursday.
France could also decide to delay the deployment of the peace implementation
force until the pilots are returned.
It is still not known whether the men, who were shot down over Bosnian Serb
territory, are alive or dead, despite persistent questioning of the relevant
authorities.
Bosnian Foreign Minister Muhamed Sacirbey pledged his Government's commitment
to do all it could to secure the release of the French pilots.
He said it would be sad if the parties travelled to Paris next week, to just a
few miles from the homes of the pilots and their families, for the official
signing of the peace agreement, without knowing their fate.
``We would hope to go to Paris with them,'' he said. ``That would be a crowning
moment in what we anticipate would be a successful signing conference.''
The pilots crisis cast a dark shadow over the conference, which was called to
mobilise the international community behind the urgent need to finalise
practical arrangements for the peace settlement and the massive reconstruction
programme.
EU negotiator and former Swedish prime minister Carl Bildt was selected as the
``high representative'' to co-ordinate the civil and humanitarian operations
and liaise closely with the Nato military commanders.
Mr Bildt will chair the steering board of a peace implementation council, which
the conference announced would be set up with responsibility for all civilian
work in Bosnia.
A total of 42 countries, who are attending the two-day conference in London,
will be represented on the new council.
Opening the conference in Lancaster House, Prime Minister John Major warned
that peace must not be allowed to fail.
``Today we must take one decision above all: that peace in Bosnia cannot fail.
That we cannot allow the nightmare of the past three years to return,'' he said.
World News 8
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Don Pasquale, Cottier Theatre, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Harry Magee</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979119</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF you are going to stage a comic opera, it's best to ensure you can make it
funny. Opera on a Shoestring have revived Donizetti's Don Pasquale and have
then successfully buried it.
Chief undertaker must be producer James Ross who loaded his production with an
excess of clever-clever props and heavy-handed stage directions. That Act One
playing with a swivel chair, the tug-of-war with bath towels, and the Act Two
pantomime with a ball of wool were all embarrassing equivalents for the true
comedy implied in the text.
It takes more than a PC workstation and a couple of mobile phones to make a
nineteenth-century opera relevant to today's audience.
Assistant undertaker was Graeme Danby in the role of Don Pasquale. He was so
over-the-top he was actually down the other side and into the excruciating. Ham
wasn't in it. Stephen Chaundy as Ernesto at least had some stage presence, but
he appeared to be pushing his voice all night and quite a few times pushed it
too far, especially in that last-act duet - ouch!
Frances Morrison can really sing and if left to be herself could have made
something of her role as Norina. Best of all was Ivor Klayman as Malatesta
performing like a real trouper levitating above the sinking sands.
And how did Studio Performance Group allow themselves to get involved in the
last-act ballet sequence? To be positive, a couple of the duets and all the
quartets demonstrated real potential in these voices if only they had been
placed in a safer pair of hands. If you want to judge for yourself it's
repeated on Sunday and Tuesday, but better wear your thermals against this
venue's Siberian draughts - and oh, maybe a blindfold, too.
</TEXT>
