<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Delay keeps protesters' powder dry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979120</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHERE there is hope, there is life - HOPE being the acronym for Hands off
Powderhall Evermore, the lobby group fighting to keep the developers'
bulldozers off one of the most historic tracts of Scotland's sporting turf.
This week, they have taken satisfaction from an Edinburgh District Council
delay in adoption of the local plan which could have approved the site's
rescheduling for housing. Each delay enhances their chances of success.
The English developers want to demolish the stadium in the face of attempts to
have it preserved as a site of historic importance, of some local opposition,
and a catalogue of other objections. Now they have had to postpone their own
application to develop the site which has earned no revenue since speedway
closed down at the beginning of October.
If the developers succeed, it will be at the expense of an irreplaceable piece
of Scotland's heritage.
Built on land owned by the Balfour family of Pilrig - the first laird was a
sponsor of the ill-fated South Sea Bubble and the second was the grandfather of
Robert Louis Stevenson - it owed its name to the fact that William III had
given the first laird the exclusive rights to manufacture gunpowder.
It was on Powderhall's ash surface that track athletics in Scotland had its
respectable roots, after riots at meetings in Portobello and Newington. The
famous professional sprint was first staged there in 1871, and switched to
Meadowbank only after George McNeill had won a century later.
It hosted the first of 16 Scottish Amateur Athletic Association championships
in 1883; Eric Liddell worked out there thrice a week prior to winning the 1924
Olympic 400m title, while whippets were trained on the opposite straight -
hence scenes for the Oscar-winning film, Chariots of Fire, having been shot
there. Liddell won the 100 and 220-yard titles on cinders in 1922 when the SAAA
championships were staged there for the final time.
Scotland's international rugby XV was undefeated on its turf, with an 8-3
victory over Ireland, in 1897, and a 3-3 draw with England the following year.
It was also the home of the former Scottish Football League side, Leith
Athletic.
The Edinburgh Cup, one of UK greyhound racing's most prestigious awards, has
attracted the finest dogs in Britain, most notably Pigalle Wonder, the English
derby winner which won twice.
Howard Wallace, a taxation manager and HOPE spokesman, is one of the greyhound
fanatics whose life has gone to the dogs since the closure battle was joined
when the traps last sprang open, back in January. ``We have to look on the
delay as good news,'' said Wallace, who is also encouraged by the refusal of
Glasgow's councillors to see Shawfield similarly disposed of.
The Edinburgh lobby group drew attention to the Secretary of State's concerns
over housing being built on land susceptible to flooding, and this week
Edinburgh's planning department admitted that construction engineers say the
ground adjacent to the Water of Leith, will have to be raised by two metres if
housing is built.
The Wildlife Trust is also watching developments with interest and concern; the
city's environmental services department is understood to be unhappy at the
proximity of housing to a refuse compaction unit committed to disposing of
three tonnes of waste per week for the next 20 years; and from January 1, the
Scottish Office will direct greater scrutiny on sports ground land rezoned for
housing. The latest delay suggests there will be no planning hearing until
January 18.
Edinburgh Monarchs are used to being let down by the district council, but
would be devastated by the ultimate betrayal which would leave them homeless.
Old Meadowbank, their previous track, was demolished to make way for the 1970
Commonwealth stadium. ``There was no speedway in Edinburgh for six years,
despite council assurances to the contrary,'' said Mike Hunter, the Monarchs'
spokesman.
In 1977, the Greyhound Racing Association welcomed them to Powderhall, but the
city fathers permitted the move by only one vote. Monarchs finances have always
lain uneasy. Sponsorless and given just four days to find #10,000 or face
closure in 1991, they succeeded in raising #18,000 in one night, at a
supporters' meeting. The season just concluded, has ironically again been
without a sponsor, yet was their best at Powderhall. They finished ninth out of
the 21 in the new Premier League.
``We are due to restart at the end of March or beginning of April. We have made
a few vague enquiries about a temporary venue, but our preferred home is
Powderhall.''
Ashes to ashes? We certainly hope not.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Edinburgh puts limits on raves</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979121</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OUTDOOR raves in Edinburgh will be allowed only in the summer in future and be
restricted to 12 hours.
The recommendations were accepted by Edinburgh Licensing Committee yesterday
after reports about an outdoor rave at Ingliston in September which lasted from
Saturday noon until 8am Sunday.
A police report said that more than 11,500 people, aged between 16 and 25, had
attended. The weather was described as ``atrocious''. Medical treatment was
required for 264 people, with 54 suffering from hypothermia.
The report added that a rest area had been provided in a restaurant. ``This
facility was intended as a `chill-out' area for dancers to rest, but due to the
severe weather conditions it was more of a `warm-up' area.''
The committee agreed to accept the recommendations for future outdoor raves and
to have talks with promoters.
It then approved an all-night indoor Hogmanay rave at Ingliston for 5000 people
lasting from 8pm on December 31 to 8am on January 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Call to reform appointments in judiciary</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979122</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND has a second-class legal system as result of fundamental flaws in
making judicial appointments, the Shadow Lord Advocate, Lord Macaulay of Bragar
QC, said yesterday.
Addressing the Standing Conference on Justice's annual convention in Edinburgh,
he said there was ample scope for reform in the wake of constitutional change.
He said the glut of temporary sheriffs ran counter to continuity, consistency
in sentencing, and public confidence in the administration of justice.
``What we have at the moment in Scotland is a second-class legal system. We
have nearly 200 temporary sheriffs wandering about the country who suddenly
appear out of the blue.
``Solicitors and sheriffs in the smaller towns and communities, who know what's
going on in their area, are presented with a member of the Bar or a solicitor
and wonder who he or she is.
``It is a ridiculous way to run things. We must try and build into the Scottish
legal system some kind of permanency within sheriffdoms,'' Lord Macaulay said.
The Labour spokesman in the Lords on Scottish legal matters said there were
similar problems higher up in the appointment of temporary judges.
``A temporary judge is supposed to have full powers of a Senator of the Court
of Justice but I am informed that some temporary judges are not allowed to deal
with rape or murder charges,'' he said.
This had led to some trials being called off, despite witnesses, counsel, and a
jury being ready, because the case had been allocated to a temporary judge.
``The greatest example, however, is the ability of the Lord Advocate to appoint
himself on to the bench.
``In no other profession can you promote yourself. Could you imagine a corporal
making himself a general or a junior doctor making himself a consultant? It is
just a complete nonsense,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rigging claim over awards</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Doug Gillon</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979123</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ATHLETICS
WILL the greatest field events performance in athletics history - Jon Edwards'
two successive world records to take world championship triple jump gold - be
rewarded by the sport this weekend? Or will the International Amateur Athletics
Federation's gala in Monte Carlo again be exposed to allegations of vote
rigging?
As candidates for the World Athlete of the Year title jetted into Monaco last
night, Chris Winner, one of those responsible for organising last year's
presentations, claimed the voting had been rigged, denying Sally Gunnell the
women's title, in order to boost TV ratings.
Winner, the former IAAF spokesman, insists that Britain's Gunnell had topped
last year's poll, having broken the world 400m hurdles record. In doing so she
became the first woman to hold world, Olympic, European and Commonwealth titles
simultaneously. Yet Winner alleges Gunnell was replaced as the female athlete
of the year by American Jackie Joyner Kersee. He also alleges that Britain's
Colin Jackson was demoted from second to fourth in the men's voting.
American Winner said that manipulation occured when the IAAF learned that
neither Gunnell nor Jackson planned to attend the ball at which the awards were
due to be announced. IAAF general secretary Istvan Gyulai last night flatly
rejected the allegations.
Writing in a US newspaper, Winner said: ``I can only express shame for
participating in what amounts to gross vote-rigging.'' He claimed that IAAF
president Primo Nebiolo wanted to ensure the top three athletes in both male
and female polls would attend, making it more attractive to TV.
After advising IAAF officials that Gunnell had narrowly beaten Joyner Kersee to
the top spot, Winner said he had been instructed to add 30 extra votes for
Joyner Kersee - two weeks after the poll had closed.
Edwards, along with double world champion Michael Johnson, is the main
contender for the men's award. Burns victim Anna Quirot, who won the world 800m
title, is the leading female candidate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>McIntyre given full-time role</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH DAN MacLENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979124</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Camanachd Association, shinty's ruling body have chosen Alastair MacIntyre
of Fort William as their first full-time paid official.
The 57-year-old has been the association's part-time administrator for the last
10 years. A keen golfer and chairman of the Ben Nevis Race Association, he has
one Camanachd Cup-winner's medal from the '60s and two runners-up awards.
He was chosen from a short leet of four which included association president
Duncan Cameron of Glasgow.
The final selection panel met in Oban following an extraordinary meeting of the
association's Executive Council earlier in the week, which was called following
Mr Cameron's decision to throw his hat in the ring.
One of the official's first tasks will be to explain his new function to clubs.
His new role has yet to be fully explained to them and the speed with which the
final specification of the job was drawn up by the game's administrators
already has caused some disquiet.
Mr MacIntyre, who runs a successful bus company, now has a three-year contract
and the backing of the majority of the executive to prove that he was the right
man for the job.
He is due to take up his #18,000-a-year post on January 1.
SHINTY
</TEXT>
