<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Checks on school buses reveal `rust-buckets'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979125</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHILDREN in Lothian may be travelling to and from school in ``rust-buckets on
wheels'', it was claimed yesterday.
Police, along with the Department of Transport Vehicle Inspectorate, have
launched spot checks on school buses.
A senior police officer said yesterday that, in some cases, ``rust-buckets on
wheels'' had been discovered during their week-long initiative, and a
Department of Transport official admitted that, since deregulation, smaller
operators have been ``cutting corners''.
Of more than 100 buses checked so far, five have been issued with defect forms
- while one had so many faults that its operator is being reported to the
fiscal.
Taxis and private hire cars are also used for transporting children to schools,
and nine have already been found in breach of the conditions of their licence.
Another three were warned to rectify minor faults.
Yesterday, police set up checks at various locations around Edinburgh and
Lothian.
While many transport operators ran vehicles in first-class condition,
transporting children in complete safety, a number had been far too lax, it was
alleged.
Chief Inspector Bryan Lowrie, of Lothian and Borders Police traffic department,
said: ``Our checks have shown some alarming discrepancies in tyres,
documentation, and other aspects of transport.
``Basically, we have found that in some cases, rust-buckets on wheels have been
used to take children to and from school.
``So far, we have checked in excess of 150 vehicles and issued 14
prohibitions.''
Mr David Wilson, of the Department of Transport, admitted that, since
deregulation, smaller operators had been able to ``cut corners''.
He said: ``This is something we monitor continually, in an effort to find the
so-called cowboy operators.
``I would admit that many of the vehicles we have checked are in excellent
condition but, in some cases, it is concerning.''
Mrs Elizabeth Maginnis, Lothian's education committee convener, said: ``We hope
this initiative will dissuade the so-called cowboy operators, because we take
the view that any future contracts would come under serious consideration.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man shot dead in street</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979126</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICE in Belfast were hunting two men and a woman last night after a man was
shot dead on a city street.
The shooting is thought to be linked to trade in illegal drugs, and is the
third such killing in recent months.
Paul Devine, a married man in his 30s, was shot as he got into a car parked in
Claremont Street off Lisburn Road.
Witnesses heard between four and six shots ring out. An office worker said: ``I
went downstairs to see the guy lying beside a car in a pool of blood. He had
been hit twice that I could see, once in the back of the head and once in the
chest.''
Devine, who was known to the RUC, lived close to where he was shot. Detectives
ruled out a sectarian motive for his murder.
Two drug dealers were shot dead by the IRA this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>IRA's refusal on arms gesture threatens talks Major angered by `slap' to peace</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979127</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister responded angrily yesterday to the IRA's refusal to
surrender any weapons, denouncing it as ``a slap in the face'' to the hopes for
peace of the people of Northern Ireland.
He challenged Sinn Fein to denounce the IRA, after the paramilitaries issued a
defiant statement rejecting demands that they make a gesture on arms
decommissioning to allow all-party talks to go ahead.
Instead, Sinn Fein accused the Government of ``intransigence'' for sticking to
its condition that some weapons should be surrendered as a sign of good faith
before talks can proceed.
The IRA statement confirmed that despite, the British-Irish twin-track
agreement signed on the eve of President Bill Clinton's visit to Northern
Ireland, the principal obstacle to the peace process remains.
Unionists interpreted it as a fatal blow to the twin-track agreement, which
allows preliminary talks to begin while the arms decommissioning issue is
examined by an international commission headed by former US senator George
Mitchell.
Mr Peter Robinson, deputy leader of the Democratic Unionists, said: ``This must
wreck the prospects that Senator George Mitchell had in terms of the arms
commission, and therefore the twin-track process must be dead.''
The Ulster Unionists' deputy leader, Mr John Taylor, added: ``If there is
intransigence it certainly exists with the IRA. It was they who over a year ago
announced a ceasefire and gave the impression that they wished to transform
themselves from being a terrorist organisation into a constitutional political
party.''
In a statement Mr Major said: ``The IRA's intransigence is a slap in the face
to the hundreds of thousands of people in Northern Ireland and the Republic,
who last week demonstrated their massive desire for peace.
``The message of all those people to the paramilitaries was that their day was
over and that now was the time to put away guns, give up violence forever and
make peace.''
Later, he challenged Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams to distance himself from the
IRA.
``Is Gerry Adams the man who wants to bring peace to Northern Ireland or is he
a straightforward spokesman for a terrorist organisation who continues
producing intransigent statements and putting a bottleneck in the way of
peace?'' he said.
The arms question has divided the Government and Sinn Fein since the start of
the cease-fire last year. Mr Adams said yesterday any decommissioning of
weapons would amount to an IRA surrender, which was unacceptable.
``These are not fresh doubts. The doubts arise from the British Government's
refusal to engage positively in this peace process from the inception, by its
repeated bad faith, by it placing a new precondition - and this business of
decommissioning is a new precondition which the British Government put forward
five months after the IRA's decision,'' he said.
The IRA's message, released in Dublin, said: ``There is no question of the IRA
meeting the ludicrous demand for a surrender of IRA weapons either through the
front or the back door.''
Government sources deny Britain is seeking an IRA surrender, and insist it is
up to Sinn Fein to find a way around the issue. Britain rejects the party's
claim that British police and army weapons in the province would have to be
scrapped as well.
In Dublin, Irish Prime Minister John Bruton remained optimistic. ``It is better
to concentrate on facts and the fact is that Sinn Fein stated that they will
speak authoritatively to the international body on the issue of IRA weapons.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trust's fears for red squirrels</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979128</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LYNNE ROBERTSON
A STUDY to monitor Lothian's declining red squirrel population was launched in
Edinburgh yesterday by the Scottish Wildlife Trust.
It will involve a unique project funded by Lothian region's environmental award
scheme to monitor red squirrel numbers.
``Sticky tubes'' made from short lengths of guttering and with double-sided
sticky tape at each end will be attached to branches and filled with food in 30
sites in East Lothian where the squirrels have been spotted.
A survey team will then analyse hairs under the microscope to assess numbers.
The study is expected to be completed next spring.
The trust fears numbers may drop as dramatically north of the Border as in
England and Wales. Changes in forestry and the environment have been blamed for
the fall.
There are also fears the native population may be overrun by the grey squirrel.
Study team member Jon Durward, said there were an estimated 121,000 red
squirrels in Scotland.
``We hope this study will also help conserve the numbers in Lothian,'' he said.
Red squirrels are now a protected species in the UK.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stiff!, Tron Theatre, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sara Villiers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979129</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Tron Theatre Company's award-winning production of Dumbstruck showcased
their panache with black comedy and this new comedy musical written by and
starring the ginger bombshell Forbes Masson offers them another opportunity to
strut their skill with theatre noir. Mind you, although the play is set in a
world of morticians and cemeteries it's hardly dark and brooding, Masson
endowing his Faustian plot with a light, frothy touch which makes it
particularly gigglesome.
He certainly doesn't flinch from extracting the full quotient of potential
double entendres in the opening title number, which is stuffed to overflowing
with gags about stiffies. But there's subtlety too - as in the romantic duet
with girlfriend Jennifer Black where he croons that coupledom is being like
gravy going with a deep ashen pie. It's a passion which is surpassed by Black's
later torch song number where she responds to him giving her the elbow with the
acidic invocation Die Soon.
The dialogue, which lacks the cutting edge of David Kane's Dumbstruck, could be
sharpened up a bit but there are plenty of hilarious observations to keep you
chuckling along, such as the description of an award-winning monumental -
that's gravestone to us lay folk - artist as someone who could ``chisel in four
languages and one of them was Gaelic.
Part of the Tron's New Scottish Writing showcase season, we can only fervently
pray that the project will flourish into production next year. This rehearsed
reading of the first act, replete with appropriate onstage corpsing, offered an
entertaining taster of a treat in store. I almost died laughing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Surgeon's role cited  in fatal operation</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979130</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FATAL accident inquiry report yesterday criticised a surgeon and the Shetland
Health Board, more than two years after an islands' councillor bled to death
following a gall bladder operation.
The health board has already made changes to its procedures.
Sheriff Colin Scott Mackenzie said it was not appropriate for his inquiry to
attribute negligence to surgeon John Parkin, 51. However, he cited evidence - a
report by two independent consultants on behalf of Shetland Health Board - that
``had, in fact, found Mr Parkin to be negligent''.
The sheriff said the death of Councillor Alex Arthur, 68, at the Gilbert Bain
Hospital in Lerwick in July, 1993, ``might have been avoided'' if senior
medical staff had paid closer attention to his condition after the operation
and if Mr Parkin had not ``misinterpreted'' the situation.
He determined that, after unexpected difficulties during surgery on the
afternoon of July 9, 1993, Mr Parkin had acted properly, until he attached a
drain tube in such a way that it later partly dislodged Mr Arthur's gall
bladder from his liver, causing severe internal bleeding.
The sheriff praised nurses who noticed the problem soon after Mr Arthur was
returned to the ward at 4.40pm. At 7.10pm a ``very junior'' hospital doctor
phoned the surgeon at home about the problem, but Mr Parkin did not question
her as closely as he might have.
Mr Parkin phoned the ward at 7.30pm and prescribed drugs. He arranged for blood
to be matched for a transfusion. He did not return to the hospital until 8.55pm.
When a nurse mentioned the persistent bleeding from the tube, he said: ``Panic
not, that is what drains are for.''
After speaking to Mr Arthur's wife, the surgeon decided to go home again while
blood was prepared. The sheriff said: ``In leaving the hospital at this time he
had misinterpreted the seriousness of Mr Arthur's condition.''
He was paged before he reached his house and arrived back at the hospital at
about 10.15pm. More than an hour later, after further delays awaiting
cross-matched blood, he began a second operation to try to save his patient's
life.
Mr Arthur died on the operating table at 1.50am on July 10, 1993.
In an immensely detailed, 50-page judgment, Sheriff Mackenzie had no criticism
of the junior hospital doctors, the nurses who ``had done all that was humanly
possible'', or of the anaesthetist, who ``battled without pause'' to keep Mr
Arthur alive.
Mr Parkin, who retired early on medical grounds last year, had been criticised
with hindsight, the sheriff said. He had admitted errors while working under
stress and should be accorded due sympathy.
Mr Arthur's only son, Alan, 45, in a statement after the judgment, said: ``The
family are satisfied that at last the findings have been published. We hope
this inquiry may lead to safer practices in the future, for the sake of all
patients in Shetland.''
Dr Cox said: ``The board of course deeply regrets this tragic event and would
wish to be associated with the sheriff's expression of sympathy to Mr Arthur's
family.''
Last night Mr Parkin said: ``Obviously my deepest sympathy goes to the family.
I'm very saddened by the fact that an operation undertaken with the best of
motives should have such a tragic outcome.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Government team searching for brain disease links did not experiment on primates Obvious CJD tests missed out</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979131</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCIENTISTS investigating BSE for the Government were accused yesterday of
failing to conduct obvious experiments which help establish whether the deadly
brain condition could be transmitted to humans.
Dr Helen Grant said researchers should have found out whether monkeys or apes
could develop BSE.
The brain expert told Radio 4's consumer programme, You and Yours, that
deliberately infecting primates with the disease should have been a priority
experiment because primates are the nearest animals in the evolutionary chain
to man.
``They should have used primates in this experiment using BSE-infected material
and they didn't,'' said Dr Grant, former consultant neuropathologist at Charing
Cross Hospital, London.
``I imagine they were terrified it might be positive: that the primates would
get the infection when injected with or fed BSE-infected materials.
``If primates caught the infection from the cows, it would suggest very
strongly that humans might do the same, because we humans are another primate.''
The microbiologist who heads the committee investigating BSE admitted, on the
same programme, that there had been no BSE tests on primates.
Professor John Pattison, chairman of the Spongiform Encephalopathy Advisory
Committee, said that even if a chimpanzee or a monkey developed the disease it
would not conclusively prove that it could be transmitted to man.
However, Professor Pattison, professor of medical microbiology at University
College London Medical School, indicated that BSE experiments might be carried
out on primates in the not-too-distant future.
A spokesman for the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries, and Food said it was
for the committee to decide which experiments were carried out.
He dismissed any suggestion that the Government might have pressured scientists
not to test monkeys for fear of the panic a positive result would cause.
``There have not been any transmissions to primates,'' Professor Pattison told
You and Yours.
``All I can say is that we, at our meeting early next month, are going to
consider the research priorities and we will be considering all avenues of
approach.''
He added: ``These are expensive and long-term experiments. It doesn't in itself
prove that it would transmit to man even if it does transmit to primates.''
On Thursday, he told PA News that it was not possible to guarantee that BSE
could not be transmitted to humans, although the evidence pointed in that
direction.
He insisted that his committee was independent and under no pressure from the
Government to say beef was safe.
Hundreds of schools around Britain have now taken beef products off their
menus. Consumer groups say the Government should hold a public inquiry into BSE
but Ministers continue to insist that beef is safe.
The latest scare was triggered a week ago when another leading brain scientist,
Professor Sir Bernard Tomlinson, told You and Yours that he no longer ate beef
products containing offal because of his concern about the disease.
Many other eminent scientists have also said a link between BSE and its human
equivalent, CJD, is possible.
NFU digs deep 25
