<HEADLINE>Ashdown warns of war in Europe</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979132</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FAILURE to agree monetary union and greater integration will lead Europe to
conflict and even war within 20 years, Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown
has warned.
Speaking in advance of next weekend's crucial European summit in Madrid, Mr
Ashdown said public sector strikes in France and British Euro-scepticism were
combining to reverse the march towards European integration.
In an interview for the BBC programme Scottish Lobby, to be broadcast tomorrow,
Mr Ashdown says that unless monetary union succeeds Europe will see ``the
return to competitive states and in my view war, or at least conflict, either
within the European borders or outside the European borders, within two
decades''.
His apocalyptic scenario is based on European history. War had been the natural
state of Europe for 2000 years. ``The biggest idea, the only idea to come out
of Europe in the last 50 years, is the idea of European unity and European
integration,'' he said.
``It's the only thing that saves us from rising nationalism within European
countries. You see it in Germany. You don't have to go to Sarajevo to see it,
you can see it at the Conservative Party conference in Britain.
``So may it be in no doubt whatsoever, if monetary union fails - and I agree,
it is now in extreme jeopardy - if it fails, then the process of European
integration will go into reverse, Europe will return to competing states, and
given our history, we know where that leads.''
Mr Ashdown's comments are the starkest warning yet of the implications for
Europe if its member states fail to agree on the monetary union and greater
integration by 1999, as prescribed by the Maastricht Treaty.
He pointed to the fall of the Soviet union leaving chaos in the east of Europe,
and warned that Bosnia was not an isolated event. ``Europe is most at danger
when empires collapse.''
</TEXT>
