<HEADLINE>Whisky price rise ahead</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robert Powell,Cameron Simpson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979134</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROBERT POWELL,
CAMERON SIMPSON
EXCLUSIVE
THE 27p cut on a bottle of whisky in last month's Budget could be wiped out
next year as distillers pass on the rising price of barley and packaging to
consumers.
It is expected cereal increases will add about 20p to the cost of producing a
bottle and Mr John Goodwin, the chairman of Highland Distilleries, which makes
Famous Grouse, said some price rises next year would be inevitable.
Last night, the SNP, which had campaigned for a 10% cut in duty in the Budget,
said the threat was a measure of how the industry had been duped by the
Chancellor.
The cut the SNP had campaigned for would have taken 76p off a bottle, said
party business spokesman, Mr Fergus Ewing. ``The industry has been tricked and
is still paying nearly #1000m a year in tax revenues. The real message of the
Chancellor's Budget is Slainte you suckers.''
The threat was also greeted with dismay by the General, Municipal, and
Boilermakers, the largest union in the Scotch whisky industry. Spokesman Harry
Donaldson said: ``If rising costs mean they would wipe out the Chancellor's 27p
cut then clearly Kenneth Clarke has not gone nearly far enough.
He added: ``My real fear is that the industry will get into a price war. The
pressure will be on for sales and that would have a catastrophic effect on the
industry. Some of the smaller players could be forced out of business.''
Mr Donaldson said he also feared that the consumer would not tolerate any
further price rises and would turn instead to wine and white spirits.
The industry has seen packaging costs rise by up to 30% this year while the
price of malting barley is set to rise by up to 10% in 1996. Maize and wheat,
which are used to distil grain whiskies, are also set to rise by a similar
margin.
This will pile even more pressure on distillers who have felt unable to pass on
rising costs
Continued on Page 2
Continued from page 1
for the past two years. Instead, they have been discounting heavily to retain
their share of a weak market awash with surplus stocks.
Mr Goodwin said: ``There is a need for some price increases because I think the
price of our cereal purchases for 1996 will be up by somewhere between eight
and 10%. We have also sustained increases over the past year on all types of
packaging so I think we need a modest increase in price.''
Mr Peter Derbyshire, the managing director of Macdonald Martin which makes
Glenmorangie malt, said they had reached a point ``where we really cannot
absorb any more increases in the price of raw materials.'' He said the expected
rise in cereal prices next year would add about 20p to the cost of producing a
bottle of whisky without allowing for any increase in profit margins.
Mr Alan Gray, a whisky analyst with Edinburgh stockbroker Sutherland and
Partners, said the inevitable rise in cereal costs would encourage distillers
to go for price increases that have been overdue for two years.
</TEXT>
