<HEADLINE>Yard threatened by ballot vote</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979135</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORKERS at the Arnish fabrication yard near Stornoway last night voted to hold
a ballot on industrial action.
The decision, taken at a mass meeting of the men, followed their rejection of a
20p-an-hour pay rise which was management's final offer after two and a half
weeks of negotiations.
Talks were held all day yesterday to try to break the deadlock.
Three weeks ago, all 305 shopfloor workers were sacked after they began an
overtime ban.
They were reinstated by yard operator Lewis Offshore Ltd a few days later after
a deal was reached with a commitment to new pay talks, which ended yesterday.
An official ballot was held during the week which decisively rejected the offer.
Feelings have been running high because LOL managing director Peter Webster
threatened to shut the yard if the men did not go back to work.
It is understood that, despite the yard's considerable work in progress and a
new #1m contract announced only last week, management have still not ruled out
closure if the men take industrial action.
However, the men claim their #7.07 hourly rate is the lowest of any fabrication
yard in the UK.
A joint statement after a further meeting between LOL and workers
representatives, including a GMB union official, confirmed the rejection of the
pay offer and that a formal ballot would be held on industrial action.
The decision to ballot was not unanimous but was carried by a substantial
majority, according to workers leaving the meeting.
Mr Webster was not available last night to comment on the men's move towards
industrial action.
</TEXT>
