<HEADLINE>Good feeling about cakes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra slice of life</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979136</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Lama Yeshe was born in Tibet in 1947 and came to Scotland in 1969. He founded a
retreat at Woodstock in the Catskill Moun-tains of the USA, and is now Retreat
Master for 40 students from 16 countries on a re-treat at Samye Ling of three
years, three months and three days. He is also manager and executive director
for projects at Samye Ling Buddhist Temple at Eskdalemuir and has founded the
Buddhist retreat on Holy Island. He tells Leila Farrah about a typical day's
eating.
n OUR Buddhist philosophy says that you should try to maintain a simple
lifestyle so food is not the main thing in our lives. For breakfast I just have
a cup of black tea, some Cheddar on toast and an orange, a habit I picked up in
America because it's good for Vitamin C.
At Samye Ling Temple, there's a differ-ent vegetarian cook every second day
doing their own dishes, but I always try to have yoghurt fresh from the farm
there. Yoghurt is so good for you and it is very popular in Tibet. Everyone at
Samye Ling knows that the Lama likes yoghurt so they always get me a bowl. I'll
have raw carrot, too, then another orange and perhaps a banana.
For the past 13 years I haven't eaten any other solid foods after my daily
lunch. For many people, food is everything but we don't feel that we should
indulge ourselves. I have many students who look to me for an example so this
becomes important, and I have a very strong self-discipline.
If hunger comes to me just before lunch I let it pass, and then I feel strong
and good. I'm not consumed by the need for food: when we become involved in
dependencies, then we jump into bad eating habits, we engage with food too
much. It also means that we have no respect for people without food; so much of
it is wasted in the garbage, and in our philosophy, we can't tolerate that.
Because I visit many different places, although I am a vegetarian, sometimes I
have no choice but to eat meat or fish - I have to be flexible. In Japan it
took me two days to find a vegetarian restaurant; very expensive and not much
food for it.
I have no favourite dishes, as such; I would never allow my mind to indulge in
that. But I am quite chubby and everyone tells the cooks at Samye Ling not to
feed the Lama cakes - sometimes I have a good feeling about cakes .....
</TEXT>
