<HEADLINE>GLASGOW AND THE CHIMERA</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Pacione</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Cartoon</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979137</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The regeneration of
a city, argues Michael Pacione, must be shaped from within, rather than left to
the creative whims of outsiders
THE approach of a new year, and of a new millennium, encourages people to
engage in reflection and stocktaking. It is a time to look back on past
achievements and mistakes and forward to, hopefully, better times. The same is
true for Glasgow. What are the prospects for the city as it approaches the
millennium? How has the city responded to the economic and social shockwaves of
the last quarter of the twentieth century? Have those responsible for guiding
the development of the city been successful? Have the foundations been laid for
sustainable urban regeneration? Or will Glasgow arrive at the millennium party
in old clothes and with a dirty face?
Let's pause to consider the main causes of the problems confronting Glasgow and
examine the effects of recent policies designed to enhance the socio-economic
health of the city and its citizens. Let us seek to identify some of the
ingredients of a prescription for the future well-being of the city.
While it is of little consolation to those experiencing social and economic
disadvantage, Glasgow is not unique in experiencing the pain of economic
contraction and urban restructuring. Many of the world's cities are currently
undergoing social, economic, political and environmental changes of
unprecedented magnitude. Such changes are the outcome of the interplay of
decisions taken by a host of private and public interests operating at a
variety of geographic scales, from global to local. In order to understand the
consequences of these changes for Glasgow it is necessary to acknowledge the
working of the capitalist system and the rise of a global economy.
An inherent characteristic of the capitalist global economic system is the
creation of uneven development which stems from the prosperity of capital to
flow to locations which offer the greatest potential economic return. This
differential use of space by capital in pursuit of profit creates a mosaic of
inequality at all geographical scales.
At any one time certain countries, regions, cities and communities will be in
the throes of decline as a result of the retreat of capital investment while
others will be experiencing the impact of capital inflows. Older industrial
cities like Glasgow have been among the biggest losers in this global
investment competition, with large areas economically and socially devastated
by the effects of global economic restructuring and the deindustrialisation of
the British economy. Within the city the outcome of the uneven development
process is seen in the poverty, powerlessness and polarisation of localities
which, though remaining meaningful places to their residents, are not regarded
as profitable spaces by capital.
Cities vary in their capacity to meet the challenge posed by globalisation and
this is reflected in the extent to which each can shape, or merely react to,
global forces. In the case of Glasgow the harshness of current economic reality
is illuminated by comparing its nineteenth-century status as industrial
powerhouse and workshop of the world with present circumstances in which the
city's development is influenced to a significant extent by forces beyond its
control. Even more striking is the fact that the day-to-day well-being of a
family in Easterhouse can be determined by decisions taken in the boardroom of
a multinational corporation located in one of the ``command cities'' of the
global economy.
Although the power of global forces to influence city growth or decline is
awesome it is not omnipotent. Economic and political action undertaken at a
national level or by regional groupings of nation states (such as the EC) or,
to a lesser extent, by local governments can modify the effects of the global
economic system.
Regulatory and tax policies shape the environments which attract or repel
investors. Decisions about public investment determine whether infrastructure
(such as housing, hospitals, roads, and schools) will be built or allowed to
deteriorate. Government procurement policy, (including the naval shipbuilding
contracts on which Yarrow depends), stimulates the local economy, and the
inter-governmental transfer payments (either directly through Urban Aid or via
agencies such as the Glasgow Development Agency) can prevent the collapse of a
local economy.
Unfortunately for Glasgow, since 1979, the emphasis in Government policy has
been to promote national economic growth irrespective of its geographical
distribution within the country. This has only indirectly addressed the
difficulties experienced by these localities which are marginal to the
market-driven development process.
Recent changes in the relationship between central and local government have
also reduced Glasgow's ability to tackle its problems. In the late 1970s, in
the face of increasing fiscal crises and the consequent search for cuts in
public spending, the earlier consensus between central and local government,
manifested in the GEAR project, was replaced by growing conflict and increased
central intervention in traditional areas of local authority responsibility
such as housing (through controls on capital spending and council house sales
policy), and tight control over local finance. The effect was increased
centralisation of power alongside decentralisation of service responsibility.
The ensuing need for Glasgow to seek financial support by entering into
partnerships with public agencies, such as the Scottish Development
Agency/Scottish Enterprise and the private sector has weakened the leadership
role of the local authority and reduced its ability to develop
locally-sensitive strategies for urban renewal. While some would see this trend
as desirable, others view it as a sign of a continued and unwelcome reduction
in the autonomy of local government.
The latest round of local government reforms which removed the higher tier
authorities also ignored the fact that the functional boundary of the City of
Glasgow extends well beyond its administrative area. While a number of
conflicts arose between the city and the regional authority, not least with
reference to planning and development issues, proponents of regional government
would contend that a major success was its ability to effect resource
redistribution through the tax system. This, of course, is one of the main
reasons why suburban local authorities around Glasgow have long resisted
integration with the city to form a functional city region.
Nevertheless, it is axiomatic that strategic planning at a level which
acknowledges the functional linkages within a city region is essential for
effective government. The question for debate is whether this should be
provided by a regional tier of government, by collaboration between unitary
local authorities for specific programmes, by a body such as a West of Scotland
Planning Commission, or possibly by a unitary system overseen by a Scottish
Assembly. These are important questions for the future.
The depth of Glasgow's current social and economic difficulties was highlighted
first in 1971 when analysis of the census placed Clydeside at the top of the
national deprivation league. Over the intervening years the nature and location
of the city's problems have changed. Between 1971 and 1981 the traditional
tenement areas of the inner city characterised by large areas of substandard
housing, recorded a relative improvement in status. This was largely a result
of a massive clearance and redevelopment programme undertaken by the local
authority combined, in some areas, with modernisation and new building by
housing associations and private developers.
This policy involved the large-scale relocation of residents in a general
process of decentralisation. By 1981 it was apparent that the focus of
deprivation, marked primarily by social and economic problems related to
unemployment and overcrowding, had shifted to the public-sector housing estates
on the edge of the city. The need for policy instruments that reflected this
new geography of need was also starkly evident.
The policy response to this revealed geography of need was unequivocal. This is
borne out by examination of the distribution of capital investment undertaken
by the main public and private agencies responible for Glasgow's development
during the 1980s.
This indicates, and most significantly, the dearth of investment in these areas
by either the Scottish Development Agency or the private sector. During its
lifetime the SDA saw itself as a body to exploit the advantages of the Scottish
economy and not as an agency for the socio-economic regeneration of depressed
council estates. As far as the private sector is conerned the outer estates are
``no-go areas''. In practice, throughout the 1980s, despite their designation
as ``planning priority areas'' the peripheral estates received little priority
in terms of attracting more investment or public-agency activity.
In areas such as Glasgow's outer estates central Government's hope of urban
revitalisation through ``capitalism with a social conscience'' is a chimera.
Glasgow's experience of the operation of pro-growth business coalitions (such
as the Chamber of Commerce), civic boosterism (characterised by slogans like
Glasgow's Miles Better and Glasgow's Alive), and local enterprise initiatives
(eg Glasgow Action) confirms that while the market approach may be a logical
response in areas of significant economic potential, it is extremely unlikely
that such a ``top down'' approach will take account adequately of the needs of
the poor, the unemployed, and the deprived residents of the most disadvantaged
areas of the city.
Justification for the Government's market-led approach to urban regeneration
centres on the concept of ``trickle down'' which argues that, in the longer
term, an expanded city revenue base created by central area revitalisation
provides funds that can be used to address social needs. In practice, however,
these funds are generally recycled into further development activity. Nowhere
has a substantial ``trickle down'' effect been demonstrated. The privatisation
of urban development inevitably means accepting a policy of triage and
concentrating on areas of greatest economic potential, with adverse
consequences for other areas.
In Glasgow, despite some involvement by private housebuilders in the outer
estates, the evidence suggests that large-scale regeneration will not occur if
left to market forces. Indeed, it is unrealistic to expect private capital, the
behaviour of which is conditioned by the precepts of risk minimisation and
profit maximisation, to take the lead in redeveloping the peripheral estates.
Easterhouse, (as well as the other outer estates), contains the population of a
medium-sized town. While its disadvantages are apparent, its advantages include
a location on the national motorway network, large areas of developable land, a
resident trainable labour force, and the not inconsiderable ``sweat equity'' of
the local communities (as demonstrated in the Calvay housing co-operative,
Easthall Residents Association, and Easterhouse Festival Society). The catalyst
required to initiate development is a major Government effort similar to that
invested in the GEAR project, or the post-war new towns.
Despite the stark identification of the problems of Glasgow's outer city by
analyses of the last two censuses, and the rhetoric of the Government's New
Life for Urban Scotland report, little has been achieved to alleviate the
difficulties confronting Glasgow's marginalised people and places. In 1993 the
theme of inter-agency co-operation was restated in the formation of the Glasgow
Regeneration Alliance, comprising the local authorities, Glasgow Development
Agency and Scottish Homes, with a remit to invest #1.5bn over 10 years in eight
``priority action areas'' of Greater Easterhouse, Castlemilk, Drumchapel,
Gorbals, Govan, the East End, Glasgow North, and Greater Pollok.
While the improved correspondence between designated action areas and the
revealed areas of need is a positive step critics have questioned how much of
the investment represents ``new money'', as well as the future of the alliance
following the abolition of the regional tier of government in 1996.
To address Glasgow's problems succesfully, urban policy must possess both a
social and economic dimension. It must be concerned as much about the
distribution of wealth as about wealth creation. Such social criteria fit
awkwardly into the conventional balance sheet of economic progress. An
effective attack on Glasgow's problems requires appropriate action at several
scales.
At the national level, a primary requirement is recognition of the fact that
the disadvantaged position of the poor is linked to the privileged position of
the wealthy. This requires enacting a policy that addresses directly the
fundamental question of the distribution of society's wealth. The position of
marginalised populations would also be improved by the creation of a new form
of partnership involving state, capital and citizens.
This would acknowledge the different motives of the partners and enable each to
achieve some of their goals within a framework that facilitates greater
distribution of wealth and opportunity in favour of the disadvantaged. In the
shorter term, easing central Government controls over local authorities would
enable the lower tier to undertake activities of direct benefit to local groups.
Local authorities could promote new forms of tenure and job opportunities by
operating as landowners and developers, or could employ income (eg from council
house and land sales) for the benefit of the disadvantaged areas. Local
government itself must seek to devise more effective strategies to attract
private-sector funding into deprived areas. This will involve both persuasion
(eg via rates relief or flexible planning) and direction (such as linked
development and leverage schemes), with the particular mix depending on the
strength of the local economy.
Local authorities must also accept the principle of subsidiarity. In practice,
this requires for the empowerment of local communities to capitalise on human
resources, and promotion of aided self-help (as pioneered in housing
co-operatives and community businesses).
This will demand a willingness to devolve financial and political power to the
neighbourhood level, with greater participation of residents in budget
formulation and plan preparation for their area. Implementation of such an
agenda is undoubtedly problematic in the short term, not least because it
represents a challenge to the ideology of current urban policy. However, as the
experience of Glasgow demonstrates, failure to achieve policies with an
enhanced social component will ensure that the crisis affecting large sections
of the city will persist well into the twenty-first century.
Since the turn of the century Glasgow has undergone a series of painful
readjustments to changing global economic circumstances, and the modern city
must strive to establish its position in the new world order. Its position as
Second City of the Empire has long gone, and in European terms it is one of a
number of older industrial cities in the throes of regeneration. The world has
moved on and Glasgow has to operate, and increasingly compete, in new political
and economic circumstances.
Most significant of these, and in marked contrast to a time when the city was
at its peak of prosperity, is the rise of a global economic system largely
outwith the control of a single country, or indeed, city. Of equal significance
at the UK level has been the shift in emphasis in public policy and finance
from local to national government.
Both of these structural trends constrain the power of Glasgow to initiate the
necessary social and economic strategies to resolve its current problems. The
task facing the city - to complete a reorientation of its economic base,
restore its economic fortunes, and to ensure fair distribution of the wealth
created - is a daunting one. Only time will tell whether Glasgow is up to the
challenge.
n Professor Michael Pacione is Professor of Geography in the University of
Strathclyde. His latest book entitled Glasgow: the Socio-Spatial Development of
the City has just been published by John Wiley and Sons.
Little has been achieved to alleviate the difficulties confronting Glasgow's
marginalised people and places
</TEXT>
