<HEADLINE>Lunchtime rumbles expose the fault line</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>George Birrell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979138</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE hundred years ago Vesuvius erupted, created a new crater and initiated the
shockwaves of an earthquake which rocked Florence. John Major's early morning
cup of cappuccino followed by a light lunch of pasta and a glass of Chianti
with the Italian Prime Minister Lamberto Dini in that city this week could well
have the same seismic effect on the Labour Party.
It is part of the Prime Minister's grand strategy to win him the next election.
Increasingly, he is convinced the issue which has dogged him and his
predecessor - Europe - is the wildcard which can trump Tony Blair. Forging an
alliance with Signor Dini to oppose the Franco/German plans for a single
currency by 1999, due to be discussed at next week's Madrid summit, is the
first attempt to play it.
No wonder Mr Blair, with his mind on other things, was so flustered during his
visit to Scotland yesterday that he was offering hostages to fortune over the
tartan tax. Apparently it will not be implemented unless the electorate votes
for it. So the assembly will have to be dissolved each time it is proposed.
Will the same be true of Westminster if Gordon Brown as Chancellor wants to put
up taxes? Or will the parliament in London be ruled with an iron fist and that
in Edinburgh with a limp wrist? When will the Scots confined to their creche on
Calton Hill be able to join the grown-ups?
Unfortunately, this faux pas, like others before it seemed to leave Labour
unscathed and the Tories floundering unable, so far, to find an answer as to
how to derail the Blair bandwagon. It is because the Labour leader is an ad
man's dream. He is good looking, articulate, intelligent and the voters
perceive him as courageous and a man of integrity. The media, sensing the
``near inevitability of his Prime Ministership, have reflected this by
unthinkingly conspiring to give him an easy ride. A luxury never permitted
Wilson or Callaghan.
The Conservatives did try to brand him as ``Bambi'' but his squaring up to the
unions over Clause 4 afforded him the opportunity to display his macho
crudentials. Even the accusations that his few declared policies are a ``con''
or that they are ``vacuous'' have fallen on stoney ground, his poll ratings
accelerating with a speed comparable to the American space probe on Jupiter.
The current scare tactics, dreamt up by Tory Central Office, that Blair has a
hidden agenda of socialism, red in tooth and claw, which he will reveal after
election is also pathetic. The public will never swallow it. He is vulnerable
but not in the way those Tory back-room chinless wonders imagine. They will
never come to terms with the Blair phenomenon until they realise it is
underpinned by the man's shrewdness and calculation. Major, in despair, has
fallen back on his own instinct, as he did in the 1992 election when he ignored
these Oxbridge ponces and stepped via his soapbox back to No 10.
This time he again has spotted Labour's (i e Blair's) Achilles heel, Europe. It
is so obvious only those with a First in Greats could have missed it.
Europe is Tony Blair's post-election escape hatch. He is far too clever not to
realise that even a scaled-down version of Labour's economic policy is doomed,
notwithstanding Gordon Brown's cure-all one-off windfall tax. His other problem
is the left in his party who would have the power, depending on the size of
majority, to make him their prisoner.
However, by signing up to the Social Chapter under the Maastricht Treaty, it
will be the European Commission who will determine the pace of socialism in
Britain not the idealists on the National Executive. Furthermore, while the
implementation will disadvantage us against our non-European competitors he
will hope that the protectionism of fortress Europe will cushion that
uncompetitiveness.
He would also want to be bolstered by a powerful, independent Central European
Bank, which, after we have signed up for the Single Currency, would determine
fiscal and monetary policy. It would be like the good old days under Labour in
the mid-1970s when the International Monetary Fund had to be called in to run
our economy. Only this time Labour would be saved that embarrassment and also
that of a sterling crisis. The financial corset of the Bundesbank would stifle
the Loony Left while ensuring measured steps towards Continental corporatism.
Mr Major can expose this deceitful programme by trumpeting the advantages of
Britain's opt-out from the Social Chapter, which has hugely contributed to the
creation of thousands of new jobs from inward investment, by joining with
countries like Italy and Spain in delaying the possibility of a single
currency, and alerting the voters to the consequences of creeping federalism.
It would also be a strong card to play in Scotland where there has been so much
drivel talked about the ``democratic deficit'', particularly from the
Nationalists with their bogus ``Independence in Europe'' platform. If a
``democratic deficit'' - the gap between citizens and institutions - exists
anywhere it is in Europe.
The last thing we want is additional powers to commissioners who are appointed
by governments and who work in secret. The European Parliament is grossly
unrepresentative with one member per 700,000 constituents and such is the
apathy among voters that they are elected on increasingly low turnouts. It has
little power and although in extreme circumstances it could force the
resignation of the Commission, this is as likely as our Queen dissolving the
Commons on a whim. The real power resides with the Council of Ministers over
which the ordinary voter had no direct influence.
This is a genuine debate waiting to take place and which only the Tories can
initiate. It is not anti-Europe it is anti-Federalist but it could scupper Mr
Blair's agenda and create not just a mythical stretch of blue water between the
parties but a yawning chasm.
Not only would it give the electorate the opportunity to have their say on the
kind of Europe they want to see Britain a part of but would present a challenge
to Mr Blair which so far the Tories have failed to deliver.
They will never get away with depicting Mr Blair as an ogre. But the issue of
Europe will represent a dignified test of his sincerity - or lack of it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>An ode to modern living</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ann Donald</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra sanctuary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979139</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ann Donald wanders through the rooms of poet Edwin Morgan
FRESH from a jam-packed week of readings and part of Glasgay!, Edwin Morgan,
one of Scotland's best-loved poets, is at home to a nosy journalist curious to
check out the room where the illustrious and industrious 75-year-old has
created such timeless and cosmopolitan works to be found in collections such as
From Glasgow to Saturn, The New Divan, and more recently a translation of the
highly-acclaimed play Cyrano de Bergerac.
Stepping through the frosted-glass sliding doors that separate the
workroom/living room from the rest of the flat, is to a degree like stepping
back in time. Were it not for the hi-tech video and TV then this could very
well be a comfortable, domestic scene imported direct from a sixties sitcom,
with its black shiny vinyl settee and comfy chairs, green mosaic coffee table,
elaborate standing window boxes, and durable ``period'' typewriter which takes
pride of place at the worktable.
``I was one of the first to move into this block when it was built in 1962,''
Morgan says of his 30-year-old home, before adding with a smile - ``I still
think of it as my `modern flat'.''
Given the flat's central location and Morgan's reliance on Glasgow's public
transport system it was ideal when he was lecturing in literature at the
University of Glasgow throughout the sixties, seventies, and eighties. This
particular room, which has the bonus of facing both south and west, and is thus
privy to as near to a Mediterranean amount of sunshine that Scottish weather
permits, also proved to be more comfortable to write in than the proposed
``claustrophobic'' study or indeed his short-lived timeshare holiday home
overlooking Loch Rannoch.
``I'm a real city person so I like to look out of my windows at the people
walking by and listen to the noise of the traffic,'' he reveals before
proceeding utterly to destroy that glorious Wordsworthian myth of the tortured
writer seeking his muse among the bracken and heather of a silent countryside.
``I thought going up to Loch Rannoch I would be able to shut myself away from
all the modern distractions and just write like mad,'' he says. ``But I looked
out at the loch and trees and just didn't feel inspired. I missed all the noise
so I sold it,'' admits the confirmed urban dweller with a shrug.
It is here, then, on his sensible and sturdy original 1962 model of a German
Adler Bluebird typewriter, that Morgan types away in the afternoons or evenings
on whatever constitutes his current project, be it poetry, plays, or
translations. ``This is extremely well-made,'' he nods, giving the machine a
friendly pat, ``and it does for my purposes very well.''
Though not a Luddite by any stretch of the imagination - the hi-tech fax and
dinky photocopying machine in his study testify to this - he is unwilling to
trade in the reliable Adler for an alien computer. ``I bought an Amstrad once
but I never got to really love it,'' he sighs. ``It's just an age gap I suppose
but I like to type and see the whole object in front of me rather than write a
poem on a computer when it may disappear if the computer crashes or there's a
power cut as happened here a few weeks ago.''
The workdesk the compact Adler rests upon has a very orderly army appearance
with the essential tools of any scribe neatly laid out in rows: a stapler, a
punch, multi-coloured glass paperweights, calculator - to calculate those
author advances? - sharpened pencils and neatly stacked piles of notes for a
future project. ``These are for a collaborative work with the saxophonist Tommy
Smith at the next Jazz Festival,'' says Morgan as he flicks through a handful
of picture postcards of wild Scottish animals that form the visual inspiration
for the proposed series of poems called Beasts of Scotland, which are intended
to inspire Smith's own creative jazz juices.
Visual inspiration also comes via the cluster of eclectic paintings that face
Morgan's workdesk and are scattered throughout the flat. A number of Glasgow
Boy Peter Howson's less stridently macho works, unrecognisable in their beauty
of colour and delicacy of touch, decorate the hall and living room.
Turning his gaze from the most recent acquisition - a small allegorical version
of Cain and Abel, Morgan then points out his favourite, The Head. ``I love the
extraordinary expression on the man's face,'' he says peering closer into the
very whites of the portrait's startled eyes. As well as Howson and a
shoe-box-sized Stephen Campbell in the hall, other artists culled from a
typical RSA roll-call include Pat Douthwaite's abstract interpretation of the
pursuit of Greek goddess Rhea by Zeus and a beautiful evocative Joan Eardley
street scene of children outside a sweetie shop, which so moved Morgan that he
was inspired to write the simply titled poem, ``To Joan Eardley''.
The unquestionably dominant interior feature in Morgan's home is of course the
thousand of books which he reveals are to be gifted to the Mitchell Library in
the event of his death. ``They come round every Hogmanay to collect a batch,''
he chuckles. ``It's the only way I have of keeping them under control.'' Indeed
a fleeting glance at the vast selection of English and foreign literature
adorning the walls of his study and hall not only suggest the words ``Brazilian
rain forest'' but makes one realise what a tremendous coup the Mitchell have
pulled off in being the lucky recipients of Morgan's personal library.
In the dark study where he confesses, somewhat abashed, that he only comes ``to
hide from the cleaning woman every week'' there is the Scottish literature
section that encompasses everything from medieval Scots to Irvine Welsh, a
comprehensive A to Z of modern twentieth-century poetry, countless shelves of
musty leather-bound bibliographies, anthologies and dictionaries, before the
paper trail explodes out into the hall which in turn boasts a foreign
literature collection that would give the British Library a serious run for its
money.
Let's hope that the Mitchell have to wait a good few years yet before they get
their hands on the contents of Morgan's workplace.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>J. P. Leach</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979140</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STUDIES have shown that British people, when faced with American know-how often
have a bit of an inferiority complex. Not that I'm saying Americans are
arrogant, just that when the average American starts to talk, they tend to
speak as though they have a right to be arrogant.
We don't feel inferior to all Americans, especially not those who take part in
TV talk shows dealing with ``human stories''. It's difficult to be impressed by
someone who's bubbling away on national TV while there's a caption flashing
beneath them saying ``Bettye-Soo: Broke up with boyfriend because of his
cocaine-addicted dog''.
So, chat show guests apart, we all agree that the Yanks in general have a good
reputation, and as they say in Louisiana, when they talk turkey, they don't
mean stuffin'. Maybe they get their image from the films, where the hero is
inevitably a square-jawed WASP who has a full grasp of science, arts, and car
maintenance. After watching them for years, we assume Americans are all like
that.
Except Jim Carrey. We know he's not smart because, Hollywood tells us, he is in
the process of becoming a huge star because of his ability to make his face
look funny while speaking in a hilarous manner. Although careers have been
built on this, as per, say Malcolm Rifkind, it's unlikely that he will do as
well as the film bosses think. So except for tele-emotional cripples and Jim
Carrey, Yanks have a fairly good reputation, right?
This is what had me worried when I was there for a few days last week. I had to
go to Baltimore to give a talk on a subject that is far too boring for a
respectable family newspaper. The Americans at the conference were exactly the
sort of smart, Apple Pie guys that would grace any film screen, and that's what
put the fear of Gawd into me. I don't mind making a fool of myself on my home
patch, but I don't want to look too stupid in the Land Of the Free, and if
anyone was going to catch me out it was these smarter, harder working, fitter
more committed Americans.
Everyone in America is extremely pleasant, but they are all congenitally unable
to understand the clear-cut tones and slow diction that characterises typical
Glaswegian speech. After the first two days where everyone thought I was Irish,
Norwegian or German, I had slowed down my words significantly. Even if they
didn't understand what I was saying, at least they all realised I was Scottish.
I thought I was ready for my talk.
On the big day I really felt terrible. The day creaked along slowly, and my
palms got sweatier as the appointed hour got nearer. I remember the chairman
calling my name, and Glasgow being pronounced (as always by Americans) as Glass
Cow. The soundtrack for the next few seconds is just the double boom of the
blood rushing through my head. My voice was at first exactly like the teacher's
voice in the Charlie Brown cartoons, and for what seemed like an eternity, the
audience went quiet.
I got to the punchline of my first gag. Nothing. There were a few loud guffaws
from the back, and slowly the rest of the audience got the cue that I had made
a joke. My nerves disappeared. I had thought that they would all be too serious
to ever laugh. You only have to see any sitcom other than the two good ones to
realise that their tolerance for cruddy jokes is actually quite high.
The next day, I went on a present-buying spree. I make a better job of buying
presents in America than my gran used to. In the sixties and seventies she used
to return from the States with her case full of gimmicky nonsense: case-loads
full of tat like Santa-shaped napkin rings, fridge magnets and Kids' drinking
straws that had been moulded into amusing curly shapes. We had Scotland's
biggest collection of American junk, the entire New York branch of
Fridge-Magnets R Us having been bought up by my gran.
Anyway, as part of a family tradition, I was paying for my collection of
camel-shaped monogrammed coasters when the young blonde cashier spotted my
accent. She said that Scottish accents like mine were, and I quote,
``beautiful''. I drew in my stomach and gave a sort of David Hasselhoff smile,
and in a cool, but basically suave manner, I joked that it would be beautiful
if only people could understand me. She fell for this obvious compliment
fishing. ``Not at all, I understand you easily,'' she gushed. ``You're easier
to understand than some of my friends, and English is their first language!'' I
gave up and sneaked out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
