<DOCNO>GH951209-000068</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000068</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Postcards from the outer edge</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ann Shaw</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979142</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE tall, bearded figure of Dr John Macleod is a well kent and familiar face
among the small population of North Uist. He's unlikely ever to forget the
faces his patients either, many of which have been captured on film during his
island rounds. More than most of his colleagues, Dr Macleod can provide a
complete picture of the place he lives and works in, and the people who give
the place its unique flavour.
As a keen photographer, he always carries a camera with him, and over the past
20 years he has built up a collection of photographs recording the fascinating
social history of the island.
Today almost all the 1700 patients he shares with his colleague, Dr Peter
Keiller, are acces-sible by car. The practice covers more than a hundred square
miles and is totally rural with the main consulting rooms in the health board
premises overlooking Lochmaddy Bay.
``This is a very scattered practice and we do a lot of work in homes,''
explains Dr Macleod.
Dr Macleod was born and brought up on the island where both his parents were
doctors. He trained in Glasgow and graduated in 1963. Before returning to the
Western Isles in 1973 he worked both in Aviemore and London where he met his
wife, Lorna, a nurse who comes from Bristol.
They have three children, Alasdair, currently studying marine science at
Glasgow University; daughter Beth doing community sport at Strathclyde
University, where she plays rugby for West of Scotland Ladies. She is also in
the Scotland A squad. Their youngest, Torquil, is still at school in Edinburgh.
``This is still a close-knit community,'' says Dr Macleod. ``And the number of
Macdonalds and Macleans can be confusing.''
Crofting, fishing for lobster, crab and prawn and seaweed harvesting plus some
employment with the local authority or the army base in Benbecula, provide the
main source of employment.
People live to a great age on the island with many in their eighties and
nineties. Because of the stable population living in one of the most
stress-free environments in the world, it provides a useful microcosm for
scientific studies. Among the ongoing projects are ones looking at certain
viruses, radioactivity and hypertension. The practice is responsible for
Lochmaddy Hospital which has 23 geriatric beds serving North Uist, Benbecula
and part of South Uist.
Daliburgh Hospital, some 40 miles south, has facilities for basic surgery. The
most common referrals are for hypertension and arthritis both of which are more
common than elsewhere.
The accident rate is very low because the crofters and fishermen are extremely
careful but if an emergency does arise they are flown to Glasgow or Stornoway
using the Scottish Air Ambulance Service or occasionally the coastguard
helicopter.
Dr Macleod is very active in the community and is a keen sailor, fisherman and
gardener as well as photographer. He is an authority on rural medicine and
writes frequently in the medical press on the subject. He is also a founder
member of the World Association of Rural Doctors and the Group for Rural and
Isolated Practitioners in Europe. Next year sees him heading for China in May
where he will be speaking at the first-ever world conference on rural medicine
in Shanghai.
He may well be remembered, however, for his role in recording the history of an
island and its people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Court told of MP's threat to kill wife</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979143</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE estranged wife of Tory MP David Ashby told the High Court yesterday of the
night her husband pointed a knife at her and said: ``I'm going to kill you.''
Mrs Silvana Ashby, 52, giving evidence on behalf of the Sunday Times which the
MP is suing over allegations that he is homosexual, dropped in at his
constituency home in Ravenstone, Leicestershire, late at night in June this
year.
She found her 55-year-old husband, from whom she separated in November 1993,
sitting with retired civil servant, Mr Edward O'Byrne, in front of the
television.
She thought Mr O'Byrne was a constituent, until her husband said: ``How dare
you come here without being invited.''
She told Mr Justice Morland and the jury: ``I realised then that something
wasn't right.''
She looked at Mr O'Byrne and asked if he was a friend of Dr Ciaran Kilduff,
with whom the paper alleges Mr Ashby is having an affair.
``My husband went mad and flew at me. He grabbed me by the neck and knocked my
head against the wall by the radiator.
``He emptied my handbag. My cigarettes and lighter came out. He lit a
cigarette, took up a lighter, and picked up the corner of my skirt, saying,
`I'm going to burn you'.
``He put the cigarette close to my face and said, `I'm going to burn you'.''
Mrs Ashby said she went into the kitchen and her husband took a very long
knife, pointed it at her, and said: ``I'm going to kill you.''
She dialled 999 but he pulled the plug out of the phone and went at her again
with the knife.
``I was very, very worried. But when he said he was going to kill me, I said,
`Do it, do it, if you have the courage. I will be dead, but you will be in
prison forever'.''
Later, she said to her husband: ``My God, David, you make me sick. First of
all, you are going for young boys. Now you are going for old and crippled men.''
Mr Ashby, MP for Leicestershire North West, is claiming damages over
allegations that he shared a double bed with a man friend during a holiday in
Goa at the end of 1993.
Times Newspapers Ltd and former Sunday Times editor Andrew Neil deny libel.
They accept that Mr Ashby did not holiday with a man in Goa but assert that he
was, and is, having an affair with 32-year-old Dr Kilduff.
Mr Ashby's counsel, Mr Geoffrey Shaw QC, said Mr Richard Hartley QC, for the
newspaper, claimed that nowadays no-one thought the worse of a man for being a
homosexual.
``Do you,'' he asked.
``Yes, I do,'' said Mrs Ashby.
The hearing was adjourned until Monday, when Mrs Ashby's cross-examination will
continue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Battling Blair wins on points in business charm offensive</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent                                                      ...</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979144</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE business community got its chance yesterday to put Labour under pressure
over its policies on enterprise and the constitution, but party leader Tony
Blair emerged from his audience with them in Edinburgh without a mark on him.
He won warm applause from a potentially sceptical gathering at the Edinburgh
International Conference when he concluded: ``This country cannot afford the
sterile ideological debates of the past. I believe this country needs a new
start.
``I want to do it with people such as yourselves. We may not always agree but
for heaven's sake let's keep the dialogue going because our country's future is
the most important thing.''
The members of the Edinburgh Chamber of Commerce and Enterprise fell to the
Blair charm offensive with surprisingly little resistance. ``The message I want
to bring to the Scottish business community is a simple one,'' he said. ``My
party understands that companies in Scotland and the rest of Britain are
selling in an increasingly tough and competitive world. You need a Government
which backs, not blocks, your efforts.''
He pointed out that business people in London and the North of England were
increasingly warming to the idea of decentralisation and local decision-making
by strategic authorities in their own areas, and the Government's announcements
last week had effectively conceded that there was a problem.
While nationalists would tear Britain apart, he said: ``The economic advantages
of the union, the ties of common history, of family, of common interest are far
too strong to contemplate breaking apart. I would never agree to anything which
threatened the Union.''
Devolution, he said, would leave access to markets, the regulation of financial
services, and business taxation all unaffected, and it was nonsense to suggest
that the power to vary income tax by 3p would automatically be used.
Devolution in Europe had in many cases been an ``aid to prosperity - so too it
can be in Scotland if the opportunity is grasped.''
He told them that under the Conservatives the UK economy had become fragile, a
victim of under-investment, with a neglected infrastructure, too little
innovation and too many people out of work. This could be overcome by a
Government working in partnership with business and taking a more positive
attitude to Europe.
``An underclass isn't just a social evil, but an economic evil as well,'' he
said. ``It should be the task of any government to build greater social
cohesion. I believe we can have a good and decent society in which ambition is
matched by compassion.''
Mr Peter Stillwell, chief executive of Edinburgh Chamber, said Mr Blair had
brought a positive message to businessmen but concerns that Scotland could have
higher taxes than the rest of the UK had not been answered.
The audience had been strangely subdued, given the opportunity to question the
Labour leader. Although the question of potentially higher income tax was
raised the attack was never pressed home.
Businessman Donald Hardie expressed fear that Scots would demand ever greater
public spending beyond the ability of the 3p on income tax to cope. He said the
business community was electorally powerless.
But Mr Blair called this ``intellectually sloppy'' and said we lived in a
democracy where the will of the people had to be accepted, and that politicians
would compete for the votes of the Scottish people.
``I dare say the Conservatives will stand,'' he said.
``It would be odd to have a body with this sort of power that didn't have some
responsibility for its own finance. If you raise taxes you have to face the
electorate - that, after all, is democracy.''
Mr John Mackenzie, managing director of an Edinburgh electrical engineering
company, said later: ``He did not address the problems facing the Scottish
economy, the problems of having a separate government detached from England.
``I employ 100 people, I am concerned about the future.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>British envoy's ordeal over</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979145</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICE have rescued a British Embassy worker who had been held by Colombian
guerrillas for nearly four months.
Staff Sergeant Timothy Cowley, an assistant to the embassy's defence attache,
was kidnapped on August 12 while on a bird-watching expedition near El Toche,
100 miles west of Bogota.
Alberto Villamizar, who heads the government's anti-kidnapping efforts,
confirmed that police had rescued Cowley, but would not go into detail.
Early reports indicated that a Cowley had been kidnapped by a small left-wing
guerrilla band, the Jaime Bateman Cayon group. However Villamizar said the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, known as the FARC, were responsible.
It is the largest of several rebel bands which have been fighting the
government for more than 30 years.
Rebels often kidnap people and demand large ransoms for their release, but
Villamizar said that neither the British Government nor Cowley's family had
paid a ransom.-AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mujahideen `will quit Bosnia'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From KURT SCHORK Sarajevo, Friday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979146</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BOSNIA pledged today to remove all foreign Islamic fighters from the country as
required by the Dayton peace deal and to reassure Sarajevo Serbs that they will
be safe when their districts come under government control.
Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic gave the pledges to US peace envoy Richard
Holbrooke, chief architect of the deal agreed in Dayton, Ohio.
``We are very encouraged,'' Holbrooke said after talks with the Bosnian leader.
``President Izetbegovic assured us, most importantly, that all foreign elements
that are within the control of the (Muslim-Croat) Federation will be removed in
30 days or less.''
In the US, politicians have expressed fears at the presence in Bosnia of an
estimated 4000 foreign Islamic troops, known as mujahideen, who have been
fighting with the Muslim-led government army.
US officials are keen that the mujahideen depart promptly to minimise the
possibility of guerrilla attacks against the 60,000-strong Nato peace force,
one-third of them Americans.
Izetbegovic told reporters that his government would do more to reassure Serbs
across Bosnia of their safety, and would step up efforts to explain the Dayton
accord to those living in parts of Serb-held Sarajevo due to fall under
government control.
``Our opinion is, the Serb part of the population is not fully informed of the
provisions of the Dayton agreement,'' said Izetbegovic. ``They are influenced
by propaganda. We will be sending strong messages to the Serb population that
they will be fully secure.''
Serb residents have been demonstrating against the handover and threatening to
flee after burning their homes.
In Serb-held parts around Sarajevo the mood was one of pessimism and
resignation, as many civilians were reported to be preparing to quit their
homes if their areas come under government control.
``Everyone is preparing to leave, making plans, packing boxes. They're just
waiting for the police to let them drive out,'' said one civilian.
Bosnian Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic stressed there could be no renegotiation
of the Dayton deal and dismissed Serb protests against its terms as ``pure
theatre''.
Silajdzic rejected a suggestion for a blanket amnesty for all Serbs in the
city. However he stressed his government was keen to ensure the Dayton deal was
implemented ``because we can't win (if war resumes) and they can't win. It
would just go on and on.''
PATRICK BROGAN writes: The US Senate faces a difficult debate on Bosnia next
week and a vote on the president's policy on Wednesday, the day after the
Dayton agreement is to be formally signed in Paris.
It is likely that an agreed version will be approved. However in the House of
Representatives, 201 of its 435 members have signed a letter to the president
saying: ``We urge you not to send ground troops to Bosnia.''
Mr Clinton intends to do so - indeed, the first 1500 are already there -
whatever Congress rules, so the debate next week will have a different cast.
The administration, supported by Senator Bob Dole and other leading
Republicans, will argue that the president's decision has committed the United
States, and any attempt to reverse it, by Congress, will be severely damaging
to America's role in the world.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cancer study targets social class Research bid to explain different survival rates</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979147</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOUR hundred women may help a Scots doctor discover why affluent women are more
likely to get breast cancer but poorer women are more likely to die from it.
Dr Una Macleod will carry out her research in Greater Glasgow, where the
population of almost a million includes areas with some of the best, and some
of the worst, health profiles in Europe.
Yesterday, Dr Macleod, who is based at Glasgow University's department of
general practice, acknowledged that many of the women in the study will be dead
before it is completed.
Her research will involve women who developed breast cancer in 1992-93 from
across the spectrum of affluence and deprivation.
As many as 20% of the sample will have died before they are subject to detailed
study and the information Dr Macleod needs will come from their case notes.
``I will be talking to the rest but, by definition, I will be talking to some
women who aren't going to survive at the end of the day,'' she added. ``We
won't know which, because breast cancer is so unpredictable. Even after five
years, we can't be absolutely certain it has been beaten for good.''
Why affluent women should be more prone to breast cancer is not known but diet
and reproductive patterns have been suspected. (Starting a family early reduces
the risk.)
Dr Harry Burns, director of public health for Greater Glasgow Health Board,
told The Herald earlier this year: ``More than half of all women who live in an
affluent area and develop breast cancer will survive. Despite receiving
identical treatment, more than half of all women with breast cancer living in
poor areas will die.''
Whether women in affluent areas do, in fact, receive a different standard of
care to those in deprived areas is one of the issues being investigated by Dr
Macleod, who holds the Cancer Research Campaign's research training fellowship
in primary care oncology, the first of its kind in the UK.
The National Lottery is paying the #205,000 cost of the research, which will
also aim to determine the ideal balance of care between hospital and GP care
for women with cancer and whether women from deprived areas have additional
needs for psycho-social support.
The most obvious possibility - that women from deprived areas are in a more
advanced stage of disease before they seek treatment - has already been
discounted, even though women from lower social classes are less likely to be
screened.
``We know from a previous study in Glasgow that women in deprived areas don't
present any later or turn up with nastier cancers,'' said Dr Macleod:
``Contrary to expectations, when they presented they were from a pathological
base that was roughly equivalent. If that had not been the case, the answer
would be relatively simple.
``The Thames Cancer Registery looked at a very similar thing to the Glasgow
study and proved exactly the same thing. They were looking at larger numbers
and came out with the same results.
``So it is nothing to do with time of presentation; that leaves you with
biological factors, lifestyle or patterns of care. There are not a lot of
things we can change but if we detect something different in terms of the
package of care, we can change it - that is why it appeals to me.
``Even if we prove there is no difference in that respect then at least it
points us in another direction. Presumably it is linked up to life-style in
some way, no doubt some hereditary factors could be involved, but that is so
complex.''
``There is no doubt that affluent women are more likely to get it. It is a
significant difference.''
The role of GPs is particularly important since breast cancer is a disease that
tends not to entail prolonged periods in hospital. Questionnaires have been
sent to family doctors in Greater Glasgow, Forth Valley, Lanarkshire, Ayrshire
and Arran, and Argyll and Clyde, and the replies are already coming in to help
form a benchmark.
Dr Macleod and her colleagues will also look at the educational needs of GPs
dealing with breast cancer but diagnosis is unlikely to be the crucial issue.
Dr Macleod said: ``Nowadays, if a woman goes to her GP with a suspected lump on
her breast, it will be treated seriously. Even if he doesn't think it is
anything serious, it will be checked.''
q.Women are three times more likely to develop breast cancer if they encounter
severely stressful events like bereavement, new research suggests.
Scientists at King's College Hospital, London, found that about half the women
they studied who developed cancer had experienced at least one severely
stressful life event in the previous five years.
</TEXT>
