<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>First black cavalryman may resign As a lonely new trooper feels the pressure, old soldiers fight on for justice</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979148</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE first black Army trooper to ride beside the Queen on state occasions is
considering quitting, it was disclosed yesterday.
But former postman Mark Campbell has refused to make an official complaint of
racism.
The Ministry of Defence confirmed that allegations of racial abuse were being
investigated.
It is understood that when Trooper Campbell, from Sedgley, near Wolverhampton,
was interviewed by the Army's Special Investigations Branch, he said he would
not make an official complaint ``at this time''.
The Army bent the rules to allow a man of his age into the ranks of the
Household Cavalry mounted regiment earlier this year.
But its faith was well rewarded when the 28-year-old won the Jackson Shield for
being the best turned-out cavalryman during his 20-week training.
``When he passed out on August 11, he was clearly a well-trained and good
soldier,'' said an Army source.
At the time, Trooper Campbell said: ``Race should not be an issue; it's no
problem to me. I'm just happy to serve.''
He was immediately thrown into ceremonial duties and made his first public
appearance during the VJ Day commemorations as one of 18 troopers escorting the
Queen.
However, he faced two serious problems - the strain of being the solitary black
face in the Household Cavalry and a serious skin complaint caused by the
traditional plumed helmet and metal chin strap.
He received medical treatment for the rash in October but it did not improve
and that is when the problems began.
As he could no longer take part in ceremonial duties, he was transferred to the
regiment's training section at Windsor. Clearly unhappy to be away from London,
he asked his commanding officer if he could be returned to the capital.
It was explained there was no job available for him in London as he could no
longer take part in duties requiring him to wear the regimental helmet.
Trooper Campbell then made accusations that one of the reasons he was unhappy
at Windsor was because people were using racially abusive words.
The CO immediately called in the Special Investigations Branch to interview
Trooper Campbell, who explained the strain he felt at being a ``novelty'' to
the regiment and the pressure from media attention.
However, he admitted he had never been picked on or harmed in any way and
refused to make a complaint of racial abuse.
The Army is keen to keep Trooper Campbell, who still has two years of his
three-year commission to run, and he may be offered a different post in the
regiment or even a switch to another unit.
``It is a messy situation,'' said an Army source. ``He is obviously a good
soldier and it is a great pity it has turned out this way.''
Accusations of racial abuse surfaced in the black newspaper The Voice, which
quotes a friend of the trooper as saying: ``If people had to go through what
I'm going through, they wouldn't hang on for a week.
``When you have to make a decision between hanging on in there and your life,
what are you going to choose?''
The Ministry of Defence said: ``Trooper Campbell has not been kicked out of the
Army. Allegations of racial abuse are being investigated and, if proven,
disciplinary action will of course be taken.''
An Army spokesman said: ``We condemn all forms of racism. The Services are
committed to a range of measures to increase ethnic minority recruiting.''
The Prince of Wales has played an active part to boost the recruitment of
blacks to elite regiments.
A spokeswoman for St James's Palace, while refusing to comment on individual
cases, said: ``It is well known that the prince called together a group
representing the regiments and the recruitment side to try to get more people
from ethnic minorities into that part of the Army.''
The prince, she said, still believed in the need for progress: ``He has been
following progress with some interest and it is something that he is still
keenly interested in.''
</TEXT>
