<HEADLINE>CIA lies fuelled Cold War arms race</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From PATRICK BROGAN Washington, Friday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979149</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE CIA now concedes that throughout the 1980s, at least, it supplied false
estimates of Soviet military strength to the American Government.
Soviet agents and moles within the CIA convinced the agency that the Soviet
Union was far more powerful than it was, and the Americans therefore spent more
on defence than was needed.
The director of the agency, John Deutch, made a report to Congress on the
ill-effects of Aldrich Ames, the CIA official who worked for the KGB from 1985
onwards. The report was released today.
Its most paradoxical conclusion is that since the CIA was misled about Soviet
strength, believing that the USSR was a rapidly increasing threat to the West
when in fact it was in the process of disintegration, it induced the US to
build up its armed forces extravagantly. This, in turn, led the desperate
Soviet government to try to match President Reagan's military expansion, and
hastened the USSR's collapse.
This was not what the KGB had in mind when it fed false information to the
unsuspecting CIA. There was a hot debate here during the 1980s on whether to
believe the CIA's alarming reports.
The hawks believed that the USSR was spending 15% or even 20% of a high GNP on
arms, and therefore demanded enormous sums for the Pentagon.
In fact, the CIA was wrong both about the amount of money the Soviet armed
forces were getting and the strength of the Soviet economy. Partly for
ideological reasons - he saw the USSR as an ``evil empire'' and a danger to the
United States - Reagan believed the hawks.
That, in turn, sharply increased the budget deficit and the national debt, a
development that has profound effects on American politics to this day.
The Deutch report specifies ways in which Ames damaged the United States. He
betrayed a long series of American agents to the KGB, and the methods of
espionage and running double-agents. He also helped the Soviets provide
disinformation to the agency.
The CIA came to doubt the accuracy of some of the reports it was receiving from
its supposed agents, suspecting them of being double agents, but all the same
passed on their claims to the president, Pentagon, and state department. The
Senate committee's two leaders both denounced the agency today for knowingly
passing on false information.
Certainly if it did so, presumably because of the dominant ideological mind-set
in Washington at the time, it contributed to the grotesque over-spending by the
Pentagon of the Reagan years and to the present political crisis over balancing
the budget.
q.Russian submarines have shadowed US missile subs and aircraft carriers off
the east and west coasts of the United States in recent months, the US Navy
said today. Officials said the surprising flurry of activity showed a
commitment by cash-pressed Moscow to a hi-tech submarine fleet.
</TEXT>
