<HEADLINE>Eagle eye will stay on drugs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES FREEMAN Home Affairs Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979150</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHIEF Constable Leslie Sharp of Strathclyde yesterday promised the region's
drugs culture that his 7000-plus force would still be sitting on top of them,
although the UK's most successful drugs purge officially has ended.
Operation Eagle has swooped on 6000 people who were charged with drug offences
in the last 180 days. Drugs worth #5m at certified street value were seized,
close on #1m of that in the last week.
Almost 14,000 people were searched, 2673 were detained under the influence of
drugs, 40 guns and nearly #500,000 in cash were recovered. Possibly the most
important figure, however, was that police received 11,000 intelligence reports
from the public.
Assistant Chief Constable John Welsh told a seminar in Glasgow that previous
thinking which had concentrated on the targeting of a handful of Mr Bigs was
wrong.
Eagle had confirmed that the street drug dealers were major players and should
be the key targets. Despite its enormous impact, said Mr Welsh, it had also
confirmed that Strathclyde was awash with drugs.
</TEXT>
