<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ebola virus strikes again Liberian has disease that killed 250 in Zaire</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979151</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Abidjan, Friday
A NEW case of the deadly Ebola virus has been found in the Ivory Coast, the
World Health Organisation said tonight.
The patient is a 25-year-old Liberian man who was admitted to a hospital last
week near Tabou, a coastal city on the Liberian-Ivory Coast border.
Tests carried out at the Pasteur Institute in Paris confirmed the disease.
The Ebola fever, whose symptoms include massive internal bleeding, killed 250
people earlier this year in an outbreak around the town of Kikwit in Zaire.
The fear is that the disease could easily spread in the Ivory Coast city of
Tabou, which is jammed with Liberians who fled across the border during their
country's six-year civil war.
Tabou itself is an overcrowded, dirty city, and the villages around it are
little more than refugee camps with dozens of people sharing cramped shacks.
This is the first case discovered since the Kikwit outbreak was officially
declared over on August 24. WHO was told of it on Wednesday and sent a team of
experts to the area within 24 hours.
The French aid agency Doctors Without Borders, the UN High Commissioner for
Refugees, and the Ivory Coast Health Ministry were today all working with the
WHO to prevent a fresh epidemic, the government said.
``The patient's condition is clinically good,'' said a senior health ministry
official. He said the man was under observation in a tiny village called Gozon,
near Tabou.
Ebola, a virus named after a river in northern Zaire where it first appeared in
1976, kills by attacking internal organs and causing massive bleeding. It is
spread by direct contact with infected blood or body fluids and has no known
cure.
Scientists suspect it has a natural host, probably an animal like a monkey,
which under certain conditions can pass it on to humans.
Microbiologists trying to find out where it comes from and how to cure it say
Ebola remains a difficult virus to detect, trace, and fight.
``We have to recognise that this virus is a very rare event,'' said Graham
Lloyd, an expert in Ebola at the Centre for Applied Microbiology and Research
at Porton Down, Wiltshire.
Lloyd said his laboratory was trying to find a way to diagnose Ebola infection
quickly. The Ivory Coast case seemed to involve a new strain of the virus. ``We
want to understand whether this strain is as virulent,'' he said.
A cure would be a long way off because Ebola presented the same challenges as
many viruses do - they do not trigger the body's immune system properly, and
mutate as fast as the body can manufacture antibodies to put up a fight.
Any cure would have to involve an approach similar to that used by researchers
battling Aids, influenza, and the cold - tackling how the virus replicates
itself and moves in the body.-AP/Reuter.
</TEXT>
