<HEADLINE>Police suspect gang link to murders of ecstasy dealers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES McKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979152</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MORE than one killer could have been involved in the gangland execution of the
three drug dealers shot dead in a lane in Essex.
Police confirmed last night that ballistic evidence proved that more than one
weapon was involved in the shootings.
The three men were murdered in an attack typical of gangland vendettas. The
victims appear to have been lured to their deaths on the pretext of a
clandestine meeting to set up a lucrative drug deal.
Police yesterday confirmed that the victims were known drug dealers, but added
that there was no connection between them and Leah Betts, who collapsed on her
eighteenth birthday and died after taking an ecstasy tablet.
The three were well known in the area for pushing ecstasy. Tabloid newspapers
were quick to link the killings with Leah's death.
The bodies of Craig Rolfe, Patrick Tate, and Anthony Tucker were found at about
8am on Thursday in a Range Rover on an isolated snow-covered farm track at the
village of Rettendon, near Chelmsford.
Detective Ivan Dibley, leading the hunt, said: ``There is nothing to suggest
that they distributed drugs to Leah Betts or her associates at a nightclub in
Basildon.''
All three men were shot twice through the head at close range. One was also
shot once in the torso.
Rolfe's girlfriend of seven years, Donna Jaggers, with whom he had a
six-year-old child, wept as she told a news conference: ``I would just like
anyone who was with them, who knows anything about what happened to them, or if
they    saw anything, to come forward. We need all the help we can get.''
Mr Dibley said the men were ``quite high up'' the drug-dealing hierarchy. They
were, he said, ``about five out on 10'' on a scale of importance.
Asked what he thought might have happened, Mr Dibley said: ``There could be a
power struggle, or there could be a double-cross which has taken place. It
might be that somebody has owed money and hasn't paid their bill.''
</TEXT>
