<DOCNO>GH951209-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fife Council to become water watchdog</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979153</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE new East of Scotland Public Water Authority was warned yesterday that Fife
Council would be playing a watchdog role over its actions once it took over
responsibility for delivering the services.
The Labour leader of the new council, Councillor Alex Rowley, said it was
determined to ensure the public got good value for money. ``We don't want a
Yorkshire Water situation in Fife where the public are paying through the nose
for an inadequate service.''
The regional council, he claimed, was handing over a well-developed
infrastructure and plans for essential future investment to the new public
authority next April. A total of #20m had been invested in improving water and
sewerage infrastructure in Fife.
``We want assurances that the water authority will maintain and, where needed,
increase this level of investment,'' said Councillor Rowley.
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth has already pledged that water rates will
not be allowed to rise by more than 6% next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forsyth playing silly games, claims councils' leader</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979154</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth was accused yesterday of playing ``silly
and futile games'' when he made his recent criticisms of new council structures
as the war of words between the Scottish Office and Cosla resumed yesterday.
In England, Environment Secretary John Gummer did not involve himself in the
structure and operation of individual councils, Cosla's Labour president
Rosemary McKenna told a seminar organised by the Unit for the Study of
Government at Edinburgh University.
She added: ``Cosla doesn't go around criticising the internal structure of the
Scottish Office. That is none of our business and it's equally none of the
Secretary of State's business to criticise the structure of individual
councils.''
If Mr Forsyth was serious about his commitment to devolution and to a new
relationship with local government, he should stop behaving in this way.
The Scottish Secretary had claimed some of the new councils were creating too
large committee structures to allow the payment of special responsibility
allowances to as many members as possible.
Mrs McKenna also warned, in the wake of the financial settlement for local
government next year, that the dawn of the unitary councils would be marked by
the prospect of poorer and more limited services.
She compared the 0.8% increase in spending allowed in Scotland with the 3.1% in
England.
The smaller provision, she claimed, underlined the Treasury's strategy of
trying to bring spending in Scotland into line with south of the border.
Why should it be assumed, she asked, that the right level of spending was the
English one. This was the level which had made 10,000 teachers redundant and
put one million school children in classes of more than 30.
The Scottish Secretary should not underestimate the degree of attachment which
the people of Scotland had to the level of their public services, Mrs McKenna
warned.
</TEXT>
