<DOCNO>GH951209-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Brief break from big freeze</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979155</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MILDER weather will return to Scotland by tonight, according to Glasgow Weather
Centre. However, the respite will be brief, as temperatures are set to drop
again on Monday.
Scotland will have cloud and rain in the far north and north-west today. The
rest of Scotland will be dry with sunny spells, once overnight fog patches
disperse.
``The Western Isles and the north-west have escaped     the worst of the cold
weather but everywhere except the Borders should see a rise in temperature
over the weekend,'' said a Glasgow Weather Centre spokesman.
``The Borders can expect to see more frost but after the weekend it will be
getting slightly colder again for the rest of us.''
After the mildest autumn on record, Scotland has spent the last few days
shivering with the first taste of the cold winter months ahead.
The south of England took the brunt of the bad weather yesterday, with parts of
the coastal region being turned into a ``skating rink'',  according to the
Automobile Association.
The London Weather Centre said yesterday that its forecast up to next Thursday
predicted no more snow but a spokesman added that ``beyond that, we don't
know''.
Meanwhile, skiers are looking forward to the prospects of another bumper season
on the Scottish slopes.
A smattering of early snow is covering the five Scottish resorts but, as yet,
there is not enough to get the tows running over the weekend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scientists hungry for Galileo's first message</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979156</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCIENTISTS were anxiously awaiting today the first transmission of data from
the Galileo space probe, which they hope will be a key to unlock the secrets of
Jupiter.
Meanwhile, as Galileo spent its first day orbiting the solar system's largest
planet, scientists were studying telemetry sent by the spacecraft on its orbit
trajectory.
``We're in almost perfect orbit so any changes will be minimal,'' said lab
spokesman Jurrie Vanderwood.
The first data from Galileo's probe, which plunged into the heart of Jupiter's
gaseous mass last night, were expected on Sunday.
The data transmission, which will consist of the first 43 minutes of the
75-minute transmission from the probe to its mother ship, will continue until
Wednesday.
It will be repeated twice more next month, when Earth and Jupiter will no
longer be blocked by the sun. Transmission of the full 75 minutes will be
completed in February.
One space scientist said information gleaned by the probe could be ``the most
amazing weather report we've ever had''.
The probe passed through clouds of water, helium, oxygen, and nitrogen and
endured hurricane-like winds of 200mph and violent lighting storms as it passed
through Jupiter's atmosphere.
The mission of the 746lb probe has been likened to a journey to the beginning
of time because scientists believe the information it has gathered could unlock
the secrets of how the solar system was formed.
Wesley Huntress, Associate Administrator for Space Science at Nasa, said
Jupiter, in many ways, was a miniature solar system in itself.
``Within Jupiter's constellation of diverse moons, its intense magnetic field,
and its swarms of dust and charged particles, the Galileo mission should
uncover new clues about how the sun and the planets formed, and about how they
continue to interact and evolve,'' he said.
``Right now, we can still only imagine the discoveries that will flow from
Galileo as it travels for months in this most unusual and unearthly
environment.''
During the next two years Galileo will make 11 orbits of the giant planet,
which is 318 times larger than Earth. The spacecraft will have close encounters
with three of Jupiter's largest moons, Ganymede, Callisto, and Europa. It will
also photograph Io from medium range on each orbit.
The mission is set to end in two years' time, when Galileo will make its
farewell transmission before plunging into the Jovian atmosphere and burning up.
q.Fragments of an old Soviet satellite, some weighing more than 440lb, will
fall to Earth tomorrow or on Monday and could hit land, Russian space officials
say.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
