<DOCNO>GH951209-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>National Garden plan takes root</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979157</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PLANS for a #20m National Garden for Scotland were revealed yesterday by TV
gardener Jim McColl.
The Beechgrove Garden co-presenter said the proposal, to create a permanent
centre of exellence for Scotland's amateur gardeners at Plean Country Park,
near Stirling, had won backing from key Government bodies and quangos.
Scottish Enterprise, Forth Valley Enterprise, Scottish Natural Heritage, the
Scottish Tourist Board, and Stirling District Council will meet next week to
consider a consultants' report on the scheme, which could create hundreds of
jobs and attract thousands of visitors a year.
An outline bid has already been put forward to the National Lottery Millennium
Fund to secure a large proportion of the funds needed.
Mr McColl said yesterday: ``What's needed is a centre to serve the amateur
gardeners of Scotland. People are always talking about the lack of information.
You buy a packet of seeds and it says on the back: `Sow in open ground from
March to May.' It doesn't say it's March in Cornwall and May in Caithness. It's
relevant information that people need.''
Plean was selected from more than 16 sites.
Meanwhile, BBC Scotland's Beechgrove Garden, which has more than half a million
viewers weekly, has won the Garden Writers Guild award for best TV gardening
programme in 1995.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stable owner is fined for horse ear incident</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979158</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A STABLE owner was convicted yesterday of assaulting a woman with a horse's ear.
Frank Carberry, 36, was found guilty of throwing the severed ear at Mrs Anne
McConnell on June 12, breach of the peace, and a bail offence.
Sheriff Kenneth McIver, fining him #500, described the incident as an ``assault
of a contemptuous nature meant to cause hurt and upset''.
Glasgow Sheriff Court heard that after Mrs McConnell's favourite horse, Fallon,
a thoroughbred chestnut mare, died of grass colic in a field, an ear was sliced
off.
She later received a telephone call from Carberry asking her to collect what
she believed was documentation from a vet relating to the death.
However, when she arrived with a friend, Miss Carol Tracy, at Carberry's
smallholding on Wester Boghead Road, Lenzie, he pulled the ear from a polythene
bag and threw it at her.
She said Carberry had then shouted: ``Here's your f******
documentation.......you'll get the rest of the horse through the post.''
The sheriff added: ``You went out of your way to cause upset to persons who
were deeply involved in horses......''
The court was told that there was a legal wrangle over debts owed to Carberry's
friend, Mr Charles Swann, relating to rental of a field and stables for a
string of trekking horses run by Mrs McConnell and Miss Tracy.
The women admitted that they had previously breached a court order by removing
horses from a field.
Carberry, who said Mrs McConnell owed him money for horse feed, accused her of
dumping the horse's ear on his doorstep.
He claimed he had simply handed the ear to her and suggested she had rubbed the
ear on her jumper to produce a bloodstain to back up her story.
Sheriff McIver said the issue was one of credibility and told Carberry, a
father of four, that he found the Crown evidence preferable and acceptable,
leaving him in no doubt that he       had thrown the ear at Mrs McConnell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hurd rounds on right wing</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979159</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd yesterday rounded on Tory right-wingers'
demands for greater tax cuts, funded by massive spending reductions.
He warned that failure to back Chancellor Kenneth Clarke would lead to
electoral defeat.
In an outspoken attack which threatens to renew Tory in-fighting over Mr
Clarke's handling of the economy, Mr Hurd said Conservatives would ``certainly
not win'' the next election if the party ``rushed to unreality''.
The Chancellor would need the help of all active Conservatives, Mr Hurd said.
The alternative was not just the election of a Labour government, but the
``collapse under excessive pressure of one or other of the main pillars of our
essential services''.
Mr Hurd told Tory activists in north Oxford: ``A Government which slashed
blindly at public services, pleading some abstract moral imperative or invoking
a political need to put clear water between itself and its opponents, will not
regain sympathy but forfeit it.''
Taxation was too high, he conceded, but only among the ``unreal fevers'' of
Westminster would it seem sensible medicine to sack more teachers in the cause
of cutting taxes even more deeply.
``It is no use blaming the electorate for wanting it both ways. They expect
Government to strike a balance between reasonable taxation and reasonable
public services.''
Mr Hurd's intervention followed sharp criticism of Mr Clarke by senior Tory MPs
after poll evidence showed the Budget had made the Government even more
unpopular.
Mr David Evans, a member of the executive of the influential 1922 committee of
Tory backbenchers said Mr Clarke had ``no nose'' for politics, and Sir Rhodes
Boyson, who also sits on the 1922 executive, said there should have been bigger
cuts in public spending to allow a greater reduction in direct and indirect
taxation.
Meanwhile, in a speech yesterday to Tories in Tiverton, Devon, Treasury Chief
Secretary William Waldegrave said Mr Clarke's Budget paved the way for more tax
cuts.
Mr Kynoch said the centre provided the opportunity for technicians working in
the more traditional industries to upgrade their skills so they could move into
electronics.
All 15 trainees who completed their course this year had gone on to jobs,
mostly in local electronics companies, but the course had been so successful
that two more were now in progesss.
Lets, he said, provided training for unemployed adults in electronics. In
partnership with LEEL, it had helped to train 1000 jobless people for entry
into electronics companies.
Its success rate of trainees going on to secure jobs was 70%.
</TEXT>
