<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MP accuses judiciary of `mad judge disease'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979160</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TORY right-winger yesterday blamed ``liberal, socialist-minded judges and
magistrates'' for rising crime levels and called for the reintroduction of
national service and corporal punishment to deter young thugs.
In an astonishing Commons outburst, David Evans, MP for Welwyn and Hatfield,
complained that some of the judiciary was suffering from ``mad judge disease''
and demanded castration of rapists.
He also suggested, in a debate on crime, that judges should be paid a
percentage of the fines they imposed to encourage them to give sentences ``that
fit the crime''.
He said it might be a good idea to double the #10 Christmas bonus for
pensioners who protected their property by shooting burglars.
``The rise in crime is down to a succession of liberal, socialist-minded judges
and magistrates who have lacked the nerve to give sentences that fit the crime.
``They have failed the Government, failed the police and most of all they have
failed the citizens of this country.
``They criticise the victim for not taking enough precautions and they counsel
and cosset the villains,'' said Mr Evans who was a leading backer of John
Redwood in the Tory leadership contest. Mr Evans said prison worked in
deterring criminals. ``One more scumbag behind bars is one less rampaging
around the streets.''
He called for measures to tackle ``pathetic parents'' who cannot control their
children.
If fines against the parents did not work ``we could put them behind bars with
their children.
``This will give the family some quality time together to reflect on the values
of responsibility and discipline.''
In schools, he said, teachers should be given powers to take on troublesome
teenagers.
``Some children need ticking off, some need a clip round the ear and some need
a bloody good hiding.
``How about the reintroduction of national service? Young people need to learn
the values of discipline, teamwork and a deference to authority.''
Junior Home Office Minister Timothy Kirkhope said Mr Evans had ``his own
particular way of putting things across'' and added: ``I cannot see that some
of those things he is suggesting might immediately be part of Government
plans.''
However, Home Office Minister David Maclean said prisoners should work for
proper pay to stop their families being a burden on the state and pay income
tax.
He was responding to Lady Olga Maitland, MP for Sutton and Cheam, who said
during a Commons debate on crime that jail regimes should be ``relevant'' and
``rigorous'' and prisoners should not watch television, but should do work to
earn their keep.
Mr Maclean said he wanted prisoners to do a proper day's work and pay income
tax.
``I am one of those who believes that if they are actually doing a proper day's
work in prison, rather than sitting round their cells, then it makes sense to
pay them a proper wage and, first of all, deduct money to send to their wives
and families, put money in for a nest egg.
``And, also, I want prisoners to face the same penalty the rest of us face:
it's called income tax.
``And I see no point in them being cushioned from that and their wives and
families being on the state, when, if they were doing a proper day's work in
prison and getting better pay rather than pocket money, then they could
actually have those deductions made.''
He said there were pilot studies looking at improved work regimes ``so
prisoners are doing better things than making mail bags''.
</TEXT>
