<DOCNO>GH951209-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Knife death was accident</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979161</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN whose lover was killed by a foot-long knife which he was holding was
cleared of responsibility for her death at the High Court in Perth yesterday.
Mr John Burns, 38, denied murdering Ms Marie McIndoer, 35, by slashing her neck
in the flat they shared at Whitevale Street, Camlachie, Glasgow.
Lord Clyde acquitted him after upholding a submission by defence counsel John
Morris that he had no case to answer.
Neighbour Peter Kerr, 41, who was visiting the couple, said that a happy
Saturday evening ended with blood spurting from Ms McIndoer's neck after the
accused unexpectedly produced a chef's knife. Police were called and Mr Burns
was found holding a towel to her neck.
As paramedics tended her, a constable said Mr Burns told him: ``It was an
accident. She walked into it. Look, I love her. The knife is under the cooker.''
During a taped interview, played to the jury, Mr Burns was heard to repeat his
claim that the wound was sustained accidentally.
Then he was heard to break down, sobbing loudly when a detective told him that
Ms McIndoer had died soon after admission to Glasgow Royal Infirmary.
</TEXT>
