<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Foreign Digest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>Foreign Digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979164</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Eight killed in
shop rampage
NEW YORK: A gunman went on the rampage at a Harlem clothing store yesterday,
then barricaded himself inside and set a fire that engulfed the building. Eight
people died and five were injured, three critically.
The gunman's body was found in the store with seven others nearby, who police
said had died from breathing smoke. First reports said the incident was a
bungled robbery, but police said the incident could have been part of a
landlord-tenant dispute.
Lama at risk
NEW DELHI: The Indian Government has been asked to tighten security for the
Dalai Lama after the arrest of three people suspected of trying to spy on the
Tibetan spiritual leader. Himachal Pradesh state has asked for a concrete wall
around the Dalai Lama's house in the Himalayan town of Dharamsala, where he
lives in exile, and a bullet-proof car.
Hunch hangings
LAGOS: Three Nigerians, including a 75-year-old herbalist, were sentenced to
hang for strangling a 15-year-old hunchback and cutting off his hunch for use
in a potion. The judge told the herbalist, his 25-year-old son, and a male
relative that their crime was barbaric and they deserved no mercy.
`Zombie' riot
DURBAN: Drunken youths chopped up coffins with axes and stabbed corpses in a
bid to stop the funeral of 10 ``bewitched'' children killed in a road crash in
South Africa. They believed witches had substituted zombies for their bodies,
reported police who had to fire in the air to disperse the youths.
Leader sits up
ATHENS: Ailing Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou was sitting up in his
hospital chair for the first time in two weeks yesterday, following a
tracheotomy operation to ease his breathing. A government spokesman said he
could go home this month, but the 76-year-old leader is still on life-support
machines. Colleagues are calling for a successor while the press is urging him
to quit politics for his own good.
Nobel delight
STOCKHOLM: Irish poet Seamus Heaney will receive the 1995 Nobel literature
prize from King Carl XVI Gustav in Sweden tomorrow. ``For once in my life, I am
permitting myself the luxury of walking on air,'' he said on arriving in
Stockholm this week. In a separate ceremony, British physicist Joseph Rotblat,
87, will receive the Peace Prize for his efforts to eliminate nuclear weapons.
Siege over
MUNICH: Police in Munich ended their second hostage crisis in under nine hours
yesterday, shooting dead a man who threatened to kill his girlfriend and a
policeman. Commandos stormed a bank on Thursday night and rescued three
hostages held by a gunman, all unharmed.
King rests
DUBAI: King Fahd of Saudi Arabia has been discharged from a Riyadh hospital
after a week's treatment for what US officials said was a stroke. The Saudi
court said his younger half-brother Crown Prince Abdullah would assume some of
his duties while the 73-year-old king recuperated.
Killer jumbo
CAIRO: An elephant in Cairo Zoo trampled to death her keeper as he fed her
breakfast, a newspaper reported. Nadia, 32, picked up the 64-year-old man,
threw him to the ground, and trod on him. Keepers said the elephant had
recently been depressed and had attacked other keepers.
Jackson `stable'
NEW YORK: Michael Jackson was in serious but stable condition in hospital after
treatment for an irregular heartbeat which caused him to faint during a
rehearsal on Wednesday night. The pop superstar was being treated for
dehydration, gastro-enteritis and heart, kidney, and liver irregularities
caused by an electrolyte imbalance, his doctors said. His estranged sister
LaToya, however, told a newspaper it was a publicity move.
Ear eaten
FORT WAYNE: A man bit off another man's ear during a bar-room brawl, then
swallowed it when police confronted him. Stevon Sutton still had the ear in his
mouth when police arrived but refused to spit it out. He sucked it in and out
of his mouth several times before swallowing it, police said. Sutton, 32, was
charged with battery and criminal recklessness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Call for change in law on strikes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979165</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LEADING union official told Scots lawyers yesterday that the postal workers'
strike showed it was time to change employment law.
Mr Bill Speirs, Scottish TUC deputy general secretary, said the Government's
employment law had driven the postal workers into taking unofficial strike
action. Yet the Royal Mail, in order to get the strike resolved, had to deal
with the workers' union, even though the action was unofficial.
The danger was, he pointed out, that if a deal could not be done with the union
then the Royal Mail would have no-one left to deal with.
He told the Law Society of Scotland's industrial law group in Crieff yesterday:
``As the unofficial action escalated, the management continued to negotiate
with the union - the only people they could negotiate with.
``As Royal Mail losses mounted to #10m, realisation was dawning on senior
management that they not only had to do a deal with the union officials, they
had to do a deal which was good enough to stick with the members since the
union no longer had any power of disciplinary action because of legislation
introduced by the Tories four years ago.
``The workforce agreed to go back to work on the basis of the deal which the
union had done. But what would have been the consequences if they had refused
to accept their union officials' advice? With whom would Royal Mail bosses have
negotiated, in the critical period running up to Christmas.
Mr Speirs argued that the dispute showed that even some employers may now wish
a shift in the balance of power in employment law back towards the employees.
</TEXT>
