<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Saviour of the slums</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>David Baird</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979166</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HE doesn't look like the popular idea of a missionary, this burly,
down-to-earth Scot with unruly hair and tattooed forearms. Nor does he accept
the old stereotyped missionary's role, that of simply saving souls and bringing
enlightenment to the natives. The Rev Brian Attwell follows a much tougher
route - he believes in practical Christianity and he practises it in one of the
Third World's poorest countries.
He has paid a heavy price, suffering hepatitis, dysentery, angina, septicamia,
and heart attacks. After the most recent attack he was warned he had only three
months to live unless he underwent emergency surgery.
Attwell, aged 50, and his wife Betty, as dedicated as he is, have shouldered a
daunting burden. But they know there is no turning back - some 30 children
rescued from the streets of poverty-stricken Peru depend on them for survival.
In the Hogar San Andres, a rambling old house at Chosica, just outside Lima,
the Peruvian capital, they shelter a collection of innocents whose only crime
was to be born. Though one would never guess it from their bright, shining
faces, each of these children, aged from two upwards, comes from a tragic
background.
Crippled Raul saw his parents killed by terrorists. Pancho was found on a
rubbish-dump. Sweet-faced Anne Maried, aged five, had a drug-addict mother.
Pepe Lucho was thrown on the street when his foster parents learned he was
retarded. Henry, an eight-year-old with a flashing smile, had alcoholic parents.
They are a few of the countless children struggling to survive on the streets
of Latin America. Their parents have disappeared, cannot support them, or have
abandoned them because they are handicapped - in a poor family with a dozen or
so mouths to feed there is no room for the helpless. Unwanted children beg or
steal on the streets, prey to drug traffickers and latter-day Fagins.
Birth control is not common in Peru, a Catholic country of ``macho'' values,
although the authoritarian President Alberto Fujimori is trying to promote it.
And the country has virtually no public safety-net for the destitute and
desperate.
The situation worsened over the past 10 yars when Indians fled terrorism and
hunger in the Andes and flocked to Lima. The Peruvian elite, of mostly Spanish
ancestry and notoriously racist, has little enthusiasm for helping these
``inferior'' descendants of the Incas.
So how did a former bricklayer and heating engineer from Inverness become
involved in their troubles?
There were two turning-points in Brian Attwell's life. The first came when he
was working in the Inverness Royal Infirmary (now closed) as a nurse. There he
met and married Betty, from Peru, who was training as a nurse specialising in
caring for children with special needs.
Then, when he was 30, Attwell, an atheist although he had been brought up a
Methodist, became a believer again. Even now he cannot explain exactly how it
happened.
``I can't say I saw a vision or that anything dramatic occurred,'' he says.
``One day I realised I hadn't done much with my life and that there has to be
something more to our existence. Within six months I decided to take holy
orders, was enrolled in a bible college, and four years later I was ordained in
the Free Baptist Church.''
He and Betty gave themselves one year to raise enough money to go to Peru. They
formed a mission in London to raise funds and in 1983 they flew to Peru on
one-way tickets. There they worked to help the poor in Lima's so-called Pueblos
Jovenes (young towns), grim, dusty slums thrown up in the bleak desert around
Lima.
Attwell dreamed of founding an orphanage and the opportunity came when a former
retirement home for British expatriates, run by the British Benevolent Society,
became available.
``We didn't have the money, #20,000 payable
Continued on Page 14
Continued from Page 13
over three years, but somehow it came in,'' recalls Attwell. ``I never know
where the money is coming from to carry on - it's hand-to-mouth. But somehow
when the need is there the cash appears.''
Thus it was with the latest acquisition, a dilapidated mansion adjoining the
Hogar San Andres (literally St Andrew's Home). It was far too costly to buy,
but an English benefactor raised some cash and lengthy haggling reduced the
price to #16,000.
Now the Attwells and their helpers, including unpaid volunteers, are labouring
to renovate the building. Once finished, it will have two dormitories, a
medical clinic for the children and street people, and a day centre for the
children of poor families.
While supervising the work, Attwell admits: ``It would be much easier just to
build a church and do normal missionary work, trying to win converts. Instead
this is a 24-hours-a-day job. I'm in it now and can't back out. All those kids
depend on us. Without this place, they would either be dead or living like
animals on the street.''
Christian teaching at the orphanage is by example rather than indoctrination
and Sunday is a normal working day. ``We give the kids Sunday school and try to
raise them in a Christian way but without any brainwashing. I see our work as a
form of practical Christianity,'' says Attwell.
The youngsters learn to help one another and those capable of it are sent to
school to prepare them for a normal adult life. A trained nurse is on duty day
and night.
When children arrive, they are usually suffering from severe malnutrition and a
variety of diseases - typhus and TB are common in Peru. ``Many have never had
proper food and don't even know what a plate is. Sometimes we have to give them
a name because nobody knows their true name,'' says Betty Attwell.
Almost every day children have to be turned away. Eventually the home will
accommodate about 40. The Attwells say they do not want more because ``we want
this to be a family rather than an orphanage''.
Cash is not the only problem they face. Difficulty in obtaining qualified
staff, corruption, and mind-boggling red tape are other frustrations.
``It's difficult to get the medicines we need,'' Attwell explains. ``They are
much more expensive here than in the UK. The cheaper ones you find here may
have been watered down and `antibiotics' have been found to be powdered milk.
``Medicine worth $600 and desperately needed for our psychiatric cases has been
stuck in Customs for over a year. The officials want more documents for those
16 kilos than for a whole container shipment and they demand duties totalling
more than the medicine cost.''
The daily battle has taken its toll. Betty, addressed as ``Mama'' by her young
charges, suffers from a bad back and arthritis and Attwell himself can no
longer do heavy physical work. In November, 1993, he had to fly to London for a
double heart bypass operation.
The Hogar San Andres relies for funds on efforts by its mission, a registered
charity, in London. Attwell resists using the services of professional
fundraisers because he feels they take too much in administrative costs.
Nor does he agree with children-sponsoring schemes - ``only the nice-looking
kids get sponsored and also people lose interest after a while, but the
children still need feeding and clothing, day in, day out''.
It costs #100 a month to look after each child, taking all expenses into
account. Children like little angelic-faced Luchito, exact age unknown,
prospects uncertain. Luchito insists on hitting his ears until they bleed. Is
he trying to escape from some dark memory? Nobody knows, because Luchito cannot
talk. But when you look into his dark, sad eyes, he smiles . . .
n The UK contact address of Hogar San Andres is Saint Andrew's Evangelical
Mission, 126 Ealing Road, Brentford, Middlesex TW8 0LD.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
