<HEADLINE>A #300,000 lottery fund gift secures madonna and child</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979167</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A #600,000 painting acquired with the help of a grant of #300,000 from the
Heritage Lottery Fund was handed over yesterday to the National Galleries of
Scotland.
Lord Lindsay, the Scottish Office Arts Minister, who performed the ceremony,
said that, given the theme of the painting, the presentation could not have
come at a more appropriate time of year.
The painting was The Madonna and Child with the Infant Saint John the Baptist
and Attendant Angels, by Guilio Cesare Procaccini, one of the leading Lombard
artists of the early seventeenth century.
The National Art Collection Fund contributed #100,000 to the purchase and the
balance of #200,000 was raised from the galleries' own resources.
Lord Lindsay, handing over the painting to Mr Angus Grossart, chairman of the
board of trustees, and Mr Michael Clarke, keeper of the National Gallery,
called the work ``this exquisite oil painting''.
Mr Clarke said the Madonna and Child was widely recognised as one of the
artist's most beautiful small-scale paintings. It was orginally in the
collection of King Charles I.
Procaccini's work was rarely seen outside Italy and this acquisition enabled
the gallery to display permanently the strongest and most varied selection of
his work in Britain, he said.
The painting was owned formerly by the British Rail Pension Fund and had been
on loan to the gallery since 1979.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Two in Borders have meningitis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979168</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO women in the Borders region have contracted meningitis, Borders Health
Board said yesterday.
A spokesman for the health authority confirmed two patients with meningococcal
infection had been admitted to Borders General Hospital at Melrose earlier this
week. Both are said to be doing well and are expected to make a full recovery.
The cases prompted the formation of an outbreak control committee, led by a
consultant in public health medicine, to meet on Thursday when it was agreed to
continue monitoring the situation.
The health board has alerted GPs in the area and prescribed antibiotics to the
families of the two young women, who have not been named.
The spokesman said that although notification of the infection had risen
earlier this year in England and Wales, this was not the case in Scotland,
where figures had fallen slightly on the numbers reported last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man loses job over pint of milk</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979169</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CIVIL servant with nine years of service has lost his job for taking a pint
of milk without paying for it.
Mr John McArthur, 49, a support manager at the Ministry of Defence's services
unit at Kentigern House, Anderston, Glasgow, had told an industrial tribunal
that there was no-one in the canteen at the time and he intended to pay for the
milk later.
He was seen by two Ministry of Defence police officers.
In its findings, the tribunal said the dismissal procedure had been
``scrupulously fair''.
Management were concerned at the level of thefts from the canteen, which were
running at around #70 a week. They had just held a meeting with the two
detectives.
As they were leaving the restaurant, they saw Mr McArthur walking towards the
service area, take two half-pint cartons from the fridge, and leave. Restaurant
staff were in the kitchen and could be heard but Mr McArthur made no attempt to
attract anyone's attention.
The officers followed Mr McArthur and told him they suspected he was in
possession of stolen property. He said he was going to pay for it later.
Mr McArthur, of Hardridge Road, Corkerhill, Glasgow, said he was on an
emotional high as he was buying his first house and had just received
confirmation of his mortgage. He claimed he was not thinking rationally or
normally.
At his disciplinary hearing, he agreed he had seen notices about pilfering and
the consequences which might follow.
That hearing concluded that he was caught red-handed in the act of theft, the
incident amounted to gross misconduct, his plea in mitigation about his state
of mind at the time was not sufficiently convincing to justify a penalty less
than that of dismissal, and that there was a breakdown of trust and confidence
regardless of the value of goods stolen.
Mr McArthur also had his previous record, which showed no previous disciplinary
action, taken into account.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>In step at nursery school</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>by Jennifer Davis</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979170</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHILE you won't actually have to present your child with his first key to the
door when he starts nursery school, he will be taking a big step down the road
towards independence.
The first days or weeks when he is left alone among a group of strangers can be
daunting for all concerned, but ultimately nursery education should be a high
point in his life, and should help his emotional and social development.
What can you realistically expect him to achieve at nursery school? Strathclyde
region has spent more than five years drawing up a policy document. Partners in
Learning, which it published two years ago. This aims to help people in all
sectors of childcare to understand how young children can be helped to learn
and how to introduce high quality practices into their work routines.
The policy is based on research which shows that although pre-school education
brings immediate benefits in the educational and social development of the
young, if these advantages are to be carried through into adulthood, the
quality of the education must be high.
All of which sounds, and is, very laudable and sophisticated, but seems somehow
highly inappropriate to a group of noisy under-fives. All very well in theory,
but how can it be made to apply to the everyday clamour of the average nursery?
Basically, it is put into practice by simple, straightforward measures which
ensure that children learn to have fun in an atmosphere of professional care
and understanding.
Given that children's attention span is short, their time at nursery is usually
divided between intervals of free play when they can go off and do whatever
takes their fancy, and structured activities, when they are guided through a
set task.
The guided activities tend to focus on developing number and language skills,
using basic techniques of colour and shape recognition. Often these activities
are linked to a general theme, such as the seasons or animals, to widen the
child's general knowledge base.
The free play, which in a sense can be just as guided as the set activities,
allows access to a wide range of textures and experiences. Painting equipment
is often available, along with sand and water play, and the various toys which
the nursery has in stock. Teachers are on hand to help the child explore these
areas, and to try to stimulate imaginative play.
Most important of all, however, is the fact that the children are thrown into
the great social melee of nursery life. They come together on a regular and
what is for them fairly lengthy basis with a group of children of their own age
and start to understand that vast, uncharted territory of social relationships.
They learn how to get along with other people, and how to become what every
parent wants their child to be, if not the life and soul of the party, then a
sociable, friendly and polite individual.
Often parents feel concerned that the papier mache masterpieces which greet
them at hometime look more like a plate of porridge than the skilled Eiffel
Tower type edifice hanging from the coatpeg next door. But in fact, there are
much more important things going on at the multiple levels of nursery life than
the number of tissue roses which can be glued to a paper plate.
However, like all aspects of educational life, it is wise to keep an eye on
your child's progress, and to choose a nursery with care. Nursery education
comes in two basic brands, private and publicly funded. State provision for
pre-fives is discretionary, so nursery schools have to compete for money with
all the other claims made on local authority budgets, and the availability of
places varies greatly. Because of the high demand, councils use a strict
allocations procedure, based on need, and it can be difficult to get a place.
Even then, most children attend for only half-days during the week.
These factors mean that parents, particularly working ones, often feel they
have to choose private provision, and many fear the facilities in this sector
are geared less towards the kind of educational standards governing local
authority provision than the more fundamental need to provide childminding
facilities. However, this is no longer the case. The Children's Act 1989
requires local authorities to carry out a registration inspection every two
years of all childcare provision for children up to eight years old.
The criteria are rigorous. The region's staff visit the nurseries to determine
whether the facilities are suitable for the purpose of looking after young
children, to ensure that the health and safety issues are being taken into
account fully, and that the amount of space available is sufficient.
The inspector takes up references from the people in charge of private
childcare, and carries out police checks on them. The region's own staff-child
ratios are recommended, which means one qualified staff member for every 10
children of three years and over, and one to six where there are babies and
toddlers.
When choosing a nursery, go along and see as many as you can and compare the
facilities available. If your child is a toddler, or older, take him along as
well and watch carefully how he reacts to the layout of each nursery, how he
behaves with the staff and how well they handle him. You have the right to see
a copy of the local authority's inspection report for the nursery, which will
give details of any problems which the inspectors identified on their last
visit.
A good nursery education will give your child an excellent introduction to the
more formal world of school. While he's grubbing around in the sandpit or up to
his elbows in plasticine, surrounded by his little chums, he will start to
realise that he is a unique person, with rights and interests which need to be
fulfilled. Hopefully, he will carry this knowledge with him for the rest of his
life.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
