<DOCNO>GH951209-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lesson for Scots legal chief</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGregor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Westminster Diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979171</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE have some bad news for Mr Paul Cullen, recently appointed Solicitor-General
for Scotland. The maverick Labour MP for Falkirk West, Dennis Canavan,
remembers that he taught Mr Cullen when he was a student in Edinburgh.
Mr Canavan told us: ``I never thought I would live to see the day when any
former pupil of mine would become a member of a Tory Government. Maybe I should
have concentrated on teaching him more about politics than maths.
``However, I suppose there is still hope for him. He is constitutionally unique
in that he is the only member of the Government who is not a member of either
House of Parliament. Maybe at the next General Election Tony Blair might find
him a safe seat.''
League campaign
OFF we go to the all-party rugby league group dinner in the Cholmondeley Room,
where the Labour MP for Makerfield, Mr Ian McCartney, has decided to put
himself forward as a candidate to manage the Scottish rugby league team in the
next World Cup.
He has impeccable credentials as the son of Hugh McCartney, the former MP for
East Dunbartonshire, Dunbartonshire Central and Clydebank and Milngavie, and
was a mean rugby union scrum half in his day. He played hooker once, but didn't
much fancy life in the front row after being punched in the face in his first
scrum.
Anyway, he tells the Diary that Scotland did so well in the recent emerging
nations rugby league World Cup that they will be included in the full
competition in two years' time. His greatest ambition is to manage a Scotland
team that will run out to play England at Hampden Park.
Musical spectacle
Who was that man tinkling the ivories at a charity concert in St John's, Smith
Square, earlier this week? It was Tory MP Toby Jessel (Twickenham) who played a
piece by Schumann described by one musically informed source as the ``suicide
sonata''.
More than 100 MPs were present at the concert, which was in aid of the NSPCC,
and apparently Mr Jessel got so worked up playing the piece that he had to keep
mopping his brow and wiping his glasses. So intense did he become, that as he
reached the climax of the piece, his glasses flew off when he struck the final
chord.
His efforts, however, helped to raise #40,000 for the charity, on top of the
#30,000 raised at a similar event last year.
To the point
FASCINATING exchanges in the Lords the other day on the Deer (Amendment)
(Scotland) Bill. All sorts of peers - Baroness Robson of Kiddington, the Earl
of Woolton and Lord Pearson of Rannoch, for example - had to declare their
interest as owners of Highland estates, with Lord Pearson even going so far as
to admit that he was largely an ``absentee owner''.
The whole thing seems to be puzzling Labour's Front Bench spokesman, Lord
Carmichael of Kelvingrove, who is being bombarded by briefings from the likes
of the World Widlife Fund, the Scottish Wildlife Trust, the British Deer
Society, and the Scottish RSPCA.
As he put it: ``I am not by any means an expert on the subject. Looking at the
benches opposite I realise that many people know a great deal about it, but it
is not a subject that is raised very often on the streets of Partick.''
One Scottish peer who did not speak in the debate has robust views on the
matter. ``We shoot deer at any time, day or night,'' he bluntly told the Diary.
``They are classed as vermin. They're lovely to eat, though.''
Caught in Act
INTERESTING information reaches us from the Scottish Office, thanks to a
question from the Liberal Democrats' Charles Kennedy. A total of 94 Acts of the
Scottish Parliament passed before 1707 are still in force.
They include such gems as the Royal Mines Act of 1424, the Lawburrows Act of
1429 and the Liferent Caution Act of 1491. Lord James Douglas-Hamilton says
that while there is a presumption that any Scots Act which has not been
statutorily repealed remains in force, that presumption can be repealed through
application of the doctrine of desuetude. The whit?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
