<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>news digest Prison regrade follows escape</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979174</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PARKHURST prison is being downgraded to a category B jail following the escape
of three inmates in January, it was disclosed yesterday.
On the recommendation of a report by Sir John Learmonth, it will no longer
house high-security prisoners. The three escapers - Keith Rose, 44, Matthew
Williams, 25, and Andrew Rodger, 44 - were recaptured after five days.
Centre slide
SNOWBOARDING is about to take off at Edinburgh's Hillend centre following the
completion of the first phase of a new 300-metre dry-ski slope.
Campus way
SCOTTISH Roads Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton has been asked to consider
a walkway for Heriot-Watt students attempting to cross the A71 at Riccarton.
Pleasing touch
MORE than 1000 people have taken part in the Welcome Host training scheme to
improve tourism services in the ``mini-Highlands'', the territory covered by
Loch Lomond, Stirling, and Trossachs Tourist Board, its chairman, Mr Bill
Petrie, said yesterday.
Sex crime
AYR man William McClung, 26, of James Brown Avenue, was jailed for three years
yesterday at the High Court in Kilmarnock for attempting to ravish a
13-year-old schoolgirl. McClung had a previous conviction for having sex with
an under-age girl.
Man safe
A FIFE man missing for almost three weeks has been found safe. Police said
yesterday that Mr Patrick Shanley, 54, of The Henge, Glenrothes, had been
staying with a friend in the Kirkcaldy area.
Ex-convener dies
MR Ian Campbell, from Sligachan, Skye, who served as convener of Highland
region for two four-year terms in the 1970s and 80s has died, aged 75. Mr
Campbell had also served on Inverness-shire County Council. He is survived by
his wife Fiona, two sons, and a daughter.
</TEXT>
