<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>One last chance for rail sell-off critics</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979175</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FINAL attempt to delay the first rail passenger franchise contracts, due to
be signed on Monday afternoon, will be made on Monday morning when the Save Our
Railways pressure group will ask the Appeal Court to review their allegations
that franchise director Roger Salmon breached Government guarantees on service
levels.
In a judicial review in the High Court yesterday, Mr Justice Macpherson
rejected claims that the passenger service levels set for the first lines to be
privatised would allow franchise bidders to cut services.
Had SOR won, its victory would have thrown the Government's franchising plans
into disarray. Instead, the judge threw out the suggestion that Mr Salmon had
not complied with the wishes of the Government and stressed that even if he had
not then that was a case for Parliament and not for the courts.
He lifted an obligation on the franchise director to give SOR 48 hours' notice
before franchises are awarded, denied leave to appeal, and awarded costs
against SOR, which includes Transport 2000, the Rail Development Society, the
rail unions, and a growing number of local authorities.
Labour transport spokesman Brian Wilson said the judgment ``removes any
pretence that there are safeguards for services in the rail-privatisation
process'', adding that the franchise director had been given a licence to do
what he liked while assurances by Ministers, both inside and outside the House
of Commons, had been exposed as worthless.
``This will bring rail privatisation into further disrepute,'' he said.
SOR secretary Keith Bill said: ``We are shocked and angered by this judge's
decision.''
The judge had accepted that there could be service cuts and he would not
intervene to protect the travelling public, said Mr Bill.
``The judge had said that if a Minister misled the public `that is a matter for
Parliament'. We don't agree. That is why on Monday morning first thing we shall
go to the Court of Appeal to ask for a hearing and a freeze on franchises
pending that hearing.''
Rail, Maritime, and Transport Union general secretary Jimmy Knapp warned that
if yesterday's judgment was allowed to stand, it would mean greatly reduced
services and the loss of around 22,000 rail jobs.
Transport Secretary Sir George Young said the judgment was ``a vindication of
the Government's approach and a triumph for the travelling public''.
Mr Nick Newton, an assistant director at the Office of Passenger Rail
Franchising, said he was ``clearly pleased with the result'' of the case. He
denied rail cuts were planned.
Mr Nigel Pleming QC, for SOR, said Mr MacGregor had assured MPs and the public
that, although he could not say ``every single train will run at the time it
runs at present'', the privatised services would be based on the existing BR
timetable.
He said that ``allowing substantial cuts of up to 52% in services, cutting out
services completely, changing the times trains stop and start'' was ``wholly
inconsistent'' with what the Minister had been saying.
The judge said the franchising director owed a duty to the Secretary of State
for Transport but had ``important discretionary powers of his own'' and added
that PSRs were not timetables and it was up to the director to decide minimum
service levels. Those who feared service cuts must wait to see whether their
fears were well founded, he said.
Bids to run train services over the east coast line between Scotland and London
closed yesterday. Opraf declined to provide even the numbers of formal bids,
let alone name those who have lodged indicative offers, now subject of scrutiny
and negotiation. A management-employee team from InterCity East Coast has
lodged a bid.
</TEXT>
