<HEADLINE>Foreign Digest Eight killed in shop rampage</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>Foreign Digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979176</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
`Dead' are dead
SAN FRANCISCO: The Grateful Dead rock group will disband following the death
of
their leader, Jerry Garcia, band members announced. ``The `long, strange
trip'
of the uniquely wonderful beast known as the Grateful Dead is over,'' they
said in a statement. Garcia, leader of the group that symbolised the
counter-culture revolution of the 1960s, died of a heart attack in August aged
53.
Nobel delight
STOCKHOLM: Irish poet Seamus Heaney will receive the 1995 Nobel literature
prize from King Carl XVI Gustav in Sweden tomorrow. ``For once in my life, I
am
permitting myself the luxury of walking on air,'' he said on arriving in
Stockholm this week. In a separate ceremony, British physicist Joseph Rotblat,
87, will receive the Peace Prize for his efforts to eliminate nuclear weapons.
Keeper quizzed
DIJON: Lyon goalkeeper Pascal Olmeta has been placed under investigation by a
Dijon magistrate on suspicion of using counterfeit banknotes. Olmeta, who
faced
Nottingham Forest in the Uefa Cup on Tuesday night, has denied wrongdoing.
King rests
BUJUMBURA: At least 53 people have been killed in a three-day offensive by the
army against Hutu rebels in Burundi, UN sources said. Thousands of civilians
have been displaced from the hills around the capital as the Tutsi-led army
pushes eastwards in attacks on rebel strongholds.
Killer jumbo
