<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Howard moves to punish organisers of child sex tours</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979178</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government yesterday outlined new laws designed to punish organisers of
child sex tours.
The legislation would target people in Britain who arrange foreign trips on
which adults commit sexual offences against children, and those who encourage
others to travel to exploit children sexually.
Home Secretary Michael Howard said: ``The full force of the law must be used
against the evil people who sexually exploit children for money.
``It is an abhorrent activity. We must do all we can to prevent it and protect
children everywhere.''
The announcement follows a review of the laws on conspiracy and incitement
prompted by the apparently growing numbers of people participating in child sex
tours.
The proposed legislation would allow the prosecution of those who: conspire to
commit abroad a crime which is also an offence in Britain; or incite others to
commit such an offence.
Offenders could face stiff penalties. Conspiracy to commit rape could attract a
life term; to have sex with a girl under 13 a seven-year term; indecent assault
on a boy 10 years; and indecency with a child under 14 two years' imprisonment.
Mr Howard said: ``These depraved people will face the same tough penalties as
they would if they had committed these offences here.''
But the proposals outlined by Mr Howard are likely to disappoint some
campaigners who wanted to see more comprehensive measures against paedophile
sex tourists.
They have argued for legislation which would allow British citizens to be tried
here for sexual offences committed while they were on foreign soil.
Other Western countries have introduced such legislation. Earlier this year, a
Swedish paedophile was jailed for having sex with a child while on holiday in
Thailand.
But the Home Office is known to have had serious misgivings about the
feasibility of legislation introducing such extra-territorial jurisdiction,
because of problems with evidence-gathering and bringing witnesses from Third
World countries to give evidence in British courts.
The plans were outlined in a written answer from Home Office minister David
Maclean to a parliamentary question from David Faber, Tory MP for Westbury.
Mr Howard said the Government was looking for a ``suitable legislative
opportunity'' to progress the proposals. It may well identify a Conservative MP
who could sponsor the legislation as a Private Member's Bill.
Mr David Ould, spokesman for the Coalition on Child Prostitution and Tourism,
an alliance of groups including Anti-Slavery International, Save the Children
and the NSPCC, said Mr Howard was not going far enough.
He added: ``Most of the culprits are individual travellers - this doesn't seem
to get at them at all.
</TEXT>
