<DOCNO>GH951209-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Solicitor appeals for information in council staffing inquiry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979180</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE solicitor leading the Scottish Office inquiry into the way senior officials
have been appointed for North Lanarkshire Council has appealed for information
from the public.
However, he stressed he did not want any anonymous communications.
Mr Ian MacLeod, a senior partner in Shepherd and Wedderburn WS in Edinburgh and
a specialist in employment law, gave a commitment to complete his report on the
matter to Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth by the end of January.
An official inquiry into allegations of religious bias and nepotism over
appointments at Monklands District Council conducted by Mr William Nimmo Smith
QC ended recently.
Mr MacLeod said he appreciated there was ``a degree of uncertainty and possibly
some unease'' among those concerned with the matter in North Lanarkshire,
particularly perhaps among the chief officers themselves.
Speaking at the Scottish Office yesterday, Mr MacLeod, 58, added: ``I would
like to reassure everyone that I approach my task with a resolve to complete it
in a comprehensive and fair manner by January 31 as requested by the Secretary
of State.''
Mr MacLeod said that although the inquiry was now under way, he did not expect
to be holding any public hearings until early in January.
The decision by the Scottish Secretary last month to set up the inquiry
followed a number of complaints and ``jobs for the boys'' allegations about
some of the senior appointments in the Motherwell-based North Lanarkshire
Council made to the Local Government Staff Commission.
The commission concluded it could not give the council a clean bill of health
and passed the matter to the Scottish Office.
One particular complaint was made over the appointment of Mr David MacKendrick,
64, as the #71,000 a year social work director. There were also claims that
Motherwell district officials were being preferred over employees of other
authorities. Five out of 10 chief officials come from that council.
In a parliamentary written answer announcing the appointment of Mr MacLeod to
conduct the inquiry, the Scottish Secretary said he was to inquire whether
North Lanarkshire had failed to comply with the duty imposed on it by section.7
of the Local Government and Housing Act 1989 to make appointments to paid
office or employment on merit and to report on the matter.
Mr Forsyth said the inquiry provided an opportunity to establish whether the
complaints were justified and whether action such as re-running the
appointments procedures was necessary.
Mr MacLeod said he suspected there would be members of the public who had
information which could be helpful to the inquiry. He asked them to write to
him at The North Lanarkshire Inquiry, c/o Shepherd and Wedderburn WS, Saltire
Court, 20 Castle Terrace, Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Well-heeled and down-at-heel on their uppers thanks to strike</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Nicholas Powell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Paris Diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979181</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TRAMPS and businessmen: among all the victims of the vast transport and public
sector strike now entering its third week in France, some are less equal than
others. Touchingly, President Jacques Chirac, attending the weekly Cabinet
meeting on Wednesday between visits to Africa and Germany, had words of concern
for both categories.
The trudging and bicycling mass of the general public, weary beyond mere
irritation and dumb with astonishment that the discomfort of this strike could
actually last so long, might at least count themselves fortunate by comparison
with Paris's thousands of homeless.
For them, the Metro is an almost permanent refuge, which takes them out of the
cold and also, more worryingly, away from basic notions of night and day.
Underground corridors and trains are also means of earning money: from begging,
busking, or selling newspapers produced by and for the benefit of the homeless.
At street level, the Metro's ventilation grids provide warm places to sleep.
With the strike, the tramps lose even that.
Last week, the first sub-zero temperatures and snowfalls of the winter inspired
the Minister for Humanitarian Action, Xavier Emmanuelli, to ask Paris's Metro
and bus authorities, the RATP, to open the disused underground station of Saint
Martin, near the Republique in the East End, as daytime shelter for homeless
people.
Yesterday, more than 100 turned up to be given Army canteen food before being
ferried away by RATP buses at 8pm to hostels in the Paris region.
A government building in the West End of the city has also been put at the
disposal of the medical teams who specialise in treating the physical and
psychological ills of Paris's tramps.
Chirac, meanwhile, at the Cabinet meeting, asked Ministers to assist town
councils throughout France in helping the homeless and to report back every day
on the sort and amount of accommodation being supplied.
Experts are only beginning to measure the damage being wreaked on France's
economy by two weeks without trains, public transport, or post.
Certain sectors (such as Paris's cycle shops, unable to cope with demand) have
made small fortunes. The domestic airline, Air Inter, free from competition of
the TGV train, has been busy scheduling extra flights and the private airline,
AOM, has recorded a 35% increase in passengers.
With people unable to make appointments reduced to doing business on the phone,
France Telecom has had a surge in calls. Messenger services in the Paris region
are providing 60% more trips than usual.
The negative side, however, is greatly alarming a government too proud and too
nervous to show it.
According to a survey carried out by the Chamber of Commerce for the Paris
region, 60% of firms have recorded a large drop in business over the past
fortnight, and 25% fear they could be forced into bankruptcy.
Takings in Paris department stores, which rely heavily on December shopping,
are 50% down on last year. The 22,000 smaller stores in the country have
experienced an average 40% fall-off in business. Wine producers and merchants
are complaining of a 10% drop in sales.
With private haulage companies unable to equal the freight capacities of the
railways, firms lack raw materials and, in many cases, because of the public
transport strike, their staff.
Goods, if they are finished, are difficult to distribute, and the post strike
means millions of cheques are blocked in depots.
The management union, CNPF, launched an appeal last week with the government
for employers late with tax contributions to be exempted from penalties.
At the Cabinet meeting, Chirac invited businessmen who are experiencing
difficulties in meeting tax deadlines to make contact as soon as possible with
their local Inland Revenue offices. The latter, he said, had received
instructions to be particularly understanding. What he did not mention,
unfortunately, was the fact that many Inland Revenue staff were on strike.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Council `cashing in' on the shopper Region accused of lifting everything but Christmas spirits with tow-away policy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By LACHIE KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979182</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STRATHCLYDE Region yesterday was accused of targetting motorists who are coming
to Glasgow city centre for Christmas shopping.
During the build-up to Christmas, traffic in Glasgow's city centre increases by
30%. At the same time, the number of cars uplifted from city streets rockets by
more than 300% from an average 12 a day to more than 50.
At a cost of #105 to become mobile again plus a #20 fixed parking fine, it is a
heavy extra Christmas expense. However, for Strathclyde region and the
contractors who carry out the removals, it is a money spinner which nets more
than #500,000 a year.
In the three years since the scheme started, more than #500,000 a year has been
collected by Strathclyde, with slightly more than 25% going to the contractor,
Bells of Richmond, who secured the three-year contract with a bid of #486,000,
netting more than #162,000 a year.
In the first year, 1993, 5123 cars were removed at a cost of #537,915 to
motorists. The following year the figure was 5416 cars which raised #568,680.
Already this year, including Thursday's figure, 5048 have ended up in the pound
and that figure is expected to increase to around 5600 before Christmas and
pump around #600,000 into Strathclyde's bank account.
Extra removal trucks are drafted in to cope with the rush doubling the three on
call during the rest of the year to six.
No-one escapes if their vehicle is illegally parked or causing an obstruction,
as one wheel-chair bound disabled driver found to his cost when he parked in
Howard Street and returned to find his car had disappeared.
Although the Automobile Association agrees with the concept of keeping traffic
moving and removing illegally and badly parked cars, their spokesman said
yesterday he felt the motorist was being targeted. He called for more
information and signs to alert drivers to the dangers of being towed away. ``It
is a purge against motorists who park illegally. We do not condone illegal
parking but we would ask the police to show a bit more discretion, especially
at this time of year and especially in the case of disabled people. Leaving
them stranded is very distressing.
``Many people do abandon their vehicle because they are not aware of the
situation. Perhaps there should be signs telling them they are in a tow-away
area. However, in the long run, ignorance is no excuse.''
A RAC spokeswoman said: ``It is a purge. We do not like this method being used
as a revenue-raising exercise. Improved sign-posting would help.''
The city centre traffic build-up in the run-up to Christmas normally starts
around mid-November. Chief Inspector Jim Neil, head of Strathclyde Police
traffic specialist services, said: ``We are not targeting motorists. We do all
we can to alert motorists to the problems by broadcasting the situation
regarding the parking situation in local car parks.''
A spokesman for Strathclyde Regional Council said: ``Only cars that are
illegally parked or causing an obstruction are moved. The whole aim of the
exercise is to keep traffic moving.''
Glasgow is not alone in the practice. Edinburgh has been impounding cars for
around two years and the penalty fixed nationally is the same. However, it has
not yet spread to other police forces.
In Aberdeen, a spokesman for Grampian Police said the problem of double parking
had not reached a level where impounding was thought to be necessary.
Northern Constabulary, while aware of the measures being taken in Glasgow, said
nothing similar was planned. ``If a vehicle is parked where it is causing a
major obstruction and we can't get the driver, then we will call someone in to
move it,'' he said.
In Dundee, Tayside Police have their own recovery vehicle for lifting cars but
use it mainly for moving cars to official car parks at football matches, said a
police spokesman.
</TEXT>
