<HEADLINE>Fraserburgh trawler held in Plymouth</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979183</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH trawler and its crew of 10 were being detained in port yesterday for
alleged illegal fishing in the English Channel.
The purse-seine boat Alert, out of Fraserburgh, was escorted into Plymouth
early yesterday by a Royal Navy fisheries protection vessel.
It was detained within the mackerel ``box'' 12 miles south of the port, an area
where trawlers are not allowed to fish for mackerel.
Outwith that zone, boats use special nets and fish at a certain depth to
maximise their haul of mackerel. The fish are migratory and tend to leave the
North Sea in winter months.
A spokeswoman for the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries, and Food at Exeter
said: ``The Alert was escorted into port by HMS Cottismore for further
inspection.''
The boat's agents, Caley Fisheries in Fraserburgh, said it had no details of
the alleged offence. The Alert is understood to be owned by skipper John Smith.
</TEXT>
