<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nuclear test veterans win Strasbourg review</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979184</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EX-SERVICEMEN campaigning for compensation from the Government after they were
used as guinea-pigs during nuclear tests in the 1950s have won the first round
of their fight for justice.
The British Nuclear Test Veterans' Association, pressing for a #2000m award,
claims its members have suffered cancers and other life-threatening diseases
from radiation exposure.
Last night, it was confirmed that the European Commission of Human Rights had
granted a review of the association's case. Now, three individual cases, each
involving Scots, will be examined in detail early in the new year.
The announcement from Strasbourg has delighted veterans who have been fighting
for compensation for 12 years.
The Commission has ordered a full review of the UK's actions in exposing
thousands of young servicemen to high levels of radiation for experimental
purposes.
Commissioners will also investigate why the UK Government attempted to defeat
war pensions claims by withholding vital military medical records from those
claiming that radiation-linked disabilities and cancers stemmed directly from
the tests.
The decision, contained in two judgments just issued, follows the complaints
raised in Europe. One is by the daughter of a Christmas Island veteran from
Glasgow. The woman, aged 28, suffers from a severe condition linked to her
father's radiation exposure. The two other cases are from veterans who suffer
similar conditions but have been denied war pensions.
New York-based lawyer Ian Anderson, a Scottish-trained advocate from Paisley,
who represented the claimants in Europe, said the decision had followed two
years of complex legal argument in which the Government resisted attempts by
the applicants to have their cases heard by the Commission.
He said: ``In rejecting the Government's arguments, the Commission referred
amongst other things to the 1985 Royal Australian Commission report which found
that the UK had displayed `ignorance, incompetence and cynicism' with regard to
the safety of persons - civilian and military - in the vicinity of its nuclear
tests.''
In permitting the full review early next year, the Commission said it was
disturbing that the British Government had withheld vital military medical
records which detailed post-detonation treatment for radiation exposure.
The Commission will look at whether the denial of such access constitutes
``inhuman and degrading treatment'' of the veterans by the UK.
Mr Anderson said the European decision represented the ``first ray of hope''
for veterans, their children and widows who have suffered as a result of the
Government's refusal to admit liability or wrongdoing, while quietly settling
the claims of others.
He added: ``For many veterans who have already succumbed to their
radiation-induced conditions, the Commission's decisions have arrived too
late.''
More than 22,000 servicemen from all over the UK witnessed the bomb testing
programmes between 1952 and 1958.
The latest development was hailed as ``fantastic news'' by Renfrew district
councillor Ken McGinley, 57, who started the bid for compensation in 1983.
The former Royal Engineer was sent to Christmas Island in 1958 and witnessed
six explosions.
</TEXT>
