<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>How Church would lose nothing and gain a great deal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART LAMONT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979249</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THOSE who have, through a slip of the tongue, said funeral when they meant
wedding (or vice versa) will understand the error which crept into last
Saturday's article in this space. Dealing with the wide variation in attitude
toward weddings among my ministerial colleagues, I pronounced that upon
induction to a parish a minister is pledged to marry and baptise those who live
within it. I should, of course, have written marry and bury.
Baptism is a very different matter. More of that in a moment, after I have
apologised to any Kirk minister who in the next couple of weeks will be
confronted by a ``consumer'' waving a copy of last week's column and demanding
that his child be baptised whether or not the family have any connection with
the church.
The fact is that while parish ministers are obliged to conduct weddings and
funerals for those who live in their patch, the conduct of baptism in the
Church of Scotland is limited to those with a definite connection to the
church. Moreover, it leads to even greater diversity of practice among Kirk
ministers than I described in the article on marriage.
Since the three rites of passage (baptism, marriage, and funeral) are the
occasions upon which vast numbers of people have dealings with the Christian
church, it is worth trying to describe what the practice of the national church
is in this regard.
I wish it was simple to do so. First, let us deal with the rules which Kirk
ministers are obliged to uphold. These state that baptism may be administered
to a child with at least one parent who has been baptised and is a church
member (or expresses the intention to become one). So far, pretty clear - but
also pretty strict since many parents who desire baptism for their children do
not fall into this category.
However, an exception is made for those who profess Christianity and are
connected with the congregation in some way even if they don't attend worship
``due to causes which make such attendance a practical impossibility''.
Night-shift working might easily be such a cause, but who is to say that
inability to get out of bed on Sunday morning is not a ``practical
impossibility'' for many young couples?
This raises the question of interpretation. Many ministers think that to
administer baptism in these circumstances is a mockery. Others try to explain
the rules and end up convincing the parents that there is no room at this inn
for them. Others simply bend or ignore the rules.
This is clearly not a satisfactory situation. The Church of Scotland can hardly
claim to be a national church if its local agents in neighbouring villages
implement totally different practices with regard to something as basic and
universal as baptism.
Some Kirk ministers from the evangelical wing are even opposed to infant
baptism. They would prefer believers baptism in which the people being baptised
takes their own vows. Certainly this has the virtue of removing the problem of
complacent parents who don't fit the system, but it implies that infant baptism
is not ``proper'' baptism.
At its worst this attitude leads ministers to refuse baptism to babies and in
some extreme cases to administer baptism again in adult life (thereby implying
the infant baptism was not valid). Several ministers have left the Kirk (or
been shown the door) for this.
At the other extreme are ministers who baptise on demand, even to the extent of
poaching babies from other parishes (and breaking more rules in the process).
The late Rev James Currie was well known for this foible. It made him popular
with the parents and unpopular with his colleagues who were trying their best
to live by the rules.
Understandably they pointed out that he was unable to take any further part in
their Christian upbringing by his ``hit-and-run'' sacraments.
The Roman Catholic and Anglican churches do not have this kind of problem. As
well as the parents they involve ``godparents'' who take vows at the baptism to
ensure the godly upbringing of the baby. If the parents hang loose to religion
then the godparents can be practising Christians, and the requirements of the
rules satisfied. (It is worth noting that the RC church accepts the infant
baptism of the C of S as valid, which makes the attitude of certain RC priests
who will not accept a practising Protestant as godparent, to be both illogical
as well as bigoted.)
It is significant that many Kirk parents have copied this practice unofficially
and turn up complete with one or even two sets of godparents.
I say unofficially because the C of S baptismal service has no vows
specifically for godparents.
However, I believe that godparents may provide the way forward through this
tangled jungle of rules, practices, and motives. If the Church of Scotland were
to change its baptismal laws to be in line with these other traditions it would
lose nothing and gain a great deal. The baby would be baptised and if the
parents did not fit the provisions of Act XVII (1963) the appropriate vows
would be taken in loco parentis by godparents in good standing, and everyone
would be happy.
The 1963 Act is now hopelessly out of step with our times and ecumenical
practice. It is also the kind of legalism which sits uneasily with true
religion. More conclusively, it would have denied Joseph and Mary a baptism for
their baby boy since they did not belong to the parish of Bethlehem.
</TEXT>
