<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nothing like a dame to bring out child in us</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979250</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT is it about panto and the Scots? There was this note of curious bafflement
in the press officer's voice - live art, visual art, films and festivals, he'd
done them all, but this was his first brush with pantomime. And he was
struggling with disbelief.
``Six weeks before curtain up, and the box office was going non-stop. And we
hadn't really done all that much...... the usual posters, a few balloons. But,
weeks in advance, people were phoning up. Six tickets - same seats as last
year, same performance as last year. And then they'd say - `By the way. What is
it this year?'''
For someone who had seen expensively publicised events come and go without a
break-even audience, such droves of spontaneous booking blew ka-whumphing great
raspberries at marketing strategy.
A couple of nights later, and I got the beginnings of an answer to his
question. The taxi driver who picked me up outside the Citizens - I'd just seen
Pinocchio - described, without any prompting on my part, his most abiding
memory of a childhood panto. It was Cinderella. And no, it wasn't the coach and
Shetland ponies that had stayed with him. It was another transport that had
delighted him. For no reason he - or his mum - could fathom then, or now, a
cut-out bus had fetched up on stage. ``A 47, to Castlemilk.'' He was absolutely
sure of the number; it had told the audience where the sketch was coming from,
as it were.
The routine had involved a Glesca clippy - he recalled some of the ``c'moan get
aff'' patter but not who had delivered it. What he did remember, though, was
how utterly gee-ed up he'd felt for days and days afterwards. You could hear
the child in the man's voice, still tickled by the daftness of it all, loving
the awful jokes, the shouting back, the colour and glitz - he hadn't even
minded the songs too much. They were a chance to unwrap your sweeties before
the Dame or the baddie came back. But the best thing, the thing that had kept
him going back as an adult, was that they were live.
But ``live'' in a vastly different way from other kinds of theatre. Pantomime
is, essentially, licensed anarchy - and I reckon that's one reason the Scots
have clung on to its traditions so vehemently. And it's about subverting gloom
in the time-honoured way: by laughing it out of countenance. It's no
coincidence that so many of the jokes are at the expense of poverty.
``We're having a big do(o) this Christmas...... we can't afford a turkey.''
Whether the accent locates it in Maryhill, Morningside or Aberdeen, the
chortles of recognition have erupted nationwide for decades.
Poor? POOR? ``We were so poor the wolf wisnae just at oor door - it had its
pups in the lobby.'' So what did we do? We told more jokes! Or maybe sang a
little song. Or maybe had a wee bit of a greet, until everybody said: `AAAAW.'
And that made us feel better. As in life, so in panto - or vice versa. (Panto
being a great place for vice versa, as you know.)
Hard times weren't the only things to take a drubbing. Authority, pomposity
hypocrisy, priggishness, are year-in, year-out targets. And it doesn't really
matter that these days we are awash with supposedly debunking forces -
newspapers, radio, television, the Internet - because there's one crucial
difference: we believe the Dame.
Well, she reminds us of a granny, an auntie, a woman up the road or - and yes,
folks, I heard this in Edinburgh years ago - ``thet's meh cleaning lady to a
T!''
The same carefully vowelled tones were later to reassure the perjink companion
when things got a tad saucy: ``It's all right to laugh, Mamie - it's Stenley
Bexter!''
It's all right to laugh because, in the end, you are laughing at care, at life,
at yourself. Wha's like us? Gey few - and they're not nearly as funny either.
But is that true? Are Scottish pantos really significantly different? Is this
wishful thinking, cultural nostalgia - tied up with a child's-eye view of
Christmases past, when someone else had the responsibility of paying for that
do(o)?
Actually, I don't think so. A historical reason first - hysterical reasons
later. In the sixties, English pantomimes underwent certain radical changes
that didn't affect the Scottish scene so irreversibly. Managements everywhere
had watched with growing unease as a one-eyed threat had crept into
living-rooms throughout the land. Comedians sat, speechless, in dressing rooms.
They were all quipped-out. That one-eyed box in the living-room corner had
gobbled up the act of a lifetime in one fell spectacular. Even the clean jokes
had been rendered unrepeatable.
It was at this point that many managements down south brought in the pop stars
and the emerging television names, not as speciality acts - pantos had had
those since the earliest of days - but as main players.
Cliff Richard and the Shadows found themselves trussed into cod-medieval
Lincoln Green, guitars hurriedly replaced with bows and arrows, so they could
wander about as Robin Hood and his Merrie Men in some hackneyed version of
Babes in the Wood.
What ho, backers? This will bring in a new, young audience, cried the panicked
management. And to a certain extend it did. But the pantos changed to
accommodate the strength - limitations, more usually - of the pop
personalities, not vice versa. And pantos, as we know, are keen on vice versa.
Could I just say in passing, that pantos and puberty don't really sit well
together. Adolescents are in a perpetual state of anarchy. They have their own
rituals for expressing it. And they certainly don't want to be part of any
anarchy that is subscribed to by their younger siblings or - worst of all -
their parents and grandparents.
Herd adolescent boys into a panto and you are asking for the villain to be
cheered, his henchmen told where the goodies are hiding, and the fairy's every
request for help to be turned down with roars of ``NOooo''. Not even the
Brownies, who probably have a badge in panto-audienceship, can outshout the
spoilsport louts.
Anyway, here in Scotland we didn't run to that many pop stars - though I have
seen Sydney Devine as Buttons. There simply wasn't the same headlong rush to
replace seasoned performers with folk who were famous for advertising chocky
bars on television. And this is where the hysterical reasons come in. Stanley
Baxter. Jimmy Logan. Una McLean. Rikki Fulton. Jack Milroy. Johnny Beattie.
Walter Carr. Phil McCall. And hosts more besides whom I've missed in haste.
These were, still are, ``oor ain folk'' who knew all about us and were allowed
to cast it all up!
But who carries on the tradition? And do younger generations really want it -
or is that old pantophiles going soggy and wistful?
Well, here you have the chicken-and-egg conundrum - should that be
goose-and-golden-egg? If managements choose to stick by the traditional panto,
then there's no shortage of new dames, new Simple Simons, Wishee-Washees,
Buttons et al, ready to carry on in the old ways. Andy Gray, Gerard Kelly, Paul
Young, John Ramage - to name but four - are all likely lads for the Dames,
Bazooms, and tackety boots.
And kids, if taken along, will respond as if some twizzle in their DNA had
predisposed them to laugh at the drop of a voluminous bloomer.
That said, there have definitely been moves away from traditional panto formats
in recent years.
Most noticeably, many repertory theatres, with Perth a resolute exception -
have opted for children's plays, the majority of them penned by the amazing
Stuart Paterson. Here Vaudeville gives way to straightforward storytelling,
albeit with panto elements - Paterson has a wise understanding of the youthful
need for the moment of anarchy: the moments of whopping vulgarity, and
political incorrectness - best summarised in a rip-snorting fart - and the
audience participation that shrieks away feelings of scaredyness and says at
the top of its piping voice: `I'm here. And I matter.'
And then there is, too, the solid rumour of mooted change at the King's in
Glasgow. After 20 years of sharing costs, which can reach the phenomenal
quarter million mark at panto - and swopping shows - Glasgow has parted company
with the consortium that had the King's Edinburgh and Sunderland Empire as the
other partners.
Babes in the Wood - which features Jimmy Logan alongside Cannon and Ball - is
the last Glasgow panto we'll see staged under this past agreement. So far,
Glasgow's Department of Performing Arts and Venues has kept its future plans
for the King's season show under heavily secured wraps. Who knows - maybe a
Phantom of the Panto is set to laser its way centre-stage next winter.
Will low comedy lose out to hi-tech? Will push-button home entertainment push
panto into the margin? If anything, as we inch nearer those superhighways, I
suspect that panto will most surely come into its finest, subversive own.
As nights draw in, wee figures will be seen slipping out of flickering arcades
where motionless bodies will be locked in virtual-reality thraldom. One by one
these cultural revolutionaries will settle into worn plush seats as an old
piano announces the strains of Pantomime, Pantomime. The stage will fill with
our most primitive emotions - fear of the darkness, of poverty, of being ugly
and unloved. The Dame and her raucous vitality will challenge the lot in a
flurry of ancient ambiguities.
And when the evil genius, Mindgrab, emerges from his hacker's lair, claiming
universal sovereignty, his boastful ``I am Lord of All Life Games'' will be
answered by a wee Brownie yelling ``Oh no you're not!''
See Scots? See panto? On a good day, ye canny tell the difference.
MARY BRENNAN
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Long-term deal keeps a young talent in Scotland Glass commits himself to Dons</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979251</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABERDEEN yesterday did themselves and the country a favour by doing a deal with
one of the best young players around, Stephen Glass, which will make sure he
continues to fulfil his potential in the premier division for the next
two-and-a-half years at least.
The piece of shrewd business done by manager Roy Aitken not only gives the
teenager, valued at #2m, a solid base to further his career at club and
international level but also will make him one of the best paid players at
Pittodrie.
The 19-year-old, who is already a probable starter in Scotland's European
Championship finals squad next summer, did not take a lot of time to agree to
the deal, despite the fact that he was very much in the transfer minds of major
clubs in England, like Spurs, Newcastle United and Nottingham Forest. ``It was
not a hard decision to reach. This is one of the best clubs to be with where I
can learn from the coaches and players and become a better player. My family
agreed on that point.
``I knew of all the transfer speculation but just ignored it as I was under
contract anyway.''
Since he forced his way into the first team a year ago, Glass has collected a
Coca-Cola Cup winning medal, as well as being named man of the match in the
final, but seems sensible enough to keep his hat size unchanged. ``I know what
Craig Brown has said about the European Championship finals and I want to be
there, but I won't worry if I'm not. I have plenty of time on my side.
Said his manager: ``He is arguably the best young player in the country and it
was only right for him to be rewarded for his progress. He is now a major part
of my team and been so consistent since the first day he came into the side.''
Aitken will be without suspended captain Stewart McKimmie and striker Scott
Booth for the visit of Motherwell as he aims for three straight home wins in
the next eight days to move up the table.
Motherwell are considering a bid for Oldham striker Darren Beckford as Tommy
Coyne looks unlikely to be fit to return for some time yet. Beckford, 28, cost
Norwich City #900,000 but is available for transfer. Said McLeish: ``There is
no sign of Coyne's injury clearing and we urgently need to get more goals. This
and our injury situation is what is causing all our problems. I have several
players in mind and will move shortly if our goals rate does not improve.''
McLeish believes his team still have a real chance at Pittodrie where they have
done well in the past. `There is a sense of deja vu going back to Aberdeen.
They were struggling in the league last season just as we are now. However, I
do not see this as a long-term problem.
``We will start climbing the table once we get our players back fit again. In
the meantime it is a question of minimising mistakes and maintaining the
fighting spirit.
``There is a freshness about Aberdeen this season and you can see where Roy
Aitken wants the club to go. They are not yet the finished article but have
come a long way since their crisis of confidence had them fighting for
survival.''
McLeish will have Brian Martin and Eddie May back in the side.
Raith Rovers, who slipped up at Falkirk last week after establishing themselves
in fourth place, will be in determined mood against Hearts at Kirkcaldy, but
have two doubts, Shaun Dennis and Jason Dair.
Hearts, who will have Neil Poynton back after a six-week absence, confirmed
that Dave McPherson, who is injured at the moment, is not going to Coventry
City.
There ought to be plenty  of action at Rugby Park where two teams with much to
play for at the wrong end of the table, Kilmarnock and Falkirk, meet.
Certainly, Falkirk's former Rangers and Hearts player, David Hagen, thinks that
will be the case. ``I reckon if the pitch is in good condition it will be a
cracking game.
Both sides like to play attacking football and I don't think there will be any
sitting back.
``Killie will obviously want to win to catch us in the league, but we can open
up a wee gap on them with three points. Whatever the outcome, I'm sure it's
going to be entertaining.''
Hagen hopes for a more rewarding time than his last appearance, which was his
Brockville debut, against Killie, when the Ayrshire lot won 2-0.
``To be fair, I think it was an even game and they caught us with a
sucker-punch, but I hope today will be different and I've got a sneaking
feeling we can win.''
His assistant manager, Gerry Collins, is convinced that a win at Rugby Park
could really set his team on their way up the league. ``Although we're near the
bottom at the moment, a couple of decent results will lift us up the table
dramatically,'' he said. ``Take Hearts, for instance. About a month ago, they
won three matches on the trot and it took them from ninth to fourth.
``Their situation is a massive incentive for everyone in the division.''
Collins was impressed by Kilmarnock when he watched them in midweek during the
game against Aberdeen which was eventually abandoned because of a power failure.
q.ENGLAND gained a diplomatic victory yesterday that could prove crucial to
their hopes of qualifying for the 1988 World Cup finals.
FIFA will meet this weekend to decide the format for Tuesday's World Cup
qualifying draw and favour a system based on their global rankings.
England's position of twentieth in the world and fifteenth in Europe would have
put them in the third group of seeds, with the chance of being drawn in the
same group as nations such as Germany and Italy.
The FA sent letter to FIFA and now have been told their Europe ranking will be
raised to fourteenth, which means they will be in the second group of seeds.
</TEXT>
