<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000113</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dunfermline face a big test of strength</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH MCKINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979252</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUNFERMLINE have more lives than a store cat, according to manager Bert Paton's
philosophy, and it seems sound so far as his side have struggled manfully
through mixed form and a list of injuries to top players almost the length of a
pitch.
They are still, albeit on goal difference, top of the first division, but his
warning was clear yesterday when he said: ``So far, the others have failed to
kill us off, and remember, we're getting stronger.''
That strength will be necessary today when the Fifers travel to Dens Park to
take on a Dundee side who not only failed to get the three points against
Dumbarton in midweek that would have taken them top, but also have been
involved in the transfer of Morten Wieghorst to Celtic.
Dunfermline's only doubt for today is striker Greg Shaw, but David Bingham is
back. The best news for the Fifers, though, is that striker Andy Smith is back
in the squad for the first time since breaking a leg in the pre-season friendly
against Bolton in August.
``He's had three reserve games recently, but we'll probably give him another
one before his first-team return,'' said Paton. However, since playing against
Dundee in his Airdrie days was one of Smith's favourite pastimes, even a place
on the bench - he was ``super-sub'' with his former club - cannot be ruled out.
Dundee, meanwhile, have Neil McCann and Dusan Vrto missing injured, but call in
19-year-old central defender Craig Tully to the squad. Player-manager Jim
Duffy, who missed the draw against Dumbarton, also returns, as does defender
Kevin Bain after suspension.
With Barry Smith's signing from Celtic going through in time, the right back
will make his debut - interesting times, indeed, for a Dens Park clash which,
because the covers went down yesterday, may survive the overnight freeze.
St Johnstone are hopeful that their clash against Dundee United also will go on
at McDiarmid Park to allow new signings, midfielder Attila Sekerleoglu from FC
Tirol and winger Leigh Jenkinson from Coventry to show their paces.
The Jenkinson deal was completed yesterday - like the Austrian, he joined in a
six-figure deal - and manager Paul Sturrock still had to make up his mind who
would make way. Up front, he also has Roddie Grant, Derek Ferguson, George
O'Boyle, and Kevin Twaddle vying for two places.
Dundee United, with Rab McKinnon still not fit, will be along the lines of the
team who took eight goals off Dumbarton last week.
Morton are also up there battling for promotion, but they must travel to
Firhill to face a Hamilton side still keen to show that their position at the
foot of the table is false.
Airdrie travel to Clydebank, who admitted yesterday that the continued freeze
might put the game in doubt, while Dumbarton, encouraged by their midweek
performance, want to follow that up with success at home to St Mirren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000114</DOCNO>
