<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Joseph Brattisani</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979253</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Joseph Brattisani, restaurateur; born July 8, 1908, died December 4, 1995
JOSEPH Brattisani, one of Edinburgh's most famous restaurateurs, has died after
a stroke at the age of 87. Known as ``Mr Chips'' in the city, he established
five restaurants there. He came from the second generation of an Italian
family, one of the first to come to Scotland.
Mr Brattissani's father originally opened a fish and chip shop in Stockbridge,
and his was among the first Italian families to do so.
The family came from a humble peasant background but saw their trade in
Edinburgh grow during the 1950s. They introduced generations of Scots to meals
in a restaurant environment, while also providing what was probably the staple
diet of the time - the take-away fish and pudding suppers.
Mr Brattisani was also involved in the running of a bookmaker's business in St
Andrews Square, Edinburgh. He is remembered for his visits to the early fish
market in Newhaven, later opening his betting shop, then returning to his fish
restaurants in the evening.
A well-known figure in the Italian community in Edinburgh, he regularly
attended ballroom dances, important to the Italian Scots of that era. As a
young man, he also played football for the Italian team in Edinburgh.
Mr Brattisani is survived by his wife, Evelyn, his sons Joseph, Charles, and
Eric, and daughter Maria.
His son Joseph said that his father had been in poor health for some years, but
had played an active part in Italian community life in Edinburgh in the past.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kathleen Harrison</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979254</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE character actress Kathleen Harrison, who played Ma Huggett opposite Jack
Warner in the radio series The Huggetts, has died at the age of 103.
Miss Harrison's first film - Our Boys - in her long and varied career was made
in 1915. George Bernard Shaw gave her tips on playing Eliza Doolittle when she
studied at RADA - to good effect, for the Blackpool-born actress came to
specialise in below-stairs Cockney cameos. ``For years I always seemed fated to
play someone from the kitchen,'' she remarked in the 1960s.
Plays she appeared in included The Cage (1927), Night Must Fall (1935), The
Corn Is Green (1938), and The Winslow Boy (1946). She also appeared in the film
version of Night Must Fall (1937), Bank Holiday (1938), A Girl Must Live
(1939), and others.
During the Second World War she toured with ENSA in the company of Emlyn
Williams, appearing in the Coward film In Which We Serve and on stage in Flare
Path. Fame arrived with the cosy Huggett series which started in 1948 and ran
for several years. It was a spin-off from the film Holiday Camp, also starring
Harrison and Warner, who became Dixon of Dock Green.
When her old friend Coward cast her with Sir John Gielgud in his play Nude With
A Violin, which opened in Dublin, Harrison played up to her Huggett role,
moving hotels when she learned Coward and Gielgud had also booked into the
fashionable Shelbourne in Dublin as well. ``I would have been so embarrassed
with them. I don't believe in artists mixing with the big boys,'' she explained.
Her TV role as Mrs Thursday, the timorous char who became a millionairess, was
the brainchild of Lord Ted Willis and became an overnight success. The first
episode shot to the top of the ratings, gaining more than 20 million viewers
and toppling Coronation Street. But Miss Harrison also valued her roles in the
Dickens serials Martin Chuzzlewit and Our Mutual Friend, as well as films of
Oliver Twist (1948), Scrooge (1951), and Pickwick Papers (1952).
Miss Harrison was protective of her privacy, rarely speaking of her family. She
leaves her son Michael and a daughter Alice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pulling the plug on clutter</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARCELLA EVARISTI</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979255</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ARE you fed up with untidy plugs? Now for people who are thus distressed there
exists a little appliance called Park-a-plug. In fact somebody out there is
going to get one for Christmas. A handy little stocking filler. I know because
I saw one in a festive catalogue. It's a flat white plastic circle with a lip -
like a secular holy water font for one.
All you do is peel off its adhesive backing and stick it to the wall. Pop in
your plug et voila votre plug will no longer be ``a real nuisance, cluttering
up the place, and generally getting in the way''.
I have never thought of a plug as getting in the way although I know people
differ as to what constitutes clutter. I mean some people think undisciplined
bars of soap need little rubber ovals with suction pads in pastel colours to
keep them firmly in their place. Lav and order, or law and ordure, what does it
matter, as long as the loo is maintained as a place where decent people may go?
Once as a child I sat for an hour with legs dangling and my confused heart
beating hard because I could not see any toilet paper and I was too shy to cry
out for help. Finally I lifted up the dolly with the satin crinoline dress and
there it was. (Costume dramas and Delsey are synomymous now, such is the effect
of childhood toilet traumas.)
For myself, I believe a true nuisance is running out of toilet paper, and a
real nuisance is not having a bath at all. To any clean-living European a
nuisance is not having a bidet. My bathroom is too tiny for one, being long and
narrow, but could I afford the cost I would solve the problem by building a
metal wall ladder which would reach a sort of mezzanine bidet area. When
selling the flat I could proudly point it out as a special feature.
I lived in a weird but magical flat in Edinburgh once; the bedroom was
perfectly round, even the door was curved and the windows too. Stand in the
right spot and you could project your voice to win your way out of any lover's
tiff with this terrific echoing acoustic on your side.
There's a word I haven't used for years: tiff. Tiffs are an early-twenties sort
of argument I suppose. As you get older the Grand Canyon is handier for victory
in the volume fight. However at this point, tiffs were made up quickly, and
would have ended in a shared bath, except there wasn't one to share. But did we
care? Well, yes. Eventually . . .
But before I'd ever been, as it were, tiffed, I was on a student drama
expedition in Dumfries, where I stayed at my very first Bed and Breakfast. I
was a virgin to Bed and Breakfasts; and stupidly thought no-one realised - you
know how it is. So with unconvincing confidence I strode down the lino stairs,
deeply breathing in the cabbage, bleach and air-freshener atmosphere, to tell
the landlady that there was no plug in the bath.
Being a polite girl and fearing she might be embarrassed, I told her I knew it
was impossible to keep tabs on all the fixtures and fittings of even the best
kept establishments. My father owns a pub, I told her, so I'm no stranger to
the amazing things which ungrateful clients customarily nick. Not just ashtrays
and glasses, but toilet seats, mirrors, and those ballcocky things from the
cisterns . . .
She glared at me. I briefly wondered whether she was one of those anti-drink
Wee Free people about whose existence I had recently learned. I was 17 and in
my first year at university, so while I knew about the species I was still
pretty vague about them geographically. Well, I was doing English, French and
Drama, not anthropology.
(Anyway, it wasn't my fault Giffnock was a Wee-Free Free-zone. As far as I
knew.)
Helpfully, I suggested that I could pop out and buy one for her, I could easily
leave my bath until after I had explored the town. My confidence was swirling
downwards. If she could just tell me where the nearest . . . couldn't say
plug-shop because she obviously thought I was being cheeky . . . the nearest um
relevant . . . She held out her hand and there on her palm was a big black
plug, the metal triangle at its centre pointing towards me. Ten pence for a
bath, she said, with a voice the Scottish Tourist Board would have shivered at,
and please tell the rest of you. All of me's here, I thought, but I didn't say
that.
I was thinking all this as I was lying in my bath the other night for I do now
have a bath of my own and a paid-up plug, but things are still problematic. The
man who put in my bathroom messed up because he broke the overflow pipe from
the sink, and instead of replacing it - he obviously wanted to get home for his
tea - and sussing that I was no expert in these matters, asked me if it would
be alright to stopper up the wee hole. When he reassured me that this did not
mean the sink would overflow for some reason or other in a way that sounded
convincing, I reassured him back - though older I was still polite - and I said
anyway it looks much neater filled in anyway.
And he was right, the sink did not overflow, but whenever I ran the bath the
plug popped out, unless you held it down with a loofah and just stood there,
while the phone rang, as it always did. I was determined to get him back to fix
things before I spent a penny, so I phoned his firm, which turned out to be his
wife, and told them/her just that. But it seems the cheque I'd forgotten that
I'd already sent had been cashed. (This was a first for me because it's the
sending of cheques I normally forget.)
She then told me he had died in the night. I knew there was no point in saying
``that'll be right'' because I could tell from her voice that it was right. So
every time I run a bath I stand holding my loofah upright, like a soldier at a
watery cenotaph. But that's OK, because now I've got an ansamachine so when the
phone goes, as it always does, I am not missing anything at all.
Of course I should get a better, living plumber to come and sort my suite out,
but I've become rather fond of my daily ritual, my minute of silence, after the
hurly burly of sitting writing by myself. I empty my mind (having practised,
this does only take a minute), I gaze into the empty ladderless wall, and the
long bars on the window where for 10 years a roller blind was meant to be, and
I relax.
Why should I deny myself this meditative pleasure when there are so many things
I'd rather blow my money on? The wonderful thing about leafing through the
festive catalogue with its Gumball dispensers, its machines for turning
newspapers into free firelighters, its Ring Snuggies (``Ideal for slim fingers
and enlarged knuckles! No more slipping rings!'' Good grief.), the mean and
deliciously sneering delight is that although once again Christmas has come
around and slammed into your already painfully extended overdraft facility, you
can still rejoice that you're not that kind of sucker.
Not like Vogue, oh no, not like Vogue at all. I have a tip for you, never read
Vogue unless in very carefully chosen company, though I believe that reading
this festive catalogue is best done in the privacy of an unshared bath.
Otherwise, some sensible person reading over your shoulder will shout in your
ear, ``What lunatic, even if they had the money, would pay #295 for a Gold
Sequined Scarf by Nicole Fahri?'' And it's no use saying, ``Please I'm too
tired for Big Issues, would you defoliate my back?'' Or replying, ``Did you
know she is married to the playwright David Hare? You know, the Keats versus
Dylan debate?'' Or cheaply, ``Well compared to a bad day at the greyhound races
. . . Pucci and Gucci for some are as addictive as the puggie is to others . .
.'' It just won't wash.
I know a Miracle Gel-Tec Microwave ``Hot Water'' Bottle would probably generate
as much heat as a pure cashmere wrap, but I also know which would give me
better dreams. Wrapped in an amazing lightweight Thermal Throw plus a Double
Heat Sheet, I would have nightmares, as sure as eggs can be Asprey eggs. I'd
find myself in a B&amp;B, lying on a single nylon sheeted bed, the room heated by a
hundred red ladders of buzzing electric bars, my toenails catching on pink
synthetic threads, my hands over my ears to drown out the landlady screaming
from the hall; ``She's in there, she owes me #295 for the meter, and she's not
wearing a nightie!'' I would then look down to see my naked body covered with
flat white leeches, dozens of them, circular leeches each containing a
slug-plug.
Whereas, in sequined gold and cashmere, I would perhaps dream I was back in
Dumfries at 17, walking by the river with my friends, doubled up with laughter
at our mistakes that day, giggling and so glad that it was only a rehearsal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jack Rose</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Appreciation by ALLAN LAING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979256</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JACK ROSE, the Hollywood scriptwriter who has died at the age of 83, was best
known for his professional association with Bob Hope.
He wrote his first full screenplay, Road To Rio, in 1947 and was credited
thereafter as being the man who gave Hope the best of the slick one-liners
which, over the years, became the great comedy actor's trademark.
Rose, a Warsaw Jew, came with his family to America to escape the uncertainty
of pre-War Europe.
They settled in Brooklyn and the teenage Rose went on to study at Ohio
University. He returned to New York where he set himself up as a press agent.
At the same time he started providing jokes for Milton Berle's legendary radio
shows of the late thirties.
This experience persuaded him to move to Hollywood where he began to provide
the wisecracking material for Hope's radio shows. The relationship continued
into movies.
Rose wrote most of his screenplays in partnership with Melville Shavelson.
The association with Bob Hope continued over the years with films such as The
Paleface (for which he provided the gags only), My Favourite Brunette, and The
Great Lover, and Sorrowful Jones. Rose and Shavelson also found time to provide
scripts for Dean Martin, Doris Day, and Jerry Lewis.
In the 1950s, the pair, not only wrote scripts, but also moved into the actual
making of movies (with Shavelson directing and Rose producing).
Their first effort was The Seven Little Foys, based on the life of the
vaudeville entertainer Eddie Foy and his performing family. Appropriately, it
starred Hope in a rare dramatic role.
Other Rose-Shavelson productions included Beau James (again with Hope); The
Five Pennies, starring Danny Kaye; and Houseboat, with Cary Grant and Sophia
Loren. The partnership split in the early sixties and Rose went on to write and
produce movies on his own.
The best - and most successful - of his later work was probably A Touch Of
Class, the 1973 London-set romantic comedy which starred Glenda Jackson and
George Segal.
Appreciation by
ALLAN LAING
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gifts sealed with love</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JANE SCOTTA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979257</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE are a fair few seal pups bobbing around at the Orkney Seal Rescue centre
bearing what the organisers tactfully call ``double-barrelled'' names. But the
person who opens the envelope on Christmas Day and discovers that they have
adopted - and named - a seal of their own, need never know that they might have
joint custody. After all, visiting rights are open to everybody.
Adopting a seal is just one of hundreds of membership schemes and subscription
ideas throughout Scotland that could make truly thoughtful Christmas presents
this year.
It takes a little imagination and a few weeks forward planning, but you could
give your friends and family a stake in an organisation, or a sport, or a
charity, or a pastime that they support, or an introduction to something they
may enjoy doing for years. The only drawback is that a slim envelope containing
membership details or activity vouchers and maybe a photograph of Sammy the
Seal doesn't cut a great dash among the wrapped and predictable bottles of
aftershave and hairdryers under the tree; but in that envelope could be the
best present they ever receive.
The Orkney scheme costs #25, and you choose the name of the seal pup, one of
the current batch of nine who were abandoned or injured and are learning the
ropes of sea life before being returned to the ocean. You get a certificate
(bearing the sponsor's name), details and a photograph of the seal as a new
arrival, plus reports and a final photograph before the pup swims off to his
new life. Write to Orkney Seal Rescue, Dyke End, South Ronaldsay, Orkney, KW17
2TJ. Telephone 01856 831463.
DOLPHINS
n If dolphins are more your thing you may like to try the adoption scheme from
the Whale and Dolphin Conservation Society, who have eight of them in the Moray
Firth rejoicing in the names Jigsaw, Sundance, Bubbles, Rusty, Splash, Nevis,
Kess and Sutor. For your #15 (or #12.50 for the under 16s) you get a
certificate, colour print, window sticker and two Echo newsletters on your
dolphin's life during the year. Write to Alexander House, James Street West,
Bath, Avon, BA1 2BT. Telephone 01225 334511.
WILDLIFE
n Or try Scotland's wildlife parks or zoos for a range of animals: Edinburgh
Zoo can give you everything from a tiny poison arrow frog for #20 to a white
rhinoceros at #1100, taking in dwarf crocodiles (#120) and Macaroni penguins
(#140); the Highland Wildlife Park will give you a Timber Wolf for #280.
Or, if an animal costs more than #60 a year to feed, you can buy units at #20 a
time. Recipients get certificate, stickers, fact sheet, complimentary ticket
and newsletter, plus (for gifts over #60) a name entered on a plaque by the
enclosure. For both of the above, write to the Royal Zoological Society of
Scotland, Corstorphine Road, Edinburgh EH12 6TS. Telephone 0131 334 7730.
TREES
n Or you could plant a tree for Christmas. The Woodland Trust plants a tree in
someone's name for a mere fiver - and sends a Christmas card and certificate to
prove it - at plantations in Formonthills, Glenrothes, Fife, or East Whitburn
Mains, Whitburn, West Lothian. For #25 a group of trees are planted, and the
trust sends details of the wood plus a wallchart; and #40 also buys membership
of the trust with information gift pack, woodland directory and carved oak
``pebble'' as a present. Details from Autumn Park, Grantham, Lincolnshire, NG31
6LL. Telephone 01476 74297.
The Scottish Wildlife Trust (individual membership #15) also offers trees as
gifts; 10 indigenous Scots broadleaf trees are planted in your loved one's name
for #25 at one of their many woodland reserves ranging from Ayr Gorge, to
Carstramon Wood in the Borders, to Ballachuan Hazel Wood, south of Oban. (Other
gifts from the Trust include the #8 education pack Wild Wood of Caledon, with
video, poster and book describing Scottish woodland and wildlife, and the
Hidden Wildlife Activity Book for #2.50, uncovering the secrets of central
Scotland's animals - the Highlands are coming later.
There's also an album, Wild Conserves, which ranges from Runrig to pipe bands,
and costs #10.99 on CD and #5.99 on tape.) Details from Cramond House, Kirk
Cramond, Cramond Glebe Road, Edinburgh, EH4 6NS. Telephone 0131 312 7765.
THE ARTS
n Leaving wildlife for the arts, Scotland's galleries, museums, orchestras and
theatres are crying out for help from the public, and most have membership
schemes. The Eden Court Theatre in Inverness, for example, is running a
donate-a-seat scheme to help raise money for refurbishment and #150 (or four
instalments of #37.50) will buy you the seat (there are 568 left to go out of a
total of 800). For your money you also get a future for theatre in the town,
and the name of your loved one inscribed on a plaque in the foyer. Details from
Rhona Kirk, Friends of Eden Court Theatre, Bishop's Road, Inverness, IV3 5SA.
Telephone 01463 239841.
In Glasgow, membership of the Glasgow Art Gallery and Museums Association
(Gagma) brings private views, illustrated talks, outings, social activities,
magazines and discounts at the museum shops. A Christmas gift subscription of
#15 for individuals (#25 couples), or #12 (#15 couples) for senior citizens,
unemployed and students #5, runs until March 1997, and is accompanied by a
special edition Charles Rennie Mackintosh flower painting card. Write to Art
Gallery and Museum Glasgow, G3 8AG. Telephone 0141 221 9600.
Or buy into the history of Scotland. Membership of the Burns Federation offers
quarterly copies of the group's newsletters, the best local Burns Suppers
you'll see anywhere this January, and invitations to regular meetings and the
annual convention - this year held in Galashiels - at a cost of #12 from the
federation at the Dick Institute, Elmbank Avenue, Kilmarnock, KA1 3BU.
Telephone 01563 572469.
Or buy membership of the Saltire Society, only #15 for newsletters and regular
luncheons, talks and Meet the Scots get-togethers with like-minded folk. Write
to 9 Fountain Close, Edinburgh 1. Telephone 0131 556 1836.
POETRY
n The Book Trust Scotland has four elegant Scottish Poetry Posters, A3 size,
featuring images by Iain Cheyne, Anne Redpath, Charles Rennie Mackintosh and
Sir William Gillies accompanying short poems from Alison Fell, Sorley MacLean,
Hugh MacDiarmid and Alastair Reid; #7.50 per set from Scottish Book Centre, 137
Dundee Street, Edinburgh EH11 1BG. Telephone 0131 229 3663. Or buy a bright
children's poster showing animals busy reading in the jungle under the banner
Wild about books! for #2.
MUSIC
n Fans of Highland music could number among the Friends of Balnain House in
Inverness, a restored Georgian house on the banks of the Ness which hosts an
exhibition ``charting the history of Highland music from day one, when people
banged rocks together to make sounds, right through the ages until you have
Runrig and Capercaillie'' - visitors are encouraged to pick up and play the
pipes, harps and fiddles on display, and often go on to take lessons afterwards.
Friends (#15 individual, #25 families, #10 concessions) have free entry to the
exhibition and reduced entry to the regular concerts and ceilidhs, plus
discounts at the music and gift shop. Details from Balnain House, 40 Huntly
Street, Inverness, IV3 5HR. Telephone 01463 715757.
Good causes can make good presents, too. For #12 you could buy someone a stake
in the Highland Hospice Bonanza, a fundraising scheme which provides a vital
and dependable #7000 a year for the institution, which cares for people from
all over the Highland Health Board area. A quarterly draw gives a first prize
of #1000 and 10 prizes of #12. Write to Highland Hospice Bonanza Club, Ness
House, 1 Bishop's Road, Inverness, IV3 5SB. Telephone 01463 243132.
LESSONS
n And finally, lessons also make a wonderful present. Local music shops can
recommend singing or instrument teachers, and dance classes are springing up
all over the place. There are lots of sports packages available; three days at
Ellis Brigham ski school in Aviemore, for example, (01479 810175) costs #86 and
includes instruction, equipment hire and lift pass, although you'll have to
arrange your own accommodation through the tourist office (01479 810363).
Details from Ellis Brigham, 9-10 Grampian Road, Aviemore, PH22 1RH.
Or try the Highland Drovers package; #18 buys an adult a day driving 4x4 jeeps
and quad bikes in the Aviemore countryside (the kids can drive too, if they're
big enough to reach the steering wheel, and over-10s can go on the quad bikes;
#15 for 10 to 16-year-olds and #10 for under-10s); special rates for families
from Highland Drovers, Kincardine, Boat of Garten, Inverness-shire. Telephone
01479  831329.
Other ideas you might like to check out for yourself include horse-riding
lessons, driving lesson packages, flying lessons, balloon flights or simply
booking a 10-pin bowling lane for the evening - and that's one you can join in
with, too.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Parisian spring when students' fancy turned to riots The recent unrest in France gives Patrick Brogan a sense of dej vu, except that the half-hearted revolutionaries of 1968 seemed more intent on having fun</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979258</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AH, how it all comes back. Paris in the spring. The smell of tear-gas and
Molotov cocktails in the air, the patter of tiny feet as students scatter from
the riot police, the reassuring thump of baton on skull, the clunk of paving
stones falling on the cops' plastic shields.
The chief difference, this time, is the weather. December is really not a good
time for a riot. In 1968, the first disturbances in suburban campuses, were in
early May, and the full crisis came at the end of the month.
The timing was exquisite. The sun was shining, bliss was it in that dawn to be
alive...... and when they weren't rioting, the students could sit on the
terrace of some cafe and discuss Marxist philosophy and the future of the world
to their hearts' content.
The student strikes soon spread to the transport unions and then all across
France. They included the drivers who delivered petrol to filling stations, and
to the petrol pump attendants, too, so there were no cars on the streets. It
was carnival time in the Latin Quarter, a time of sex, revolution and
rock'n'roll (drugs reached France later).
If there was any particular cause of the explosion, it was the overpowering,
stultifying weight of General de Gaulle, and overcrowding in the universities:
this was at the height of the baby boom. It was also at the height of the
miniskirt, which gave a particular delight to rioters on barricades and even to
police chasing them through the streets.
Students took over the Sorbonne and ransacked the offices of unpopular
professors, and camped in the library. They invited tramps to live in the
Odeon, a classic theatre near there, and were surprised at their insanitary
habits.
They talked, endlessly, about reforming society. They were hereditary
revolutionaries: one of their slogans was ``There are 40,000 communes (villages
and towns) in France - we are on the Second,'' meaning that they were heirs to
the Commune that took over Paris in 1871 and burned a lot of it to the ground.
They weren't, of course. Lenin would have despaired. They much preferred talk
to real revolutionary activity. 1968 was quite unlike all previous moments of
French fervour: no-one wanted to kill anyone. It was not 1944, or 1871, or 1848
- let alone 1789.
The handful of fatalities in 1968 were traffic accidents. It was a bourgeois
demonstration for the students, no more, even though they insisted that they
would overthrow General de Gaulle and all his works, and replace him with a
workers' paradise.
They believed in solidarity with the labouring classes, and were hurt and
offended when the unions declined their pressing invitations to join in taking
on the bourgeois state. The workers followed the students' example, and there
was a general strike - but it was not the strike of communist mythology. The
workers were not in the least revolutionary, least of all the communists among
them: all they wanted was the minimum wage raised.
All the same, it was a close-run thing. For a few days, the Fifth Republic was
on the verge of collapse.
The biggest of the student demonstrations, an evening affair, poured across the
Seine waving torches and threatening to bring down the government. It wended
its way to the Bourse, symbol of capitalism par excellence.
They argued with the porter who abused them through the door. He was
unsympathetic to their cause and wouldn't let them in, so they set it on fire.
Once the fire was burning nicely, they let the fire engines through to put it
out before too much damage was done. A special correspondent of the Sunday
Times carried off the tricolour that had flown over the building (it was
subsequently stolen from his office in London - some people have no shame).
Then the crowd marched along the Seine past the Louvre, but instead of
attacking the Elysee, as their predecessors had attacked the emperor's palace,
the Tuilleries, in 1871, or even the Assemblee Nationale or the Prime
Minister's residence, they simply crossed the river again and marched back to
the Latin Quarter.
The government was paralysed, fearing that the regime would fall. General de
Gaulle fled to Germany, to see his army there, just in case he needed it to
retake Paris. Then he decided that enough was enough and the whole business
must end.
He broadcast to the nation, over the radio, in his best military manner, and
that was that.
There was a huge Gaullist demo, perhaps half a million people on the Champs
Elysees the next day, and then it was high summer, time for vacations, the
strikes were settled and the students headed for the coast.
Now there were a few genuine anarchists and revolutionaries among the posturing
and preaching demonstrators. They turned up later, as urban terrorists, in
Action Directe, just as their German comrades formed the Baader-Meinhof gang
and the Italians produced the Red Brigades. But we didn't hear about them for
several years.
The French authorities learnt their lesson. The most damage had been done and
the best barricades built with the paves, granite blocks weighing about 2lbs
each, that had surfaced the roads of Paris for generations.
The moment the rioters had left on vacations, municipal workers were out
tearing up the paves from the Boulevard St German, the Boul' Mich' and all the
other streets of the Latin Quarter, to replace them with tarmac - an inferior
road-covering but much less dangerous. This year, the barricades are much less
solid than those of 1968, thanks to those hasty road-works.
The French economy took years to recover from the concessions made to get the
general strike called off, and the French educational system was thrown into
turmoil, which continues.
As for the general, he came up with an elaborate reform plan, designed to make
people happier at their work. He offered it in a referendum the next summer,
was defeated, and promptly resigned. In due course, the rioters became
respectable and rose to the tops of their various professions, including the
government.
One of the favourite slogans chanted in 1968 was ``This is just a start - keep
up the fight!'' It was all theatre, and very exciting, too. This year's effort
doesn't look like the real thing, either, but it does look much less fun. It's
too cold - and o sont les minis d'antan?
</TEXT>
