<DOCNO>GH951209-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wriggling on the hook of  tartan tax</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979260</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNTIL yesterday we knew one thing, for certain, about the circumstances under
which Labour, in power, would use the discretionary taxation powers of a
Scottish parliament.
The devolved power to raise or lower basic rate income tax in Scotland by up to
3p in the pound is one thing, Labour spokesman after spokesman kept telling us.
But using that power is quite another matter, they would intone, without
pausing for breath.
That oft-repeated rubric was designed to do two things. It ensured that Labour
and its Convention partners could be seen to have imposed on a Scottish
parliament some fiscal responsibility for the decisions it would take.
Even 3p in the pound would raise no more than #550m a year, compared with a
current Scottish Office budget of more than #14,000m. Or, as Tony Blair put it
in his Herald interview, less than 5% of the total. But to have included no
fiscal powers at all in a constitutional settlement would have opened the
devolution side of the argument to charges of creating a toothless, client
assembly, dependent on Whitehall for everything it did.
The rubric's second aim was to still latent fears that a Labour-controlled
parliament in Edinburgh would use those powers to the hilt at the first
opportunity. Not to give away 3p in the pound to Scottish taxpayers, but to
impose it. New Labour, after all, is determined to be seen as ultra-responsible
on tax.
That line of argument - power to tax one thing, using said power quite another
- served well enough until Michael Forsyth became Scottish Secretary and
started turning up the heat on what he dubbed Labour's tartan tax.
Let there be no doubt that the Forsyth assault on the tartan tax has hurt
Labour. As Chancellors of both persuasions down the years know only too well,
pennies up or down on the basic rate of income tax have a symbolic significance
in British life out of all proportion to the actual sums involved.
For someone on average earnings, with taxable income of #12,000 say, a 1p
change in the basic rate means #120 more or #120 less in their pocket over a
full year. But, in terms of direct publicity value, no other taxation measure
is anything like as potent.
As the most publicity-conscious Scottish Secretary in the history of the office
drummed on daily about the ruinous tartan tax, Labour found its established
rubric on the issue crumbling at the edges. Privately, a number of Scottish
Labour MPs readily concede they would get off the tartan tax hook if they
could. But a complete U-turn on taxation powers for the assembly would be
another gift for Mr Forsyth.
Short of a U-turn, Labour's shadow Scottish team has gone on repeating the
power-to-tax-one-thing mantra, hoping against hope that the tartan tax jibe
would become time-expired. It hasn't. If anything, it has grown in potency with
time.
The only thing left for Labour to do was to further refine the rubric, to
define more clearly and precisely the circumstances under which the party would
seek to use that devolved taxation power. When my colleague Ben Brogan and I
went to interview the Labour leader Tony Blair in his rooms at Westminster on
Thursday morning, that was the subject at the top of our list.
Mr Blair, we were both convinced, came up with two significant refinements to
Labour's assembly tax plans. The first is that Labour will accept the
``political obligation'' to put to the Scottish electorate, before each set of
assembly elections, any plans it has to use these taxation powers during the
life of that parliament.
As Mr Blair put it to us: ``Taxes will only go up if the people vote for
them.'' That, in itself, represents a significant hardening of Labour's
approach. If the use of the 3p in the pound power is to be subjected, in
advance, to the democratic mandate of the Scottish electorate, some of the
force of Mr Forsyth's tartan tax allegations is undermined.
But the Labour leader said something else, at least as significant. He said:
``There will be no tax raised at all unless the party goes into an election
promising it and succeeds. We have no plans to do that, never mind anyone
else.'' He went on to say that that meant that all the fears stirred up by Mr
Forsyth were ``completely misplaced''.
Maybe I have failed, down the years, to absorb the real nuances of political
speech. But who, reading that, would fail to conclude that Labour is not
planning to raise taxes in the first term of a Scottish parliament, the words
with which we started our front-page story in yesterday's Herald?
Yet Mr Blair and his office now say that is not what he meant. Why? I can think
of only one substantive reason. It is that, by being seen to say publicly that
there are no plans to raise tax in the assembly, he is seen to be dictating
some of the terms, from London, for the first Labour assembly manifesto in
Scotland.
That may not play well with his shadow Scottish team, led by George Robertson.
It may play even less well with a Scottish Labour Party which, in recent years,
has regarded itself as a major player in an increasingly federal party
structure. Hence the charges of misrepresentation, repeated in Alastair
Campbell's letter to today's Herald.
Only one question remains. Did Mr Blair plant the seed deliberately, despite
the subsequent denial? Or did he, in one unguarded phrase, reveal his private
strategy to defuse Mr Forsyth's tartan tax bomshell, then, when upbraided by
some in his party in Scotland, attempt to backtrack?
(Letters to Editor - page 14)
</TEXT>
