<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Members to be circulated with the facts on BSE NFU digs deep in beef campaign</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY GREGOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979261</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish National Farmers Union is backing moves by the Meat and Livestock
Commission to make the public aware of what the meat industry sees as the facts
about BSE, and the issue will be debated at the Scottish Grand Committee in
Edinburgh on Monday.
The commission is to spend more money this weekend out of its annual #42m
budget in a bid to reassure the public that beef is safe.
In national newspapers, it will be continuing with its ``consumer reassurance
message'' and, in an unprecedented action, is to circulate its 13,000 members
with the latest available information.
The moves show how the meat industry is concerned about threatened public
boycott of beef products and, possibly, even beef.
SFU president John Ross said the farming and meat industries were aware of
widespread public confusion over the consumers' understanding of what is
happening in the beef production system and how it might affect consumers.
He said that Scottish farmers were proud of their reputation as producers of
high quality beef. ``Like farmers throughout Britain, we have given complete
support to Government regulations which deliver the most ultra-precautionary
measures to protect public health,'' he said.
``We are no less concerned about alarmist media reports than the rest of the
public. But the facts, the scientific research, and evidence don't give any
cause for concern about eating beef or beef products.''
At Scottish NFU headquarters, they were maintaining that the message that must
be conveyed to the public is that beef is safe and that there is no scientific
evidence to link BSE with the human disorder Creutzfeld-Jacob disease (CJB).
The Scottish Office maintains that BSE is ``a declining problem with no proven
link to CJB''.
Jim Arbuckle, a leading light in the SFU's beef producing area of Aberdeen and
Kincardine, has called on scientists to pronounce that British meat is safe.
``We need scientists to come out and and speak up for the industry.''
Within the industry, new efforts are being made to decide who should be
responsible for the expense of disposing of specified bovine offal (SBO), the
parts of cattle carcases that are deemed to be unsuitable for any processed
product. It is estimated that the meat industry faces a #23m-a-year bill to
meet stringent health requirements - equivalent to #7 on every beef animal sold
at auction.
Slaughterhouse operators, livestock auctioneers, and cattle producers cannot
agree on who should foot the bill for SBO disposal since the Government has
said it is a problem for the industry to resolve.
In a bid to ease the situation, MLC chairman Don Curry has agreed to act as
independent chairman of a working party involving the Scottish Association of
Meat Wholesalers, the Institute of Auctioneers and Appraisers in Scotland, and
the Scottish Federation of Meat Traders' Associations. It is understood that Mr
Curry had a meeting with Scottish meat industry leaders yesterday.
</TEXT>
