<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dmitri Volkogonov</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Professor BILL WALLACE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979264</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
General Dmitri Antonovich Volkogonov, military commander and historian; born
Anita, Eastern Siberia, March 22, 1928, died Moscow, December 6, 1995
ONE of the most difficult problems facing any society is creating a worthy new
order out of a thoroughly disreputable old one. This was the situation facing
Germany and Japan, for instance, at the end of the Second World War. It is the
morass in which Russia is still toiling as it struggles to get rid of the past
that Lenin, Stalin, and Brezhnev bequeathed to it. And as so often, success
depends above all on the perception and courage of a handful of individuals.
At first sight, General Dmitri Volkogonov must seem an unlikely candidate to be
accorded such an accolade. Revolutions are made by dissidents like Andrei
Sakharov or politicians like Mikhail Gorbachev. Born in 1928, Volkogonov was a
professional Red Army officer from 1949, and for a time he was its senior
propogandist. He served Stalin who had orphaned him when his father was shot in
1937 and his mother was sent to die in the camps. And in Brezhnev's time he
rose to be head of the establishment's Institute of Military History.
Yet Sakharov worked on Russia's bomb and Gorbachev sat in the Politburo.
Society has to use the material it finds. In Volkogonov's case he looked back
on 1941-1945 as the Great Patriotic War; and although he remained ready to
defend his country, he could not in the end do the same for its leaders.
Ironically it was his gradual rise to the institute that gave him access to the
archives that documented the terror though which Stalin had orphaned millions
of other Russians. It was his reflections on these revelations that drove him
back to examine the dictatorship that Lenin established in the name of
scientific Marxism and caused him to question Soviet communism.
And it was Breznev's refusal to sanction publication of his critical biography
of Stalin that led him to work quietly but effectively to help create the
atmosphere in which Gorbachev could emerge as proponent of reform. Gorbachev
authorised publication in 1988.
For outsiders who long knew the catalogue of Stalin's misdeeds it is not easy
to appreciate the impact of Volkogonov's tale. But inside the Soviet Union it
prepared the ground for the banning of the party three years later. His
subsequent biography of Lenin infuriated many communists by turning their
patron saint into a devil but left them powerless to do anything but protest;
and his forthcoming history of the Soviet Union may well complete the
demythologising of Marxism.
The progress of reform turned Volkogonov into at least a semi-politician. He
was elected to the Congress of Deputies in 1990 and to the Duma in 1993, and he
worked steadily to try to bring the liberal reformers together. He became one
of Yeltsin's advisers and eradicated Marxism from the armed forces. In fact, he
had finally become his own man, supporting the storming of the White House in
1993 but opposing the invasion of Chechnya in 1994. On his death Yeltsin issued
a public tribute, while his parliamentary colleagues stood in unusual silence
to honour his passing.
But the purging of the past is far from complete. A new election approaches.
The liberals are divided. Yeltsin is unwell. The Communist Party has been
resurrected and is gaining credibility. And there are some communists who would
now ban Volkogonov's works. However, their new leader, Gennadi Zyuganov, does
not appear to be among them. Perhaps he realises, like most others, that
Volkogonov has done what had to be done. He has exposed the past for what it
was and enabled his countrymen, communists included, to get down to the
long-drawn-out and often frustrating work of creating a better society.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Getting facts on Monklands</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979265</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I NOTE that a group of Labour MPs, headed by Clydesdale's Jimmy Hood, had
tabled a Commons motion criticising Dover Tory MP, David Shaw, and inferring
that in pursuing the Monklands affair he is neglecting his own constituents
(December 2).
It is typical of the West of Scotland Labour Party, and the group of MPs known
colloquially as ``the Jimmies'', that they should seek to intimidate one of the
hardest-working MPs in Parliament.
David Shaw is an accountant and a leading expert in local government finance.
For three years he has been of considerable assistance to local Conservatives,
and others of no political persuasion, as we have attempted to get to the
bottom of the Monklands affair.
That is no easy task from the outside, looking in on a Labour council group
which is riven by dissention.
As chairman of Monklands West Conservative Association it has become obvious to
me that David Shaw works very long hours in advancing the cause of the party,
not only in connection with Monklands, and I deplore the tactics which Jimmy
Hood and his friends are about to adopt.
Against the sort of background which prevails in Monklands, the Scottish Labour
MPs supporting Mr Hood may well find that they have bitten off more than they
can chew.
Indeed the exercise of harassing David Shaw may prove to be counter-productive.
Gordon M Lind,
25 Irvine Crescent,
Coatbridge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Food scares</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979266</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN the past 10 years we have witnessed various food scares involving eggs,
shellfish, cheese, and even a well-known brand of mineral water. Some of these
scares were based on fact and the sector concerned acted quickly and
efficiently to resolve the matter. Other scares were initiated by prominent
public figures (many with a second agenda) or tabloid media creating a public
issue without a shred of factual evidence. The current BSE debate is most
definitely in the latter category.
The fact remains, BSE is a disease of cattle not humans, and although a similar
disease occurs in humans - Creudtzfeldt Jakob Disease - (not the ``human
equivalent'' as popular myth would have it) there is no scientific evidence to
demonstrate a link between the two. Since BSE was first identified as a disease
affecting cattle, there has been a massive effort by farmers, supported by the
Government, to identify the causes and to eradicate the disease. The industry
has an excellent track record of dealing with such problems and the continuing
drop in BSE cases indicates that the present programme is very much on target.
While this eradication process continues, there is considerable independent
work being carried out to establish whether there is any risk to human health.
None has been found.
We are fortunate in Scotland that our beef herds are relatively unaffected by
BSE. There is a worldwide demand for Scotch beef which is still increasing -
for example our exports to Europe have expanded by 300% in the past five years.
Consumers - at home and abroad - are demanding more information on the source
of their beef and in Scotland we have established quality assurance schemes
from farmer to retailer which are the envy of the world: full traceability from
point of consumption to source of primary production.
Our customers can continue to purchase and enjoy Scotch beef with confidence -
confident that it is a quality article reared and processed to the highest
standards of health and hygiene. When coupled to flavour and taste, that means
that Scotch beef can take its place in a healthy and balanced diet.
Responsible consumers retain their faith in our product. It is a pity that
certain scientists and the tabloid media have not listened to the facts.
Eddie Bisset,
Chairman,
Guild of Scotch Quality
Meat Suppliers,
West Mains,
Ingliston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fudging the issue</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979267</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RECENTLY the word "fudge" has been much used to describe the peace process in
Ireland.
But this word is confusing. For many, especially the English, it has pleasant
associations since it is also used by them to describe a sweet confection which
in Scotland is usually called tablet.
Perhaps there is indeed a connection between fudging an issue and sweetness.
However, our strict Scottish ancestors probably decided that our language
should cause no such confusion.
Constance A C Ross,
67 Munro Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Genetic disorder</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979268</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABOUT your report, ``Tragedy of parents who give life and death'' (December 4),
I was a teacher in special education for four years. I object to the parents
having all this guilt laid on them. God gives life and death.
The genetic disorder was responsible for the illness or death not the parents.
I object to them being branded as ``carriers'' by geneticists. We are talking
about people not animals.
One in a million is very rare and testing all relatives is ethically and
morally questionable, as is the whole issue of gene therapy.
Did they agree? How much pressure is being put on parents and relatives by
geneticists and medical advisers? Babies and children are not guinea-pigs.
I object to Jeans for Genes Day. Who thinks these Health Days up anyway? Such
research should be curtailed.
Ruth Gilmour,
45h Chapel Street,
Airdrie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>James Reston</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979269</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
James Barrett Reston, journalist; born Clydebank, November 3, 1909, died
Washington DC, December 6, 1995
IF a model of the emigre Scot was needed James Reston, who has died of cancer
at the age of the 86, might have provided it. If, meanwhile, an exemplar of the
immigrant yielding to none in devotion to his adopted country was sought, the
columnist known for 50 years at the New York Times simply as ``Scotty'' would
have been the man.
James Barrett Reston, born in poverty at Clydebank as the second son of a
machinist, became an American only at the second attempt. His family emigrated
when he was a toddler but returned to Scotland when his devoutly Protestant
mother (who entertained hopes of his entering the Church) became ill. When he
was 11, however, they tried again, moving to Dayton, Ohio, where an
all-American life commenced.
It led to Reston breaking some of the biggest stories around, altering the face
of American newspapers, winning two Pulitzer prizes, and becoming, with Walter
Lippmann, the most influential journalist of his day, a print institution who,
as its Washington bureau chief, lent the Times the aura of omniscience that
still allows Manhattan's grey lady an influence greater than her readership.
``I think newspapering is important,'' he remarked, ``to say nothing of being
fun. It not only involves a man in the struggles of his time, thus keeping him
from going to sleep, but gives him the opportunity, unmatched by the university
or the law, to write on the big issues when people are paying attention.''
Reston, who avoided retirement until he was 80, began with small matters,
however. A poor student at the University of Illinois, he majored in journalism
but secured top grades only in sports reporting. In 1931 he was taken on by the
Springfield (Ohio) Daily News as a sports editor at $10 a week.
Declining to linger, Reston in 1934 found himself a position with the
Associated Press in New York. In 1937 the agency sent him to London with a
brief granted to few, then or now: to cover ``sports'' in the summer and the
Foreign Office during other seasons.
In 1939 he joined the New York Times, signing on the day Hitler's troops
marched into Poland. The salary of $85 a week was enviable, but so little
thought did the home office give to its latest hiring that when his first
by-line appeared it followed newspaper tradition and got his name wrong.
He had a good war nevertheless. Matching in print what Edward R Murrow was
doing in broadcasting, Reston helped to shift American public opinion to
Britain's side with his coverage of the Blitz. Like Murrow, he had a ringside
seat from which to observe London's devastation, and his despatches did much to
end American isolationism.
It was after the war, however, that Reston came into his own. As chief
correspondent for the Washington bureau of the Times from 1953 to 1964 he put
himself, in American parlance, ``in the loop'', with matchless contacts, an
acute historical sense, and a fine discrimination of when it was (and was not)
appropriate to unleash the clout of his paper.
By that time he had won his first Pulitzer prize, having been tipped off in
1944 of plans being laid at Dunbarton Oaks for the United Nations.
Reston had the entire story, and parcelled it out over a week in a series of
exclusives. In 1956 his coverage of the presidential elections won him a second
Pulitzer.
He was by then a nationally-syndicated columnist, having begun a thrice-weekly
column in 1953 that was to continue until 1987. His career was briefly marred
in 1968 by a spell as executive editor of the Times, a job for which he had
neither aptitude nor appetite, but from 1969 to 1974 he served as a
vice-president of the paper, an institution within an institution, holder of
the Legion d'Honneur, recipient of the CBE, the Norwegian Order of St Olav, and
the Chilean Order of Merit. Meanwhile, he introduced America to the concept of
the ``op-ed'' comment page.
His influence led to criticism that he pulled his punches. Reston played down a
report of plans for the Bay of Pigs assault, for example, and ``spiked'', at
JFK's request, an exclusive account of the Soviet missiles being sited on Cuba.
The charge was that he had ceased to scrutinise the Establishment and had
become part of it.
In 1980 he replied: ``If you spend your life as a hatchet man - and there's
something to be said for that - then eventually you find that everybody's out
to lunch when you call. You're left with your opinion. I wouldn't like that
because my own opinions aren't that good.''
He was rarely so disingenuous. Of Nixon and Watergate, for example, Reston
recorded the verdict: ``There is scarcely a noble principle in the Constitution
that he hasn't defended in theory or defied in practice.''
But it was of his adopted country that the emigre spoke with love. Interviewed
in 1991, he said: ``In the 50 years that I've been working here there is no
country in the history of the world that has done so much for the human family
as this country has.''
He is survived by his wife, three sons, and five grand-children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Republic and the Jews</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979270</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HUGH McLoughlin, like many apologists for Irish nationalism, is strong on
rhetoric but rather weak on the facts (December 1).
In the Irish Republic in 1923 there was one Protestant Cabinet Minister and 14
Protestant MPs. Now there is no Minister and only two MPs.
The census of the population of Ireland, taken in 1881, shows that there were
17,660 Methodists; in 1981 there were 5790. In 1881 there were 56,498
Presbyterians; in 1981 there were 14,255.
In 1881, 317,576 people were members of the Church of Ireland; in 1981 members
totalled 95,366. Over a 100-year period during which Irish nationalism has been
the major force on the island, approximately three out of four Protestants had
fled the Republic.
Should Mr McLoughlin be in any doubt as to the major ingredient in stampeding
Protestants out of the Republic, I suggest that he invest in some history books.
With regard to the Jewish community in the Republic, the record of the state is
appalling. Mr McLoughlin opines that the treatment of Jews in the Republic ``is
to the credit of Eamon de Valera''. The facts tell a different story.
Attempts by Jewish refugees fleeing Nazi persecution to get asylum in Ireland
in the 1930s and 1940s ran up against an official anti-Semitic policy which saw
Jews as a ``potential irritant in the body politic'' and as having
``disproportionate wealth and influence''.
In 1939 Mr de Valera turned down requests from both Mr Bob Briscoe, the only
Jewish Fianna Fail TD, and the father of Mr Gerald Goldberg, later to be a
Jewish Lord Major of Cork, to grant asylum to a German Jew who jumped ship at
Cobh. The man was returned to continental Europe where he was arrested and put
in a concentration camp although he managed to survive the war.
The Irish ambassador who served in Berlin from 1932 to 1939 claimed in his
report to Dublin that ``Jewish emigrants in the countries which they have been
permitted to enter have created, and are creating, grave moral scandals and are
a source of corruption of the populations among which they dwell''.
The Departments of Justice and Industry and Commerce, headed by Mr Gerry Boland
and Mr Sean Lemass respectively, strongly opposed any entry of Jews into
Ireland even after the full facts of the Holocaust were known.
A Department of Justice memorandum on the admission of refugees from the
continent, dated September 24, 1945, had a section on Jews which read, ``The
immigration of Jews is generally discouraged. The wealth and influence of the
Jewish Community in this country appears to have increased considerably in
recent years and there is some danger of exciting opposition and controversy if
this tendency continues.''
I would submit that the record of the Irish Republic with regard to its
Protestant and Jewish citizens is not one to be proud of.
Mark Dingwall,
30 Rotherwood Avenue,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000132</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000132</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Emu debate Pragmatism not brute economics</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979271</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JUST for a change let us look at Europe beyond the self-interest of one
political party in the United Kingdom and see the prospect of a single currency
as perceived by most of the EU's member states. Those in favour are all in the
D-mark zone, unworried by the prospect of the great single currency adventure
ending in tears. For them there won't really be any nasty consequences if
economic and monetary union (Emu) turns out to be a bird that cannot fly.
Theirs, after all, is the kingdom of monetary peace, with or without the single
currency. The D-mark rules, and that is an end to it. How else can you explain
why, for example, 75% of the Dutch support the idea of a single currency, as a
poll showed yesterday? This debate is more about pragmatism than brute
economics among the EU member states who do not share the British
Conservatives' hang-ups about national sovereignty.
But what of the French? They are the real players in this increasingly tense
game. France has been forced to recognise that German economic power really
does rule. France knows its economic self-determination has long since been
lost to Frankfurt. Opting out of Emu would solve nothing. Opting into Emu,
however, would give France shared control of Europe's monetary destiny. It
would give Paris a voice and a vote in the boardroom of the European Central
Bank which would be the French way of winning the political battle after losing
the economic one. Britain please note. This is why Chancellor Kohl and
President Chirac remain close on the Emu issue and why Chirac is prepared to
test the will of his resentful workforce on behalf of Emu's demanding
qualification criteria.
Emu will consign the Bundesbank to history. The Germans stand to be outvoted
and their influence limited, if not neutered. Why, therefore, does Chancellor
Kohl insist that the single currency is the holy grail? Because, of course, he
is a genuine European, and one who carries history on his German back. He wants
a vibrant Europe with a strong currency and a powerful, wealth-producing
Germany embedded politically and economically in a Europe safely distanced from
Russia which is, in turn, why he wants new EU buffer states to the east. That
way, he believes, lies permanent European peace and prosperity. Those who still
cling to romantic notions of British sovereignty being essential to monetary
power might reflect on the fact that there was a time, not so long ago, when
the pound bought 10 D-marks. Now it buys two. Next question, please.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Surrender of weapons Hardliners back manoeuvring for position</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979272</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE should be little surprise over the IRA's latest outburst about
surrendering weapons. It is a well-worn tactic, another example of their
brinkmanship skills, a talent they have sharpened since last year's ceasefire
and a talent being exercised by every grouping in Northern Ireland.
The timing is important here. Bill Clinton has returned to Washington,
strengthened in his election campaign by the fortuitous a
Intransigence is not the exclusive property of the IRA, however. Loyalist
defiance on giving up arms is as strong as ever and Senator Mitchell is
unlikely to find any chink in their wall of resistance. So, after the explosion
of optimism around the Christmas tree in Belfast's Guildhall Square last week
the hardliners are quickly back to the business of manoeuvring for position and
avoiding loss of face. The people of the province have shown astonishing
resilience over more than 20 years of terrorism. Their patience and courage
deserve greater reward. Senator Mitchell must be at his disarming best to find
a form of words that will satisfy the gunmen. Perhaps a few words from
President Clinton's address in a West Belfast factory would bear repeating to
all sides. ``Engaging in honest dialogue is not an act of surrender, but an act
of strength and common sense.''
</TEXT>
