<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cold comfort Good to be back in winter</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979273</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS week saw the start of the cold spell in Scotland; well they said it would.
We had all those chaps predicting that the country would be awash with cold
fronts from Siberia. We are never sure about predictions: we are aghast at
nonsense about far-away countries. Siberia might be cold and Scotland certainly
is. But we doubt that cold winds from the Steppes result in anything quite as
miserable as the bleakest corners of the industrial belt.
There are those who are happy in this. After all, Scots can't complain much.
They had a wonderful spring with balmy breezes, a summer which demanded girls
in white dresses and an autumn with a leaf left on a tree enough for O'Henry's
short story The Last Leaf. It is, rather like all O'Henry stories a bit
fleeting, a bit slight, a lot important. It was about a dying girl in the
mid-winter. There is some romance about mid-winter, and a touch of melancholy,
and O'Henry got it right. Sadly British weather forecasters do not seem to find
the right note on the matter of cold weather, and indeed many Scots freeze on
this too. The fact is that a cold winter is natural to Scotland and we should
all look forward to it, the way we enjoy hot summers. Blazers and white ducks
in summer are spendidly contrasted with Dents gloves, cashmere scarves, and
Crombie overcoats in the white freeze of the first season of the year.
It is somehow good to be back in winter. Doubtless readers look forward to
coats out of the cleaners, and cheery children with faces red with frost and a
decent bottle of sherry at a fireside. And then spring, and summer, and even
autumn. But Siberian cold is welcome. Comfort in the frost.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Getting the message</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979274</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONSERVATIVE politicians complain that the reason for their poor showing in the
polls is that they are not getting their message across, the problem being the
packaging not the product.
There is one issue on which I think the Tories are genuinely not getting their
message across, and that is on the subject of a devolved legislature for
Scotland as proposed by the Constitutional Convention.
One one hand Michael Forsyth and other Scottish Ministers have told us that
such a parliament would be a disaster for Scotland. They have predicted another
Albania, a jobs holocaust, and a stampede of jobs across the Border.
On the other hand Michael Forsyth tells us that such a devolved parliament
would create a slippery slope resulting in the restoration of Scottish national
independence by 2002.
I can only take this to mean that a devolved parliament will be so successful
and popular that voters will demand more and more powers for it.
Which of these predicted outcomes are voters supposed to believe, the jobs
holocaust scenario or the slippery slope scenario? They appear to be mutually
exclusive.
If the devolved parliament is a disaster, there will be no popular demand for
additional powers for it and no slippery slope, instead perhaps a demand for a
return to centralised government from Westminster.
However, if indeed there is a slippery slope, it will have come about only
because it was seen as a success by a majority of the electorate.
Mr Forsyth cannot have it both ways. Would he please get his message across?
Denis Bain,
35 Colthill Crescent,
Milltimber,
Aberdeen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
