<DOCNO>GH951209-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Familiar names</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979275</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UGH Dougherty's Tale of two Hughs sounded familiar, although my wife and I had
a good excuse - our son was born on my birthday.
In the early years we became known to family and friends as ``big'' and ``wee''
Bruce respectively, that is until ``wee'' grew into ``big'' (we're both 6ft
5in).
In correspondence we thought we would overcome the problem by each using our
middle initial, but few replies are received in like fashion; the only time
Junior has the monopoly is on St Valentine's Day.
My advice to Hugh Sen is to encourage Jun to change direction at university and
study medicine, divinity, or such profession that carries a specific title.
Bruce C, studying medicine, has been warned not to take such steps as would
cause him to revert to Mr, although presumably by that time he will be living
at a different address.
Bruce R Henderson,
East Lodge,
Corraith,
Symington,
Ayrshire.
</TEXT>
