<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Smollett's origins</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979276</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONRAD Wilson ought to refrain from regurgitating the publicity blurb from
Cameron House on Loch Lomond that their mock baronial pile is the birthplace of
Tobias Smollett.
The eighteenth-century wordsmith was a Vale man born on the shores of the
mighty Leven in the fair village of Renton. A fine memorial to this event with
Latin inscription by none other than Dr Johnson stands in the grounds of Renton
Primary School for all to view.
James P Rogers,
1 Cumberland Avenue,
Helensburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Elgin sign Fort pair</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979277</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HIGHLAND LEAGUE
ELGIN City have made a double signing swoop for two Fort William players.
Keeper Billy Neilson and club top-scorer Alan Moir will both make their debuts
in today's Highland League tussle with on-form Wick at Borough Briggs.
The pair were among five Inverness and Aberdeen-based players put up for free
transfer after Fort William admitted they could no longer afford to pay
travelling expenses.
Experienced defender Billy Skinner is Elgin manager Chico McHardy's next
target, but Clach and Forres are also chasing his signature.
Neilson will replace off-form keeper Dean Lawson, while Aberdeen University
student, Moir, could prove the perfect foil up front for Iain Polworth.
Clach have a welcome rest this weekend, but will give fringe players a chance
to step up their challenge for a first-team spot during a reserve outing.
Nairn County entertain Buckie Thistle, who tore Elgin apart in a 4-1 win last
weekend.
In the game of the day, leaders Huntly travel to play Qualifying Cup champions
Fraserburgh, while title-chasers Cove face unpredictable Rothes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tartan tax</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979278</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE first sentence of your front page story (Blair promises Scots a veto on
tartan tax) was a misrepresentation of the interview on which it was based
(December 8).
Mr Blair made the point, as he has many times before, that though Labour has no
plans to raise tax the programme of the Labour Party will be put forward by the
Scottish Labour Party at the time of the elections for the Scottish parliament.
Nothing more. Nothing less.
I regret that this means that your editorial was based upon this
misrepresentation and I would be grateful if you would publish this letter to
set the record straight.
Alastair Campbell,
Press Secretary to
Tony Blair,
House of Commons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Action on wages in Third World</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979279</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT would be sad if the report (December 4) contrasting the treatment of the
Third World workers who make sports shoes with the obscene amounts of money
paid to sports stars for wearing them simply left us with a sense of guilt when
it is positive action that is really needed.
Manufacturers are always telling us they respond to consumer demand: it is time
we started telling them that the injustice suffered by Third World workers is
unacceptable.
It may mean that sports shoes will cost a bit more, but if it means better
health and a fairer deal for the workers it is surely a price worth paying.
What better time than Christmas to be making a point that could bring good
tidings to the poor?
Ailsa E Henderson,
10 Ferry Road,
Fairlie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gough having a tough tour</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979280</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DARREN Gough's tour to South Africa was under a new cloud last night after he
limped out of England's attack with a knee injury in Paarl.
On a day when Jack Russell again could do little wrong by scoring a century,
Gough pulled up in pain during his fourth over and played no further part as
Boland reached 129 for four in reply to the tourists' 402 for eight declared.
The Yorkshire fast bowler's Test place is already under threat following a
disappointing performance during the Johannesburg draw. And now Gough must not
only show some decent form over the last two days of this match but prove he is
fit enough to warrant a place in a four-man attack when the series resumes at
Durban next week.
``We want to see Darren bowl here,'' said manager Ray Illingworth. ``If we play
a four-man attack in the third Test we couldn't risk one not being fit.
``The injury is a concern but we should have a better idea about it tomorrow
after he's had a night's rest.''
While not much is going right for Gough, Russell has found the Midas touch. A
world-record 11 catches in Johannesburg was followed by his rearguard action
with Mike Atherton to save the second Test.
Now he is celebrating his highest first-class score, the fifth century of his
career, and a second hundred in England colours - six years after having made
128 not out against Australia during an Ashes Test at Old Trafford.
The home side lost four wickets yesterday before the close, with Terrence
Lazard stumped by Russell, Lloyd Ferreira bowled, Kenny Jackson taken bad and
pad, and Bryan Baguley caught at third slip.
England 402-8 dec (R C Russell 129 no, R K Illingworth 57 no, G A Thorpe 56).
Boland 129-4.
q.NASSER Hussain's England A team had to battle hard yesterday in Peshawar to
protect their Test series advantage.
Put into bat after having lost the toss, Hussain's side made sound progress in
the hour's play possible before a lunch interval extended to accommodate
holiday prayers.
But in the afternoon session, batting became more difficult as Pakistan A
seamers Shahid Nazir and Athar Laiq began to swing the ball. ``Seam bowlers
like to use an older ball here because they can get reverse swing,'' sid the
England captain. ``It was reverse swinging both ways here and it made for the
trickiest session we have yet faced on this tour.''
Hussain, Anthony McGrath, and top scorer Nick Knight all fell lbw to the
swinging ball after Akram Raza snapped up Jason Gallian.
q.SHANE Warne moved within sight of a double century of Test wickets as Sri
Lanka struggled to 251 all out on the first day of the first Test against
Australia in Perth. Warne claimed three Sri Lankan wickets and lift his Test
haul to 198.
q A 50-run partnership between Chris Cairns (32) and Roger Twose (44) took New
Zealand to 179 for four in their first innings at lunch on the second day of
the one-off Test in Christchurch as they replied to Pakistan's total of 208.
Stephen Fleming's was the only wicket to fall in the session, stumped for 25.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Scots Tung</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979281</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF Messrs Hodgert (Herald Essay) and Heinsar have their way The Herald's
correspondence will soon require sub-titles (December 2).
Mr Heinsar's letter identifies him as convener, Scots Tung. How quaint! I
wonder what they have in their sandwiches.
I think I have, however, translated sufficient of his maunderings to elicit
that he agrees with me. This will, no doubt, come as a shock, or some wholely
appropriate Scots word known only to those who speak in tungs, etc.
We both, apparently, agree that the Scottish Education Department is absolutely
correct in employing Mr Hodgert. He does, after all, earn his livelihood by
teaching (ie, instructing, expounding, preaching) English.
David S Wilson,
11 Lomond Drive,
Newton Mearns.
</TEXT>
