<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wheat export tax</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<FLAG>digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979282</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE EU has agreed to impose a tax, of #30 a tonne, on wheat exports for the
first time in 21 years. The aim is to safeguard Community supplies by making it
more difficult for farmers to sell on the world market where demand is high.
Auction profits up
RISING livestock prices helped Scottish auctioneer John Swan &amp; Sons increase
interim pre-tax profits to #279,000 from #193,000. The number of lambs handled
at the company's auction yards in Edinburgh and Newtown St Boswells was static
during the six months to October 31 but there was a small increase in the
number of cattle sold.
Arable payments
SCOTTISH farmers will receive a further #64m in arable aid payments over the
next few days. Early payment of about #38m was made in October to 2800 farmers
in the North-east as a response to flooding problems. Agriculture Minister Lord
Lindsay said the pay-outs were considerably earlier this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Get a provincial act in order, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN BEATTIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979283</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THAT'S it. Ready. . . aim . . . fire! Stirling, kindly extricate yourselves
from the Glasgow set-up if that's what you want. And Glasgow, take a leaf out
of Stirling's history, and embrace the need for some provincial rugby to lead
the way.
There's a solution, and it includes stipulating in black ink that you play for
the province in which you live, and no other.
And the provinces play in Europe. That's the only way to stop players from
moving to England.
If they move to England, then they miss out on European rugby. Read on.
Let's not muck about here. All these high level meetings between the current
``big'' clubs in Scotland are all about how to get money at the expense of the
districts. It has nothing to do with protecting the poor little clubs against
extinction, it's about getting the big clubs into Europe so that they can get
the cash.
In an effort to keep sweet those who don't make it, I am convinced that those
that do will offer to divvy up the cash. Whatever, the money paid to the
provinces when they play in Europe must, in turn, go to the clubs who provide
the players.
I am a big fan of Stirling County Rugby Club. It has become the modern Hawick
in a way. Unlike Hawick, there's no feeder system in the town, but I well
remember Brian Edwards at the start of the season saying that he wanted
Stirling to become, in effect, a provincial side.
And it has. Frankly, however, I find it a farce that you can have five County
blokes in a Glasgow side playing a load of County blokes in a North and
Midlands team. If the SRU, or the provinces only had the bottle, the Stirling
County lads would have to play for a stipulated team. Whichever doesn't matter,
so long as it's just the one.
Where does that leave Glasgow? Well, this little old place should get its
little act together and lay down the foundations for success. That means
getting a team into the first division as soon as possible, and generating a
real city identity which means that if you don't live in it, then you can't
play for it.
Glasgow has a few options. The city could, on the one hand, go to the SRU and
say that they were going their own way by setting up a regional league based
around Glasgow, but there would be two teams put forward for the existing
Premier Leagues - Glasgow North and Glasgow South, which would be selected by
the existing clubs.
I like that idea. I've always liked the two-finger approach. We keep West, GHK,
Accies, Hillhead Jordanhill, Kilmarnock, Ayr, Glasgow Southern and all the
others. They would play each other regularly. It would be fearsome stuff. But
would the North and South teams get support?
On the other hand, West of Scotland, who own their own ground, could hold the
key if they were willing to give up their identity, sell their ground, and use
that money to kick start a Glasgow North team that, again, would be selected by
the feeder clubs and take over the West of Scotland fixtures. Clubs like GHK
would survive, and try to stay in the Premier Leagues.
The third option, and the most likely, is to swallow the medicine and accept
that the current league format is here to stay, and if Glasgow wants a team in
the top division, or maybe even two teams, then some amalgamations have to
happen. Hard, hard medicine.
There's no doubt that clubs are the bedrock of Scottish rugby, and they always
will be. Glasgow immediately must get all of the clubs around the table to sort
out what it is going to do, and then spend the summer training its players as
never before. But there has to be a step up from club level for our players
before they play internationals, and it's the success or failure of the
international team that counts in all of this. And, being a Glasgow chappie,
what matters is the success or failure of the Glasgow side and the city's clubs.
I don't think we're a boot in the nether regions away from a good domestic set
up, even though it takes a statistician's brain to look ahead the way you have
to.
Europe will be exciting, and I think it is plainly unreasonable for the clubs
to want in. Scottish provinces, possibly even joint provinces, must take on the
Baths of this world.
For they are provinces too.
It's up to Glasgow what they do now. The smiling and joking has to stop. Get
the clubs round a big table to get strong clubs and a strong city. The
provinces have to go into Europe, and you can't play for a province unless you
live in it.
It's how Glasgow get clubs into the first division that's the big question.
</TEXT>
