<HEADLINE>Bordering on  the beautiful</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LESLEY DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>book review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979284</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n THE garden is dank with rotting vegetation and the skeletal remains of
summer's flowers. What better time for getting dug into a gardening book which
mixes advice and information with delightful pictures? Molly Ephraums's Easy
Borders is just such a book - with the additional lure of offering insights
into ``high performance plants for low-maintenance gardens''.
Ephraums's aim is to remove the drudgery of traditional borders with their
labour-intensive requirements. Since she writes from experience of her own
cottage garden in Angus, Scottish readers, used to taking the advice of
southern tomes with some scepticism, can be sure the information relates to
local conditions.
Ephraums started the restoration of her derelict cottage garden 25 years ago.
The remains of its two herbaceous borders affected her then ``in much the same
way as two abandoned strays would affect a devoted dog-lover''. Canine analogy
apart, she has an endearing habit of referring to border plants like children
of varying degrees of naughtiness and good behaviour. Her reports cards are
candid: ``Beautiful they might be but their manners left a great deal to be
desired . . .''
For her the secret of successful borders lies largely in using the correct
plants. Perhaps she overemphasises the problems of unruly vegetation but she
also describes the joys of finding something unusual, like old varieties of
dianthus or double primroses.
Her advice on design includes defining freestanding beds by using a hose pipe
which can be staked out into all sorts of curving shapes; and much else
besides, from general cultivation to the use of weed gloves (a touch sinister,
the last). All this, however, is mere preparation for herbaceous planting plans
for various situations and colour schemes.
Her poolside planting - illustrated in watercolours - looks delectable with
hostas and primulas and astilbes among its range of 18 easy perennials in
shades of pink and blue and white. A golden trollius gives contrast. There's
also advice on pond maintenance.
There are illustrated plans for a variety of herbaceous borders, some involving
shrubs and summer bulbs as well as perennials, and a plant directory -
illustrated this time with colour photographs. Plant lists - showing height,
colour, and flowering season - plus a list of useful addresses pad out this
slim charmer of a book.
n Easy Borders by Molly Ephraums is published by David and Charles at #15.99.
</TEXT>
