<HEADLINE>Brochs, bagpipes, and brigands</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ADRIAN GARDINER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>39</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979285</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE name has nothing to do with Sardines. Legend has it that when the ancient
Greeks first mapped the Mediterranean, the island looked like a footprint - the
Greek for which was Sardinia.
Those Greeks were among many early visitors. The Carthaginians and Phoenicians
have left tangible evidence of occupation. The Spanish planted vines. Lord
Nelson, recognising its strategic importance, tried unsuccessfully to buy the
island for #500,000. Later, Sardinia allied with the Piedmont region to build
the foundations of the modern Italian State.
It has, however, remained a backwater. At least nine hours by ferry from the
Italian mainland, an hour by air from Rome, it is as remote as Shetland is from
Lowland Scotland. And do not be put off by D. H. Lawrence's petulant
observations in Sea and Sardinia: ``Nothing to see. Sights are an irritating
bore.'' He could hardly have been more wrong.
Around 500BC and earlier, there lived a race called the nuraghi people. We know
as little about them as we know about the Picts. They lived in circular stone
towers - also nuraghi - resembling Scottish brochs, with which they share
several architectural features. There are some 7000 on Sardinia: most ruined,
some undergoing meticulous stone-by-stone restoration.
The nuraghi people had a hierarchy too: the royal palace at Su Nuraxi is one of
the most impressive sites.
In more recent times Sardinia was put on the map by the Aga Khan. In the early
1960s his yacht was hit by a sudden Mediterranean storm and anchored in a
sheltered bay on the north-east coast. Impressed by the clear sea and pristine
white beaches, he built a holiday villa. News spread among the jet-set. A hotel
followed, a marina, a golf course, another hotel . . . and, because the sea is
more green than blue, the area was dubbed the Costa Smeralda, the Emerald
Coast.
A consortium was formed to monitor development along careful environmental
guidelines and today it is one of the world's most upmarket resorts.
Elsewhere, Sardinia slumbers in a time warp. Only in recent years have those
scourges of the visitor, the brigands of Barbagiaolollolia, abated their
activities. Earlier this century travellers dared not visit the mountains of
the inhospitable interior. Kidnapping was rife, usually of the children of the
rich and famous. To encourage prompt payment of ransom, parts of the body were
sent, beginning with the ear lobes.
Community support for this activity has waned. On the last occasion, some years
ago, the entire population of the town of Oliena hung white sheets from their
windows in protest.
St Efisio is the patron saint of Cagliari, Sardinia's capital. On the first
Sunday in May, every year since 1656 (apart from two cancellations because of
world wars) the city celebrates his feast day.
Thousands line the streets as a procession of traccas (floats) decorated with a
riot of flowers and pulled by oxen trundles through the town. Bands play.
Finally an ornate gilded coach carrying the saint's effigy makes its majestic
way out of the city and along the coast road to the chapel dedicated to Efisio.
It causes a traffic jam which looks impressive even by our motorway standards.
Sassari, Sardinia's second city, holds it cavalcata a fortnight later. A
horseback race as spectacular as Siena's Palio is followed by a procession in
which every village on the island is represented in vivid traditional costume.
From Cagliari's tiny station the Trenino Verde (Green Train) climbs for 120
miles through mountains of oak and chestnut, arriving after nine hours and 35
stations at Arbatax on the east coast. Built in the 1890s as rural transport,
the narrow-gauge track is reminiscent of a fairground rollercoaster, with
fantastic gradients, tunnels and bends. The elegant carriages of polished wood
and brass are normally pulled by a diesel, but on occasion the engineers' pride
and joy is given an outing. The little black steam locomotive Goito was new in
1896.
Farther north - if you can drag yourself away from those immaculate beaches and
uninhabited rocky coves - is the province and town of Nuoro. It is home to
Sardinia's chief ethnographic museum. The collection of folklore is
comprehensive, but lacks hands-on appeal. Much more intersting, we thought, is
the tiny museo degli strumenti popolare Sarda at Tadasuni.
Giovanni Dore has collected 450 traditional instruments and he can play them
all. Many are percussive: strange contraptions of wood and string. A curious
drum producing ultra-low frequencies was once used as a weapon of war between
local tribes.
There are accordions ancient and modern. The traditional pipes of Sardinia,
lauddas, typically consist of three reeds: two short ones played by the fingers
and a longer one functioning as a drone. They take a lot of puff, so later a
tartan-covered bag was added and the zampogna bears a striking resemblance to
our own bagpipes. I could not place the tartan, however . . . the McSard,
perhaps?
Music featured on our final Sardinian excurison. From the Capo d'Orso, named
from a bear-shaped rock on the northern tip of the island, we sailed through
the scattered islets of the Maddalena archipelago. Gari-baldi, the Italian
patriot, had his holiday home on one. With Corsica on the horizon, we anchored
off a beach of white sand enclosed by a ring of pink porphyritic rocks set in
an emerald sea. A quick dip is followed by lunch on deck, then the crew produce
accordions and treat us to some Sardinian sea shanties. Bellissimo.
n Getting to Sardinia is easier now that Meridiana, Italy's largest private
airline, has introdicued ten direct flights per week from London Gatwick to
Cagliari and Olbia on the Costa Smeralda. Return flights cost #239-295,
depending on season. Its London office is on 0171 839 2222.
Accommodation: some hotels on the Costa Smeralda are among the most expensive
in the world. Off-season (May and September) they are more affordable. Good
value is the Hotel Capo d'Orso; half-board per person per day #35 low season,
#68. Agriturismo, B&amp;B with a local family, is beginning to catch on. It is run
by the Women's Co-operative of Sheep Breeders and B&amp;B costs about #12 per
night, though there's a minimum stay of seven days. Contact the Coop
Allevatrici Sarde Agriturismo, casella postale 107, 09170 Oristano, Sardegna,
Italy.
Tour operators specialising in Sardinia: Citalia 0181 686 0677; Sardatur
Holidays 0171 242 2455; Magic of Italy 0181 748 7575; and Costa Smeralda
Holidays 0171 493 8303. The Italian State Tourist Board is at 1 Princes Street,
London, W1R 8AY (0171 355 1439).
</TEXT>
