<HEADLINE>First impressions count for so much</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LIZ TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979286</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNLIKELY as it may sound to people who know me, I have, in the interests of
this column, been running for Rembrandt . . . in the New York Marathon no less.
It was all a mistake, of course, and could well have ended in disaster.
I was to be in New York on holiday when Sotheby's were showing a magnificent
selection of 122 Rembrandt etchings which span the artist's career and are of
the very highest quality; the sort of collection art lovers will travel a very
long way to see.
The etchings could only be viewed by appointment so I arranged to see them on
the afternoon of Sunday, November 12, at Sotheby's premises in E 76th Street.
Imagine my horror when I turned up on 3rd Avenue and found my way blocked by a
solid stream of puffing, sweating, blank eyed marathon runners.
More than 27,000 people were taking part in the New York Marathon and my route
to the Rembrandts was bisected by them.
``How do I cross the road? I've an appointment over there at two o'clock,'' I
complained to a policeman who merely shrugged and said, ``Can't stop the
marathon for you, ma'am.''
Then, out of the crowd of spectators came my saviour, a tall young man with a
mop of wild curls. ``I'll run you across,'' he said.
``Run me across?''
``Yeah, take my hand and run with me and we'll get across.''
``I'm scared,'' I said, eyeing the runners, a phalanx of bodies, pounding
shoulder to shoulder along the street and none of them looked prepared to stop
for anything.
``They'll run over the top of me.''
By now the cop was in on the act. ``If you run with them, and cross bit by bit,
you might do it,'' he said, and before I knew what was happening, I was running
across the avenue, hanging on to the young man and dodging marathon runners.
We made it without incident and when we reached the other side, he shook my
hand, wished me a good day and disappeared.
The exhibition was worth the effort for it was easily the finest collection of
etchings I have ever seen.
All 122 of the works were brought together with infinite care and
discrimination over a period of 20 years by a Dutch collector called Joost R.
Ritman. He is a supplier of utensils to airlines but his business has hit a bad
patch and he has been forced to put his cherished Rembrandt collection up for
sale.
The etchings will not be sold individually but as a complete collection and the
price is in the region of #20m.
In the interest of alerting serious collectors with that sort of money,
Sotheby's have been touring the etchings very discreetly - some of them were on
view in London and in the Hague, but it was only in New York that they could
all be seen together.
Nancy Bialler, director of Sotheby's Old Master Prints Department in New York,
says there is already serious interest from several private connoisseurs who
want to buy the collection which matches in quality works held by the British
Museum or the Rijksprentenkabinet in Amsterdam.
The etchings give a panoramic view of the work Rembrandt did throughout his
life - biblical scenes, landscapes, genre scenes, portraits, nudes and
still-lifes.
Among the ones that particularly pleased me was a tiny scrap of paper, an
etching of a sleeping puppy, done around 1640. Also impressive was a portrait
of Clement de Jonghe, dating from 1651, which bears in the top left hand corner
a distinct thumb print of the artist.
The star of the show was the largest picture in the collection (383 x 447mm), a
drypoint etching entitled ``Christ Presented to the People, the Ecce Homo''.
This picture was bought by Ritman at Christie's London auction of prints
belonging to the Duke of Devonshire in 1985. He paid #580,000 for it. Nancy
Bailler reckons it is worth around #1m today.
When he bought, Ritman went for quality and from time to time he was able to
buy duplicates of certain prints, done on different sorts of paper or vellum
and when they are displayed side by side, the variations caused by the
different types of paper are clear to see.
He also sought out rarities like one of the few erotic prints Rembrandt ever
made. Called ``The Monk in the Cornfield'', it shows a monk and a peasant woman
caught in flagrante delicto.
Bailler was amused by the reactions of solemn art lovers reverently viewing the
selection when they came across this one - ``They always do a surprised second
take,'' she says.
It is thought that Rembrandt got the idea for this etching from an engraving by
Heinrich Aldegrever entitled ``The Monk and The Nun'' but he stripped it of its
anti-Catholic, pro-Reformation message and left only the erotic.
Rembrandt was superb at portraits and prominent in the selection on show were
two stunning examples of self-portraiture - one of himself in portly old age
and the other of him as a young man with wildly curling hair and a dashing look.
When I saw it, I stood back in surprise and said to Bailler: ``That could be
the young fellow that ran me through the marathon.''
It was uneerily like him. That's a plot for a story now, isn't it?
n Coincidentally, Rembrandt also figures in a major exhibition being staged
until January 7 at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York. Entitled
``Rembrandt/Not Rembrandt'', it displays works by the artist with others that
were once attributed to him but have now been assigned to his pupils or
emulators. Several works that were once thought to be by Rembrandt have been
shown to be by other hands by the use of X-radiographs, cross-sections, and
autoradiographs. Museums and collectors must be shaking in their shoes.
</TEXT>
