<HEADLINE>Davies is in control</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN BALL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979287</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S Laura Davies set herself up to finish an already fine American season
in a blaze of glory when she teamed up with Mardi Lunn from Australia to win
their first-round match by 4 and 3 against Americans Michelle McGann and Donna
Andrews in the Diners Club matches yesterday in Palm Springs, California,
writes John Ball.
In today's semi-finals, the Commonwealth pair take on Julie Inkster and Betsy
King. Should they win again, the $250,000 prize for the winning side would seem
to be within their grasp.
Davies has won $2.25m since she joined the American tour in 1987 and she has
won twice over here already this year.
``Curiously, I do not like matchplay competitions very much,'' she said.
``Once, in Spain, I was 17 under par for four rounds and still got beaten. It's
frustrating although I always enjoy playing in the Californian desert.''
It certainly seems so, as she smoothly stroked in four birdie putts between
five feet and 25 feet for a score of 32 on the outward nine, at which point her
opponents were four down and with little to look forward to. Scores (USA unless
stated):
Regular tour - T Lehman and D Waldorf beat K Triplett and S Stricker, 1 hole; B
Tway and S Verplank beat D Duval and D Austin, 2 holes; K Perry and J Huston
beat T Kite and B Andrade, 2 and 1; J Gallagher and S Lowery beat P Azinger and
P Mickelson, 2 and 1.
Women's tour - K Robbin and T Green beat J Lidback and A Dibos, 3 and 2; N
Bowen and A Sorenstam (Sweden) beat B Daniel and M Mallon, at 19th; L Davies
(Britain) and M Lunn (Australia) beat M McGann and D Andrews, 4 and 3; J
Inkster and D Mochrie beat B King and V Skinner, 1 hole.
Seniors tour - R Floyd and D Eichelberger beat A Palmer and J Nicklaus, 3 and
2; D Stockton and H Irwin beat T Weiskopf and I Aoki, 2 and 1; J Colbert and B
Murphy beat J C Snead and G Gilbert, 2 and 1; G Archer and D Douglass beat C
Rodriguez and M Albus, 1 hole.
q A DISASTROUS 8 at the 470-metre, par-4 second at Vila Sol yesterday cost
Scotland's John Chillas a share of the lead at the halfway stage of the Algarve
Land of Golf Pro-Am finals in Portugal, writes David Bryden.
The Glenbervie player battled back to finish four behind leader German Garrido,
of Spain, who carded a two-over-par 74.
Antonio Sobrinho, of Portugal, and Spain's Manuel Vargas were one off the lead
on 75.
In the Stableford team event, Glenbervie were the leading Scots team with 76
points, six behind leaders Club de Campo, with Hilton Park on 73. The second
round of the 36-hole tournament is being played today at Palmares.
</TEXT>
