<HEADLINE>In discord and anger, the great adventure falters</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL FRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979288</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DERBY, December 9 - The Jacobites have turned around. After getting to within
130 miles of London, Prince Charles Edward Stewart has been forced by the fears
of his Highland chiefs to return to Scotland.
The clansmen left Derby in a hurry three days ago. Tonight they are already in
Manchester where they were met by a violent mob. They quelled it with a show of
force, and exacted a fine of #2500 on the town as punishment. The money was
raised in cash by the merchants, but a platoon sent to collect it was fired on
as it crossed Salford Bridge.
Later, a sniper narrowly missed Colonel John O'Sullivan, quartermaster of the
Jacobite army. It was all a stark contrast to the apparent welcome the
Highlanders received when they passed through on the way south only last week.
The sudden retreat took place after several days of intricate military
manoeuvres against a background of seething discord in the Jacobite camp as the
Scots' qualms about going on grew. The brilliant tactics of their general, Lord
George Murray, had created a gap and let them slip in between the two English
forces trying to intercept them, from the west under the Duke of Cumberland and
from the north under General George Wade.
After leaving Manchester, the Highlanders had reached Derby in a two-day march
on December 4. At that point they were about the same distance from London and
Cumberland, who had got as far as Stafford. They could move faster than the
royal army, and an open road seemed to lie before them.
Still, the Scots' nerve broke. The only intelligence they had was of another
force concentrating against them at Northampton, and of the militia preparing
to defend the immediate approaches to London.
They also knew that the mob in the capital was militantly anti-Jacobite. For an
army of 4500 clansmen to break through and seize it seemed a hopeless task. The
fact that next to no English recruits had joined them clinched the chieftains'
decision to go home.
None of this could easily have been suspected when the Highlanders reached here
five days ago. The Duke of Devonshire, Lord-lieutenant of the county, had fled
before them from his house at Chatsworth, and many leading citizens followed.
Derby was taken by a Jacobite vanguard of just 30 cavalrymen, without
resistance. On the contrary, the people rang bells and lit bonfires in an
effort, familiar from all the other captured towns, to humour the clansmen and
prevent looting.
A corps of 150 lifeguards led by Lord Elcho and several of the chieftains
arrived next. Then came the main body of soldiers under the Duke of Perth,
carrying their standards, accompanied by their pipers, and by a carriage full
of Jacobite ladies.
All looked happy and confident, but reactions among onlookers were mixed. One
thought them ``lousy, pitiful-looking fellows''. Another said their speaking
Gaelic made them sound like ``a herd of Hottentots, wild monkeys in a desert,
or vagrant gipsies''.
The remaining city fathers were forced to parade on the market square in their
robes of office while King James III and VIII was proclaimed. Only then did
Prince Charles appear, at the head of his rearguard. As usual he was on foot
and as usual he made an impression even on those hostile to him. Amid a lively
and curious crowd, he went to his lodgings at Exeter House.
During dinner he assured his officers that ``the people of England, as is their
duty, still nourish that allegiance for the race of their native princes which
they are bound to hold sacred, and if I do but persevere in my daring attempt,
Heaven itself will fight in my cause''.
The next morning, December 5, told a different story. The prince, about to
leave Exeter House with his bonnet on his head, was suddenly accosted by Lord
George Murray, who blurted out that it was high time to think about what they
were doing.
Charles asked him what he meant, if not to march on. Lord George replied that
most of the chiefs thought differently. He ushered the prince back into his
lodgings. In an oak-panelled drawing room on the first floor, an impromptu
council of war was called.
It produced a showdown. All the doubts the Scots had harboured ever since
leaving Edinburgh boiled up. Murray made plain they were against marching on,
for reasons even better than he had given at Carlisle, Preston and Manchester.
One was lack of English support. If a Jacobite party existed in England, they
ought to have heard something from it, at least in the way of money or
intelligence or advice. Nor was there word of the promised French invasion
across the Channel.
Murray asked Charles for documentary evidence that anyone in France or England
was going to help him. The prince could not provide it.
Murray turned up the pressure with information he had from a captured spy of
the British Government, that the clansmen were surrounded by 30,000 men in
three armies, each twice the size of their own. To reach London, they would
have to meet at least one of them, and were bound to suffer heavy casualties
even in defeating it. They would still have the militia to deal with, before
going on to subdue a panic-stricken city of a million people.
If the prince thought this could be done, he was obviously being swayed by
advisers who, as officers in the service of France, would be ransomed if taken
prisoner. The Scots, on the other hand, would be executed as traitors.
According to eye-witnesses, Lord George looked Charles in the eye and summed
up: ``The Scots army have done their part. We came into England at your
request, to join your English friends, and to give them courage by our
appearance to take arms and declare for you publicly as we have done, or to
join the French forces if they landed. But as none of these things has
happened, certainly 4500 Scots never thought of putting a King on the English
throne by themselves. So my opinion is we should go back and join our friends
in Scotland, and live and die with them.''
Murray then asked the other members of the council for their views. The three
most influential chiefs, Donald Cameron of Lochiel, Alexander MacDonald of
Keppoch, and Ewan MacPherson of Cluny, agreed with him, as did even the
prince's Irish adviser, Sir Thomas Sheridan. Only the Duke of Perth and Sir
William Gordon dissented.
Charles was stunned. Until this meeting, he had assumed the only question was
how to get to London as fast as possible. According to Lord Elcho, ``he fell
into a passion and gave most of the gentlemen that had spoken very abusive
language, and said that they had a mind to betray him''.
He did not at this stage give up but, with the help of Sir John MacDonald,
spent most of the day lobbying his officers in favour of continued advance. In
the evening, a fuller council of war was reconvened. On his side the prince had
Colonel O'Sullivan and his secretary, John Murray of Broughton, with the Dukes
of Atholl and Perth and Ranald MacDonald of Clanranald.
In a final effort to win over the rest, he revealed the latest news of the
landing at Montrose by Lord John Drummond, as commander in Scotland over the
forces of the King of France, with 800 men and several times that number
expected shortly. But this did not go down as he hoped.
The other Scots took it as a further and better reason to return to the defence
of their homeland. They assured Charles that the Highlanders could march 20
miles a day. At that pace they would outstrip Cumberland. Once past Preston
they might reckon on reaching the border with their army intact.
As the arguments went on, Murray called in the English spy whose information he
had earlier quoted. Under questioning this man, Dudley Bradstreet, stuck to his
story that 8000 or 9000 troops were lying in wait at Northampton. Prince
Charles, who was listening from a side room, burst in and shouted: ``That
fellow will do me more harm than the Elector's army.''
He turned to the council and said: ``You ruin, abandon and betray me if you
don't march on.'' Then he walked out and slammed the door. But the council's
mind was made up. Later the prince informed Murray: ``In future, I shall summon
no more councils, since I am accountable to nobody for my actions but to God
and my father and therefore I shall no longer either ask or accept advice.''
In the freezing dawn of ``Black Friday'', December 6, the Highlanders began
their retreat, though this was at first unknown to them. As the bagpipers
played reveille, they thought they were marching onwards. They knew that the
bridge over the River Trent at Swarkeston south of Derby had been secured by a
vanguard of 80 cavalry.
But then the clansmen were ordered back the way they had come. An officer,
James Maxwell of Kirkconnell, said: ``They began to suspect the truth, and
seemed extremely dejected. All was sullen and silent on that day.''
The prince left two hours later, mounted on a black horse. For the first time
he was riding rather than marching with his men. Lord George Murray followed in
command of the rearguard.
The change of strategy was so unexpected that the Duke of Cumberland did not at
once grasp what was happening. He believed a retreat impossible because it
could be cut off by Wade, and decided this was just another of the Jacobites'
manoeuvres. Since his soldiers were exhausted by their own, he let them rest.
Even two days later the duke expected the clansmen to turn south again. Still
trying to get between them and London, he set out with his cavalry and a
thousand infantry mounted on borrowed horses. These have now started the
pursuit, but they represent only a fraction of Cumberland's troops and it will
take the rest some time to catch up. The Highland army may therefore well
succeed in getting back to Scotland.
The news of its retreat has been received with immense relief in London. The
reports of panic heard by the Jacobites were true. The spy's story of a fresh
army at Northampton was a fiction. Only the militia, bolstered by a few
regiments of regulars, defended the capital.
Most of its citizens thought an attack imminent. Guards had been posted in the
streets to keep order. There was a run on the Bank of England, which it could
only slow by issuing its reserves in sixpences. Many people packed their
valuables and prepared to flee. The King was reported to have a yacht moored
ready for his escape at Tower Quay.
Once again rumours circulated that the Prime Minister, Henry Pelham, and his
brother, the Duke of Newcastle, were about to switch sides. Some Jacobites out
in the country did actually start to raise men, but the encouraging messages
they sent to Prince Charles at Derby only arrived after he was gone.
Now the most cheering thing to the Hanoverian authorities is the realisation
that he cannot after all have been acting in concert with the French. He would
have carried on if he had been certain an invasion across the Channel was
coming.
The threat of one remains, but the initiative has now clearly passed to the
British Government for the first time. The man about town and son of a former
Prime Minister, Horace Walpole, said: ``No one is afraid of a rebellion that
runs away.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
