<DOCNO>GH951209-000150</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000150</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The gleam machine</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN DAVIDSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979289</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOU are that Dancing Queen. You are the Lady in Red. Or at least you may quite
possibly believe you are following a few lethal cocktails at the office party.
For, dearie me, the season of frenetic festivity is upon us once more.
Sadly all attempts to outlaw these potentially disastrous ordeals have
floundered. Work in any environment where the staff exceed one in number, and
some bright spark will insist on arranging a Christmas night out. You know this
is dangerous. Propriety evaporates in direct proportion to sobriety. But a
refusal does offend; so there is no easy escape. You simply have to put on a
brave face (plenty of eyeliner, lashings of lipstick), thrust your best high
heel forward, and - like poor old Gloria Gaynor - insist: ``I will survive''.
Tomorrow, you can search for a miracle hangover cure. Next week, you can
address that trusted agony aunt with the worrying details of any amorous
indiscretion. But your first, pressing priority has to be choice of attire.
Full combat gear. Nothing less will do.
What's cool for Yule in party dressing? The new rule is simple. But sexy. You
may fall for the rock chick chic of a lean-fitting shirt with boot-leg flares.
Perhaps you'll be bewitched by the silver screen allure of a bias-cut frock.
But the real sensation of the season is satin. Taffeta is taboo. And sequins
are out. So untie those straight-laces (which help you maintain a certain
9-to-5 decorum), and slip into something slinky. The fool-proof formula for
night-time glamour this Christmas? Don't glisten - just gleam.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000151</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000151</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why many lights  make hands work</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra frontiers</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979290</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LET there be light. That's how creation starts in most of the genesis stories.
Yet whether light was created by a deity or by the natural wave motion of
photons, it is the fundamental basis of all life. Without it, plants would not
grow, supply us with oxygen and they would not feed the rest of the creatures
of this earth.
Light has fascinated man since he was able to think. Primitive humans made up
tales about the lights in the sky while they sat in the light of their fires.
We use light in fibre optics to communicate around the globe, and to peer
inside the human body. We need it to see where we're going.
It seems however, that animals, and primitive ones at that, have been using
light a whole lot longer than us. Scientists call it bioluminescence, the
natural organic light that living things are able to generate, whether they are
bacteria, bugs, or fish. Now scientists are using advanced techniques to adapt
that light for the greater good of mankind.
In particular, one Aberdeen academic, Professor Ken Killham, has devised a way
of using natural light as an organic toxic contaminant detector which seems to
work better than anything so far devised.
Killham's as happy as a NEWT, which is the acronym for his Novel Ecotoxicity
Water Test which has attracted #500,000 in funding from BBSRC in conjunction
with Yorkshire Water Services and Siemens Environmental Systems. It's based on
the use of the BBB's, which sound like an extension of the brigade, but are in
fact bioluminescent bacterial biosensors. They can be used to cast a light on
pollution and thus make it easy to identify.
As the picture shows, he's turned the old Chinese proverb around. It now reads:
``Many lights make hands work.'' The hand in question is covered with
light-emitting bacteria, shining powerfully enough to let the wearer read a map.
``Genetic modification involves cloning genes from naturally luminescent marine
bacteria,'' Killham says. ``We take the genes and clone then into organisms
which don't naturally shine. In the terrestrial world there are very few
luminescent organisms, because there is little advantage in creatures emitting
light, except for fireflies and glow worms. But in the sea there are many
species of animals, right down to bacteria which produce their own light and
glow in the dark of the deep.
``The amount of light they emit tells us how happy they are. They are
definitely not happy when the water is polluted and shine much less. If light
output declines, it allow us to predict possible contamination.
``At the moment it's very difficult, costly and time-consuming to test whether
a water supply is toxic. But in mere seconds, our system will tell you how
toxic the water is. It's a simple matter of measuring the light. If it's
dimmer, then there's pollution. It tells us, literally, if the shit has hit the
fan.''
Frontiers likes a scientist who tells it the way we can understand.
``Not only that, but we can fix the lux genes to other genes which are involved
in the breakdown of specific toxins. That allows us to make our little bacteria
target specific. If we clone the light genes with the toxin finders, the
bacteria can be programmed to find heavy metals like lead, or mercury and other
poisons in water. That lets us produce a biosensor that tells you whether
there's lead in the water for instance, or even in soil. The bacteria attach
themselves to the metal molecules and then they light up. All we have to do is
measure the light. Basically, in a general situation, we look for less light
for overall contamination, or brighter light from some bacteria which pinpoints
a poison.
``It's very fast indeed. We can take a sample of water, mix in some of our
bacteria and know immediately how toxic it is.''
Killham says the genetic modifications which clone the marine bioluminescent
gene on to a terrestrial bacteria were carried out at Aberdeen University's
Molecular and Cell Biology department under colleague Dr Anne Glover who's the
senior lecturer in the department.
``The gene was put into a whole host of different bacteria,'' he says.
While Killham says that the biosensor bacteria can tell when the solids have
hit the punkah, sewage detection is a little more tricky, because while much of
sewage is pollution, it is not toxic. He does assure us, however that the
biosensor can be designed to pick up the traces of that too. Good news for
beaches. Good news for us all.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NO HEADLINE PRESENT</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KENNY LOGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979291</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF District rugby is mostly about exposing the country's top players to a
higher grade of competition, then there has to be something wrong with a system
which allows the likes of Gary Armstrong and Derrick Patterson to languish on
the bench.
When the South play North and Midlands tomorrow at Kelso, Gary will be a
replacement, with Bryan Redpath in the side, and when the Exiles come to
Glasgow ``Deek'' Patterson is benching, and Andy Nicol is on from the start - a
reversal of their roles when the Exiles played Edinburgh on Wednesday night.
It may well be that the South plan to rotate their two scrum-halves as well,
but with the country's four top scrum-halves battling for places in two sides
and, obviously, with a couple of them destined to act as spectators for 50% of
the championship, I just cannot see how that fits into the plan to have the top
players in regular, meaningful action throughout December.
That scrum-half situation is the most glaring example of what I'm talking
about, but there are other instances all over the shop. For instance, if they
were all fit, then the South would presumably want to give Tony Stanger, Graham
Shiel, Scott Nichol, and Del Bain a run at centre. Obviously, they can't all
play.
I'm a fan of district rugby, and I believe that the championship is important
in its own right but, on the wider front, if the master plan is to get all the
top players - internationalists and cap hopefuls - into meaningful competition
in the run-up to the Five Nations tournament, then the current system is not
working.
I haven't got a clue as to the answer, but there may be some pointers to be had
from the system that New Zealand are adopting for the new International
Provincial Competition.
The NZRFU want to make sure that all of their top players are involved, and
basically what will happen is that the union will have a list of contracted
players who will be allocated to the hybrid teams which will take part in the
tournament.
Obviously, the district unions over here would not take kindly to that sort of
interference from higher authority but, maybe, it is something that could be
looked at.
Another aspect of the district set-up which needs examination is just who is
eligible to play for whom. The situation, as it stands, is just chaotic. For
instance, Stirling County is part of the Glasgow set-up, but we are also
eligible to play for North and Midlands. That's been great for North and
Midlands, but not so good for Glasgow.
I've chosen to show a bit a loyalty and stick with Glasgow, but I'll not be
playing tomorrow against the Exiles because I've got a knee problem which is
taking longer than I had expected to clear up. I received a knock when we
played against the Barbarians and since then, the knee swells up whenever I
train or play.
I am receiving treatment from the SRU doc, Jimmy Graham, and, fingers crossed,
I should be OK for our crunch premiership game against Heriot's next weekend.
Last weekend, against Boroughmuir, I was delighted to get a couple of tries and
go some of the way towards answering the critics in the media and elsewhere. I
also enjoyed playing at fullback. Craig Sangster has been playing really well
at full-back for us, and it was my first time there since the Scotland tour to
Argentina last year.
Basically, though, it was just good to get a decent performance under my belt
and, hopefully, once Jimmy has worked his medical magic, that can be maintained
next week against Heriot's and beyond.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
