<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Away with panic and  let us to  the lists SAUSAGEMEAT AND CHESTNUT STUFFING</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LADY CLAIRE MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979292</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANYONE who knows me well will admire the restraint with which I have,
uncharacteristically, shown in only now, at this comparatively late stage,
discussing Christmas. I love Christmas. In fact, it is my best time of the
whole year. I begin to anticipate Christmas about June, and I love the shopping.
I realise by now, to those who don't know me, I must sound like a raving
lunatic. We are beset with statistics of the great numbers for whom the very
mention of the word Christmas induces stress. That, combined with the increase
each year in the commercialisation, tends to produce a collective moan at the
thought of the festive season.
This is tragic, and so much can be done to decrease any rising panic felt by
those who don't anticipate Christmas with the same glee I do. I am convinced
the major reason for such anxiety is the thought of planning and cooking meal
after meal over a period of time when the house will be full of family and
friends, and when entertaining is expected too.
You tend to read so much that is unhelpful about preparing food over Christmas;
in truth, there is a vast amount to be prepared in advance, at your comparative
leisure, and the results frozen. There are two prerequisites to this: that your
freezer has a good clear-out - a task I loathe - to make space for all you are
about to cook and freeze, and that you make a list of what you need to take out
of your freezer, and when, to allow sufficient thawing time.
The anguish I have felt on the odd occasion when I have forgotten to take out
of the deep freeze a vital dish, or the stuffing for the turkey, can only be
imagined. The answer is to live by the lists. I can't rely on my memory at the
best of times, but over the Christmas and New Year season there are just so
many things to remember it is endlessly reassuring to have lists to refer to,
and they should be pinned or stuck in a prominent place.
Christmas lunch or dinner, if you have roast turkey as your traditional main
course, is the easiest and simplest meal of the year - providing you have made
and frozen the stuffings and the bread sauce. None of these deteriorate with
freezing, and I thaw the stuffings in good time to let me stuff the turkey,
prepare it for the roasting, and wrap it in its foil all on Christmas Eve.
I plan to discuss this with you on the Saturday before Christmas Day. The point
of a stuffing is two-fold; to provide a substance which complements the taste
of the bird, and to provide flavours which infuse the meat. We always have two
stuffings - one recipe I give you today - and the other is made of white
breadcrumbs with half the weight in suet, well flavoured with finely chopped
and sauteed onions and plenty of grated lemon rind and chopped parsley - I use
flat leaved parsley for maximum flavour. When you pack your stuffings into poly
bags it is vital to clearly label the bag with the contents - you always think,
when you put something into the freezer, that you will never forget what it is,
but it is frightening how quickly an object assumes total anonymity once frozen.
However fashionable cranberries are, roast turkey would not be complete without
accompanying bread sauce. We are bread sauce fanatics in our family; indeed, I
have a cousin who feels so passionately for this humble fare that,
post-Christmas, he takes bread sauce sandwiches on long walks! I prefer my
bread sauce hot, and, if not with roast turkey, with grilled sausages. But it
must be well made.
For this you need day-old baked bread, as opposed to steam sliced bread which
will result in glue-like sauce. You need, for my taste, 1!s-2 pints of full-fat
milk and one skinned onion, stuck with several cloves. Salt and add a good
grinding of black pepper. The contents of the saucepan should be brought to the
point where the milk forms a skin and then the pan taken off the heat and left
to cool, when the onion and cloves will infuse the milk with their flavours.
I then stir in the breadcrumbs, about 6-8oz and before freezing the sauce I
fish out and throw away the onion. If you cut about 3oz of butter into small
bits - easy when the butter is hard - and stir this into the bread sauce you
will find as it reheats on Christmas Day the butter improves the texture and
taste. Allow 36 hours to thaw the sauce. It can be frozen in a well-buttered
ovenproof dish, needing only to be put into the oven, once thawed.
This amount is suitable for a 12-15lb turkey:
3lbs best quality sausages with as high a percentage of pork meat as you can
find
2 onions, skinned and very finely chopped
2 tablespoons oil - I use olive oil, but sunflower would do instead
A couple of pinches of thyme and plenty of freshly ground pepper
1lb chestnuts - the vacuum packed ones are almost indistinguishable from fresh,
and much less bother. Avoid dried chestnuts which, even after days of
reconstituting, still manage to have the taste and texture of cardboard, but
tinned chestnuts would do.
Slit each sausage with a sharp knife and peel off the skins. Put the sausages
into a large mixing bowl. Saute  the onions in the oil till they are soft -
about four mins - then cool completely. Mix all the ingredients together with
your hand. Mix thoroughly, then pack into a polythene bag. Label and freeze.
Allow 36 hours to thaw. Make sure it is completely thawed before stuffing the
turkey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
