<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000155</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000155</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>IT STARTED WITH A PACK OF SEEDS, CONFESSES A GARDEN JUNKIE</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE TRODDEN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979294</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE whole process began innocently enough. A few seeds pressed into a pudgy
childish hand by an old woman. No cow was handed over and no beanstalk
appeared. The seeds produced a blaze of wall flowers that licked their way up
the front of our house.
Friends and family admired the display. My interest spread to a small
strawberry patch and then to vegetables and flowers, and I spent long summer
evenings pottering beside my mother in our over-large garden.
Puberty and a friend's cruel remarks about the potato heads on Gardener's
Question Time conspired to draw a veil over my interest. I couldn't risk guilt
by association. Worse even than being accused of nurturing a prurient interest
in root vegetables, was the accusation of being boring.
The truth is it's never been boring. Not just the wonder of nature stuff;
sowing the seeds, growing the seeds, and what not. Quite miraculous, of course,
but the boredom factor has been held at bay by the fact my passion had to be
secret.
It caused much lewd debate at one party when we - a flushed young disco queen
and the teenage party host - arrived back in from an hour-long bout in the
garden. Their guesses were wrong, of course. Our shared passion, was not for
each other. It was for the garden. And what a garden that was. Night-scented
stock wafted out its sweet stench and white lilies gleamed in the soft glow
from the path lighting. There was an arch leading to a small secret garden at
the back with its own little arbour. No wonder we were dewy-eyed after all that.
We swore each other to secrecy. The agony in the garden would have been nothing
to our punishment at the hands of our cool friends. Fortunately, my sequinned
boob tube was disguise enough for both of us. No-one guessed that behind that
spangly exterior lurked desires only usually found among the green welly
brigade.
The condition has not improved with the years. In fact it's grown worse as my
secret has been forced under ground. There's no street cred in gardening but
the sad fact is I am a garden junky. It's a habit I have, I can't help it. I
try to stay away from them - I don't even have one of my own - but I can't.
I love them, big, small, wild or carefully planned. I consume them all. It's
shameless voyeurism but I can't help it. I stalk the streets of Edinburgh's New
Town peering through railings at the amazing creations some basement dwellers
have lovingly raised. Greenery, flowering shrubs, climbers - even some scents
force their way upwards - uniting in a gloriously subversive force against the
soulless symmetry of the unyielding stone.
I love all the little features people employ in their gardens. Babbling Gre
Foliage by the line obscured some of them during summer but during spring and
autumn there is a clear view. It's not so much that the gardens themselves are
spectacular - though there is one lightly terraced with never-ending flower and
vegetable beds, sun lounging area and an archway that stands out. It's more
that these people seem to do so much in them. Some are little more than drying
areas, others are strewn with toys and paddling pools in season. There are
barbecues, pot-filled patios, green houses, pigeon lofts - oh yes, and lots of
plants. All gardening life is there and all in such a short stretch. At times
I'm tempted to take a detour and drive by to see if their fronts match up.
Most of all, I admire those who garden in defiance of nature. I've seen brave
souls, notably in St Monans and Stenhousemuir, battle the elements and win with
their tropical shows of towering yukkas and palms. These seem to stand tall
right through the winter, laughing in the face of frost and snow.
I, too, laugh in the face of winter. It doesn't stop me in my tracks. It simply
strips away all that summer finery. But that allows a clear view of the real
structure and form of the garden. Nature in the raw, if you like. Then I can
look on and plan and savour what's to come in the spring. All this and I don't
even get my hands dirty.
Now that I've come clean it doesn't seem such a bad habit after all. Maybe
confession is good for the soil . . . and perhaps I'll never grow out of it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000156</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000156</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>TOM: The Unknown  Tennessee Williams Lyle Leverich Hodder &amp; Stoughton, #25 Untrue statesman</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN BOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979295</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GUILT-edged insecurity: such is the human condition conveyed in the work that
is the world of Tennessee Williams (1911-83).
Think of the tormented body of Laura in The Glass Menagerie (1944), the
tortured mind of Stanley Kowalski in A Streetcar Named Desire (1947), the
trials of Brick and Maggie in Cat on a Hot Tin Roof (1955). Think of Tennessee
Williams and you think of psychic wounds inflicted on souls forever lost.
When Williams died, his brother Dakin described him as the greatest
poet-dramatist since Shakespeare. Dakin was too close to Tennessee to realise
how completely his talent had been confined by a father called Coffin -
Cornelius Coffin Williams - and few would agree with Dakin's family affair of
an assessment, given the competing gifts of such histrionic Americans as Arthur
Miller who praised the ``poetic lift The Glass Menagerie.
Lyle Leverich does not go all the way with Dakin, but goes along with Miller in
honouring Williams as an author who, with The Glass Menagerie, emerged as ``a
poet-playwright and a unique new force in theatre throughout the world''.
Williams was uniquely obsessed by himself.
Williams wrote about the autobiographical basis of his work in Memoirs (1975)
but Leverich, who got to know the dramatist when he staged a production of The
Glass Menagerie in 1976, told Williams he deserved a better book. Williams told
Leverich: ``Baby, you write it!'' And he did, in astonishing detail. This
volume takes the trauma of Williams's life up to the triumphant drama of The
Glass Menagerie. Another volume will follow. The length of Leverich's biography
establishes it as a labour of love: a tribute to a man the biographer regards
as a disturbing genius and a disturbed man dominated by his sexually frustrated
father and emotionally smothering mother and schizophrenic sister.
The theme of the biography is succinctly stated by Leverich: ``Throughout his
life, Tennessee Williams had two overriding devotions: his career as a writer
and his sister, Rose.'' His career as a writer was mainly influenced by his
addiction to the dark art of Hart Crane whose collected poems he carried with
him everywhere. He identified with Crane obsessively. Crane was raised by a
bullying father determined to drive the poetry out of him. So was Williams.
Crane was a self-destructive drinker and homosexual. So was Williams.
When Williams turned 21 in 1932, Crane took his own life by boarding the
steamer Orizaha and jumping into the water some 300 miles north of Havana. It
was Williams's wish that when he died his body be sewn up in a simple white
sack and borne out to sea to rest as close as possible to Crane's remains.
Instead, Williams's body was buried in St Louis - a city he detested since it
was from there that his father attempted to form his character. The decision to
bury Williams was taken by his brother Dakin and by the late Maria St Just, a
trustee of the Williams estate and, apparently, a woman who attempted to block
Leverich's biography.
Williams claimed his classmates at Iowa gave him the nickname of Tennessee. Not
so. He chose the name because he needed to renew himself for a play contest
created by the Group Theatre of New York. The age limit for entrants was 25
and, at the time, Tom was too old to enter so he assumed the name Tennessee -
after his father's Tennessean forebears - and pretended he was born in 1914
rather than 1911.
It was a fabrication he fretted over: ``Long after, Tennessee worried that,
having faked his birth date, his deception would be made public; he even
instructed his agent to warn reporters not to bring up his age at any interview
he might be willing to give.'' As a result, even the Library of Congress gave
his birth date as 1914 until the truth was told. Williams could live with his
lies for long enough to tell the truth in his plays. As Marlon Brando put it:
``He told the truth as best he perceived it.'' He played with perception.
As Leverich puts it: ``Tennessee was a fabricator - that was his profession -
and often, too, that was what he was personally.''
Leverich is clearly the ultimate authority on Williams. He intelligently
analyses his hero's motivation and the many men and women in his occasionally
heroic life. This book tells you everything you need to know about Tom aka
Tennessee until the next volume appears, and all the fans will look forward to
that.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000157</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000157</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>McManus a treble Scot</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979296</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORLD No.6 Alan McManus completed a 5-3 victory over David Roe to reach the
semi-finals of the German Open in Frankfurt yesterday - the third Scottish
player to reach that stage.
McManus, who also made the last four of the Grand Prix in October, now tackles
fellow Scot John Higgins for the fourth time this season. ``I will have to play
a lot better than I did today if I am to have a chance of getting through,''
said McManus, who has already lost to Higgins three times this season.
``You are better off playing someone you know. I didn't know what to expect
against Paul Hunter in the UK championship, and it was a bad day for me,''
added McManus, beaten in the first round of that event.
``I do know John's game. He is a tough competitor, and I always enjoy playing
him. I didn't make a lot of mistakes, though Dave did, and got away with them.''
Roe, from Derby, said: ``I was careless and I don't think I got the run of the
balls.'' Then he joked: ``All these Scots in the semi-finals is doing my head
in. Can't we English play the game any more? I'll have to go and live in
Glasgow.''
McManus surged into a two-frame lead against Roe, helped by a break of 69 in
the first. But the Englishman, despite scoring only four points in the second
frame, hit back with a break of 51 to win the third, and another run of 55,
without McManus scoring a point, to level at 2-2.
The roles were reversed in the fifth frame, with the Scot hitting a break of 60
without Rose scoring. He took the next by 63-25, lost the seventh by 81-42, and
then closed out the match by taking the eighth frame 69-16.
World champion Stephen Hendry confirmed his place yesterday, making up the
three Tartan players. Until the Grand Prix in October, this had never happened
before, but now the Scots, for the second time launch a three pronged attack on
the two final places.
Ken Doherty concludes the semi-final line-up having beaten Mark Bennett 5.2.
The bad news for Doherty is that Hendry is next.
``After I had won the third frame Mark, who had played well up until then, got
a bit too tense,'' said Doherty. ``I was pleased with the way I played. My game
seems to be coming together again.''
</TEXT>
