<TEXT>
n.WE should all take our hats off to Panama. Without it, we might not even be
here, according to a paleontologist who believes he can show that without the
little Central American connection, the ape-like ancestors of humans would
never have come down from the trees.
The Isthmus of Panama, the narrow strip between North and South America, was
formed three million years ago by a chance movement of the tectonic plates in
the earth's crust, forming a solid barrier between the Atlantic and Pacific
oceans.
The barrier changed ocean flow patterns, preventing warm water from reaching
the Arctic Ocean, which started a cascade of events that brought about the Ice
Age.
The chain of climatic and ecological changes ultimately resulted in the origin
of human beings thousands of miles away, in tropical Africa, according to
Steven Stanley, a professor of paleobiology in the Johns Hopkins Department of
Earth and Planetary Sciences. More arid and slightly cooler conditions caused a
dramatic shrinking of the rain forests.
Humankind's tree-dwelling ancestors, suddenly faced with a dwindling forest
habitat produced by climate change, were forced to begin living on the ground,
setting the stage for the evolution of larger-brained, upright-walking
descendants, Stanley said. His book outlining the theory, Children of the Ice
Age, will be published in April.
The Panama proposal is based on the motion of ocean currents which regulate the
earth's temperature. Previous theories have failed to explain why the Arctic
suddenly grew colder slightly more than three million years ago. Stanley argues
that the glaciers were the result of the Arctic freeze.
Before the Isthmus of Panama, warm water from the Atlantic Ocean mixed freely
with the Arctic Ocean. The barrier cut off that source of warm water and
touched off the Ice Age, sending frigid air and water southward, and bringing
about a dramatic change in global climate.
Scientists have also documented changes in deep sea flora and animal life in
the same time period near the mouth of the Labrador Sea, where fossil records
indicate that the Arctic Ocean grew much colder at that time.
``Previously, it was quite warm in the Arctic,'' Stanley says. Instead of
frozen tundra, the region was covered with something resembling evergreen
forests. ``We didn't have cold winters before the Ice Age. They were much
warmer before the Ice Age, and summers were not as warm as they are today.''
Sounds as if the pre-human days were very much like our Scottish climate.
n.THE deep mud around Rockall off our West Coast has been found to be as rich
in lifeform diversity as the equatorial rainforests. Most of the diversity,
however, is in species of nematode worms, and the Rockall Trough is one of the
deep oceanic trenches where they like to gather in greatest numbers.
n.SURGEONS may soon be using military style night sights in heart operations.
The thermal imaging technology has found yet another peacetime use after
surgeons discovered that blood flowing in arteries, veins and the heart has a
higher temperature than the surrounding tissue.
Now a nightsight camera has been developed specifically for cardiac surgery,
allowing doctors to see instantly if grafted tissue is working properly, or
whether there are any dangerous leaks. It also lets them see how well supplied
the heart muscle is.
n.SPIKING Mortality is a new disease which is wiping out millions of turkeys in
the USA. The disease was only discovered four years ago, but it has spread
across the continent. It kills very quickly, and could eventually affect turkey
supplies the world over. Once the disease strikes, a grower can lose 60 of his
flock in a couple of weeks. So far no-one knows the cause of the disease.
</TEXT>
