ANNABEL GOLDIE - Deputy chairman of the Scottish Conservative and Unionist
Party talks to Ann Donald about her late night reading
n ONE of the most fascinating books I've been reading is by a historian of
great repute called Martin Gilbert about Winston Churchill called In Search of
Churchill. This is not so much a biography than an account of how Gilbert got
on to the track of information about Churchill detailing how he went from one
clue to another.
He constructs it much like a detective story and in so doing the book emerges
as a very honest account of a great man because rather than depend on the
subjectivity of people's opinions it's built on fact and circumstance. A most
illuminating depiction of Churchill.
I don't feel obliged to read all political biographies pertinent to my
position, I read them out of genuine interest. Alan Clarke's Diaries were
absolutely supreme. I'd love to meet him. In fact I don't think that there's a
woman in Christendom who wouldn't like to meet him. I found that I couldn't
take offence at him because there was a refreshing honesty and candour about
his own shortcomings. Contrary to what many people think, I think that takes
humility to admit. Undoubtedly the man has charisma and charm.
Another book that I dip into on a regular basis is Palgrave's Treasury. It's
really a compendium of our most noted poet's work from the Romantics onwards.
My particular favourite is Betjamin. In a funny way he's like a Burns for the
Home Counties because he has the couthy touch and engaging way of using simple
language in a crystal cut fashion that allows him to cut a scene and create a
picture. Like Burns he sees through the pomp and ceremony and manages to prick
the minds of the fashionable London Wimbledon set.
</TEXT>
