<HEADLINE>Ol' bossy cowboy boots is back The Herald's regular team of reviewers  listens to the best sounds around</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER, ROB ADAMS, MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>45</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979299</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Ghost Of Tom Joad, Bruce Springsteen (Columbia)
q A dirty-realist dispatch from the scabbier parts of blue-collar America's
underbelly. Ol' Bruce documents desperate lovers, accidental muggers, and
lust-driven thieves; fearful illegal immigrants, and cons who question the
worth of trying to go straight. It's a sombre, stripped-down album, reflecting
Brucie's unease at the many social malaises currently rife in the rootless
Yewess of Ay.
Of course, such problems have a history stretching back to the Depression, as
documented by John Steinbeck in The Grapes of Wrath. Indeed, the novel is
credited on the album sleeve as one of Bruce's inspirational sources - having
given the LP its title - along with a couple of newspaper articles on the
Mexican cross-border trade in human misery.
All this has led to a morally-complex, panoramic album which should see off
Bruce's more mindless Born In The USA-era following. Yet I'm not sure that even
the most dedicated Springsteenophile will be voluntarily immersing himself in
its bleakness too often. Ever considered penning film-scripts, though, Your
Bruceness? The Ghost of Tom Joad has got enough sparse, gripping storylines to
power several Hollywood films.
Anthology, the Beatles (Apple)
q Did you know that ``Anthology'' and ``the Beatles'' is almost an anagram of
``Sell tat-age booty, hen''? Oh, you did? No need for me to mention it then.
Out On The Floor, various (Goldmine)
q Waft me to northern soul heaven! Twenty-five total belters, kicking off with
Chuck Wood's steaming Seven Days Is Too Long. Believe me, seven minutes without
this album rattling your hi-fi will be too long, too. For there can surely be
no more corruscating song of contempt-fuelled revenge than I Dig Your Act by
the O'Jays. There is no finer place to be than Out On The Floor with Dobie
Gray; no more stratospheric a soarer than the Fascinations' Girls Are Out to
Get You. As the Four Larks say: groovin' at the go-go is the only way to be.
DAVID BELCHER
The Rose of the San Joaquin, Tom Russell (Round Tower)
q Too country for the folk market, too folky for the country market, it's been
a heck of a life being Tom Russell these past 20 years. But forget the pigeon
holes and listen to the voice.
Given a regular service to hell and back, this man would have a season ticket.
Not that Russell invites pity. Like their predecessors, this latest batch of
songs are essentially stories. They could happen to anyone. They rock, they
smoulder, they don't waste a word, and if there's any justice, they'll exocet
Russell's well-kept secret status.
ROB ADAMS
Classical Music: A New Way of Listening, by Alexander Waugh (De Agostini
Editions)
q THIS book claims to offer to the readers, especially those who ``want to get
more out of classical music'', an explanation of how to ``navigate your way
through absolutely any piece of music''. However, much of the book, despite its
title, describes an old, traditional way of listening to music - drawings and
definitions of instruments, their sounds (often a bit woolly, here), technical
elements of music (melody, harmony, counterpoint), historical periods, composer
profiles, technical glossary, etc.
Where it is on less sure ground is when it attempts to define and categorise
mood in music (which, of course, is the wrong way round - you cannot prescribe
the emotional reactions of any two different listeners, or their perceptions of
mood in music). The ``new'' element involves ``timelines'' - illustrations
described as a ``computerised image of the music, working on the same
principles as a cardiograph''.
It seems a bit naive to assume that what is essentially an oscillograph
representation of dynamic and textural highs and lows in a piece of music is
actually going to open a door for anybody who is trying to find a way into
classical music. Anyway, it's #14.99. Suck it and see. And let me know if it
works for you. Comes with CD.
MICHAEL TUMELTY
n The Herald has six copies to give away to the first half-dozen readers to
answer this question: How many symphonies did Beet-hoven write? Answer to
Michael Tumelty, The Herald, 195 Albion St, Glasgow G1 1QP.
</TEXT>
