<TEXT>
SCOTTISH men's champions City of Glasgow Ragazzi showed how much they had
learned about European competition in their opening match in the European
Confederation Cup tournament at the Kelvin Hall last night.
Up against Balkancar Tran Sofia, who had four players in their ranks who had
helped Bulgaria finish fourth in the recent World League, the Scottish side
were expected to have little chance.
However, they kept the Bulgarians on court for more than an hour-and-a-half
before giving way - 15-9, 15-10, 13-15, 15-2 - after one of the most creditable
performances by a Scottish club side in Europe.
In the opening match of the tournament, Paris University Club defeated
Croatians Osijec, 15-11, 15-1, 15-7, with legendary setter Alain Fabiani in
exquisite form.
Sports awards
GAVIN Hastings is Glasgow City Council's sports personality of the year,
following Gary Jacobs, Stephen Hendry, Pat Clinton, and Liz McColgan.
But Hastings was unable to accept the annual award at a civic dinner last
night, and the trophy was accepted on his behalf by Scotland winger Kenny Logan.
Oarsman Peter Haining, the three-times world lightweight sculls champion,
received a special trophy. Other awards:
Service to Local Sport: Frank Hughes (football). Lord Provost's award: Fiona
McLean (netball). Team of the Year: Glasgow Western Klick Photopoint. Disabled
Sports award: Ross Low (athletics). Service to Sport: Thomas Dowens
(Volleyball).
Golf
AMERICAN Clay Devers fired his second consecutive bogey-free 66 to take a
three-stroke lead after the second round of the Vietnam Open yesterday.
The event, being played over the Golf Vietnam, Thu Duc layout, is the first pro
tournament the country has hosted.
Devers, whose 12-under-par total is the lowest halfway aggregate on the Omega
Tour this year, heads the leaderboard from Thailand's Boonchu Ruangkit, who
also posted a 66.
Hong Kong's Dominique Boulet followed his first-round 68 with an eagle, four
birdies, and three bogeys for a three-under 69.
He lies third at seven under, one shot ahead of overnight leader Jeff Senior,
of Australia, who carded an even-par 72. Leading scores:
132 - C Devers (USA) 66, 66. 135 - B Ruangkit (Thailand) 69, 66. 137 - D Boulet
(Hong Kong) 68, 69. 138 - J Senior (Australia) 66, 72.
Curling
Summit Centre: RCCC Henderson Bishop Trophy. Summit final - K Letton 10, A
Mackellar 4.
Speedway
GLASGOW Tigers face one of their toughest races in years if they are to survive
in the Premier League next season.
On Monday, the British Speedway Promoters' Association will convene an
emergency meeting to determine the future of the team after the departure of
owner and promoter Douglas Hopes.
Hopes had his track licence withdrawn by the Control Board earlier this week
following alleged irregularities over payment to riders.
The Shawfield club and its riders may now be put on sale by the BSPA, and any
would-be successor is required to post a bond of #40,000 to take over the reins.
AMERICAN Jack Milne, the sport's second world champion, has died at his home in
California at the age of 88. Milne took the title at Wembley in 1937 and rode
regularly in Britain before the Second World War.
Athletics
RICHARD Singer, Mackie Academy's triple medal-winner in the national track and
field championships, is out of the Scottish team for the TSB Home Countries
Schools indoor multi events match at the Kelvin Hall today.
His absence decreases the Scots chances of deposing holders, England. However
Jackie Tindall, UK under-17 heptathlon champion, is favourite for the women's
under-18 crown.
Badminton
CRAIG Robertson (Fauldhouse) defeated English No.4 Tony Bush yesterdy in the
second round of the Irish Open in Belfast. Robertson lost the opening game
13-18 but took the remaining two 18-17, 15-6.
Gillian Martin (Renfrew) beat Yvonne Naef (Switzerland) 11-1, 11-0.
Squash
RODNEY Eyles, the top seed, reached the quarter-final stage of the Mahindra
Challenge in India after a 15-11, 15-12, 15-12 second-round victory over
Britain's Mark Chaloner. Eyles now meets another Briton, Mark Cairns, who
defeated Egypt's Amir Wagih 15-6, 15-9, 12-15, 9-15, 15-12.
Basketball
EDINBURGH Burger Kings will have a new coach for tonight's inter-city clash
with City of Aberdeen Leopards at Meadowbank. Former Scottish junior cap Paul
Dalrymple steps in for Australian Greg Gurr who has flown home to Perth for
Christmas. Dalrymple also will coach the capital side in the annual Boroughmuir
Tournament at Meadowbank on December 16 and 17.
Beefeater Kool Kats, who are lying second to Polonia Phoenix but have lost four
matches, go for a double over Edinburgh rivals Team Caledonia in the Scottish
Women's League match before the Kings' game tonight.
Meanwhile Edzell Enforcers and Paisley can use home court advantage to
strengthen their chances of a men's Top Five place at the expense of
Boroughmuir and Bruins respectively.
Boxing
GERMANY'S Axel Schulz goes into today's fight against Frans Botha in Stuttgart
quietly confident of clinching the vacant IBF world heavyweight title on a
points decision.
The South African, meanwhile, predicts an early knock-out will give him the
crown abdicated by George Foreman, who won the title in a controversial points
decision over Schulz in April and then retired rather than defend it.
