<HEADLINE>On the coast of broken dreams</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LESLEY DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979302</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND has more than enough scenery, huffed and puffed a politician (Labour
it must be said) of my acquaintance in the early seventies. He was justifying
the quixotic determination of politicians and planners to bring heavy industry
to the Firth of Clyde at its prettiest reaches between the Hunterston peninsula
and Inverkip.
Till that time, the nuclear power plant of Hunterston A (opened in 1964) was
the only industrial blemish on a stretch of coastline of heart-melting beauty,
with the rolling Ayrshire hinterland and its little seaside communities to the
east and the island-dotted firth to the west, guarded by the miniature
Himalayas of Arran. And as for Hunterston A, weren't school children, after
all, encouraged to be proud of the pioneering nuclear establishment round which
cows grazed? At least it was compact and chimneyless and didn't disseminate
industrial dust and dirt - or so the argument went in those more innocent days.
Then came the proposal of the American oil company Chevron to build an oil
refinery at Portencross on the Hunterston peninsula to the south of the nuclear
station. After a public inquiry that absurd plan was quashed. However, the lure
of deep water facilities and the equally absurd idea of relocating the whole
Lanarkshire steel industry on a green, seaside site combined in an unstoppable
momentum. Fairlie, picturesque haven of yachts and the Arran ferry in bad
weather, was disfigured by the dust and visual aggression of a giant ore
terminal. Two direct iron reduction plants were plonked on adjacent reclaimed
ground at the beauty spot of Black Rock Beach.
The Scottish people - at least as represented by the media, politicians, trades
unionsand civil servants - seemed almost unanimous in their conviction this was
a splendid thing for jobs and the economy. It's not the first time Scots have
manifested a tendency for communal hysteria about something inherently daft.
Shades of the Darien Scheme.
In the event, the direct iron ore reduction plants never reduced a thing -
except the appeal of the landscape. The complex, with its dark towers and
sloping gantries, is grotesquely at odds with its setting overlooking the
Cumbrae islands. The only consolation for the residents of Fairlie and Largs is
that its pollution has remained merely aesthetic.
British Steel's official line is that the rise in fuel prices made the use of
the reduction plants uneconomic. And certainly by the time they were completed
the world steel market was contracting. But didn't this in itself show a lack
of foresight on the part of the planners of the then nationalised industry?
Some people still believed, too, that putting this kind of heavy industry so
close to nuclear facilities was, to say the least, injudicious. Whatever the
reasons, the waste of public money - and who will admit accountability at this
late date? - is staggering.
Today, of course, there is no Scottish steel industry for the mills or the
eyesore ore terminal to serve. The jetty with its massive cranes stretching out
into the channel to intimidate Millport is now owned by the privatised
Clydeport. Access is barred to the casually passing citizen. ``This is a hard
hat site,'' says a sign beside the manned security barrier. Perhaps this
justifies the exclusion of the public, except for organised groups, on safety
grounds - but it marks a diminishing of the freedom enjoyed by previous
generations to wander freely to the water's edge. It's fine to have an oyster
farm and bird reserve on the site, though oystercatchers, if not oysters,   may
have the whole firth for their playground.
What is being imported at the Hunterston terminal now is cheap foreign coal
from South America, Australia, Russia, and Poland. This to the county of
Ayrshire that traditionally was a coal exporter. The imported coal is not even
mainly for Scottish consumption but is merely being rerouted to Northern
Ireland's Kilroot power station. Hunterston's deep water facilities allow
``Cape-sized'' vessels of up to 150,000 tons to berth. Sometimes the coal is
transferred directly to smaller vessels. But much is temporarily dumped in the
enormous coalyard between the steel plants and the Clydeport jetty, there to be
screened, washed, and sized. In spite of automatic sprinkler systems and a
lorry washing plant, the coalyard is a visual scar.
Now irony rather than iron may be Scotland's new heavy industry. For
Hunterston's direct reduction plants are being dismantled - like the industrial
equivalents of London Bridge - to be resurrected transatlantically in Mobile,
Alabama. There they will finally spark into action to serve British Steel's
mill in Tuscaloosa and another joint venture in the southern state. The
preparatory work has been done; 7500 tons of machinery and 2500 tons of liner
for the furnaces will go west, the work probably being completed by next
autumn.
The fate of what remains of the complex is not clear. Will it be razed and the
ground landscaped or adapted for some other industrial purpose? British Steel
understand that Clydeport will take the land over. Clydeport merely say they
have ``an option on the land currently occupied by the BS plant, and if it
became available they would consider exercising that option, incorporating the
land as part of the terminal''.
So major question marks continue to hang over the Hunterston site and the lives
of the inhabitants of the adjacent coastal communities. Understandable unease
is in no way mollified by a consultants' report, dated December 1992, to the
Scottish Office and Scottish Enterprise. This looked at planning policy and
development on the Hunterston peninsula.
Behind the detailed examination of strategies (it being taken as axiomatic that
major industrial use remains a good thing) is an admission of economic
realities: ``The site will need to be marketed actively. Hunterston will not
naturally attract attention, being remote from large centres of demand, unable
to offer superior infrastructure currently and having a limited and narrow
competitive advantage.''
In spite of this (from the report's point of view) dispiriting situation, it
looks at all sorts of industrial possibilities and improbabilities from steel
(now a dead duck) and oil refining (``unlikely to be developed, given its
hazardous nature within the nuclear safety zone'') to aluminium manufacturing,
chemical industries, and waste incineration. Economic factors - or the nuclear
one - vitiate most prospects, except coal importing and trans-shipment. The
fact is that the world economy has moved on, particularly in Asia, and
green-field sites on the extremities of northern Europe are nobody's top
priority.
It's a sad state of affairs; a lovely area has been despoiled without even the
justification of economic necessity. To be fair, some people did foresee this
future, including those who organised the spirited local opposition to the
original developments.
Brenda Dick (now Brown) was a prominent protester. More than 20 years on, she
says she's had her fill of fighting big business and government, but takes a
rueful pleasure in seeing it proved that the ore terminal was not viable
(``Every expert confirmed the steel industry was in a downward trend'').
She also recalls how two decades ago a British  steel boss took her aside
during a sightseeing tour of the  #160 million terminal and told her, ``If I
had lived in a place like this I would have done the same as you.''
She realises in retrospect that ``politicking'' and ``this wonderful promise of
jobs'' had proved too strong to counter. ``It was as though they had looked at
the most beautiful spot on the Clyde and said `How can we despoil it?'.'' Mrs
Brown also claims that the legal requirement for a five-mile unbuilt area round
the nuclear power station had been abandoned; also that a promise had been made
that should developments fail, the ore terminal site would be reinstated. Now,
of course, different people and different organisations are on the scene. The
action group's protests did achieve some results - for example the screening of
the steel works and terminal from the A78 coastal road at a cost of #4!fm. An
effigy of  the then Tory Secretary of State for Scotland, Gordon Campbell, was
burned in symbolic protest, proving that political responsibility was perceived
to span both major parties.
As for the present, Mrs Brown (``I can still get worked up after 20 years'')
fulminates against the unused rail link with its ``ghastly'' storehouse above
the main road and its searchlights, which she considers a hazard to motorists.
Clydeport confirm that the rail link is intact and could be used again if there
were sufficient customer demand.
Hunterston's nuclear facility meanwhile runs rings round its neighbours in
public relations. Visitors are welcomed to Hunterston B (the decommissioning of
the original Hunterston A was completed last year ahead of schedule). There are
guided tours and even tourist paraphernalia, from sweatshirts to sports bags,
to be had.
Eleven few miles north at Inverkip, the 800ft tower of the oil station rears
above the massive generating halls, an example of nineteenth-century technology
erected out of its time. Its basic principle - that if you pour noxious sulphur
gases high enough into the atmosphere they will go and pollute someone else's
backyard - is much less acceptable in these globally sensitive times. Besides
the power station is oil fired - planned that way to offer an alternative to
the then stranglehold of coal.
The Inverkip power station, commissioned in 1976, was never used to any extent,
except during the miners' strike of 1984-1985. It has not generated any
electricity at all since 1987. Contrary to some local rumours, however, its
machinery has not been removed. The plant has simply been mothballed and is
looked after by a handful of maintenance workers. In theory it could be called
into service again, but this is an unlikely option in an industry with
over-capacity (almost half of Scotland's needs are produced by the two nuclear
plants, Hunterston B and Torness).
So the great concrete phallus of Inverkip, erect but impotent, continues to
brutalise the views of the upper firth, diminishing everything in its
proximity. The fact that Scottish Power rents out its deep-water facilities to
passing ships from time to time is hardly justification for its existence. ``I
don't understand why they're keeping it,'' says Christine Gallon, who chairs
Inverkip Community Council.
She recalls that a year-and-a-half ago there was a proposal to bring an Italian
oil rig there for finishing work. More than 200 local people signed a petition
claiming the platform would be visually obtrusive and adversely affect
recreation and tourism. But Inverkip District Council gave the go-ahead on the
basis that jobs outweighed other considerations.
On that front, Mrs Gallon points out that the contract work on the rig would
not necessarily have gone to locals; also that if the rig had not found a buyer
it could have remained at Inverkip indefinitely. She didn't want to see a
Cromarty Firth situation created on the Clyde.
Scottish Power has, of course, merely inherited a problem which an earlier
generation of short-sighted planners didn't address. A spokesman said there
were no plans to get rid of Inverkip but that the future was constantly under
review and obviously there were questions about how long the plant was going to
sit there not doing anything.
But where would the funds come from to dismantle the Inverkip monster? Perhaps
the limitless maw of the EU is the answer.
Meanwhile one may wallow in the wisdom of hindsight. The great mistake of the
1970s, it could be argued, was not just a slavish preoccupation with jobs at
all costs but the lack of a comprehensive fuel and industrial policy for
Scotland, either independently or within the wider UK context. Five-year plans
and national strategies, of course, smack of totalitarian ways and even worse
things might have been perpetrated under them. But the messing of the
Hunterston pensinsula and Inverkip were the results of piecemeal decisions
without consideration of their overall impact on this once idyllic piece of
coastline. The position was exacerbated by the fact that public inquiries of
the time had such narrow remits.
Would things be done differently now when there's a greater appreciation of the
environment and when tourism is one of Scotland's few predictable growth
industries? It would be good to think so. Perhaps, however, those twin
shibboleths of jobs and deep-water facilities would still rule the day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
