<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>From Bloody Sunday to a war-winning bra</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra books of the year</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979303</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JULIA   LANGDON
n Stranger Than Fiction, Michael Crick (Hamish Hamilton, #17.50)
Enigma, Robert Harris (Hutchinson, #15.99)
Hidden Lives, Margaret Forster's (Viking, #16)
THE art of biography is not easy to define, but a book which informs and amuses
while also being revealing and interesting about the subject has to be judged a
success. Michael Crick's biography of Jeffrey Archer, Stranger Than Fiction,
was a triumph. It is full of fascinating information and is as thrilling, in
its way, as a detective story.
Robert Harris has thoroughly researched his second novel Enigma, set among the
codebreakers of Bletchley Park during the Second World War. It is a thriller, a
love story and a thumping great read. It really is one of those books that you
decide to miss most of the night's sleep in order to finish.
And there is a detective element, too, to Margaret Forster's Hidden Lives, a
compelling and beautifully written memoir of three generations of her family. I
loved it.
CARL MACDOUGALL
n Ladder of Years, Anne Tyler (Chatto &amp; Windus, #14.99)
Follow Your Heart, Susan Tamaro (Secker &amp; Warburg, #10)
Meshugah, Isaac Bashevis Singer (Hamish Hamilton, #15.99)
WHEN Delia wanders off, her absence is unnoticed for four hours. Neither her
husband nor their three adult children know the colour of her eyes, nor can
they agree on what she is wearing. Ladder of Years by Anne Tyler, forces us to
acknowledge the place of women society takes for granted; in so doing, it makes
shelves of political tracts and argument redundant.
Susanna Tamaro talks of women's lives like dead fireworks, brought to earth by
family and society instead of scoring to the sky. Follow Your Heart, is an
older generation's plea for understanding which is also at the heart of
Meshugah by Isaac Bashevis Singer. He explores a panoply of Holocaust survivors
whose plight is as stark and hoplessly moving as the piles of spectacles, shoes
and human hair that is Auschwitz's most elonquent testimony.
STEPHEN McGINTY
n The Troubles, Tim Pat Coogan (Hutchison, #20)
Rebel Hearts: Journeys Within the IRA's Soul, Kevin Toolis (Pan, #15.99)
The Missing, Andrew O'Hagan (Picador, #14.99)
IT took 23 years to understand the full horror of Bloody Sunday, the day I was
born. Tim Pat Coogan's section on the events of January 30, 1972, when British
Paratroopers shot and killed 14 unarmed people, in The Troubles is clear and
concise. Facts impact like plastic bullets. It is ironic that despite a strong
Irish heritage I should choose the first year of the ceasefire to dig the
emerald isle's blood-sodden turf.
Coogan's book is brilliant, a disturbing portrait of the how, why and where of
bitter men and Britain's fatal arrogance. For illumination behind the black
balaclavas Rebel Hearts: Journeys Within the IRA's Soul by Kevin Toolis is
first class. By journey's end he wears his republican colours with, at times,
shame for the sins of others. And, of course, Andrew O'Hagan's The Missing was
unmissable.
LORN MACINTYRE
n Paula, Isabel Allende (HarperCollins, #14.99)
THERE are those who dismiss magic realism fiction, with its dependence on the
survival after death of the human personality, as an evasion of reality. But
when the 28-year-old daughter of the Chilean writer Isabel Allende sank into a
coma in 1991, the author of The House of the Spirits used her fertile
imagination as a way of communicating with her daughter in the long, silent
vigil by the bedside.
Paula begins: ``Listen Paula, I am going to tell you a story, so that when you
wake up, you will not feel lost.'' In making meaning of Paula's life, Allende
evaluates her own life in this magnificent book which is both biography (the
daughter's) and autobiography (the mother's). Allende recalls her own story and
that of Chile's - and the fact that Paula dies gives this testament an added
poignancy and honesty.
robert mclauGhlan
n The Path to Power, Margaret Thatcher (HarperCollins, #25)
Gladstone, Roy Jenkins (Macmillan, #20)
Gladstone 1875-98, Colin Matthews (Oxford, #25)
MARGARET THATCHER'S The Path to Power, is her first volume of autobiography,
published after the second! It is the better read with less self-justification
and more personal revelation, particularly concerning her most tender years and
her mother's role in them. It is also good on Denis Thatcher who was so
essential to her success.
Mrs Thatcher was either loved or hated. Gladstone had the same experience: his
first biographer said he found half the doors of London closed firmly against
him. Lord Jenkins, his latest biographer in Gladstone, can be recommended with
enthusiasm. His own political experience informs the book at every turn. He is
not uncritical but sustains the high opinion Gladstone has eventually come to
enjoy in a book whose fluent qualities make for easy reading.
Jenkins's book must not be allowed to squeeze out Colin Matthews's Gladstone
1875-98. It is very good and rightly emphasises Gladstone's vital religious
dimension even more than Jenkins.
JACK McLEAN
n Dirt and Deity, Ian McIntyre (HarperCollins, #20)
The Ultimate Giles, Peter Tory (Headline Books, #25)
Jane At War (Pedigree, #14.95)
IAN MCINTYRE'S Rabbie Burns book Dirt and Deity because it gets you arguing,
and that's what these supine Burns Club always want to slide out of. Read it,
yes read it - and bloody well weep for Scotland.
You must get The Ultimate Giles by Peter Tory, if only for the 300 lavishly
reproduced cartoons. The text is a little reverential; bugger the text, look at
the artistry of this draughtsman who invented and interpreted in turns the
Britain in which I grew up, and generations before me too.
Also, a cartoon book: Jane At War. Wartime and the delectable blonde of the
dissolving dress, detaching bra, and gravity-prone panties. Nae wonder we won
the war. The Jerries had a chap with a silly moustache. We had Jane.
FRANK McLYNN
n Palimpsest, Gore Vidal (Deutsch, #17.99)
Millennium, Felipe Fernandez-Armesto (Bantam, #25)
The Oxford Companion To Philosophy, edited by Ted Honderich (OUP, #25)
MY three nominations share a common characteristic: all are wildly uneven but
never less than engrossing and, at their best, are quite brilliant.
Accordingly: Palimpsest by Gore Vidal, a candid autobiography disfigured only
by the rutting episodes; Millennium by Felipe Fernandez-Armesto, a universal
history, great on China, Latin culture and frontiers, but almost throwing the
baby out with the bathwater when it comes to Europe; and The Oxford Companion
To Philosophy, edited by Ted Honderich, which manages the astonishing feat of
running the gamut from outstanding entries to banal, jejune or incompetent ones.
n The Herald books of the year selection continues in next week's Weekend Extra.
</TEXT>
