<HEADLINE>Dam the  consequences</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM HEWITSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979304</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CIVIL engineering and flood control are not skills you would normally associate
with medieval warfare but in 1335 a squad of English military engineers could
scarcely contain their delight when they came up with a plan for the Drowning
of Lochleven Castle.
Occasionally, in trawling the backwaters of Scottish history I've come across
brief references to the Middle Ages equivalent of the regiment of engineers.
A few years ago we looked at the spectacular arrivial in Stirling of a
procession of exotically named siege engines, including War-Wolf and All the
World, the former a great towering brute of timber construction which was
reckoned to be the most sophisticated piece of military hardware in Europe in
its day. The engineers were out in force for that siege.
But back to the shores of Loch Leven. Having dealt in successive years with the
exploits of Bonnie Prince Charlie, Rob Roy and William Wallace, the movie
industry might consider turning its attention to this romantic affair in Fife.
Our principal characters would be the hero, Alan de Vipont (cheers!) and the
villain, John de Strivelin (jeers!). Yes, you're right - both were from Norman
stock but that didn't prevent either Bruce or Wallace hitting the big time.
This de Vipont held the castle in the loch (most famously the prison of Mary
Queen of Scots) for David II. With the English invaders traipsing around the
central lowlands, the island fortress was, according to one historian, a
``tempting mark for knightly enterprise and ambition''. You know what those
chivalrous chaps were like. The motto engraved on their hearts was something to
the effect ``Once a King always a King but once a Knight is never enough''.
A blockade was established, de Strivelin building a fortalice in the churchyard
of Kinross on a neck of land looking out across the waters to the castle.
Fleets of boats set out to assault the stronghold but were driven back by the
well-prepared garrison. Then, at a point where the river by the same name
leaves Loch Leven, a strong and high bulwark of stones and turf was
constructed, designed to raise the level of the loch and flood out the
defenders.
As the waters began to rise, de Strivelin was so confident in his masterstroke
he took most of his force off to a party at Dunfermline to celebrate the
anniversary of the canonisation of Queen Margaret of Scotland.
Meanwhile, back at the ranch, four soldiers from the island armed with picks
and crowbars rowed ashore and stealthily approached the dam, reassured that
they had gone undiscovered by the snoring of the nightwatch. Soon they had
undermined the dam and water began pouring through finally bursting on the
sleeping English camp and drowning men as they slept.
Despite de Strivelin swearing terrible vengeance he was eventually forced to
raise the siege and the general opinion of fourteenth-century historians,
notably Fordoun and Wynton, was that the invader got what he deserved, having
sacrilegiously built his temporary fort on the consecrated ground of Kinross
kirkyard.
</TEXT>
