<TEXT>
Loud and
dirty
guests
n MIDWINTER on the Ythan, and a shocking pink dawn over the black dunes. Ice
floes hush against the banks, borne inland on a rising tide. Long-tailed ducks
flight in from their roosts offshore, laying the arctic sky onto the river
where they settle. They make vees on the moving water, then dive, then flight
again, calling out the winter's necessities in a romantic yodel: ``Coal and
Candlelight''. Of all the transliterations of their call, this old name evokes
most strongly the frosty northern coasts where they winter.
It is only since the 1970s that we have found out how many ``Caloos'', as they
are known in the northern isles, winter with us. A great roost was found off
Burghead, ten or 15 thousand strong, too far out to be seen from land. In Scapa
Flow they roost likewise in the centre, where the German sailors must have
heard them in winter of 1919. By day they scatter in little parties off the
coast, diving for molluscs longer and deeper than any other duck: a minute at a
time and well over a hundred feet down.
Off any sandy shore from Barra round to Bellhaven you could pick out twos and
fours through binoculars. They look white against a blue sea, but closer you
see a patchwork pattern of browns and blacks. In flight the long, pointed
tailfeathers show which give them the fowler's name ``sea-pheasant''. By April
you will see bigger parties on the lochs and bays of Orkney, now moulted to a
darker brown with white cheeks. By the Churchill Barriers they perform a rich
repertoire of bowing, stretching, twisting, splashing displays, pairing for the
long flight to the arctic. They look like a different species then, until you
hear that unforgettable, musical cry.
As a child, on first looking into the Observer's Book of Birds, the prints of
the long-tailed ducks, with a wild northern shore behind, held me spellbound.
Every time I see them again, or hear their ``Coal and Candlelight'', the spell
is woven anew.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
