<HEADLINE>Double up for Scots</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979306</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND toasted success in the men's and women's singles at the Irish Open in
Belfast yesterday.
In the men's section, West Lothian's Craig Robertson moved into the last 16
with two fine wins, while Gillian Martin progressed into the last eight in the
women's competition.
First victim for Robertson was Dane Kim Nielsen, dispatched in three sets,
before the Fauldhouse man notched up a notable, hard-fought 13-18, 18-17, 15-6
success against highly-rated Englishman Anthony Bush.
After having received a bye in the first round, Martin progressed almost as
easily through her second-round clash with Switzerland's Yvonne Naef, the Scot
winning 11-0, 11-1. Results:
Men. First round - C Robertson beat K Nielsen (Denmark) 12-15, 15-3, 15-9.
Second round - Robertson beat A Bush (England) 13-18, 18-17, 15-6.
Women. Second round - G Martin beat Y Naef (Switzerland) 11-0, 11-1.
q THE Scottish squash championships, starting at Heriot Watt University in
Edinburgh next Friday, suffered another blow yesterday with the withdrawal
through illness of No.2 seed Alasdair Taylor.
With Peter Nicol and Stuart Cowie already having informed the organisers that
then will not make the event, Newland's Barry Sutherland has now been elevated
to second favourite behind world No. 30 Martin Heath.
</TEXT>
