<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000168</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000168</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Keeping it in the family</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MIKE HAGGERTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974979307</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is a case of ladies first for Scotland this weekend when the European
championships start in Grindelwald, Switzerland.
Kirsty Hay's team of her sister Karen, and Katie and Edith Loudon start their
round-robin campaign this afternoon against France, and, with tricky games
against Germany and Norway to come, a win today would be a good insurance
policy for the Scottish women as they attempt to qualify for the quarter-final
stages.
With Karen - based in France but who returns to Scotland regularly - in the
team this season in place of Jo Pegg, Hay's quartet is an experienced line-up
and should do better than the sixth place they managed at this event last year.
The Scottish men, Hammy McMillan, Norman Brown, Mike Hay, and Roger McIntyre
won this title in Sweden last year, have set themselves the target of retaining
their crown, a feat never before achieved by any Scottish team.
They open their campaign tomorrow with two games that look relatively straight
forward on paper, against Austria and Hollnd, but following stuttering
performances in their last two domestic tournaments, the Stranraer team
withdrew from last weekend's Edinburgh international to concentrate on
preparing for these championships.
Two victories over this weekend would do their confidence and chances of
retaining the title a power of good.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
