<HEADLINE>Forest drawn against Bayern</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979308</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN DRAWS
NOTTINGHAM Forest yesterday found a Jurgen Klinsmann-inspired Bayern Munich
blocking their path to UEFA Cup glory.
Frank Clark's side, the only British team left in European competition, were
drawn to face the Germans in the quarter-finals when the draw was made in
Switzerland.
The first leg will be in Munich on March 5, with the return at the City Ground
two weeks later.
Klinsmann, who returned to Germany in the summer after his season with
Tottenham, has been in stunning form in the competition, scoring six of his
side's goals in their two-leg destruction of Benfica in the last round.
He also helped knock out Raith Rovers in the previous round.
It will be Klinsmann's first return to England since he quit White Hart Lane
and he is sure to provide the sternest test of Forest's defensive resolve,
which has been the key behind their progress.
``I'm delighted to head over to England again,'' said Klinsmann. ``But Forest
will be a very hard nut to crack. I've a lot of respect for them.
``They play the old British style and put you under pressure with high, long
crosses. Our chances are 50-50.''
Forest have not conceded a goal since losing the first leg of their first round
match 2-1 to Malmo.
In the Cup-winners' Cup, Paris St Germain, who put Celtic out in the second
round, have been drawn against Parma, with the first leg in Italy. Full draws:
UEFA CUP
Barcelona v PSV Eindhoven, Bayern Munich v Nottingham Forest, Slavia Prague v
Roma, AC Milan v Bordeaux. (Matches to be played on March 5 and 19).
CUP-WINNERS' CUP
Dynamo Moscow v Rapid Vienna, Parma v Paris St Germain, Deportivo La Coruna v
Real Zaragoza, Borussia Moenchengladbach v Feyenoord. (Matches to be played
March 7 and 21).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000170</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000170</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>When a Royle gaffe should be pardoned</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979309</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ASK any football gaffer, and he will admit to a gaffe. Everton's Joe Royle did
it in regal fashion yesterday considering that his #4.3m striker, Duncan
Ferguson, had recently spent some time under the guidance of Her Majesty's
officials.
``His problems have not been on the field, and sometimes I wish he was more
aggressive on the field,'' said Mr Royle, obviously forgetting the incident
which led to Ferguson's enforced absence.
``He's had two sendings off down here - one for heavy breathing at Arsenal, and
one for a misunderstanding at Leicester.''
To be fair, Royle was enthusing about the Scottish internationalist being
``bursting to play'' in Everton's live TV game against West Ham on Monday night
after a highly successful comeback.
Ferguson scored two goals and lasted the full 90 minutes of Everton Reserves'
5-0 victory over Newcastle on Thursday night in his first competitive game of
football since August, and his name has been added to Royle's squad for Monday.
The manager added: ``He will feature at some stage. I think it's unlikely that
he'll start, but he'll certainly be in the squad, and we now have the knowledge
that if an emergency arose, Duncan would be ready.
``He did very well for the reserves, and looked sharp. It was a gentle
reintroduction, but he scored two goals and overall I was very impressed.
``He was blowing a bit towards the end, as you would expect, but I was
pleasantly surprised at his fitness level considering the time that he's been
away.''
Royle has no qualms about throwing Ferguson back into the pressure pot after
his spell in prison, but Ferguson may have to cope with West Ham's aggressive
full back Julian Dicks in a game which is being broadcast to the nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
