<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hard lessons on the hill</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH OUSTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979310</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PHILIP is two months off five and I am older than I should be. It isn't much of
a hill, Beinn Lighe, just a seventh wave on the rolling swell of grassy moor
that runs along the Ross of Mull. We have no hillwalking gear, just lace-up
boots and jackets with a pocketful of sweets. And we didn't leave the house
till after four. But it is just us and we have set off to climb.
As we walk along the road the sheep scurry before us, scrambling over muddy
gaps into the bogs where the irises are unsheathing their green swords. Deep in
the scrub the first willow warbler sings his cadence, overlaying the trickle of
water from a pipe into the roadside ditch. We cross the Iona road and climb up
the side of a taught wire fence. We don't hurry. We do look back. There's no
point in climbing any other way.
The slope of the hill is dry and heathery, with little bosses and promontories
of close cropped grass. We follow a sheep track at a place that suits us both.
A hundred feet or so up, we sit to look north across Loch Scridain and the
ocean beyond.
Staffa sits like a little black box on the silent water, its volcanic angles
echoed by the Treshnish Islands and by the tors of the nearer headlands. Behind
them all, Coll smudges the horizon. There is only the lightest wind. Opposite
us the great cliffs of the wilderness of Ardmeanach rise, scree and step,
fronting the mountains of Mull. Our little hill opens up a grand landscape.
When I talk about volcanoes, I can't tell whether Philip accepts the idea so
readily because everything in the world is possible, or because everything in
the world is incomprehensible. Come to think of it, I don't know which is true
myself. I am learning what any parent could tell me: that talking to your
children is a way of learning about yourself. And more: a way of learning again
how to learn. Metacognition. We'll have some chocolate when we reach that
little cliff on the horizon.
In the dry, grey spring wind birds of prey fly round the hillside. Two
buzzards, then a third, circle with their wings held forward in a shallow vee.
How difficult to mistake them for eagles, with their huge flat wings, that we
had seen the day before cruising the ridges of Glen More - but how often have I
made that mistake.
A pair of kestrels were hunting the field edges on the west slope of the hill,
their wings quivering as they worked the wind to steady their hunting eyes. We
looked over the rough ground to guess what they were hunting. Then we began to
notice the vole holes. At the edge of patches of grass among the heather were
little excavations, burrows an inch wide and a fan of fine soil in front of
them. This was more interesting than geology. Woodmice, aka long-tailed
fieldmice, were suckling the first of their four annual litters in the nest
chambers below our feet. Piles of droppings caused us raucous amusement as we
ferreted among the grass.
We saw where tiny seedlings were taking advantage of the handful of bare earth
to push up. I suggested - very speculatively - that they might be seeds which
the mice had eaten and excreted.
Nor were we far from geology still, for the richness of the rock, and of the
soil it breaks down to, determine the abundance of grass and thence of mice -
and thence, of course, of kestrels and buzzards. Field mice are sedentary - as
well as short-sighted - but field voles are our own lemmings, with population
peaks and crashes, and short-eared owls in particular, as specialist predators,
breed synchronously with these rhythms.
As food chains don't appear in the 5-14 curriculum till Primary 7, I avoided
burdening Philip with this knowledge. The fact that the hawks were hunting the
voles was enough, but being together on the hill was the best of all. It must
be recorded that Philip got more out of the droppings than the birds.
THREE hundred and fifty feet above the sea, we sat on a lichened outcrop and
munched chocolate bars. A few yards off, a ewe started bleating at us, standing
her ground with the sealoch behind her. At her feet a white, red-flecked bundle
lay on the green grass. I walked across and she moved off a pace or two, but
the lamb had been born and died only minutes before. Here was a subject for
Philip's questions. ``What?'' was difficult enough. ``How?'' was just about
possible. But ``Why?'' was beyond my powers. Maybe the best answers were there
before him and needed no words: the ewe's aimless little runs and cries at
nothing, the indifferent grass and the hoodies sliding past. One day, I'll tell
him Hugh Macdiarmid's poem:
I met ayont the cairnie a lass wi' golden hair
Cryin till a bairnie that wis nae langer there.
Winds wi warlds tae swing dinna sing sae sweet
The lecht that bends ower a'thing is less ta'en up wi'it.
It's not a matter of anthropomorphism; the lass and the ewe were crying over
the same thing.
We didn't climb much higher. When we passed our chocolate rock on the way down,
the ewe was already a little further off and the hoodies a little nearer.
Slipping through a patch of deep heather I asked if Philip wanted a roll. He
looked back, hungry, then laughed when he realised his mistake.
We tumbled and rolled sideways down the slope, ran a little and did it again.
Then we lay in the heather for a few minutes, panting and giggling, looking up
at the grey sky - until the crows slid past above us, too. I did say that they
would raise their chicks from the hill's carrion. It even sounded positive. I
would have liked to agree with John Muir: ``But let Children walk with Nature,
let them see the beautiful blendings and communions of death and life, their
joyous inseparable unity.''
But sometimes it's too close to home and then it's hard, impossibly hard.
</TEXT>
