<HEADLINE>Hubble catches an interstellar pile-up</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra frontiers</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979311</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n.BY pinpointing individual suns in the glare of the most tightly packed
cluster of stars in our galaxy, the Hubble Space Telescope has unveiled the
possibility of either a massive black hole or another remarkable phenomenon: a
``core collapse'' driven by the intense gravitational pull of so many stars in
such a small volume of space.
Astronomers at Santa Cruz have tallied an extraordinary number of stars in the
ancient globular cluster M15, about 37,000 light years away and part of our own
Milky Way family of stars.
While it is local, just a neighbourly group by astronomical calculation, it is
pretty mind-bogglingly distant. Those light years translate into a distance of
approximately 200 million billion miles, give or take a league or two.
Careful analysis of the distribution of the stars suggest that at some point in
the distant past, they converged on M15's core, like bees swarming to their
hive. This runaway collapse, long theorised by researchers but never seen in
such detail, may have lasted a few million years - a mere moment in the
12-billion-year life of the cluster.
The core probably stopped collapsing before many of the stars collided. Rather,
stars near the centre would have settled into an uneasy cosmic waltz, both
attracted to each other by gravity and repelled by close encounters that
slingshot them through space. An alternate scenario could explain the stellar
pile-up: a black hole that formed early in the cluster's history. If it exists,
the black hole would be several thousand times more massive than our sun, and
swallowing up everything within its event horizon, the gravitational pulling
distance.
Fortunately for us all, the solar system is well out of its fatal attraction.
</TEXT>
