<DOCNO>GH951209-000173</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000173</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Getting it together</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>45</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979312</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE are some jazz pairings which are made in heaven: Lester Young and Billie
Holiday, Roy Eldridge and Coleman Hawkins, Zoot Sims and Al Cohn, Bob Wilber
and Kenny Davern, Howard Alden and George Van Eps, and Ruby Braff and Ellis
Larkins.
The last two have combined only occasionally over the past 40 years but each
time they have gone into the recording studios the results have been sublime.
There was that memorable meeting back in l955 when record producer John Hammond
turned them loose on a selection of Rodgers and Hart gems. Seventeen years
later Hank O'Neal at Chiaroscuro records enlisted Hammond's aid to bring them
together again.
Eighteen months ago it happened again and the initial results have just
appeared on a CD on the Arbors label. Here is Braff, the mellow toned
cornettist saluting that giant of American song, Irving Berlin, with Larkins,
the pianist who remains one of the most in-demand accompanists around New York.
While Braff has always been recognised as a major figure on the mainstream
scene, a cornet player who eschewed bop in favour of the older forms, Larkins's
jazz presence has always been less publicised.
The man from Baltimore was classically trained but his career in jazz began at
Cafe Society in the forties. He played for Mildred Bailey following that and
became her favourite backing pianist.
So accomplished did he become in supporting some of the finest vocalists
around, this became his major role and jazz playing was left to occasional
record dates scattered across the last four decades.
Larkins has long been a mysterious figure in the jazz world and even a lengthy
recording project financed by the late Ernie Anderson, who spent his working
life as PR man for John Huston and then Charles Bronson, and his jazz life
organising such extravaganzas as the entire series of Eddie Condon Town Hall
Concerts and the legendary date at the same venue for Louis Armstrong, seems to
have vanished without trace.
Enough material for seven CDs was recorded but nothing has yet been released .
. . The Berlin tribute, though, is at hand and more is to follow and we can all
be happy with that prospect.
Their obvious mutual admiration shines through on every track with Braff
revealing in the sleeve note how he came to admire Larkins's playing. He first
heard him on an Ella Fitzgerald album which saluted the music of George
Gershwin.
Even now, the songs recorded then had such an impact on the cornet player that
he has dedicated his current CD to Ella.
So now, 40 years on, these two giants meet again combining to add further
lustre to such Berlin songs as Blue Skies, Easter Parade, This Year's Kisses
and How Deep Is The Ocean, among others.
There is also a haunting five- minute reading of Russian Lullaby which is
startlingly appropriate because it was that song which rocketed Braff to jazz
stardom when he recorded it as a member of the Vic Dickenson Septet.
This is melodic jazz at its very finest and Mat Domber deserves praise for
bringing Braff and Larkins back to the studios to make such wonderful music
together. I can scarcely wait for the second volume . . .
</TEXT>
