<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Light of the lagoon</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE HENRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979313</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDNA WHYTE's studio on the Isle of Luing is truely magical. Her window, which
slides back so you can hear the seagulls, smell the sea - you can see Scarba,
Mull, Lunga, the Black Isle, even the Garvellachs and Belnahua on a clear day.
``It knocks me over; it's mindblowing!''
How on earth does one paint when the distractions of ever changing moods of
ocean currents, tides, cloud formations and fabulous, breathtaking sunsets hang
on your every glance? These spellbinding scenes from dawn to dusk, in winter
and summer, sun or rain, are grist to her mill: inspiration for her impressive
graphite drawings and oil paintings currently on show at the Lillie Gallery,
Milngavie, later to be seen at Ayr's Maclaurin Gallery.
Whyte is a woman of many talents: artist, designer, illustrator, teacher,
business woman, restaurateur, raconteur. Till 1990 her career spread in many
directions, her Buttery and Gallery winning awards for food, design products,
and prints produced by her Old Rectory Design firm.
But with the backing of business partner, Audrey Stone (who was the chef behind
the Buttery and co-director at their Residential School at Achnamara), in 1990
they chucked in the business to allow Whyte, then sixty, to focus on her
painting. It's been worth it, for her work has proceeded by leaps and bounds.
To understand her new work, I went to visit Luing, near Oban, an island a mere
six miles long and two across. To get there you cross the Atlantic Bridge at
Clachan Seil and follow the road to Cuan Ferry.
Luing is unique, and different to other Hebridean inshore islands. There are no
gold sands. It's a slate island with dramatic black beaches, low white
cottages, and wonderful seafood! Its roof slates, mined till the mid 1960s, can
be found on Iona Cathedral. Whyte first came to Luing at 14. Her uncle had a
house there, which now belongs to her cousin. Family holidays from London to
Aberdeenshire relatives established her love of Scotland - and a sense of
journeying, of motion. ``Those journeys had a big influence on me,'' she says.
Since 1967, her studio has overlooked the Luing lagoon where seals and otters,
mackerel, wild salmon, lobsters, scallops, saithe and lythe joust the waves
under turbulent skies. It's a lonely, isolated place for a gregarious soul like
Whyte, but many friends from around the world frequently come to stay.
``This place matters to me,'' she says. ``I love the starkness of the
landscape, the stubborn rocks, the dramatic bowels of the deserted quarries.
Year round I experience the impact of sea, sky, cloud, vapours, horizon: the
mercurial, rumbustious, evershifting elements of water, air and light. These
elemental forces display their dramatic existence across vast perspectives.
``This perpetual activity sets the problem: how to convey in drawings the
nature of this chaotic, everchanging expression of natual forces?'' Whyte
demonstrates that you don't need colour, only a pencil to recreate Luing's
elemental flux of wind and weather. Her linear concentrations evoke rhythm and
movement. Sometimes her visionary drawings give one the impression of being on
a speedboat roaring at the island through spray and swell towards a blinding
sun. There's an almost scientific, meterological feel to several images.
Sometimes she uses line in an abstract way to express the very fracture of the
elements; energy dissolving in sunlight, raindrops sparkling, rainbows
scintillating - evoking the whole panorama of Argyll's miraculous theatre of
the elements.
Her studio at the top of the house is designed by architect David Meek, of
Oban. It's full of easels, rows, piles and boxes of paints and pencils;
hundreds of brushes.
``You can't pop out to the corner shop here and buy art materials. I use acres
of pencils and wear out a lot of brushes! So I keep a stock in!''
Whyte paints on wood, (``I've been selecting the knots!'') or on gesso where
she can incise turbulent linear activity in monochrome using pencil, paint,
rags and rubbers. ``I've never fancied canvas. The intensity of gesso white is
wonderful and Pelican grey putty rubbers are the best for taking out highlights
from impacted graphite. I use sandpaper and old biros for markmaking too!''
She can only work standing up at the easel and likes to be able to step back
from her work so her studio has ``long runs''. Nowadays, she doesn't sketch at
the sea edge.
``I have it all in my head. I've spent a large proportion of my life looking,''
she explains: ``I work by obliteration. I draw; then scrub out and go on to the
next phase. An image needs energy in it. I use putty rubbers to create
highlights. Surface is very important to me. I don't mind bashing it; pounding
it! I'm quite gestural. I want a drawing to have erosion. As the wind changes
or the water ripples, I destroy and go with the orchestration of what happens
next. Perspectives of space don't satisfy me. I want to achieve tonality by an
intensity of light.''
Whyte went to Kingston Art School at 14. (``As a child I knew I always wanted
to go there''), then to London's Royal College at 19 where she was taught by
Carel Weight, Edward Bawden, Nash and Moynihan.
``I've been exceptionally privileged and have never had to submit to the
tyranny of a restricted life. And the island people also taught me how to see.
They are such sharp observers. It's all to do with song, music and dance. Art
is all music, isn't it?''
As I leave, Whyte confides: ``Both Audrey and I are very keen on surprise. And
remember I'm not the only artist here. Audrey makes designs like Kandinsky from
beautifully selected food, salads and such like, in wonderful colours. Meals
which look good are a colossal pleasure. There's not enough design around these
days.''
</TEXT>
