<HEADLINE>SAVE THE LAZY HOUSEWIFE</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TINA JAMES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979314</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n Fruits of the earth: such a variety of delights from the garden could soon be
a thing of the past. It's estimated we have lost around 2000 varieties of
vegetable since the 1970s. Now new laws from Brussels could see an even sharper
decline in the abundance of lesser-known but much loved names.
DO you ever think that vegetables tasted better when you were young? It is not
necessarily pure nostalgia. The vegetables we eat today are dominated by the
requirements of supermarkets and so many of the fondly remembered varieties of
the past have simply disappeared.
``We have lost 2000 vegetable varieties since the 1970s,'' says Jackie Gear,
executive director at The Henry Doubled Research Association's Ryton Organic
Gardens near Coventry.
``It is terrible to see some of our most beloved vegetables disappearing.
Varieties our grandfathers and great-grandfathers would have grown, right back
to the 1700s' need to be protected. They survived in the past because people
used to save the seeds and replant them. People adopt chimps and dolphins, so I
thought why not adopt-a-vegetable.''
At Ryton, #12.59 a year ensures your vegetable's protection by guaranteeing its
inclusion in Ryton's Heritage Library. This contains 700 vegetables in the form
of seeds which are available to Ryton's 3000 members.
The reason so many of our beloved, traditional vegetables have become a
threatened species is because supermarkets want different characteristics from
amateur gardeners.
``Supermarkets want varieties that they can harvest all at once, so their big
machines can harvest all the peas in one day,'' says Gear. ``Amateurs want
varieties that won't crop all at the same time, vegetables that will keep on
coming so they can pick a little every day.
``Supermarkets want things to sit neatly on shelves. They want tomatoes with a
thick skin so they won't get damaged on the shelves. But who wants to eat a
tomato with a thick skin? You want a tomato that tastes good, the thinner the
skin the better. Amateur gardeners couldn't care less about the shape, they
don't want to put them in packets.''
The other reason the beloved British vegetable is under threat is due to Euro
regulations. The Brussels bureaucrats have decreed all varieties must be
registered before they can be sold. Incredibly, it costs around #800 a year to
maintain a vegetable on this list, so all but the best selling varieties of
vegetables have been dropped. And family seed firms whose business was selling
a multitude of varieties have now discovered they can't afford to offer the
same range.
Rooting for Scotland in the gardens at Ryton, I saw a flourishing Laird's
Victory Turnip. The survival of this turnip is something of an adventure story.
``It arrived at Ryton as two flowering turnips in a padded envelope.'' says
Gear.
``The donor, from Dundee, said they had belonged to his neighbour. When he
died, aged 90, his family threw away his collection of seeds. But they left
Laird's Victory in the garden and our donor had rescued two plants. The Laird
in question was not a Scottish ruler but Laird and Sinclair, the old Dundee
seed merchant. It is doing well; safe, we hope, forever.''
There are more than 700 varieties which still need adopting. Who could not help
but want to protect the Lazy Housewife Climbing French Bean: a runner bean with
the intriguing name of Mortgage Lifter; Ragged Jack Kale; Uncle Bert's Purple
Kale; the Lancashire Lad onion; Rat's Tail radish; Lady Godiva Squash or a
Boothby Blond cucumber?
When you adopt at Ryton you get a signed certificate of ownership and your name
is put in a commemorative book. You can also go on to obtain the seed of your
threatened favourite so that you can grow it in your own back garden. But will
the general public empathise with a threatened Silsden Bomb cabbage as easily
as a delightful dolphin?
Sophie Grigson, cookery writer and broadcaster, has adopted the Fablonelystnyj
tomato. ``It has a wonderful hint of Russia and is absolutely delicious with
that marvellous intense tomato taste, a lovely balance of sweetness and acidity
with a delightful fragrance,'' she says.
She couldn't resist the charms of oca either. ``I came across oca in South
America, in Ecuador, it's like a cross between a cooking apple and a potato,''
she says. ``It has the starchiness of a potato and the fruitiness of a cooking
apple with a hint of chestnut. It is related to the nasturtium and is a type of
oxalis like sorrel. I'm growing a small crop in my garden and it's delicious
boiled with butter.''
Less exotic, but just as commendable, are the choices of Dr Ian Allison of
Penicuik, Midlothian, - a Laxton's Exquisite Pea and a Bronze Arrow lettuce.
``I'm trying to grow organic vegetables in my garden here because I don't want
to use pesticides,'' he says. ``Have you ever seen a slug on a supermarket
lettuce? I refuse to use slug pellets, but, of course, a lot of my veg gets
eaten. However, I firmly believe that the old varieties of vegetables, grown
naturally, do taste better.''
Diana Milne of Dalkeith, Midlothian, says: ``I adopted an Oak Leaf lettuce
which is similar to the Salad Bowl lettuce, widely grown by organic gardeners,
and the superb Early White broccoli. I wanted to support Ryton and I am looking
forward to growing them from seed. We have a third of an acre on the River Esk
and try to live off our garden produce. Winter Greens are so vital for good
health and we love to eat vegetables which look and taste that little bit
different.''
However, it is too late for some, like Carter's Sunrise tomato; the winner of
the only First Class Certificate from the Royal Horticultural Society in a
trial at Wisley.
``Although we have unearthed some Carter's Sunrise seed, it has all proved too
old to germinate,'' says Gear. ``And there is no sign of Carter's Fruit which,
according to an old description, `Peels like a peach and can be eaten raw like
an apple at any time of the day'. Where is the luscious sounding tomato now?''
Perhaps, like so many of life's great mysteries. we shall never know.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000176</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951209-000176</DOCID>
<DATE>951209</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lotus eaters of the secret Algarve</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JULIE DAVIDSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979315</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE things men do for women. Once there was a Moorish king of the Algarve who
deeply loved his Scandinavian wife. But the bride from the north pined for her
own country and homesickness threatened her life. The king was desperate to
save her. He imported thousands of almond trees from his own North African
homeland and planted them round his castle, between the barrier hills of his
kingdom and the great ocean. When the trees came into blossom the landscape
turned wintry with snowflake flowers, and the queen recovered.
I've promised myself something: my next visit to the Algarve will be in
February, when the almond trees flower. Their history may be folklore, although
it's true they were introduced to southern Iberia by the Moors, but their
reputation is fact. In January, the first buds open and by February blizzards
of blossom cover the hills around Silves and Sao Bras de Alportel, the
butterflies return and the Algarvian spring is under way. From then on it's
wall-to-wall mimosa, cistus, lavender, iris, wild tulips and jacaranda until
the oleander and bougainvillea take over for summer.
I've never seen the Algarve short of flowers, wild or cultivated. When I was
there last, in late August, I expected to see some signs of heat exhaustion but
the gardens were gung-ho and the hills verdant and the grass (more truthfully,
the well-watered lawns and golf courses) was achingly green. Who'd have thought
you'd have to go to southern Portugal last summer to find a patch of green
grass?
Six years ago I'd never seen the Algarve at all. Six years ago I was a
blinkered bigot. Mention the Algarve and it brought out the Jean Brodie in me.
All very well for those who like that sort of thing if that's the sort of thing
they like: golf-courses and time-share complexes, high-density beaches,
concrete coast, sardines with everything, suburban colonies of ex-pats.
And then, at the invitation of an editor who suggested I investigate ``the
alternative Algarve'', I spent a week in a villa near Sao Bras de Alportel and
found the Algarvian alternative was only 20 minutes inland from Faro airport;
while half an hour to the east - in the opposite direction from the
tourist-intensive hubs of Quarteira, Vilamoura, Albufeira and their satellites
- were beaches as long and empty as the strands of Harris, pounded by warmer
waters of the same ocean.
I fell out of the airport's sub-Beaubourg arrivals hall and into a shock of
delight. Within minutes the car left the grisly jostling on the coastal highway
(now supplanted by a sleek new motorway between the Spanish border at Vila Real
and Albufeira) and burrowed into green hills flecked with white houses.
The country roads were pitted with potholes and mysteriously empty. We passed
three cars and a mule and cart. We passed the outskirts of Santa Barbara de
Nexe, which has a parish church celebrated for its Manueline workmanship and
the sardonic soubriquet of ``the Hampstead of the Algarve''. We saw a sign to
Loule, the largest inland town, centre of artisans since the thirteenth century
when the Moors were expelled from its castle and replaced by brass and copper
craftsmen.
We went onwards and upwards, noting the cluster of rented cars in the wayside
forecourt of Maria's Supermercado. Capitalising on fluent English learned in
New York, Maria is the fairy godmother of self-caterers, even if she does hike
the prices of her deli produce. Finally, we reached a fold in the hills, rocked
up a track between olive groves and arrived at Casa da Cruz Alta.
For all the rackety practices of a few low-cost developments - remember those
horror stories about carbon monoxide poisoning in the eighties? - the quality
of self-catering property in the Algarve is high. You can live like rock stars
in the sumptuous villas of upmarket resorts like Quinta do Lago and Vale do
Lobo (Michael Jackson and Madonna have villas among the umbrella pines of
Quinta do Lago - more residential investment than holiday home) but beyond
their cordons sanitaires you can find charm, comfort, seclusion and your own
swimming pool for half the rent you pay for similar billets in France or Italy.
There was nothing flashy about Casa da Cruz Alta, but this converted farmhouse
tucked into a shelf of uneventful countryside 10 miles from the sea became
quite dear to me. From the top of the hill we could see the coast, with some
dreaming towers shining in the sun; distance lent enchantment to the high rises
of Quarteira. The shepherd drove his flock past our door and our next-door
neighbours, a Portuguese family who spent hours in their vegetable garden,
offered lemons and potatoes.
In our own garden were three carob trees, four olives, two kumquats, an almond
and a fig tree, with a prickly pear at the back door and flowers everywhere.
The swimming pool overhung a valley of orchards and terraces and at dusk we
could see the lights of Sao Bras, and hear its dogs bark between cuckoo calls.
When we drove into the little town to shop we passed a derelict canning factory
(tuna fishing was once a cornerstone of the Algarve economy, but in the 1970s
the great shoals of tuna suddenly changed their migratory path and body-swerved
the region) and on its chimney stack was a nesting stork. A stork! I had only
ever seen storks in the illustrated Grimms, or on birth greetings cards.
Casa da Cruz Alta had martins nesting between its cane ceilings and its Santa
Caterina tiles, baked at a plant in the eponymous village on the Tavira road,
and two tall chimneys pierced in the Moorish style. The Moors arrived in the
eighth century, stayed for 500 years, and when they were evicted from their
last Algarvian stronghold in 1253 by Afonso III, king of the youthful nation of
Portugal, the monarch was proclaimed ``King of Portugal and the Algarve''. This
south-west corner of Iberia with its equable climate and marketable 3000 hours
of sunshine a year has since preserved an identity quite distinct from its
mother country. I find the Algarvians a little like sunburnt Scots: reflective,
undemonstrative, a bit dour, perhaps, but with slow-burning kindliness in their
faces. They have the build of peasants and traces of the Moorish gene in their
swarthiness.
The devastating Portuguese earthquake of 1755 (the worst in Europe, flattening
Lisbon and killing 60,000 people) wiped out most of the original architecture
of the Moors. The mightiest of their surviving fortresses is the red sandstone
castle at Silves, built on a site used by the Romans. Today, bee-eaters hoover
the spaces between its courtyard jacaranda trees.
The ghostly influence of the Moors persists, however, in old and new domestic
architecture, in the pierced chimneys of farmhouses and villas and the openwork
balconies of apartment blocks, and in a love of ornamental tiles. Portuguese
azu lejos, painted glazed and assembled into decorative panels, are found all
over the country and have been used since the sixteenth century, but the
Algarvians have a passion for them. They deploy the square clay tiles on all
sorts of building, inside and out.
Churches traditionally use blue and white tiles for their panels of Biblical
scenes but azu lejos come in all colours, and often ornament the entire faades
of buildings. I can think of several humble cottages in Sao Bras with azule jos
faades, and a handsome, three-storey town house in Lagos which is tiled in
glazed leaf green from roof to doorstep.
Lagos, which gave its name to the Portuguese trading post which became the
capital of Nigeria, and which launched the sixteenth century caravelles on
their long voyages to chart the sea routes to India, is the place to be if
you're a student of maritime history. This attractive town and one-time naval
dockyard of Henry the Navigator marks the western boundary of my experience of
the Algarve.
This is a little shaming, because although I've sailed round Cape St Vincent on
a cruise ship I've never explored the wilder extremities of the Algarvian
seaboard, yet I love lonely seascapes. The coast west of Sagres, I'm told, has
been spared the commercial indiscretions which disfigure some of the golden
cliffs and sea-sculpted grottoes between Albufeira and Portimao, and to the
north of Cape St Vincent the exposed Atlantic beaches and 200ft cliffs are now
protected from development.
Portugal has slapped environmental protection legislation on this sparsely
populated region.
Rumour has it that the far west secretes the Algarve's only empty beaches and
unspoiled coastal communities. False rumour. I have found my lonely seascapes
within 20 minutes of Faro (whose peaceful old city, Renaissance cathedral,
Baroque church of Sao Francisco and other quiet satisfactions are usually
ignored by the masses belting through the airport) among the dunes and lagoons
and sandspits of the Ria Formosa Nature Reserve.
The coast around Faro, and between the Algarvian capital and the Spanish
border, is atmospheric rather than spectacular: flat but complex, with long
fingers of sand heaped into peninsular dunes and barrier islands. Sixty
kilometres of coastal wetland are managed by the authorities of the Ria Formosa
Natural Park, who describe their fief as a habitat of world importance for
aquatic birds and other wildlife; and here, from a very luxurious hide in the
Quinto do Lago Hotel (the balcony of my bedroom), I learned the Algarve is
heaven for twitchers.
Twenty per cent of the reserve falls into the Quinta do Lago estate and its
only hotel, a five-star Orient-Express enterprise, has quietly begun playing
the environmental card. Bird-watching may never replace golf as its number one
activity, but the staff have noticed an increase in the number of guests who
borrow binoculars, or bring their own. There's a resident colony of flamingos
on the estuary, and the estate's new nature trail invites sightings of royal
terns, eagles, and every variety of duck and wader. In the last two years the
spoonbill, once a visitor, has started to nest and the migrants include
hoopoes, bee-eaters, azure-winged magpies, golden orioles and Alpine swifts.
Seasonally, African butterflies drop in.
I have a soft spot for Quinto do Lago, which other, ruder and more superior
travel writers call Surrey-by-the-Sea. I took a morning ride through its
pinewoods when I was last there, and the early golfers on the forest fairways
were unfussed, and the Home Counties householders and proprietors sitting on
their blameless lawns by their immaculate villas were harmlessly idle.
Later, I walked across water on a long, rickety wooden bridge to a favourite
(if expensive) beach restaurant, Gigi's, which serves fresh fish and seafood to
die for. But I took my chances and worked off lunch in the breakers of a
boisterous sea: our own Atlantic, which makes the dear, dreamy Mediterranean
seem a little stale. When push comes to shove, however, I know my place: the
humbler end of the eastern seaboard, the etiolated Ilha de Tavira with its
limitless beach, its widely dispersed population of wind surfers and its
strategically placed chip-and-chicken bars. They serve fish and seafood, too,
when the market is kind; and you do yourself a kindness if, en route, you visit
the fish market at Olhao, a port which has lost some of its Cubist charm to the
moribund factories of the canning industry, but where the harbour and its
vessels - everything from deep sea trawlers to bright little inshore craft with
protective eyes painted on their bows - are worth seeing.
On Saturdays, gipsies in their painted carts gather at the market while the
fruits of the sea provide the cabaret. The catch is so fresh that inspecting it
is hazardous: clams spit at you, crabs nip, eels wriggle, monkfish bare their
teeth. You half-expect the swordfish to strike poses and shout ``En garde!''
You can reach Ilha de Tavira by miniature railway from the west side of Santa
Luzia, or by five-minute ferry from the edge of the salt pans at my
best-beloved Algarvian town, Tavira, once its largest town one of the oldest.
Loule is homely, Olhao is functional, Lagos has style, but Tavira has natural
charm. Its centrepiece is the seven-arch Roman bridge over the River Gilhao
(Tavira was once a busy estuary port, but its harbour is now silted up) and on
the riverside promenades you can walk beneath noble date palms and the faades
of Renaissance buildings.
Despite a substantial Roman presence in the Algarve the legions didn't leave
many traces of their passing. There are remnants of the ancient city of Milreu
at Estoi, six miles inland from Faro (in a region not heavily endowed with
official ``sightseeing opportunities'' you can bag two at Estoi, where the
formal gardens of an eighteenth century country mansion are open to the public)
but Tavira's bridge is a handsome memento; and the rest of the town is
delightful.
The castle has a terraced garden and the churches are splendid, rich with
porcelain-blue tiles, while Tavira's jumble of red-roofed houses have made few
rash moves to accommodate tourism. Despite its reputation - the town is
well-known as one of the Algarve's most relaxed and appealing - it remains
largely untainted by development. But I did get one surprise when I was there
in August, my first visit for two years. The Roman bridge now has a rival: the
monster span of the new motorway which leaps across the Gilhao. It looks like
the bridge to Skye.
There is more to explore: the western coast, of course, and the deeper
interior. Everyone goes up to the Serra de Monchique for its chestnut woods and
views and a chicken piri-piri lunch at the roadside restaurants between the
pretty town of Monchique and the peak of Foia, the Algarve's highest. But there
are far lonelier serras and much emptier landscapes between the two arteries of
the Lisbon motorway and the River Guadiana, the Spanish frontier.
For explorers, however, there is this problem with the Algarve: it can't be
rushed. It cultivates lotus-eaters. For my part, once installed in my little
rented farmhouse in the olive-green hills, once submerged in geraniums and
marguerites and the sweet-smelling heat of summer, I find it hard to move;
which is why, some day, I must go back in brisk February for the almond blossom.
n BETWEEN May and October, Faro international airport is served by weekly
charter flights from Glasgow, Aberdeen, and Edinburgh, with charters from
Glasgow also available from November to April.
Otherwise, TAP Air Portugal - in conjunction with British Midland - offers good
connections through Heathrow, daily in summer and four times a week in winter.
Fares from #293. TAP also has a winter fly-drive programme at discounted rates.
Tour operators which feature the Hotel Quinta do Lago include Elegant Resorts
(01244 350 461), Caravela Tours (0171 630 9223) and, for golf holidays, British
Airways Holidays (01293 723 131) and Longshot Golf Holidays (012730 268 621).
Direct reservations can be made through the worldwide reservation number for
Orient-Express Hotels (0181 568 8366), which also gives details of special
programmes and any discounted seasonal offers.
Self catering: quality villa specialists include The Villa Agency (01273
747811) and CT Travel (0171 581 0851).
The Portuguese currency is the escudos, and the current rate of exchange is
about 224 escudos to the pound. Portugal remains one of the most inexpensive
destinations in Europe.
</TEXT>
