<HEADLINE>Danger lurks in Livingston</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL SUTHERLAND</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979316</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF there is a team in the basement which Stranraer would have wanted to avoid
in today's first round of the Tennents Scottish Cup it is leaders Livingston.
Jim Leishman's team have collected a number of scalps this season in other cup
competitions, and another run in the major knock-out event could be the tonic
for a team who have yet to win at their new stadium in Livingston.
Stranraer manager Alex McAnespie has watched Livingston and knows that his team
will have to keep an eye on striker Jason Young, whose 12 goals so far this
season is twice as many as anyone their Division 2 opponents can boast.
As at Stranraer a senior club is bound to fall by the wayside after the
encounter between Stenhousemuir and Arbroath. John Brogan, now in charge of the
latter, returns to Ochilview, a ground he knows from his days in charge of
Stirling Albion, who had to play there for a season. Stenhousemuir have found
their scoring touch and should be too strong.
One non-league team is sure to progress as Edinburgh's Spartans visit Glasgow
University at Westerlands. Living up to their name, the existence of a Spartan
can be tough, as their manager, Sam Lynch, explains that the players even pay a
standing order to a bank to help keep the club in funds. The pay-to-play team
from the capital, or the students, will meet East Fife in the second round.
Spartans should be favourites as their ranks include striker Paul McGovern, who
has played for Hibs and Partick Thistle, and central defender Mark Thomson, who
played in the cup last term for Meadowbank before moving across Edinburgh to
rejoin Spartans.
</TEXT>
