<HEADLINE>Daring darling of the Place Vendome</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANNE COWAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979318</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHE is remembered as the designer of the lobster dress and the hat like a shoe,
and as the creator of shocking pink. But as with the Surrealism which inspired
her style there was more to Schiaparelli than met the eye. If the garments were
dreamlike, so too, was her life.
Elsa Schiaparelli was born in 1890 in the Renaissance pallazo Corsini, near St
Peter's in Rome. Her father was in charge of the magnificent library in the
pallazo so the family lived in an apartment there. Behind the facade of the
building lay a garden and as a child Elsa was surrounded by rich colour,
frescos, illustrated manuscripts, gilded interiors and Roman antiquity.
After a conventional upbringing and with no suitable husband on the scene, the
plain, unhappy Elsa was a worry to her parents. In 1913, at the age of 22, she
visited Paris which she instantly loved. She then went to London where she met
her husband, Comte William de Wendt de Kerlor.
The year 1915 found the young couple living in Nice but here the trail runs
cold. There followed three-and-a-half years of Schiaparelli's life of which
nothing is known. In 1919 the count and countess were living in New York. After
the birth of her only child, Elsa was deserted by her husband.
After a period of hopelessness, beset by poverty and by the illness of her
daughter, Gogo, Elsa returned to Paris. The city was seething with artistic
ferment. Inspired and encouraged by Paul Poiret, Schiaparelli designed
innovative clothes. Her trompe l'oeil sweaters were an instant success. Before
long the smart set was clamouring for her striking sportswear and modern
jewellery. By 1928 her Display No 1 and Display No 2 collections had been
chronicled in Vogue and drew comment from the New Yorker. Elsa Schiaparelli had
arrived.
International high society shopped at her salon in the Place Vendome, or at her
boutique, Schiap (pronounced Scap). She applied witty embroidery, mirrors, and
toy-like buttons to her dresses and jackets. She brought out a circus
collection, a musical note look, and she introduced big shoulders.
Greta Garbo followed her dictate. Film costume departments put Hollywood's
designing females, Joan Crawford, Bette Davis and Rosalind Russell into outfits
inspired by Madame Schiaparelli. The confident jacket and pert, perched hat
were as much part of the 1930s actress's armoury as was brittle repartee.
When in 1936 Schiaparelli showed shocking pink, the colour which was to become
her signature, Salvador Dali used it for his divan in the shape of Mae West's
lips. The Shocking perfume bottle was shaped like Mae West's torso.
Schiaparelli worked with Cocteau who drew profiles to be embroidered on to
dresses and jackets. In 1938 Dali's ``tear'' dress and the torn headscarf were
forerunners of punk design.
There are other surprises in this strikingly illustrated book, Elsa
Schiaparelli by Palmer White (Aurum Press, #19.95), ``She haunted Linton (sic)
in the Borders of Scotland and ranged as far North-west as the isles of Lewis
and Harris.''
After dining with the MacLeod of MacLeod on Skye she incorporated tartan and
tweed into her collection. At the entrance to her 18-room house at 22 Rue de
Berri, Paris, stood two life-sized Venetian figures, M and Madame Satan which
Schiaparelli had bought in an Edinburgh secondhand shop.
Elsa Schiaparelli died in 1973. She was survived by Gogo and by two
grand-daughters, Berry Berenson who married the film actor Anthony Perkins and
Marisa Berenson, jet-setter and actress of Cabaret and Barry Lyndon fame.
Schiaparelli left a legacy of bold and startling garments in wardrobes and
museums across the fashionable world. Yves Saint Laurent and Karl Lagerfeld
among others have acknowledged the debt they owe to Schiaparelli. Both have
paid tribute to her in designs inspired by her brilliant, idiosyncratic work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
