<HEADLINE>Plots within plots</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROSE PIPES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979319</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS we sow, reap, and grunt over spades, marvelling at nature's bounty, how many
allotment holders are aware, I wonder, of the controversies that have raged
around our innocent pursuits? It was when I began to dig (naturally) into the
matter that I realised how much our apparently private plot-worlds have been
the subject of public concern.
As well as Acts of Parliament, there has been a Government Enquiry (which led
to the Thorpe Report, 1969), not to mention attempted ``Bills to amend the law
in relation to allotment gardens and to confirm that allotment gardening has
the status of a recreation''. However, the Enquiry made little impact and no
progress, and the attempt by Lord Wallace to pilot a Recreational Bill through
Parliament in 1984/85 was judged by a fellow Lord as ``not apprppriate for
modern times . . . recreational gardening is a matter for education and not for
legislation''. Our bonfires continued unquenched.
Our activities have also brought forth numerous publications on the subject,
the most thumbed of which in my collection is The Allotment: its landscape and
culture by David Crouch and Colin Ward. Published by Faber in 1988, this
enchanting book explores the culture of the allotment and the part it has
played in Britain's life and landscape for 150 years.
After re-reading the first chapter, I emerged damp-eyed and determined to
defend allotments, ``the last bastions of individualism'', against the
``professional designer, municipal tidiness and imposed order'' and from the
zeal of ``reformers'' and others who, like the late Professor Thorpe, viewed
allotments as ``neglected eyesores''. To Thorpe, they carried the ``stigma of
charity'' rather than self-help. He felt they should be replaced by the
``leisure garden'', with sites improved and upgraded as recreation facilities
for all the family (oh please, no paradise patios!).
Amongst other aims, some very sensible such as tidying up the impenetrable
legislation, the Thorpe Report proposed a completely new image for allotments.
It was highly critical of the allotment movement, finding few ``public spirited
allotment holders'', and many ``individualists who consider their allotment to
be as private as their home gardens, who are seldom interested in anything
beyond its boundaries, and who are blind to their further responsibilities''.
Here lies the paradox: many plot-holders (I would guess the majority) resemble
Thorpe's individualists; those like myself for whom the plot is a blessed
relief and means of escape from the daily round so often dominated by ``further
responsibilities''. Yet we know that, threatened with unacceptable regulations
or extinction, we would all rise up, armed with implements and indignation, to
defend our rights and bludgeon our associations into vigorous lobbying activity.
The activities of my own Allotment Association, let alone the local council are
remarkably unobtrusive. They surface only periodically with requests for rent
or notices of forthcoming produce shows. Despite their rules and missives of
let, and strange appeals such as one I received recently ``to desist from the
use of carpets on plots'', the council eye that turns to the wonderfully varied
and makeshift landscape of my own allotment site seems blessedly blind.
For example, to the best of my knowledge, no one has yet been forced to
demolish a hut which did not conform to the specified standards (apart from one
monster sky-scraper around which brassicas drooped in perpetual twilight). And,
I might add, it was mostly off-the-peg huts that sailed skywards from their
moorings in the recent gales - not the ingeniously cobbled together variety,
dismissed as eye-sores by Thorpe and his ilk.
All right, so some allotments have suffered the indignities of regulation huts
and tarmacked paths, and others have been scrapped altogether in favour of more
profitable housing schemes, but on the whole, the prevailing policy seems to be
one of dig and let dig. Some councils, conscious of the increasing size of
waiting lists for plots and of the cost of preparing new sites, are now
encouraging people to take on half-plots as they recognise the growing demand
for would-be plotters to carve out their own patch of rural sanity in the
stressful fast-lane urban world of the 1990s. This is enlightened policy.
But what of local government reorganisation? Are we under threat as the
inadequately funded new councils look for savings? Will this be the moment for
reports to be dusted off and Acts re-written? This we can't yet know, though I
was assured by the allotment officers in both Glasgow and Edinburgh their jobs
would remain in place. However apolitical we wish to be in our apparently
private gardening worlds, we need to be mighty vigilant in future if we are to
preserve and protect our patches from being bulldozed or gentrified. I for one
intend to brush the mould off my allotment notice board and note down the name
of the local association secretary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
