<HEADLINE>All set for gift giving</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>45</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra </FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979321</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FABER VIDEO BOX SETS (retail, #24.99/#34.99).
NOW, as Max Miller used to say, here's a funny thing: why is it that a film
made out of a book is almost always less posh than the book, but films actually
gain status when they're published as books?
A movie becomes accepted as a classic, such as Citizen Kane, when you can buy
the screenplay and read it quietly at home without all those distracting
pictures; but when Kenneth Branagh makes a film of Henry V, not even Kenny's
best and oldest pals would say that it was the Swan of Avon who was on the
receiving end of the compliment.
Maybe Faber and Faber would know why this is; already possessed of the smartest
movie-book list of any British publisher, they've just launched (handily in
time for Christmas) two very snazzy series of book-and-video boxed sets, any
one of which on your shelf (but which shelf? There's always a problem) will do
more for your film-buff cred than a complete set of French New Wave laserdiscs.
The Film Series sets comprise a video, in widescreen and director's-cut version
as appropriate, and a copy of the screenplay. The first three titles are:
Arthur Penn's Depression masterpiece Bonnie and Clyde (1967, cert 18, #24.99),
whose screenplay includes critical essays, notes on the making of the film, and
material on the social and historical background to the story.
Giuseppe Tornatore's Cinema Paradiso (1989, cert 15, #24.99), a loving
celebration of the power and comfort of movies, set around an Italian village
cinema in the 1950s where a young boy falls in love with the succession of
celluloid dreams. The video is the restored 167-minute version.
Quentin Tarantino's Pulp Fiction (1994, cert 18, #34.99), which needs no
further introduction except that it costs more because you get the soundtrack
CD as well.
The first three sets in the Directors Series, which comprise a book by or about
the director and a video of one of his major films, are:
Tim Burton (#24.99) - a copy of Burton on Burton and a widescreen tape of his
heartbreaking suburban-Frankenstein fairytale Edward Scissorhands (1993, cert
PG), starring Johnny Depp and Winona Ryder.
Martin Scorsese (#24.99) - a copy of the new edition of Scorsese on Scorsese
and a widescreen video of his brutal boxing melodrama Raging Bull (1980, cert
18), regularly voted the best film of the 1980s and an Oscar-winner for Robert
De Niro. This one won't be out until January, to coincide with Scorsese's new
film Casino.
Edward D Wood Jr (#24.99), the master of poignant ineptitude and beloved maitre
of Tim Burton, whose biopic Ed Wood is out on video shortly, is represented by
Rudolph Grey's Visions of Ecstasy: The Life and Art of Edward D Wood Jr, and by
his finest cinematic hour (such as it is), Plan 9 From Outer Space (1956, cert
PG), starring Bela Lugosi (posthumously) and many folk weird enough to make
poor old Bela look like James Stewart.
Every one a gem, folks: post early up the lum for Christmas.
KENNETH WRIGHT
</TEXT>
