<HEADLINE>A favourite of Signor Favorita</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>conrad wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979322</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOW is the time to get down to some serious wine buying, when there is an
excuse to crash the #3.99 price barrier for the sake of all that turkey that
lies ahead. Most of us, on such occasions, opt for something French - for that
life-enhancing bottle of claret or burgundy we can't usually afford - even if
it means assessing vintages in a way that New World wines make unnecessary.
But as someone who usually spends at least part of December in Italy, it is
upon Barolo and Brunello, on Gavi and Moscato that my own thoughts tend to
dwell. If I can find something new - and Italy these days is awash with new
ideas - so much the better.
A white that fills the bill - a genuinely appetising aperitivo, but equally
good with a seafood starter - is Gianni Gagliardo's 1994 Casa Favorita del
Piemonte which, because it costs #6.99, has been confined by Oddbins to their
``fine wine'' departments in Glasgow and Edinburgh. Favorita, which is the name
of a grape rather than a statement of preference, used to be one of the
nondescript Italian wines about which nobody had much to say.
The Alba area, from which it comes, is so famous for its hefty reds that its
whites don't get much of a look in. With all that quaffable Dolcetto around,
who wants a feeble Favorita?
Quite a few people nowadays it seems, if Gagliardo's name is on the label. Not
only has this north Italian producer shown belief in the grape, he has
transformed it into one of the most luxurious of dry Italian whites,
impressively smooth, delicately rounded, with a flavour of fruit and nut that
is the outcome, on Gagliardo's part, of almost 20 years of loving attention. In
Alba they now call him Signor Favorita, and it is easy to see why.
If you think #6.99 is a crazy price to pay for an Italian white, bear in mind
that even a humdrum Orvieto is likely to cost you #11 or more in your
neighbourhood pizzeria. But if you insist on something cheaper then Sainsbury's
1994 Cortese del Piemonte at #4.49 is a reasonable second-best. The Cortese
grape, like the Favorita, can be boring or interesting, depending on who is
handling it. Since it's the source of top-class Gavi, however, Italians do tend
to treat it with respect. The Sainsbury version, though a bit hard-edged, has
some flavour - that of lemon and pear, according to the label - to compensate.
Another Sainsbury success is its own label 1994 Frascati Superiore which, at
#4.99, is everything a good Roman wine should be. Totally clean on the palate,
this, too, has enough taste to offset accusations of sterility. But if #4.99
seems too much for something as mundane as Frascati then Oddbins will sell you
an even more mundane 1994 Colli Romani for #2.99 - and pretty good it is at so
risky a price.
For a classy Italian red that is neither a Barolo nor a Brunello, a bottle of
Pasqua's 1990 Amarone Vigneti Casterna shows what a Verona wine should really
taste like. It will make you dissatisfied once and for all with the many thin,
vinegary reds that masquerade as Valpolicella. Corney &amp; Barrow Whighams (who
have opened a tasting room at 31 Rutland Square, Edinburgh, in addition to
their Ayr premises) sell it for #8.74. Most restaurants would charge more than
#20 for it.
Finally a sweet fizz to banish memories of the more cloying sorts of spumante.
It comes from Gianni Gagliardo - with whom this article began - and it comes in
a fashionable bottle with a red seal instead of a label. Don't let this put you
off what is a glorious Moscato del Piemonte, #5.99 from Oddbins Fine Wines,
whose Scottish premises are at 93 Mitchell Street, Glasgow, and 5 Queensferry
Street, Edinburgh.
CONRAD WILSON
</TEXT>
