<HEADLINE>Readers submit to unfinished business</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KENNETH WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>book review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra paperbacks</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979323</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n F Scott Fitzgerald (ed. Matthew J Brucolli). The Love of the Last Tycoon: A
Western (Abacus, #5.99).
THERE is something poignant and perfect about an unfinished book. This edition
of The Last Tycoon, for many readers (partly because of that unfinishedness)
Fitzgerald's greatest novel, is all the more so because of the inclusion of
many facsimile pages of Fitzgerald's working notes. The reader can more or less
finish it off as he likes. The manuscript itself is unchanged except for the
correction of obvious slips and for the title, one of several Fitzgerald
considered for his wish-fulfilment fantasy figure of Hollywood mogul Monroe
Stahr. Brucolli chose it, I think well, because ``Fitzgerald was in fact
writing a Western - a novel about the last American frontier, where immigants
and sons of immigrants pursued and defined the American Dream''.
n Tobias Wolff. In Pharaoh's Army: Memories of a Lost War (Picador, #5.99).
A SEQUEL to that extraordinary American memoir This Boy's Life, this man's book
takes the author through his army service (volunteered for on his regular
principle that it seemed a good idea at the time) and his years in Vietnam -
but don't let the V-word put you off. Avoiding the standard Nam-writing
alternatives of breast-beating self-reproach and tough-guy narcissism, Wolff
recounts his bootneck years with wit, humanity, and a casual swing in his style
that puts one in mind of Catch-22. The result is funny, moving, and honest.
n Phil O'Keeffe. Down Cobbled Streets: A Liberties Childhood (Brandon, #6.95).
DUBLINERS say there are two kinds of people: real Dubliners and people who wish
they were, which gives this memoir of slum Dublin in the 1930s a decent-sized
potential readership. Unsentimental about poverty but full of warm pride in
family, people, and place, Down Cobbled Streets has the dignity and charm of
plain words and simple storytelling. A good example of the informal history of
the Plain People of Ireland - and everywhere else.
n Tamasin Day-Lewis (ed) Last Letters Home (Pan, #5.99).
LOVE and war bring out the best in letter writers, and this Second World War
collection of letters between British civilians and family and friends in
uniform - not all as final as the ominous title might suggest - is, as well as
variously funny, touching, and sad, a remarkable testimony to the articulacy of
ordinary people in times of trial. When the words are really needed, it seems
that most of us manage to find them.
n Leslie Dick. The Skull of Charlotte Corday and Other Stories (Secker &amp;
Warburg, #9.95).
SHARP as broken glass and challengingly erudite, these nine stories about the
(mostly) female condition deal in a far from simple way with the elementary
stuff that T S Eliot sums up as birth and copulation and death. Approaching
their subject from angles as tangential as the Los Angeles earthquake, the
assassination of John F Kennedy, and the strange history of the skull of the
title story, they demonstrate an originality and a chilly humour that is
faintly unsettling but distinctly memorable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
