<HEADLINE>Disaster by the tail</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL FRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979324</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIKE every man I have my faults, but quite honestly I do not think there is
much anybody in the world can tell me about oxtail. In my lifetime I must have
consumed a whole herd's worth of these delectable appendages, chewing steadily
through the recipes for them in the classical French authorities.
But oxtail is not an easy cut to deal with. It hardly does for an elegant
dinner party, because even when long and perfectly cooked you can only eat it
all by picking it up to gnaw it, a rewarding but sticky and messy business.
Also, you really have to finish the tail at one go, no small task. It does not
keep well once done. If reheated, the outer layer of flesh turns a little black
and hard, and is no longer so meltingly delicious as in its first flush.
Having attained that degree of expertise in the matter, I was surprised to find
an extraordinary recipe in the cookbook by John Burton-Race, a young English
chef with a brilliant reputation. I have never had the pleasure of visiting his
restaurant, which is somewhere in Berkshire. If I did not know it had already
won two Michelin stars, I would never have believed his dish was possible.
The recipe at least has the virtue of setting out everything step by step, and
this is how it goes. First prepare an oxtail, but not in the ordinary way. Buy
a whole oxtail, and cut it in half. Soak the thick part for 24 hours. Dry it.
Brown it. In the same roasting tray, brown chopped-up vegetables and remove
them. Pour out the fat, pour in red wine, reduce it. Add it to chicken stock in
a casserole, and in this cook the oxtail for up to five hours. Take it out and
cool it.
So far, so simple, but now you have to construct an ``oxtail package.'' Mr
Burton-Race is sanguine about this: ``With a small sharp knife, place the tail
on its back and gently ease the meat away from the bones. If the tail is cooked
properly this should be quite easy. The result should be a rectangular piece of
meat that is quite boneless. With a flat spatula, lift the tail on to a large
piece of cling film, still keeping it flat.''
That was the easy bit. Now dice some mushrooms and mix them with chicken
mousse, prepared in advance. Place the mixture down the middle of the oxtail,
where the bone was, then use the cling film to wrap the flesh round it so as to
reform the tail. Twist each end of the film, to seal the whole thing from the
air, then wrap it in another piece of film. Cook the package for half-an-hour
in simmering water, and cool it. When cold, cut it into six pieces. Put more
mousse on one flat side of each piece. Wrap each piece in caul.
Had enough? Mr Burton-Race has not. Heat the oven. Reduce the stock from the
casserole. Place the pieces of oxtail in the stock in a deep pan, ``and cook
for about 15 minutes, removing every now and again to spoon the stock over the
oxtail. This stock will reduce and become sticky while the mousse cooks. Be
careful not to overcook the topping.'' Boil vegetables to garnish. After the
usual last-minute touches, serve.
This strikes me as the kind of recipe which should never appear in any cookbook
whatsoever. From beginning to end, the preparation takes at least 33 hours. The
effort involved is out of all proportion to any conceivable result. At several
different stages, there is a fair likelihood that he entire process will
collapse in disaster, with no chance of rescue. What happens if you cannot
remove the flesh from the bones neatly, and are left with a mangled mess? What
happens if water gets inside the package, and makes it all googly? What happens
if the mousse squirts out when you cut the tail in pieces? What happens indeed,
if, right at the finish of 33 hours' slaving, you manage to burn the sticky
stock in a hot oven?
A lucky chef will, I think, have failed in the initial attempt to chop the
oxtail in half, given it to the dog and decided to serve his guests cheese
sandwiches instead. Better still, they could all go off to Mr Burton-Race's
restaurant and pay him to do the slaving. I wish him every good fortune, and
hope that one day he gets his third star. But he seems to me to show up very
well the fact that great cooks do not inevitably write great cookbooks, for
which certain special qualities are needed: for instance, some regard to the
practical capacities of the long-suffering housewife working alone in an
ordinary kitchen. For her, this recipe is useless.
It is rather a relief to turn to two other books which may set the aspirant
chef on the way to a good domestic cuisine which is not absurdly demanding.
After all most of us, unlike Mr Burton-Race, do have other things to do than
cook.
Pat Chapman's offering is just right for the busy working lad or lassie, with a
taste for curry, who wants to avoid the dreaded microwave meal in plastic.
There is an admirable range of dishes including all the standard favourites and
some interesting variations, none taking - though the claim is perhaps a little
optimistic - more than 30 minutes.
Just as commendable, one level up, is Fiona Hamilton-Fairley's book for those
who would love to entertain at home but have never dared to. She gives a
complete rundown on the equipment and stocks of basic ingedients that every
pantry should have, timed recipes with unmistakable instructions, and again a
varied selection of recipes, from vegan suppers to carnivorous feasts.
n Recipes from an English Master Chef, JohnBurton-Race, Headline, #15.
n Quick After Work Curries, Pat Chapman, Piatkus, #12.99.
n I Can't Cook Entertaining, Fiona Hamilton-Fairley,  Bloomsbury, #16.99.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
