<HEADLINE>Tales of the unexpected</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PAUL YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979325</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT is it, I wonder, about us fishermen that sometimes gives us a slightly
unsavoury reputation among the great non-angling public? Why are we perceived
as less than truthful as we pursue our lonely vigils by the riverbank or enjoy
a cheerful communal day aboard a boat at sea?
The pursuit of fish is one of man's oldest activities; indeed the fish-hook is
one of his most ancient inventions and writings on fishing are among the
earliest of printed works. The vast selection of fishing literature involves
not just straight descriptions of ``how to do it'' but the realisation that
there is a bit of mystery involved.
That tantalising thin sliver of the surface of the water divides us from an
unknown realm. This gives that realm a magic, which was succinctly put to me by
a gillie on the broad lower Tay one day. I gazed across the popples and gurgles
of the water and said, rather inadequately, that I thought it was a remarkable
piece of water.
``Aye son,'' he said, ``and you're just seeing the tap o' it.'' He was a keen
fisherman with many a tale to tell.
Yet look up ``fisherman's tale'' in the dictionary and you will find the
calumny: ``An implausible and boastful story.'' To further impugn the family of
fishermen, a fishwife is defined as a ``coarse and abusive woman''.
I suppose we anglers must suffer from the old ``you should have seen the one
that got away'' syndrome. The monster that got off just as it was about to be
landed or the specimen roach taken by a pike as you drew it over the landing
net. Nowadays, it can only be that kind of blarney that gives us a bad name.
For, if you decide to keep a fish for the table, it isn't possible to make it
any bigger on the way home, is it? And if, as so many anglers are doing, you
decide to return it to the water, there is almost certain to be a camera in the
fishing bag to record the event. Very well, when the pictures come back, you
might want to add a phantom pound or two to that skate, but since it probably
wasn't weighed absolutely accurately because you didn't want to put the fish
under more stress than was necessary, you might still be guessing under its
actual weight.
In fact, when we were filming for a programme on pike fishing down near
Lochmaben, we came across a couple of characters from the St Helens area who
made the journey north regularly to fish in Scotland. They had caught many pike
from the same water and when I asked if they had ever caught the same fish more
than once, a stream of statistics tripped off their tongues. Yes they had. In
fact, they'd had one fish nine times . . . they could tell by the fact it only
had one eye. They called it Nelson and reckoned it had a suntan because if had
been out of the water so often and it knew exactly when to smile for the
camera. The interesting thing was that it didn't get bigger and bigger every
time they caught it. Sometimes it was lighter because of the feeding conditions
prevalent at the time.
One of the great things about the angling fraternity is its diversity. You will
meet people from every facet of society. And I suppose, as with society, you
will always find the odd chap who will want to bend the rules. At one rainbow
trout fishery, I was told of a chap who seemed to be walking rather stiffly
after his short session. He was asked by the management to remove his waders
before getting into his car and eight rainbows, twice the permit limit, slid
out. I've known men in high office (who had to catch more fish than their
colleagues) who would not be averse to flipping a Toby across a pool well away
from the road on a fly-only river.
However, most of the anglers I meet aren't trying to get away with more fish
than they have paid for or wanting to be top dog. Most simply want to enjoy a
day exploring the fascination that water can offer, either alone or with
like-minded companions. So let's hope future dictionaries will define a
fisherman's tale as: ``A story told by one who has something dramatic to tell.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
