<TEXT>
NORTH and Midlands, after their eight-try romp against Glasgow on Wednesday,
enter the second round of the inter-district championship tomorrow cast in the
unaccustomed role of title-chasers, even favourites, writes Derek Douglas.
They are at Kelso where South of Scotland, in the enviable position of having
the likes of Gary Armstrong sitting on the bench, will provide more of a
challenge than did weakened Glasgow in midweek.
The Exiles, defending champions as well as operating under a cloud due to the
uncertainty surrounding their status next season, are at Burnbrae where Glasgow
will seek to redress the balance after their mauling in mid-week.
It is a big game for international outcast Eric Peters after Wednesday's dreich
outing against Edinburgh at Richmond, and the Exiles also enjoy the luxury of
