<HEADLINE>The time - April 1997: the place - Scotland</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974979327</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
World rugby's youth
set to have its fling
THE international festival of youth rugby, which Scotland will host in April
1997, is shaping up to be the most ambitious jamboree the world has seen in the
game.
The four-day festival, the brainchild of three Glasgow enthusiasts, now has won
the support of the Scottish Rugby Union, and will be backed by The Herald. The
event is expected to attract more than 10,000 teenagers from all over the world.
The tournament will take place from April 1-4, with the opening and closing
ceremonies and the finals to be staged at Murrayfield.
The competition will cater for four age-groups, with players born in the years
1982-85 participating in simultaneous leagues.
The concept was conceived inititally by Dr Ronnie Graham, a committee-man and
youth coach with Glasgow Academicals. Another Academical junior coach, Peter
Laverie, and Whitecraigs president John Hutton became involved, and the nucleus
of the organising team was born.
Yesterday, SRU director of rugby, Jim Telfer, declared: ``It is a first-class
idea and, to be truthful, I wish that we had thought of it first. It represents
a great opportunity to raise the profile of the game and to bring to Scotland
youngsters from all over the world.
``It will be an opportunity for them not just to play rugby, but to widen their
horizons in a general sense. It's a tremendous step forward for the game as a
whole.
``The overall organisation is being done by Ronnie Graham and his people, and
we will provide the technical back-up with our development officers and so on.
I can't speak highly enough of the work that they have done. It's excellent and
they deserve a lot of credit for bringing the concept this far,'' said Telfer.
A company has now been set up to handle tournament administration, and more
than 6000 brochures providing details of the competition are being sent out
this week to schools, clubs and governing bodies all over the globe.
In addition to the Home Nations, invitations are going to France, Australia,
New Zealand, South Africa, Italy, Argentina, Japan, USA, Canada, Belgium,
Denmark, Western Samoa, Romania, and Spain.
Players and coaches will be accommodated at centres throughout Scotland, and
the proposal is that games will take place in Glasgow, Edinburgh, Dundee, St
Andrews, Stirling, the Borders, and Perthshire.
Each team will play 12 games, each of 15 minutes' duration, over the two days
of league competition, with the finalists converging at Murrayfield on April 4.
In addition to the sporting action, the organisers also will lay on a rock
concert, firework display, sightseeing trips, and other recreational activities.
Laverie, who is chairman of Glasgow Academicals' youth section, said: ``What we
wanted to do was to raise the profile of youth rugby, and at the same time to
provide a unique event that would allow youngsters from different countries and
different backgrounds to celebrate the game of rugby as well as taking part in
a meaningful competition.
``Bringing children from all over the world to Scotland also underlines the
global nature of the game and gives them the chance to play rugby and the
opportunity to experience a country that, perhaps, they would not otherwise
have seen.
``We took the concept to the SRU and, right from the start, they were
incredibly enthusiastic and really took it on board. Now that the thing is off
the starting blocks, we've realised that something which began over the
diningroom table requires a full-time effort, and we've set up Keysport
Scotland as the company which will handle the mammoth task of administering the
undertaking,'' he said.
Iain Forbes, managing director of Caledonian Newspapers, said: ``We see our
involvement in the tournament as an extension of our unrivalled rugby coverage.
We are keen to see the game prosper, and an obvious starting point is at youth
and junior level.
``This will be a major event on a global scale which represents a good
opportunity for Scotland to show what we can do. We're already involved in
football with the Herald Sevens national competition, and we're equally pleased
to support rugby at junior level as well.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951209-000189</DOCNO>
