<HEADLINE>Lunchtime rumbles expose the fault line</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>George Birrell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979330</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE hundred years ago Vesuvius erupted, created a new crater and initiated the
shockwaves of an earthquake which rocked Florence. John Major's early morning
cup of cappuccino followed by a light lunch of pasta and a glass of Chianti
with the Italian Prime Minister Lamberto Dini in that city this week could well
have the same seismic effect on the Labour Party.
It is part of the Prime Minister's grand strategy to win him the next election.
Increasingly, he is convinced the issue which has dogged him and his
predecessor - Europe - is the wildcard which can trump Tony Blair. Forging an
alliance with Signor Dini to oppose the Franco/German plans for a single
currency by 1999, due to be discussed at next week's Madrid summit, is the
first attempt to play it.
No wonder Mr Blair, with his mind on other things, was so flustered during his
visit to Scotland yesterday that he was offering hostages to fortune over the
tartan tax. Apparently it will not be implemented unless the electorate votes
for it. So the assembly will have to be dissolved each time it is proposed.
Will the same be true of Westminster if Gordon Brown as Chancellor wants to put
up taxes? Or will the parliament in London be ruled with an iron fist and that
in Edinburgh with a limp wrist? When will the Scots confined to their creche on
Calton Hill be able to join the grown-ups?
Unfortunately, this faux pas, like others before it seemed to leave Labour
unscathed and the Tories floundering unable, so far, to find an answer as to
how to derail the Blair bandwagon. It is because the Labour leader is an ad
man's dream. He is good looking, articulate, intelligent and the voters
perceive him as courageous and a man of integrity. The media, sensing the
``near inevitability of his Prime Ministership, have reflected this by
unthinkingly conspiring to give him an easy ride. A luxury never permitted
Wilson or Callaghan.
The Conservatives did try to brand him as ``Bambi'' but his squaring up to the
unions over Clause 4 afforded him the opportunity to display his macho
crudentials. Even the accusations that his few declared policies are a ``con''
or that they are ``vacuous'' have fallen on stoney ground, his poll ratings
accelerating with a speed comparable to the American space probe on Jupiter.
The current scare tactics, dreamt up by Tory Central Office, that Blair has a
hidden agenda of socialism, red in tooth and claw, which he will reveal after
election is also pathetic. The public will never swallow it. He is vulnerable
but not in the way those Tory back-room chinless wonders imagine. They will
never come to terms with the Blair phenomenon until they realise it is
underpinned by the man's shrewdness and calculation. Major, in despair, has
fallen back on his own instinct, as he did in the 1992 election when he ignored
these Oxbridge ponces and stepped via his soapbox back to No 10.
This time he again has spotted Labour's (i e Blair's) Achilles heel, Europe. It
is so obvious only those with a First in Greats could have missed it.
Europe is Tony Blair's post-election escape hatch. He is far too clever not to
realise that even a scaled-down version of Labour's economic policy is doomed,
notwithstanding Gordon Brown's cure-all one-off windfall tax. His other problem
is the left in his party who would have the power, depending on the size of
majority, to make him their prisoner.
However, by signing up to the Social Chapter under the Maastricht Treaty, it
will be the European Commission who will determine the pace of socialism in
Britain not the idealists on the National Executive. Furthermore, while the
implementation will disadvantage us against our non-European competitors he
will hope that the protectionism of fortress Europe will cushion that
uncompetitiveness.
He would also want to be bolstered by a powerful, independent Central European
Bank, which, after we have signed up for the Single Currency, would determine
fiscal and monetary policy. It would be like the good old days under Labour in
the mid-1970s when the International Monetary Fund had to be called in to run
our economy. Only this time Labour would be saved that embarrassment and also
that of a sterling crisis. The financial corset of the Bundesbank would stifle
the Loony Left while ensuring measured steps towards Continental corporatism.
Mr Major can expose this deceitful programme by trumpeting the advantages of
Britain's opt-out from the Social Chapter, which has hugely contributed to the
creation of thousands of new jobs from inward investment, by joining with
countries like Italy and Spain in delaying the possibility of a single
currency, and alerting the voters to the consequences of creeping federalism.
It would also be a strong card to play in Scotland where there has been so much
drivel talked about the ``democratic deficit'', particularly from the
Nationalists with their bogus ``Independence in Europe'' platform. If a
``democratic deficit'' - the gap between citizens and institutions - exists
anywhere it is in Europe.
The last thing we want is additional powers to commissioners who are appointed
by governments and who work in secret. The European Parliament is grossly
unrepresentative with one member per 700,000 constituents and such is the
apathy among voters that they are elected on increasingly low turnouts. It has
little power and although in extreme circumstances it could force the
resignation of the Commission, this is as likely as our Queen dissolving the
Commons on a whim. The real power resides with the Council of Ministers over
which the ordinary voter had no direct influence.
This is a genuine debate waiting to take place and which only the Tories can
initiate. It is not anti-Europe it is anti-Federalist but it could scupper Mr
Blair's agenda and create not just a mythical stretch of blue water between the
parties but a yawning chasm.
Not only would it give the electorate the opportunity to have their say on the
kind of Europe they want to see Britain a part of but would present a challenge
to Mr Blair which so far the Tories have failed to deliver.
They will never get away with depicting Mr Blair as an ogre. But the issue of
Europe will represent a dignified test of his sincerity - or lack of it.
</TEXT>
