<HEADLINE>An ode to modern living</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ann Donald</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra sanctuary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974979331</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ann Donald wanders through the rooms of poet Edwin Morgan
FRESH from a jam-packed week of readings and part of Glasgay!, Edwin Morgan,
one of Scotland's best-loved poets, is at home to a nosy journalist curious to
check out the room where the illustrious and industrious 75-year-old has
created such timeless and cosmopolitan works to be found in collections such as
From Glasgow to Saturn, The New Divan, and more recently a translation of the
highly-acclaimed play Cyrano de Bergerac.
Stepping through the frosted-glass sliding doors that separate the
workroom/living room from the rest of the flat, is to a degree like stepping
back in time. Were it not for the hi-tech video and TV then this could very
well be a comfortable, domestic scene imported direct from a sixties sitcom,
with its black shiny vinyl settee and comfy chairs, green mosaic coffee table,
elaborate standing window boxes, and durable ``period'' typewriter which takes
pride of place at the worktable.
``I was one of the first to move into this block when it was built in 1962,''
Morgan says of his 30-year-old home, before adding with a smile - ``I still
think of it as my `modern flat'.''
Given the flat's central location and Morgan's reliance on Glasgow's public
transport system it was ideal when he was lecturing in literature at the
University of Glasgow throughout the sixties, seventies, and eighties. This
particular room, which has the bonus of facing both south and west, and is thus
privy to as near to a Mediterranean amount of sunshine that Scottish weather
permits, also proved to be more comfortable to write in than the proposed
``claustrophobic'' study or indeed his short-lived timeshare holiday home
overlooking Loch Rannoch.
``I'm a real city person so I like to look out of my windows at the people
walking by and listen to the noise of the traffic,'' he reveals before
proceeding utterly to destroy that glorious Wordsworthian myth of the tortured
writer seeking his muse among the bracken and heather of a silent countryside.
``I thought going up to Loch Rannoch I would be able to shut myself away from
all the modern distractions and just write like mad,'' he says. ``But I looked
out at the loch and trees and just didn't feel inspired. I missed all the noise
so I sold it,'' admits the confirmed urban dweller with a shrug.
It is here, then, on his sensible and sturdy original 1962 model of a German
Adler Bluebird typewriter, that Morgan types away in the afternoons or evenings
on whatever constitutes his current project, be it poetry, plays, or
translations. ``This is extremely well-made,'' he nods, giving the machine a
friendly pat, ``and it does for my purposes very well.''
Though not a Luddite by any stretch of the imagination - the hi-tech fax and
dinky photocopying machine in his study testify to this - he is unwilling to
trade in the reliable Adler for an alien computer. ``I bought an Amstrad once
but I never got to really love it,'' he sighs. ``It's just an age gap I suppose
but I like to type and see the whole object in front of me rather than write a
poem on a computer when it may disappear if the computer crashes or there's a
power cut as happened here a few weeks ago.''
The workdesk the compact Adler rests upon has a very orderly army appearance
with the essential tools of any scribe neatly laid out in rows: a stapler, a
punch, multi-coloured glass paperweights, calculator - to calculate those
author advances? - sharpened pencils and neatly stacked piles of notes for a
future project. ``These are for a collaborative work with the saxophonist Tommy
Smith at the next Jazz Festival,'' says Morgan as he flicks through a handful
of picture postcards of wild Scottish animals that form the visual inspiration
for the proposed series of poems called Beasts of Scotland, which are intended
to inspire Smith's own creative jazz juices.
Visual inspiration also comes via the cluster of eclectic paintings that face
Morgan's workdesk and are scattered throughout the flat. A number of Glasgow
Boy Peter Howson's less stridently macho works, unrecognisable in their beauty
of colour and delicacy of touch, decorate the hall and living room.
Turning his gaze from the most recent acquisition - a small allegorical version
of Cain and Abel, Morgan then points out his favourite, The Head. ``I love the
extraordinary expression on the man's face,'' he says peering closer into the
very whites of the portrait's startled eyes. As well as Howson and a
shoe-box-sized Stephen Campbell in the hall, other artists culled from a
typical RSA roll-call include Pat Douthwaite's abstract interpretation of the
pursuit of Greek goddess Rhea by Zeus and a beautiful evocative Joan Eardley
street scene of children outside a sweetie shop, which so moved Morgan that he
was inspired to write the simply titled poem, ``To Joan Eardley''.
The unquestionably dominant interior feature in Morgan's home is of course the
thousand of books which he reveals are to be gifted to the Mitchell Library in
the event of his death. ``They come round every Hogmanay to collect a batch,''
he chuckles. ``It's the only way I have of keeping them under control.'' Indeed
a fleeting glance at the vast selection of English and foreign literature
adorning the walls of his study and hall not only suggest the words ``Brazilian
rain forest'' but makes one realise what a tremendous coup the Mitchell have
pulled off in being the lucky recipients of Morgan's personal library.
In the dark study where he confesses, somewhat abashed, that he only comes ``to
hide from the cleaning woman every week'' there is the Scottish literature
section that encompasses everything from medieval Scots to Irvine Welsh, a
comprehensive A to Z of modern twentieth-century poetry, countless shelves of
musty leather-bound bibliographies, anthologies and dictionaries, before the
paper trail explodes out into the hall which in turn boasts a foreign
literature collection that would give the British Library a serious run for its
money.
Let's hope that the Mitchell have to wait a good few years yet before they get
their hands on the contents of Morgan's workplace.
</TEXT>
