<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>J. P. Leach</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974979332</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STUDIES have shown that British people, when faced with American know-how often
have a bit of an inferiority complex. Not that I'm saying Americans are
arrogant, just that when the average American starts to talk, they tend to
speak as though they have a right to be arrogant.
We don't feel inferior to all Americans, especially not those who take part in
TV talk shows dealing with ``human stories''. It's difficult to be impressed by
someone who's bubbling away on national TV while there's a caption flashing
beneath them saying ``Bettye-Soo: Broke up with boyfriend because of his
cocaine-addicted dog''.
So, chat show guests apart, we all agree that the Yanks in general have a good
reputation, and as they say in Louisiana, when they talk turkey, they don't
mean stuffin'. Maybe they get their image from the films, where the hero is
inevitably a square-jawed WASP who has a full grasp of science, arts, and car
maintenance. After watching them for years, we assume Americans are all like
that.
Except Jim Carrey. We know he's not smart because, Hollywood tells us, he is in
the process of becoming a huge star because of his ability to make his face
look funny while speaking in a hilarous manner. Although careers have been
built on this, as per, say Malcolm Rifkind, it's unlikely that he will do as
well as the film bosses think. So except for tele-emotional cripples and Jim
Carrey, Yanks have a fairly good reputation, right?
This is what had me worried when I was there for a few days last week. I had to
go to Baltimore to give a talk on a subject that is far too boring for a
respectable family newspaper. The Americans at the conference were exactly the
sort of smart, Apple Pie guys that would grace any film screen, and that's what
put the fear of Gawd into me. I don't mind making a fool of myself on my home
patch, but I don't want to look too stupid in the Land Of the Free, and if
anyone was going to catch me out it was these smarter, harder working, fitter
more committed Americans.
Everyone in America is extremely pleasant, but they are all congenitally unable
to understand the clear-cut tones and slow diction that characterises typical
Glaswegian speech. After the first two days where everyone thought I was Irish,
Norwegian or German, I had slowed down my words significantly. Even if they
didn't understand what I was saying, at least they all realised I was Scottish.
I thought I was ready for my talk.
On the big day I really felt terrible. The day creaked along slowly, and my
palms got sweatier as the appointed hour got nearer. I remember the chairman
calling my name, and Glasgow being pronounced (as always by Americans) as Glass
Cow. The soundtrack for the next few seconds is just the double boom of the
blood rushing through my head. My voice was at first exactly like the teacher's
voice in the Charlie Brown cartoons, and for what seemed like an eternity, the
audience went quiet.
I got to the punchline of my first gag. Nothing. There were a few loud guffaws
from the back, and slowly the rest of the audience got the cue that I had made
a joke. My nerves disappeared. I had thought that they would all be too serious
to ever laugh. You only have to see any sitcom other than the two good ones to
realise that their tolerance for cruddy jokes is actually quite high.
The next day, I went on a present-buying spree. I make a better job of buying
presents in America than my gran used to. In the sixties and seventies she used
to return from the States with her case full of gimmicky nonsense: case-loads
full of tat like Santa-shaped napkin rings, fridge magnets and Kids' drinking
straws that had been moulded into amusing curly shapes. We had Scotland's
biggest collection of American junk, the entire New York branch of
Fridge-Magnets R Us having been bought up by my gran.
Anyway, as part of a family tradition, I was paying for my collection of
camel-shaped monogrammed coasters when the young blonde cashier spotted my
accent. She said that Scottish accents like mine were, and I quote,
``beautiful''. I drew in my stomach and gave a sort of David Hasselhoff smile,
and in a cool, but basically suave manner, I joked that it would be beautiful
if only people could understand me. She fell for this obvious compliment
fishing. ``Not at all, I understand you easily,'' she gushed. ``You're easier
to understand than some of my friends, and English is their first language!'' I
gave up and sneaked out.
</TEXT>
