<TEXT>
Twelve months of literary luxury: Herald writers and regular reviewers continue
their selection of books which impressed, moved and inspired them
LESLEY DUNCAN
n Sophie's World, Jostein Gaarder (Phoenix House, #16.99)
NORWEGIAN author Jostein Gaarder has said endearingly of Sophie's World that he
feared it would fall ``between all stools'' but instead it had fallen on them.
His book is indeed a phenomenon - a survey of Western philosophy embedded in a
magical mystery story. The aim of the Sophie-in-Wonderland plot is to make the
intellectual demands of the core material less formidable. It succeeds.
Millions of copies have been sold worldwide. Readers are kept enthralled by the
sparky heroine's encounters with the messenger dog Hermes and the enigmatic
Alberto Knox. The latter is determined to make Sophia think about the basic
questions of existence (and tell her what successive philosophers have made of
them). The fact that the tale involves reality within reality is itself a
paradigm of the philosophical matter it is handling. Too deep for comfort? Not
a bit of it.
JOHN FOWLER
n The New Naturalists, Peter Marren (HarperCollins, #14.99 paperback, also
available in hard cover)
Naturalist, Edward O Wilson (Allen Lane, #20)
IN wartime Soho, Billy Collins the publisher, the scientist Julian Huxley and
two others met for lunch to discuss a proposed series of nature books to be
written by specialists for the interested general reader.
The New Naturalist books were born. The first volume, on butterflies, appeared
in 1945. Number six was Frank Fraser Darling's Natural History in the Highlands
and Islands, later revised by J Morton Boyd, himself the author with his son of
The Hebrides (published 1990), number 76 in the series. Fifty years on new
titles still appear. Peter Marren's The New Naturalists charts the half-century
history of this enriching library. Lively, shrewd and carefully researched,
it's endlessly fascinating. So is Naturalist, by the eminent American
entomologist Edward O Wilson, which is both a beguiling memoir of his life and
an insight into contemporary views on biology and the natural world.
ANVAR KHAN
n Paula by Isabel Allende (HarperCollins, #14.99)
I NOMINATE Paula by Isabel Allende, because the novel is a sign of strength.
Hers.
Some writers believe you have to give part of yourself in a piece of work. They
say that even fiction demands some truth. Poets ``soul-search'' because they
think good literature is created by loneliness and the unconscious mind.
It was never in Allende's remit, to adopt the writer's version of the
philosophy of aerobics - no pain, no gain. But she decided to make one chapter
of her life a full novel. Her daughter died, and the only way she could recover
was by writing it all down.
A novelist is a tourist with a typewriter, one part appreciation, one part
detachment. But a great writer is someone who was as lost as Allende, but can,
and without cynicism, showcase a talent so big it stands brighter for her
confusion.
n Gridiron, Phillip Kerr (Chatto and Windus, #15)
Dead Man's Walk, Larry McMurtry (Orion, #15.99)
The Paperboy, Pete Dexter (Viking, #14.99)
SCOTS author Phillip Kerr has been threatening to write the Real Belter for
years and with Gridiro, a marvellous edge-of-the-seat thriller set in a
futuristic LA skyscraper, he appears to have finally done it. The genuinely
thrilling result of a wildly fertile imagination and a rare combination of fine
writing and popular appeal. Elsewhere, Dead Man's Walk, Larry McMurtry's
sublime ``prequel'' to Lonesome Dove is worth its weight in gold. A wonderful
elegiac cowboy book. And, finally, a word of praise for Pete Dexter's The
Paperboy, a great novel by a brilliant writer at the peak of his abilities. A
crime book which transcends the genre.
STEWART LAMONT
n Law &amp; Practice of the Kirk, Andrew Herron, (Chapter House, #20)
SCIENCE and theology, once happily married in alchemy, were apparently divorced
last century. Since then, books on theology by scientists were either few and
far between or strictly of the atheist persuasion. Now each year there are
several examples of such books in which biologists and physicists seem to wish
to reclaim theology as ``queen of the sciences''. None are exactly easy bedtime
reading. Even less so must seem my choice, which brings together the uneasy
bedfellows of law and gospel, whose marriage in Calvinism gave the Kirk of
Scotland a character of its own.
But Andrew Herron's Law &amp; Practice of the Kirk, is more than a textbook for
legally minded ecclesiastics. That role was filled by Cox, the tome of practice
and procedure which was essential reading for Kirk cognoscenti but few others.
Dr Herron's book might be described as Cox without the boring bits (ie the
edicts and laws which are now printed in looseleaf form). It blends a guide to
Kirk lore with a commentary that might easily qualify as ``all you ever needed
to know about the Kirk''. The fact that the book is already in its third
printing and has sold more than 2000 copies, suggests that its appeal is a lot
wider that the 1400 manses in which it will be essential reading.
Where else would you learn that a minister, whose glebe borders a loch upon
which the laird enjoys sole fishing rights, can assert his own right to fish if
he has been there more than 13 years? The bulk of the book is less esoteric and
a lot more instructive about the national church than many history books, and
has the advantage of doubling as a DIY manual for those involved in
congregational affairs.
</TEXT>
