<TEXT>
Herald writers and regular reviewers choose the books which stopped them in
their tracks
CAROL ANDERSON
Snow Falling On Cedars, David Guterson (Bloomsbury, #5.99)
Volume of Plays, Sharman MacDonald (Faber, #8.99)
Voices and Votes, edited by Glenda Norquay (Manchester University Press, #14.99)
So I Am Glad, A L Kennedy (Jonathan Cape, #9.99)
THE novel that has lodged most in my mind this year is David Guterson's Snow
Falling On Cedars, a gripping, intelligent whodunnit set on an island off the
Pacific north-west coast. It offers a sensitive account of relations between
German/Scandinavian and Japanese/Americans, and is often moving.
I'm currently reading A L Kennedy's thought-provoking novel So I Am Glad, but
as I imagine it will be much mentioned, I'll draw attention instead to Sharman
MacDonald's Volume of Plays. And I want to mention an interesting anthology,
Voices and Votes, edited by Glenda Norquay, a selection of short stories, poems
and extracts from novels and autobiographies, dealing with the women's suffrage
campaign of the early twentieth century.
DAVID BELCHER
n High Fidelity, Nick Hornby (Victor Gollancz, #14.99)
alt.culture, edited by Nathaniel Wice and Steven Daly (4th Estate, #12.99)
1996 Guinness Soccer Who's Who, compiled by Jack Rollin (Guinness Books, #7.99)
AFTER the high-scoring success of his soccer memoir, Fever Pitch, Nick Hornby
faced an all-too-inevitable backlash with his first novel, High Fidelity, a
story of love, vinyl and male inadequacy. Too autobiographical, his detractors
sneered. Two-nil to Nick Hornby, we, his fans retort. High Fidelity sits
toppermost of our adult contemporary soul charts, truly.
Unsnared by the Internet? A floating voter in the micro-politics of identity?
Wise up by cyber-surfing through alt.culture, edited by Nathaniel Wice and
former Orange Juicer Steven Daly. Starting with Abortion clinic violence and
ending at Zines, this encyclopaedia of the nineties is as assertively diverse
as the decade itself. But stuff cyber-surfing. Instead, trawl the 1996 Guinness
Soccer Who's Who, comprehensively compiled by Jack Rollin, for players of
promise (and cheapness) to augment Partick Thistle's current heroes.
GAVIN BELL
n Winter Tales, George Mackay Brown (John Murray, #15.99)
The Heart of India, Mark Tully (Penguin, #16)
IF the essence of good writing is simplicity of style, George Mackay Brown is a
master of the craft. His prose is sparse yet lyrical, conjuring vivid images of
his native Orkney through the eyes of generations of seafarers, warriors, and
crofters. His latest collection of short stories, Winter Tales, is as fresh and
vibrant as ever, confirming Brown's position as Scotland's most compelling
story-teller.
A similar economic style, combined with a distinguished journalist's eye for
fine detail, makes The Heart of India, by Mark Tully a fascinating account of
an ancient culture besieged by brash modernity. The short stories from Uttar
Pradesh, based on real characters and incidents, are reminiscent of Kipling at
his best in portraying a complex society with sympathy and understanding.
ALAN BOLD
n The Moor's Last Sigh, Salman Rushdie (Jonathan Cape, #15.99)
Auden, Richard Davenport-Hines (Heinemann, #20)
Michelangelo, George Bull (Viking, #25)
SALMAN RUSHDIE has done it again and I don't mean causing political controversy
with a novel. The Moor's Last Sigh is more than a newsworthy work of faction;
it is a magical fiction about the meaning of fiction. The narrator tells a
story about himself telling a story: ``we are no more than the few tales that
persist.'' This magnificently telling tale, haunted by horror and betrayal,
will persist long after Rushdie is allowed to rest in peace.
``About suffering they were never wrong,/The Old Masters'', so said W F Auden,
whose sufferings are sympathetically considered by Richard Davenport-Hines in
Auden. Interestingly, since so many biographies out macho men as closet queens,
Davenport-Hines outs the openly homosexual Auden as a secret straight in this
admirable assessment of a modern master.
Which only leaves me a sentence to commend an Old Master admired by Auden's
hero T S Eliot who watched the women come and go, talking of Michelangelo.
George Bull's Michelangelo entertainingly puts you in the picture and the
sculpture and the architecture and the poetry.
KEITH  BRUCE
n The Missing, Andrew O'Hagan (Picador, #14.99)
The Road to Xanadu, Orson Welles, Simon Callow (Jonathan Cape, #20)
High Fidelity, Nick Hornby (Victor Gollancz, #14.99)
The Destiny of Nathalie X, William Boyd (Sinclair Stevenson, #9.99)
ANDREW O'HAGAN'S The Missing is a superb piece of journalism, the more welcome
because it comes during a slide towards tabloid values. His melding of family
memoir with sociological and historical analysis, ignited by his coverage of
the Fred West case, is in a proud Scottish tradition in the craft. Orson
Welles, The Road to Xanadu, is biography at its best, fascinated but critical,
and the work of an under-appreciated theatrical polymath, Simon Callow.
William Boyd's collection of short stories The Destiny of Nathalie X, is a
global and philosophical tour of his oeuvre - and proof of what a smart jacket
can do for sales. Nick Hornby's High Fidelity (Victor Gollancz, #14.99), should
be prescribed reading for women everywhere who find us chaps difficult to
comprehend. Too close for comfort from this perspective, but you gotta laugh.
JOHN CAMPBELL
n Gladstone, Roy Jenkins (Macmillan, #20)
Accountable to None: The Tory Nationalisation of Britain, Simon Jenkins (Hamish
Hamilton, #16.99)
FOR sheer historical verve, the biography of the year is Roy Jenkins's
Gladstone. It is a book of fans, admittedly: his critics will think it
self-indulgent, but his admirers will find inimitable delights on every page.
It is not so much a biography, actually, as a sustained narrative reflection,
as Lord Jenkins marvels at Gladstone's amazing physical and intellectual energy
(his life conveniently measured out in quarter-hours) and gently mocks his more
bizarre absurdities, while effortlessly drawing comparisons across 150 years of
political life. Among other surprises he claims Gladstone - father from Leith,
mother from Dingwall - as the most Scottish of Prime Ministers.
The sharpest book on current politics is Simon Jenkins's Accountable to None:
The Tory Nationalisation of Britain - the most devastating account yet of how
Thatcherism, like most revolutions, has produced outcomes contrary to its
professed intentions. Essential reading for all politicians - but will they
read it?
BERTIE DENHAM
n Come to Grief, Dick Francis (Michael Joseph, #15.99)
Beyond the Silence, Ted Allebury (Hodder and Stoughton, #16.99)
The Island of the Dead, Philip Hook (Hodder and Stoughton, #15.99)
IN Come to Grief by Dick Francis, an injured jockey turned investigator puts
one of his best friends, a cult racing television hero, in the dock for a
particularly nauseating crime. This year's offering must stand highly among
Dick's other 32.
Ted Allebury is author of Beyond the Silence.
Lord Carling, who worked for the SIS during the war, was known to have had
left-wing views before it. But did they stop there or could he be the ``fifth
man''? Allebury's best for years.
Rapidly galloping after the other two, Philip Hook, a director of first
Christie's and then Sotheby's, is the author of The Island of the Dead. He
contrives to make the world in which he lives clear as a background for
suspense stories. In one of the London public galleries a valued painting is
vandalised. Why?
</TEXT>
