<TEXT>
THE most common form of planning for the future is savings, and this is where
Scrooge was an amateur. The biggest factor affecting the value of your savings
is the quality of the investment you choose and definitely not investing a few
pence more by what what you save in not burning a few candles.
Douglas McCrea, of Glasgow-based Fraser Insurance Services, has dramatic
examples of the difference the right and wrong choice can make. ``The right
choice can be vital in choosing an account for investment funds,'' he said.
``The difference in performance between investment funds can be vast,
highlighted by the fact that #1000 invested in the best performing insurance
mangaged fund in the 10 years from November 1, 1985, to November 1, 1995, would
have returned #3260.
``This compares with a return of #1620 in the worst performing fund - a
difference of 164%.
``Even in the shorter five-year period the variance is vast, with the top
performing fund returning #2579, compared to #1281 from the worst - a
difference of 130%.''
Investments which can vary so much over the medium and short terms will vary
even more markedly over the long term, and here the right choice is even more
crucial. ``It would be fair to say that people gear the majority of their
financial affairs towards the day they retire,'' said Mr McCrea.
``Many people have set up their mortgage so that it is paid off prior to
retirement. People are well aware that the state provides only limited
assistance in retirement, and many individuals are keen to build up their own
retirement kitty through one of the many different investment vehicles
available to them.''
These different investment vehicles range from straightforward instant-access
building society accounts to personal equity plans, investment bonds and
investment trusts.
With more than 500 different bank and building society accounts available to
the UK investor and 272 listed insurance managed funds, the options available
can be confusing. Only an independent financial adviser is independent of the
companies offering these accounts and funds and can therefore recommend the
correct choice of all the products on the market.
Timing is also critical because investments in equities, or company shares,
depend upon the value the Stock Market places upon those shares. Late last
month the FTSE 100 - or Financial Times Stock Exchange index of the 100 leading
companies' shares - reached its highest point.
``If a client had invested in an insurance company's UK equity fund, which
allows him to invest in a wide range of UK-listed shares under the expertise of
a company's fund managers, the difference in performance as with the managed
funds can be vast,'' said Mr McCrea.
``One thousand pounds invested over the same period from November 1985 to
November 1995 would have returned #3733 in the best performing fund, compared
with #1055 in the worst - a colossal 268% difference.
``In the five-year period, the poorest performing fund would have lost the
client money, returning only #943 compared to the best performing fund which
would have returned a mammoth #2229, a difference of 129%.''
Although they should be viewed as long-term investments, customers do not
necessarily have to stay in a particular fund for years on end. ``The majority
of insurance companies now offer the facility to switch between their range of
funds, allowing one free switch a year,'' said Mr McCrea.
``Gains can be safeguarded by switching from high-risk funds at their peak to
lower-risk funds in order to avoid any downside in the markets.
``The offices of the majority of independent financial advisers are now fully
computerised and have investment performance statistics, comparisons,
up-to-date rates, etc, at their fingertips.''
Many people have existing investments that they have had for years but could
not say with confidence exactly which fund their money is invested in. This
could be costing them thousands of pounds even over the short and medium terms.
The right advice about profit-taking and fund-switching could correct this.
Tax and the thought of the Inland Revenue strikes fear into most people but an
adviser can deal directly with the Revenue and can provide information on
changing tax legislation.
``With the Financial Services Act and the Personal Investment Authority,
financial advisers now have to pass examinations covering areas such as
taxation, the use of trusts and many other vitally important areas,'' said Mr
McCrea.
``Retirement is a time that people should look forward to. An independent
adviser can assist in the enjoyment of your retirement by helping you to
organise your finances in a way best suited to your requirements.''
INCREASING uncertainty about state-provided pensions has led to some alarming
predictions. ``For those in non-pensionable employment it is essential to start
preparing for their income in retirement, or retirement will become a dismal
prospect,'' said Graham Hill of Roxburgh &amp; Co.
``It would be prudent to seek advice from an IFA to keep on the right track
through pension planning.''
Tax breaks offered by some personal pensions mean some investors can roll out
the barrel in retirement. At the highest rate tax relief is available for
contributions and that money can be invested in a tax-free environment.
Careful planners can receive a full quarter of that investment as a tax-free
lump sum on retirement. The remainder can then be used to purchase whichever
annuity the investor chooses.
Kennth Clarke's Budget has had both good and bad effects on pension planning.
``The reduction of basic rate tax, the expansion of the 20% band and increased
personal allowances and thresholds will have an impact on certain individuals'
pension contributions,'' said Mr Hill. ``Relevant net earnings will either be
not subject to tax or will be liable only to tax at 20%. Contributions can be
made net of the new basic rate of 24%. In other words, investors may get more
tax relief than they pay in tax.
``On the other hand, the increase in the higher rate threshold will limit the
amount of relief available. Setting contributions from 1996-97 against those
from 1995-96 may therefore be much more beneficial in the future.''
When planning a pension it is important to remember that it is a two-stage
process - choosing a pension and deciding how best to use it on retirement. The
retirement fund should be built up with whichever pension provider is most
suitable.
Charges vary widely not only between pension providers but also within specific
pension products offered by a single company. These can change depending on the
amount to be invested and the length of time until retirement. Being aware that
no single company comes out top across the board is an important element of
making a choice.
When choosing a plan, the object is to build up as large a retirement fund as
possible from the money being invested. Once retired, it is important to find
the most beneficial way of using that fund. IFA's are committed to finding the
best possible financial result for each individual client, and provide
objective advice.
``New-style personal pensions give the client the facility to improve
retirement income,'' said Mr Hill. ``This is called the `open market' option.
It allows the client to take the retirement fund into the pension market to try
to improve on the terms offered by the holding company. By doing so it is
possible to increase the annuity being offered.''
There is a bewildering array of plans to choose from - single life pensions,
joint life pensions, escalating pensions and so on. An IFA will evaluate the
client's current circumstances and ensure he or she finds the best available
option.
Most people opt for the maximum tax-free lump sum, as annuities are seen as
earned income and are therefore taxable. It is still worthwhile, however, to
take the lump sum and immediately buy a life annuity with tax-free capital
content.
The ``open market'' option does not suit everybody. It can be used to construct
a phased retirement plan which allows control of the pension fund, but an IFA
should be consulted before that choice is made.
The importance of getting it right is highlighted by the problem facing
pensioners in need of full-time care. ``Long-term care is becoming more of an
issue in today's environment,'' said Mr Hill. ``Tax-free cash from your
retirement fund helps relieve this burden.''
NEITHER Scrooge nor his tight-fisted chum Jacob Marley ever benefited much from
their scrimping and saving. For all their years of hoarding every penny,
Scrooge spent his nights alone in a hovel and Marley died miserable, leaving
no-one to care.
The idea that wealth related to happiness was fairly scotched in Dickens's
tale, but in reality the accumulation of a nest egg can guard against some of
the trials of later life.
``Many of us have accumulated some form of wealth as we approach retirement,''
said Les Shields, of Shields Financial Services. ``It might be in the form of a
house owned outright, a nest egg tucked away in the building society and
perhaps some investments in the Stock Market.
``We aim towards the day we can stop working and enjoy retirement.''
Often plans for retirement have no contingency for the unforeseen. A loved one
facing disability or full-time care after an accident or illness, for example,
could lead to financial hardship.
The 1993 Community Care Act transferred responsibility for funding for care to
local authorities rather than central Government. The result was that anyone
with savings of #8000 or more became liable to pay for their own nursing care.
The recent Budget had some element of ``God bless us, everyone'' when Kenneth
Clarke doubled that threshold to #16,000 - but failure to plan for every
consideration could still result in life savings being wiped out by the cost of
care.
``People are living longer today due to better standards of living, improved
health care and medical advances,'' said Mr Shields. ``Increased life
expectancy means the number of people reaching retirement is growing.
``In turn, the elderly population as a whole is getting bigger and will
continue to do so well into the next century. In less than 20 years there will
be 50% more people in Britain aged 85 or over.
``Simultaneously, the working population is declining. By the end of this
decade there will be a drop of more than 15% in the number of 15 to
29-year-olds, which means we are approaching the situation where the state has
to support a growing elderly population resourced by a diminishing number of
tax payers.''
Not exactly tidings of comfort and joy. Mr Shields thinks that in a little more
than 50 years this country may see as much as 75% of its population being
supported by the other 25%. The financial demands on the state will be
significantly increased, and all political parties are agreed that the welfare
state cannot meet the increasing costs of care for the elderly.
The result is that people must increasingly make their own provision for
ill-health in old age, just as they must make provision for retirement and even
for beneficiaries after death.
There have been cases of families having their life savings wiped out by the
costs of nursing care, and the press has featured horror tales of those who
have even lost their homes trying to pay. Typically, a nursing home costs
around #17,500 a year - an amount which will go through any savings all too
quickly.
``Careful planning with the help of an IFA can solve most of these problems in
relatively simple ways,'' said Mr Shields. ``Many are reasonably inexpensive
compared to the loss of capital which might be incurred without them.
``Similarly, many people are reluctant to consider Estate Planning because they
fear they may need the money themselves to pay for care. People therefore pay
unneccessary inheritance tax bills when a little planning would have resolved
the matter.
``This is not only a problem for the elderly - families become involved and
lose out as well.''
IFAs will help find the right financial packages to prevent these painful and
upsetting eventualities. They can advise on gifting a house for example -
leaving it to family but retaining the right to live there.
They can also help find insurance policies covering the cost of long-term care
on a tax-free basis. The earlier planning starts, the less expensive the policy.
``If your are concerned that future loss of health could cause this
unhappiness, contact an IFA and get the facts on protecting your estate,'' said
Mr Shields. ``It's your life - take control of it.''
