<TEXT>
Catherine Brown is
impressed by the array
of home produce at a
major show, with one
notable exception
AS thousands ate their way around the BBC Good Food Show in Birmingham this
year, their senses challenged at every stand by food sights, smells and tastes,
the food industry revelled.
Walking the aisles was a hungry audience - so what did the producers put on
show? Hi-tech, gosh-factor products? An overkill of foreign exotica? Not any
more.
Since the food scares of the eighties and the subsequent demand for less
mucked-up, more honestly produced food, the message - at this exhibition at any
rate - is that good food is not dependent on a trick. The razzmatazz of the
show came instead from a theatre of extrovert chefs demonstrating to huge
audiences, as well as smaller cooking demonstrations going on throughout the
show, and volunteer children competition-cooking for fun.
Meanwhile, skilled artisans were quietly getting on with their hand-crafted
products. A pork pie maker, Morris,was moulding hot water pastry up the side of
the wooden pie mould; an Indian had installed his tandoori oven and was
manipulating naan bread dough before baking it on the hot walls of the oven.
The queue growing longer by the minute, the bread was brushed with oil and
spiced seasonings. The British public were flexing their gastronomic muscles in
unprecedented fashion.
I had not, however, been invited to the show to linger over a tandoori oven, or
watch a hand-crafted Melton Mowbray pork pie take shape, but to report on the
Scottish contingent of producers who had joined the buzzing throng. Scotland
had taken the largest national area in the show, the Highlands and Islands the
largest individual stand area.
``In the late 1980s and early 1990s,'' said Kevin Gruer, Marketing Development
Manager of Highlands and Islands Enterprise, ``the small, innovative Scottish
producer was having a hard time as the multiples demanded uniformity and bulk.
Now this is completely reversed, and the multiples have recognised the need to
bring character to their shelves with more local products made by smaller
producers.''
From the clear, unpolluted waters of the North, there are gleaming silver
salmon. Gareth Crichton of Orkney Seafoods has developed a number of hot smoked
salmon cures, while on Shetland, Magnus Flaws of Shetland Salmon Farmers is
selling salmon nuggets coated in batter made by Framgrod which have recently
become a speciality at Ashdales, the award-winning fish and chip restaurant in
Aberdeen.
Still on Shetland, the Shetland Smokehouse has become the first producer of a
chilled soup in a clear microwaveable can with a seafood range which includes
Cullen Skink.
From Orkney, the veteran exhibitor and creator of delectable herring cures, Ken
Sutherland, of Orkney Herring continues to develop his range. There is a choice
of thick, thin, hard or crunchy Tods of Orkney oatcakes on to which busy
workers are spreading the pate, developed by Castle MacLellan in Kirkcudbright,
made with crabs caught by members of the Orkney Fishermen's Society. And to
sharpen the palate there is a range of seafood dressings and dips from Orkney
Gold using seaweed such as local kelp.
On the meat front the Scotch Quality Beef and Lamb Association's display of
fine butchery (the best in the show) is getting across the quality meat message
very efficiently. But where is the haggis? What, no haggis!
English good-food-tasters are dismayed. The haggis-exhibitor (MacSweens of
Edinburgh) has been prevented from appearing since he is moving premises. If
there is a flaw in the Scottish stand, this is it.
But there is no lack of flavourful jams, original jellies, piquant chutneys,
sharp pickles, herby vinaigrettes and tangy mustards for use as gifts, or on
festive tables. Murray McGregor of Denrosa Apiaries in Coupar has a huge range,
set out on a table for tasting, including Port, Bramble, Elderberry and Apple
and Rosemary jellies, plus a new award-winning range of colourful aromatic oils.
Sheila Robson, of Marmion's Brasserie in Melrose, has developed two vinaigrette
dressings in handled bottles. Also from the Borders, Neville Talbot, of
Pettigrews, the old-established Kelso preserve makers, has widened the range to
include more chutneys as well as festive cakes and a Christmas pudding with rum
or brandy butter. Next door is Simmers, the only remaining bakers in Scotland
who continue to make a buttery Scotch Abernethy biscuit.
On the drinks front, the whisky industry is out in force providing warming
mouthfuls of whisky and whisky-based liqueurs. But for me, the drink highlight
of the show is Fraoch Heather Ale, made by Scott Williams of Glasgow. No, not a
gimmick, but made according to an ancient recipe using native heather blossom
to produce another distinctly authentic national drink.
