IF you arrive in Plymouth, Massachusetts, by coach as I did, you may be excused
for thinking you were in the Stateside equivalent of Gullane
or Joppa with drifts of sand heaped up against every kerb. It's only when you
discover the bus station is actually some distance inland and the shore is
fairly rocky anyway, that you realise this fine grit is part of the soil
indigenous to the area. In fact, this is the medium which has given rise to the
cultivation of one of America's favourite fruits - the cranberry.
Haute cuisine and the supercooks can dictate the fortunes of any food, and the
cranberry has enjoyed a renaissance, partly thanks to the fact that it features
heavily among Delia Smith's new crop of Christmas recipes.
But long before Delia first jellied or sauced them, the first settlers stepped
ashore on Plymouth Rock, and found this tart fruit which played an important
part in the culture of the local Indian tribe, the Wampanog, who used it for
cooking and as a dye for producing the vivid red of their rugs, blankets, and
clothing. It was even used as a poultice for the treatment of wounds caused by
poisoned arrows.
Several names for the cranberry are derived from the Indian language; Eastern
Indians called it ``Sassamanesh'', while tribes in other parts of the continent
referred to it as ``Ataqua'' or ``Pakimintzen''. It is commonly held that our
word cranberry comes from the crane bird frequently seen in the marshlands
feasting on the berries, and also for the delicate pale pink blossom which
resembles the bird's head.
Indian squaws passed on their knowledge and uses for the berries to the Pilgrim
women, who soon adapted it for use in sauces, tarts, and cranberry nog and
wine, but it was not until over 200 years later that Henry Hall of Dennis, Cape
Cod, saw the commercial possibilities of the berries.
Some Americans are often surprised to learn our traditional Christmas fare is
turkey with all the trimmings - including cranberry sauce or jelly - which is
of course their pice de resistance on Thanksgiving Day, with glazed ham forming
the centrepiece of their festive menu.
The cranberry, a member of the Ericaceae family, is a native shrub growing in
bogs and wet heathlands in northern England, Wales and Ireland; there are
trials taking place in Ireland at present to assess the commercial viability of
raising the fruit as a crop.
It is now possible to raise plants successfully in the garden. Although it
prefers areas with rougher weather, do plant it in an area which receives full
sunlight. Minimal fertilizing is required - in fact decay may occur with too
much fertilizer - and usually a simple mulch of compost, peat, or wood chips
will suffice.
Its low creeping habit makes it an ideal groundcover plant for rockeries and
ornamental gardens, with planting carried out in autumn or late winter/early
spring. Plant 8-10 inches apart, working in a little acid peat round the roots.
There is little maintenance other than occasional trimming of the shoots
protruding from the soil, and propagation is carried out by the formation of
runners which can be separated and planted out during the spring.
Cranberry shrubs for planting can be supplied by J Tweedie Fruit Trees,
Maryfield Road, Nursery, Terregles, Dumfries DG2 9TH. Tel: 01387 720 880.
